examples.annotated_text: Arsenal_F.C.: Arsenal began winning silverware again with the surprise [dblookup('Arsenal_F.C.', 'Manager Appointed In 1966') -> Bertie Mee] appointment of club physiotherapist Bertie Mee as manager in 1966. After losing two League Cup finals, they won their first [dblookup('Arsenal_F.C.', 'First European Trophy') -> 1969–70 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup] European trophy, the 1969–70 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup. This was followed by an even greater triumph: their [dblookup('Arsenal_F.C.', 'First League and FA Cup Double') -> 1970–71] first League and FA Cup double in 1970–71. This marked a premature high point of the decade; the [dblookup('Arsenal_F.C.', 'Double-winning Side Breakup') -> Early 1970s] Double-winning side was soon broken up and the following decade was characterised by a series of near misses, starting with Arsenal [dblookup('Arsenal_F.C.', 'FA Cup Runners-up') -> 1972] finishing as FA Cup runners up in 1972, and [dblookup('Arsenal_F.C.', 'First Division Runners-up') -> 1972–73] First Division runners-up in 1972–73.
examples.text: Arsenal_F.C.: Arsenal began winning silverware again with the surprise appointment of club physiotherapist Bertie Mee as manager in 1966. After losing two League Cup finals, they won their first European trophy, the 1969–70 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup. This was followed by an even greater triumph: their first League and FA Cup double in 1970–71. This marked a premature high point of the decade; the Double-winning side was soon broken up and the following decade was characterised by a series of near misses, starting with Arsenal finishing as FA Cup runners up in 1972, and First Division runners-up in 1972–73.

examples.annotated_text: Roman_Republic: Citizens were organized on the basis of centuries and tribes, which would each gather into their own assemblies. The [dblookup('Comitia Centuriata', 'Type') -> Assembly of Centuries] Comitia Centuriata ("Centuriate Assembly") was the assembly of the centuries (i.e. soldiers). The president of the Comitia Centuriata was usually a consul. The centuries would vote, one at a time, until a measure received support from a majority of the centuries. The Comitia Centuriata would elect magistrates who had imperium powers (consuls and praetors). It also [dblookup('Comitia Centuriata', 'Elect Censors') -> True] elected censors. Only the Comitia Centuriata could [dblookup('Comitia Centuriata', 'Declare War') -> True] declare war, and [dblookup('Comitia Centuriata', 'Ratify Census Results') -> True] ratify the results of a census. It also served as the [dblookup('Comitia Centuriata', 'Function As Highest Court of Appeal') -> Certain Judicial Cases] highest court of appeal in certain judicial cases.
examples.text: Roman_Republic: Citizens were organized on the basis of centuries and tribes, which would each gather into their own assemblies. The Comitia Centuriata ("Centuriate Assembly") was the assembly of the centuries (i.e. soldiers). The president of the Comitia Centuriata was usually a consul. The centuries would vote, one at a time, until a measure received support from a majority of the centuries. The Comitia Centuriata would elect magistrates who had imperium powers (consuls and praetors). It also elected censors. Only the Comitia Centuriata could declare war, and ratify the results of a census. It also served as the highest court of appeal in certain judicial cases.

examples.text: Utrecht: About 69% of the population is of Dutch ancestry. Approximately 10% of the population consists of immigrants from Western countries, while 21% of the population is of non-Western origin (9% Moroccan, 5% Turkish, 3% Surinamese and Dutch Caribbean and 5% of other countries). examples.annotated_text: Matter: Matter should not be confused with mass, as the two are not quite the same in modern physics. For example, mass is a conserved quantity, which means that its value is unchanging through time, within closed systems. However, [dblookup('Matter', 'Conservation Status') -> not conserved] matter is not conserved in such systems, although this is not obvious in ordinary conditions on Earth, where [dblookup('Matter', 'Approximate Status on Earth') -> approximately conserved] matter is approximately conserved. Still, [dblookup('Special Relativity', 'Implication On Matter') -> matter may disappear by conversion into energy] special relativity shows that matter may disappear by conversion into energy, even inside closed systems, and it can also be [dblookup('Matter', 'Creation From Energy') -> created from energy] created from energy, within such systems. However, because [dblookup('Mass', 'Equivalence With') -> energy] mass (like energy) can neither be created nor destroyed, the quantity of mass and the quantity of energy remain the same during a transformation of matter (which represents a certain amount of energy) into non-material (i.e., non-matter) energy. This is also true in the reverse transformation of energy into matter.
examples.text: Matter: Matter should not be confused with mass, as the two are not quite the same in modern physics. For example, mass is a conserved quantity, which means that its value is unchanging through time, within closed systems. However, matter is not conserved in such systems, although this is not obvious in ordinary conditions on Earth, where matter is approximately conserved. Still, special relativity shows that matter may disappear by conversion into energy, even inside closed systems, and it can also be created from energy, within such systems. However, because mass (like energy) can neither be created nor destroyed, the quantity of mass and the quantity of energy remain the same during a transformation of matter (which represents a certain amount of energy) into non-material (i.e., non-matter) energy. This is also true in the reverse transformation of energy into matter.

examples.annotated_text: Oklahoma_City: Oklahoma City was settled on [dblookup('Oklahoma City', 'Settlement Date') -> April 22, 1889] April 22, 1889, when the area known as the "Unassigned Lands" was opened for settlement in an event known as [dblookup('Oklahoma City', 'Settlement Event') -> The Land Run] "The Land Run". Some 10,000 homesteaders settled the area that would become the capital of Oklahoma. The town grew quickly; the [dblookup('Oklahoma City', 'Population Change 1890-1900') -> doubled] population doubled between 1890 and 1900. Early leaders of the development of the city included Anton Classen, John Shartel, Henry Overholser, and James W. Maney.

examples.annotated_text: Republic_of_the_Congo: Marien Ngouabi, who had participated in the coup, assumed the presidency on [dblookup('Marien Ngouabi', 'Became President On') -> December 31, 1968] December 31, 1968. One year later, [dblookup('Marien Ngouabi', 'Proclamation') -> Congo Africa's first "people's republic"] President Ngouabi proclaimed Congo Africa's first "people's republic", the People's Republic of the Congo, and announced the decision of the [dblookup('National Revolutionary Movement', 'Name Change') -> Congolese Labour Party (PCT)] National Revolutionary Movement to change its name to the Congolese Labour Party (PCT). Ngouabi survived an attempted coup in 1972 but was [dblookup('Marien Ngouabi', 'Assassinated On') -> March 16, 1977] assassinated on March 16, 1977. An [dblookup('Military Committee of the Party', 'Interim Government Leader') -> Joachim Yhombi-Opango] 11-member Military Committee of the Party (CMP) was then named to head an interim government with Joachim Yhombi-Opango to serve as President of the Republic. Two years later, [dblookup('Joachim Yhombi-Opango', 'Forced From Power In') -> 1979] Yhombi-Opango was forced from power and [dblookup('Denis Sassou Nguesso', 'Became President') -> 1979] Denis Sassou Nguesso became the new president.
examples.text: Republic_of_the_Congo: Marien Ngouabi, who had participated in the coup, assumed the presidency on December 31, 1968. One year later, President Ngouabi proclaimed Congo Africa's first "people's republic", the People's Republic of the Congo, and announced the decision of the National Revolutionary Movement to change its name to the Congolese Labour Party (PCT). Ngouabi survived an attempted coup in 1972 but was assassinated on March 16, 1977. An 11-member Military Committee of the Party (CMP) was then named to head an interim government with Joachim Yhombi-Opango to serve as President of the Republic. Two years later, Yhombi-Opango was forced from power and Denis Sassou Nguesso become the new president.

examples.annotated_text: Late_Middle_Ages: The period saw several important technical innovations, like the principle of linear perspective found in the work of Masaccio, and [dblookup('Linear Perspective', 'Described By') -> Brunelleschi] later described by Brunelleschi. This can be seen particularly well in his sculptures, inspired by the [dblookup('Donatello', 'Inspiration') -> classical models] study of classical models. As the centre of the movement shifted to [dblookup('High Renaissance', 'Movement Centre') -> Rome] Rome, the period culminated in the High Renaissance masters [dblookup('High Renaissance', 'Major Artists') -> Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, Raphael] da Vinci, Michelangelo and Raphael.

examples.annotated_text: Oklahoma: Two inland ports on rivers serve [dblookup('Oklahoma', 'Ports') -> Port of Muskogee, Tulsa Port of Catoosa] Oklahoma: the Port of Muskogee and the Tulsa Port of Catoosa. The only port handling international cargo in the state, the [dblookup('Tulsa Port of Catoosa', 'Distinction') -> most inland ocean-going port in the nation] Tulsa Port of Catoosa is the most inland ocean-going port in the nation and [dblookup('Tulsa Port of Catoosa', 'Annual Cargo Volume') -> over two million tons] ships over two million tons of cargo each year. Both ports are located on the [dblookup('Port of Muskogee and Tulsa Port of Catoosa', 'Waterway Connection') -> McClellan-Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System] McClellan-Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System, which [dblookup('McClellan-Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System', 'Connects To') -> Mississippi River] connects barge traffic from Tulsa and Muskogee to the Mississippi River via the Verdigris and Arkansas rivers, contributing to [dblookup('McClellan-Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System', 'Importance') -> one of the busiest waterways in the world] one of the busiest waterways in the world.
examples.text: Oklahoma: Two inland ports on rivers serve Oklahoma: the Port of Muskogee and the Tulsa Port of Catoosa. The only port handling international cargo in the state, the Tulsa Port of Catoosa is the most inland ocean-going port in the nation and ships over two million tons of cargo each year. Both ports are located on the McClellan-Kerr Arkansas River Navigation System, which connects barge traffic from Tulsa and Muskogee to the Mississippi River via the Verdigris and Arkansas rivers, contributing to one of the busiest waterways in the world.

examples.text: Houston: Houston (i/ˈhjuːstən/ HYOO-stən) is the most populous city in Texas and the fourth most populous city in the United States, located in Southeast Texas near the Gulf of Mexico. examples.annotated_text: British_Empire: During the 19th century, Britain and the [dblookup('Great Game', 'Major Rivals') -> Russian Empire] Russian Empire vied to fill the power vacuums that had been left by the declining [dblookup('Great Game', 'Affected Empires') -> Ottoman Empire, Qajar dynasty, Qing Dynasty] Ottoman Empire, Qajar dynasty and Qing Dynasty. This rivalry in Eurasia came to be known as the [dblookup('Rivalry in Eurasia', 'Name') -> Great Game] "Great Game". As far as Britain was concerned, defeats inflicted by Russia on Persia and Turkey demonstrated its imperial ambitions and capabilities and stoked fears in Britain of an overland invasion of [dblookup('British Empire', 'Colonial Interests Threatened') -> India] India. In [dblookup('First Anglo-Afghan War', 'Initiated In') -> 1839] 1839, Britain moved to pre-empt this by invading Afghanistan, but the First Anglo-Afghan War was a disaster for Britain.

examples.text: Comics: Outside of these genealogies, comics theorists and historians have seen precedents for comics in the Lascaux cave paintings in France (some of which appear to be chronological sequences of images), Egyptian hieroglyphs, Trajan's Column in Rome, the 11th-century Norman Bayeux Tapestry, the 1370 bois Protat woodcut, the 15th-century Ars moriendi and block books, Michelangelo's The Last Judgment in the Sistine Chapel, and William Hogarth's 17th-century sequential engravings, amongst others.[b]

examples.annotated_text: Uranium: To be considered 'enriched', the [dblookup('Uranium', 'Enrichment Range for Uranium-235') -> 3% to 5%] uranium-235 fraction should be between 3% and 5%. This process produces huge quantities of uranium that is depleted of uranium-235 and with a correspondingly increased fraction of uranium-238, called [dblookup('Depleted Uranium', 'Uranium-235 Concentration Maximum') -> 0.3%] depleted uranium or 'DU'. To be considered 'depleted', the uranium-235 isotope concentration should be no more than 0.3%. The price of uranium has risen since 2001, so enrichment tailings containing more than [dblookup('Enrichment Tailings', 'Uranium-235 Percentage Threshold for Re-enrichment') -> 0.35%] 0.35% uranium-235 are being considered for re-enrichment, driving the [dblookup('Depleted Uranium Hexafluoride', 'Price in July 2007') -> $130 per kilogram] price of depleted uranium hexafluoride above $130 per kilogram in July 2007 from [dblookup('Depleted Uranium Hexafluoride', 'Price in 2001') -> $5] $5 in 2001.
examples.text: Uranium: To be considered 'enriched', the uranium-235 fraction should be between 3% and 5%. This process produces huge quantities of uranium that is depleted of uranium-235 and with a correspondingly increased fraction of uranium-238, called depleted uranium or 'DU'. To be considered 'depleted', the uranium-235 isotope concentration should be no more than 0.3%. The price of uranium has risen since 2001, so enrichment tailings containing more than 0.35% uranium-235 are being considered for re-enrichment, driving the price of depleted uranium hexafluoride above $130 per kilogram in July 2007 from $5 in 2001.

examples.annotated_text: Adolescence: A questionnaire called the teen timetable has been used to measure the age at which individuals believe adolescents should be able to engage in behaviors associated with autonomy. This questionnaire has been used to gauge [dblookup('Teen Timetable', 'Used For') -> differences in cultural perceptions of adolescent autonomy] differences in cultural perceptions of adolescent autonomy, finding, for instance, that [dblookup('Cultural Group', 'Expected Autonomy Age') -> White parents, earlier] White parents and adolescents tend to expect autonomy earlier than those of [dblookup('Cultural Group', 'Expected Autonomy Age') -> Asian descent, later] Asian descent. It is, therefore, clear that cultural differences exist in perceptions of adolescent autonomy, and such differences have implications for the lifestyles and development of adolescents. In sub-Saharan African youth, the notions of individuality and freedom may not be useful in understanding adolescent development. Rather, African notions of childhood and adolescent development are relational and interdependent.

examples.annotated_text: John, King of England: By the Victorian period in the 19th century, historians were more inclined to draw on the judgments of the chroniclers and to focus on [dblookup('John, King of England', 'Moral Assessment by Kate Norgate') -> "almost superhuman wickedness"] John's moral personality. [dblookup('Kate Norgate', 'View on John, King of England Downfall') -> "almost superhuman wickedness"] Kate Norgate, for example, argued that John's downfall had been due not to his failure in war or strategy, but due to his "almost superhuman wickedness", whilst [dblookup('James Ramsay', 'Cause of John, King of England Downfall') -> family background and cruel personality] James Ramsay blamed John's family background and his cruel personality for his downfall. Historians in the "Whiggish" tradition, focusing on documents such as the Domesday Book and Magna Carta, trace a progressive and universalist course of political and economic development in England over the medieval period. These historians were often inclined to see [dblookup('John, King of England', 'Reign Assessment by Whiggish Historians') -> positive step in constitutional development] John's reign, and his signing of [dblookup('John, King of England', 'Signed Document') -> Magna Carta] Magna Carta in particular, as a positive step in the constitutional development of England, despite the flaws of the king himself. [dblookup('Winston Churchill', 'View on John, King of England') -> contribution due to vices] Winston Churchill, for example, argued that "[w]hen the long tally is added, it will be seen that the British nation and the English-speaking world owe far more to the vices of John than to the labours of virtuous sovereigns".
examples.text: John,_King_of_England: By the Victorian period in the 19th century historians were more inclined to draw on the judgements of the chroniclers and to focus on John's moral personality. Kate Norgate, for example, argued that John's downfall had been due not to his failure in war or strategy, but due to his "almost superhuman wickedness", whilst James Ramsay blamed John's family background and his cruel personality for his downfall. Historians in the "Whiggish" tradition, focusing on documents such as the Domesday Book and Magna Carta, trace a progressive and universalist course of political and economic development in England over the medieval period. These historians were often inclined to see John's reign, and his signing of Magna Carta in particular, as a positive step in the constitutional development of England, despite the flaws of the king himself. Winston Churchill, for example, argued that "[w]hen the long tally is added, it will be seen that the British nation and the English-speaking world owe far more to the vices of John than to the labours of virtuous sovereigns".

examples.annotated_text: Asthma: As of [dblookup('Asthma', 'Data Year') -> 2011] 2011, [dblookup('Asthma', 'Global Prevalence Range') -> 235–330 million] 235–330 million people worldwide are affected by asthma, and approximately [dblookup('Asthma', 'Annual Global Mortality Range') -> 250,000–345,000] 250,000–345,000 people die per year from the disease. Rates vary between countries with prevalences between [dblookup('Asthma', 'Prevalence Range by Country') -> 1 and 18%] 1 and 18%. It is more common in [dblookup('Asthma', 'Prevalence Greater In') -> developed countries] developed than developing countries. One thus sees lower rates in [dblookup('Asthma', 'Lower Rates Observed In') -> Asia, Eastern Europe, Africa] Asia, Eastern Europe, and Africa. examples.text: Tajikistan: Tajikistan (i/tɑːˈdʒiːkᵻstɑːn/, /təˈdʒiːkᵻstæn/, or /tæˈdʒiːkiːstæn/; Persian: تاجيكستان‎‎ Тоҷикистон [tɔd͡ʒikɪsˈtɔn]), officially the Republic of Tajikistan (Persian: جمهورى تاجيكستان‎‎ Tajik: Ҷумҳурии Тоҷикистон, Çumhuriji Toçikiston/Jumhuriyi Tojikiston; Russian: Респу́блика Таджикистан, Respublika Tadzhikistan), is a mountainous, landlocked country in Central Asia with an estimated 8 million people in 2013, and an area of 143,100 km2 (55,300 sq mi). It is bordered by Afghanistan to the south, Uzbekistan to the west, Kyrgyzstan to the north, and China to the east. Pakistan lies to the south, separated by the narrow Wakhan Corridor. Traditional homelands of Tajik people included present-day Tajikistan, Afghanistan and Uzbekistan.

examples.annotated_text: Military_history_of_the_United_States: The British, for their part, lacked both [dblookup('British Military Command', 'During American Revolution') -> Unified Command] a unified command and a clear strategy for winning. With the use of the [dblookup('British Royal Navy', 'Role in American Revolution') -> Capture Coastal Cities] Royal Navy, the British were able to capture coastal cities, but control of the countryside eluded them. A British sortie from Canada in 1777 ended with the [dblookup('Battle of Saratoga', 'Outcome for British Army') -> Disastrous Surrender] disastrous surrender of a British army at Saratoga. With the coming in 1777 of [dblookup('General von Steuben', 'Contribution to Continental Army') -> Training and Discipline Along Prussian Lines] General von Steuben, the training and discipline along Prussian lines began, and the Continental Army began to evolve into a modern force. France and [dblookup('Spain', 'Entered American Revolutionary War') -> 1779] Spain then entered the war against Great Britain as Allies of the US, ending its naval advantage and escalating the conflict into a world war. The Netherlands later joined France, and the British were outnumbered on land and sea in a world war, as they had no major allies apart from Indian tribes.

examples.annotated_text: British_Isles: Scotland, meanwhile had remained an [dblookup('Scotland', 'Political Status Before 1603') -> independent Kingdom] independent Kingdom. In [dblookup('Union of the Crowns', 'Year') -> 1603] 1603, that changed when the [dblookup('James VI and I', 'Inherited Crowns') -> Crown of England, Crown of Ireland] King of Scotland inherited the Crown of England, and consequently the Crown of Ireland also. The subsequent [dblookup('British Isles', 'Political Climate in 17th Century') -> political upheaval, religious division, war] 17th century was one of political upheaval, religious division and war. English colonialism in Ireland of the [dblookup('Ireland', 'Colonialism Period') -> 16th century] 16th century was extended by [dblookup('Ulster', 'Colonization By') -> Scottish, English colonies] large-scale Scottish and English colonies in Ulster. Religious division heightened and the King in England came into conflict with parliament. A prime issue was, inter alia, over [dblookup('English Monarch', 'Religious Policy') -> tolerance towards Catholicism] his policy of tolerance towards Catholicism. The resulting [dblookup('English Civil War', 'Also Known As') -> War of the Three Kingdoms] English Civil War or War of the Three Kingdoms led to a revolutionary republic in England. Ireland, largely Catholic was mainly loyal to the king. Following defeat to the parliament's army, large scale land distributions from loyalist Irish nobility to English commoners in the service of the parliamentary army created the beginnings of a new Ascendancy class which over the next hundred years would obliterate the [dblookup('Ireland', 'Nobility Displaced') -> English (Hiberno-Norman), Gaelic Irish nobility] English (Hiberno-Norman) and Gaelic Irish nobility in Ireland. The new ruling class was [dblookup('Ireland', 'Ruling Class Characteristics Post-Civil War') -> Protestant, British] Protestant and British, whilst the common people were largely [dblookup('Ireland', 'Common People Characteristics') -> Catholic, Irish] Catholic and Irish. This theme would influence Irish politics for centuries to come. When the [dblookup('Monarchy', 'Restoration In') -> England] monarchy was restored in England, the king found it politically impossible to restore all the lands of former land-owners in Ireland. The "Glorious Revolution" of [dblookup('Glorious Revolution', 'Year') -> 1688] 1688 repeated similar themes: a Catholic king pushing for religious tolerance in opposition to a Protestant parliament in England. The king's army was defeated at the [dblookup('Battle', 'Decisive Conflict in Glorious Revolution') -> Battle of the Boyne, Battle of Aughrim] Battle of the Boyne and at the militarily crucial Battle of Aughrim in Ireland. Resistance held out, and a guarantee of religious tolerance was a cornerstone of the [dblookup('Treaty of Limerick', 'Significance') -> guarantee of religious tolerance] Treaty of Limerick. However, in the evolving political climate, the terms of Limerick were superseded, a new monarchy was installed, and the new Irish parliament was packed with the new elite which legislated increasing intolerant [dblookup('Penal Laws', 'Effect On') -> Dissenters, Catholics] Penal Laws, which discommoded both Dissenters and Catholics.
examples.text: British_Isles: Scotland, meanwhile had remained an independent Kingdom. In 1603, that changed when the King of Scotland inherited the Crown of England, and consequently the Crown of Ireland also. The subsequent 17th century was one of political upheaval, religious division and war. English colonialism in Ireland of the 16th century was extended by large-scale Scottish and English colonies in Ulster. Religious division heightened and the King in England came into conflict with parliament. A prime issue was, inter alia, over his policy of tolerance towards Catholicism. The resulting English Civil War or War of the Three Kingdoms led to a revolutionary republic in England. Ireland, largely Catholic was mainly loyal to the king. Following defeat to the parliaments army, large scale land distributions from loyalist Irish nobility to English commoners in the service of the parliamentary army created the beginnings a new Ascendancy class which over the next hundred years would obliterate the English (Hiberno-Norman) and Gaelic Irish nobility in Ireland. The new ruling class was Protestant and British, whilst the common people were largely Catholic and Irish. This theme would influence Irish politics for centuries to come. When the monarchy was restored in England, the king found it politically impossible to restore all the lands of former land-owners in Ireland. The "Glorious Revolution" of 1688 repeated similar themes: a Catholic king pushing for religious tolerance in opposition to a Protestant parliament in England. The king's army was defeated at the Battle of the Boyne and at the militarily crucial Battle of Aughrim in Ireland. Resistance held out, and a guarantee of religious tolerance was a cornerstone of the Treaty of Limerick. However, in the evolving political climate, the terms of Limerick were superseded, a new monarchy was installed, and the new Irish parliament was packed with the new elite which legislated increasing intolerant Penal Laws, which discommoded both Dissenters and Catholics.

examples.annotated_text: Police: All [dblookup('United Kingdom', 'Police Officer Legal Title') -> constables] police officers in the United Kingdom, whatever their actual rank, are 'constables' in terms of their legal position. This means that a newly appointed constable has the same arrest powers as a [dblookup('United Kingdom Police', 'Senior Rank Example') -> Chief Constable or Commissioner] Chief Constable or Commissioner. However, certain [dblookup('United Kingdom Police', 'Higher Rank Authority Example') -> Inspector, Superintendent] higher ranks have additional powers to authorize certain aspects of police operations, such as a power to authorize a search of a suspect's house (section 18 PACE in England and Wales) by an officer of the rank of Inspector, or the power to authorize a suspect's detention beyond 24 hours by a Superintendent.

examples.annotated_text: Guam: In [dblookup('Guam Postage Stamps', 'Overprinted Year') -> 1899] 1899, the local postage stamps were overprinted "Guam" as was done for the other former Spanish colonies, but this was discontinued shortly thereafter and regular U.S. postage stamps have been used ever since. examples.annotated_text: Kanye_West: West's third studio album, Graduation, garnered major publicity when its [dblookup('Graduation', 'Release Date Competition') -> 50 Cent's Curtis] release date pitted West in a sales competition against rapper 50 Cent's Curtis. Upon their [dblookup('Graduation', 'Release Date') -> September 2007] September 2007 releases, Graduation [dblookup('Graduation', 'Billboard 200 Debut Position') -> number one] debuted at number one on the U.S. Billboard 200 chart and [dblookup('Graduation', 'First Week Sales') -> 957,000 copies] sold 957,000 copies in its first week. Graduation once again continued the string of [dblookup('Graduation', 'Critical and Commercial Success') -> Kanye West] critical and commercial successes by West, and the album's [dblookup('Graduation', 'Lead Single') -> Stronger] lead single, "Stronger", garnered the rapper his [dblookup('Stronger', 'Number-One Hit Count') -> third number-one hit] third number-one hit. "Stronger", which samples [dblookup('Stronger', 'Sample') -> Daft Punk] French house duo Daft Punk, has been accredited to not only encouraging other hip-hop artists to incorporate house and electronica elements into their music, but also for [dblookup('Stronger', 'Impact On Music Genres') -> revival of disco and electro-infused music] playing a part in the revival of disco and electro-infused music in the late 2000s. Ben Detrick of XXL cited the outcome of the sales competition between 50 Cent's Curtis and West's Graduation as being responsible for [dblookup('Graduation', 'Impact On Hip-Hop Direction') -> altering the direction of hip-hop] altering the direction of hip-hop and paving the way for new rappers who didn't follow the hardcore-gangster mold, writing, "If there was ever a watershed moment to indicate hip-hop's changing direction, it may have come when 50 Cent competed with Kanye in 2007 to see whose album would claim superior sales."
examples.text: Kanye_West: West's third studio album, Graduation, garnered major publicity when its release date pitted West in a sales competition against rapper 50 Cent's Curtis. Upon their September 2007 releases, Graduation outsold Curtis by a large margin, debuting at number one on the U.S. Billboard 200 chart and selling 957,000 copies in its first week. Graduation once again continued the string of critical and commercial successes by West, and the album's lead single, "Stronger", garnered the rapper his third number-one hit. "Stronger", which samples French house duo Daft Punk, has been accredited to not only encouraging other hip-hop artists to incorporate house and electronica elements into their music, but also for playing a part in the revival of disco and electro-infused music in the late 2000s. Ben Detrick of XXL cited the outcome of the sales competition between 50 Cent's Curtis and West's Graduation as being responsible for altering the direction of hip-hop and paving the way for new rappers who didn't follow the hardcore-gangster mold, writing, "If there was ever a watershed moment to indicate hip-hop's changing direction, it may have come when 50 Cent competed with Kanye in 2007 to see whose album would claim superior sales."

examples.annotated_text: Josip Broz Tito: On December 21, 1941, the Partisans created the [dblookup('First Proletarian Brigade', 'Commander') -> Koča Popović] First Proletarian Brigade (commanded by Koča Popović) and on [dblookup('Josip Broz Tito', 'Second Proletarian Brigade Creation Date') -> March 1, 1942] March 1, 1942, Tito created the Second Proletarian Brigade. The Anti-Fascist Council of National Liberation of Yugoslavia ([dblookup('Anti-Fascist Council of National Liberation of Yugoslavia', 'Abbreviation') -> AVNOJ] AVNOJ) convened in [dblookup('AVNOJ', 'First Session Location') -> Bihać] Bihać on [dblookup('AVNOJ', 'First Session Dates') -> November 26–27, 1942] 26–27 November 1942 and in [dblookup('AVNOJ', 'Second Session Location') -> Jajce] Jajce on [dblookup('AVNOJ', 'Second Session Date') -> November 29, 1943] 29 November 1943. In the two sessions, the resistance representatives established the basis for post-war organisation of the country, deciding on a [dblookup('AVNOJ', 'Post-War Decision') -> federation of the Yugoslav nations] federation of the Yugoslav nations. In Jajce, a 67-member "presidency" was elected and established a nine-member National Committee of Liberation (five communist members) as a de facto provisional government. examples.text: Josip_Broz_Tito: On 21 December 1941, the Partisans created the First Proletarian Brigade (commanded by Koča Popović) and on 1 March 1942, Tito created the Second Proletarian Brigade. In liberated territories, the Partisans organised People's Committees to act as civilian government. The Anti-Fascist Council of National Liberation of Yugoslavia (AVNOJ) convened in Bihać on 26–27 November 1942 and in Jajce on 29 November 1943. Tito was named President of the National Committee of Liberation.

examples.annotated_text: Energy: There are strict limits to how efficiently heat can be converted into work in a cyclic process, e.g. in a heat engine, as described by Carnot's theorem and [dblookup('Heat Conversion Efficiency', 'Governed By') -> second law of thermodynamics] the second law of thermodynamics. However, some energy transformations can be quite efficient. The direction of transformations in energy (what kind of energy is transformed to what other kind) is often determined by [dblookup('Direction of Energy Transformations', 'Influenced By') -> entropy] entropy (equal energy spread among all available degrees of freedom) considerations. In practice, all energy transformations are permitted on a small scale, but certain larger transformations are not permitted because it is statistically unlikely that energy or matter will randomly move into more concentrated forms or smaller spaces.

examples.annotated_text: Exhibition_game: Since the introduction of league football, most club sides play a number of friendlies before the start of each season (called [dblookup('Pre-season Friendlies', 'Purpose') -> player warm-up] pre-season friendlies). Friendly football matches are considered to be [dblookup('Friendly Football Matches', 'Competitive Status') -> non-competitive] non-competitive and are only used to "warm up" players for a new season/competitive match. There is generally [dblookup('Friendly Football Matches', 'Stakes') -> nothing competitive at stake] nothing competitive at stake and some rules may be changed or experimented with (such as unlimited substitutions, which allow teams to play younger, less experienced players, and no cards). Although most friendlies are simply one-off matches arranged by the clubs themselves, in which a certain amount is paid by the [dblookup('Friendly Football Matches', 'Paid By') -> challenger club] challenger club to the incumbent club, some teams do compete in short tournaments, such as the Emirates Cup, [dblookup('Short Tournament', 'Example') -> Teresa Herrera Trophy] Teresa Herrera Trophy, and the [dblookup('Short Tournament', 'Example') -> Amsterdam Tournament] Amsterdam Tournament. Although these events may involve [dblookup('Short Tournament', 'Characteristics') -> sponsorship deals, trophy awarding, television broadcasting] sponsorship deals and the awarding of a trophy and may even be broadcast on television, there is little [dblookup('Short Tournament', 'Prestige') -> little prestige] prestige attached to them.
examples.text: Exhibition_game: Since the introduction of league football, most club sides play a number of friendlies before the start of each season (called pre-season friendlies). Friendly football matches are considered to be non-competitive and are only used to "warm up" players for a new season/competitive match. There is generally nothing competitive at stake and some rules may be changed or experimented with (such as unlimited substitutions, which allow teams to play younger, less experienced, players, and no cards). Although most friendlies are simply one-off matches arranged by the clubs themselves, in which a certain amount is paid by the challenger club to the incumbent club, some teams do compete in short tournaments, such as the Emirates Cup, Teresa Herrera Trophy and the Amsterdam Tournament. Although these events may involve sponsorship deals and the awarding of a trophy and may even be broadcast on television, there is little prestige attached to them.

examples.annotated_text: Cork_(city): The city's charter was granted by [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Charter Granted By') -> Prince John] Prince John, as Lord of Ireland, in [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Charter Granted In') -> 1185] 1185. The city was once fully walled, and some wall sections and gates remain today. For much of the Middle Ages, Cork city was an outpost of [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Cultural Influence During Middle Ages') -> Old English] Old English culture in the midst of a predominantly hostile Gaelic countryside and cut off from the English government in the Pale around Dublin. Neighbouring Gaelic and Hiberno-Norman lords extorted [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Form of Extortion') -> Black Rent] "Black Rent" from the citizens to keep them from attacking the city. The present extent of the city has exceeded the medieval boundaries of the [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Medieval Boundaries') -> Barony of Cork City] Barony of Cork City; it now takes in much of the neighbouring Barony of Cork. Together, these baronies are located between the [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Neighboring Barony To The East') -> Barony of Barrymore] Barony of Barrymore to the east, [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Neighboring Barony To The West') -> Muskerry East] Muskerry East to the west and [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Neighboring Barony To The South') -> Kerrycurrihy] Kerrycurrihy to the south.
examples.text: Cork_(city): The city's charter was granted by Prince John, as Lord of Ireland, in 1185. The city was once fully walled, and some wall sections and gates remain today. For much of the Middle Ages, Cork city was an outpost of Old English culture in the midst of a predominantly hostile Gaelic countryside and cut off from the English government in the Pale around Dublin. Neighbouring Gaelic and Hiberno-Norman lords extorted "Black Rent" from the citizens to keep them from attacking the city. The present extent of the city has exceeded the medieval boundaries of the Barony of Cork City; it now takes in much of the neighbouring Barony of Cork. Together, these baronies are located between the Barony of Barrymore to the east, Muskerry East to the west and Kerrycurrihy to the south.

examples.annotated_text: Russian_language: The language was first introduced in North America when [dblookup('Russian Language', 'Introduction In North America By') -> Russian explorers] Russian explorers voyaged into Alaska and claimed it for Russia during the [dblookup('Russian Explorers', 'Claimed Territory Century') -> 1700s] 1700s. Although most colonists left after the United States bought the land in [dblookup('United States', 'Purchase Year of Alaska') -> 1867] 1867, a handful stayed and preserved the Russian language in this region to this day, although only a few elderly speakers of this unique dialect are left. Sizable Russian-speaking communities also exist in North America, especially in large urban centers of the U.S. and Canada, such as [dblookup('Russian-speaking Communities', 'Locations in North America') -> New York City, Philadelphia, Boston, Los Angeles, Nashville, San Francisco, Seattle, Spokane, Toronto, Baltimore, Miami, Chicago, Denver, Cleveland] New York City, Philadelphia, Boston, Los Angeles, Nashville, San Francisco, Seattle, Spokane, Toronto, Baltimore, Miami, Chicago, Denver, and Cleveland. In a number of locations they issue their own newspapers, and live in ethnic enclaves (especially the generation of immigrants who started arriving in the early 1960s). Only about [dblookup('Russian-speaking Communities', 'Ethnic Russian Proportion') -> 25%] 25% of them are ethnic Russians, however. Before the dissolution of the Soviet Union, the overwhelming majority of Russophones in [dblookup('Brighton Beach, Brooklyn', 'Dominant Language Pre-Soviet Union Dissolution') -> Russian-speaking Jews] Brighton Beach, Brooklyn in New York City were Russian-speaking Jews. Afterward, the influx from the countries of the former Soviet Union changed the statistics somewhat, with ethnic [dblookup('Brighton Beach, Brooklyn', 'Post-Soviet Union Immigration Groups') -> Russians, Ukrainians, Russian Jews, Central Asians] Russians and Ukrainians immigrating along with some more Russian Jews and Central Asians. According to the United States Census, in [dblookup('Russian Language in the United States', 'Spoken By In 2007') -> 850,000 individuals] 2007 Russian was the primary language spoken in the homes of over 850,000 individuals living in the United States.
examples.text: Russian_language: The language was first introduced in North America when Russian explorers voyaged into Alaska and claimed it for Russia during the 1700s. Although most colonists left after the United States bought the land in 1867, a handful stayed and preserved the Russian language in this region to this day, although only a few elderly speakers of this unique dialect are left. Sizable Russian-speaking communities also exist in North America, especially in large urban centers of the U.S. and Canada, such as New York City, Philadelphia, Boston, Los Angeles, Nashville, San Francisco, Seattle, Spokane, Toronto, Baltimore, Miami, Chicago, Denver and Cleveland. In a number of locations they issue their own newspapers, and live in ethnic enclaves (especially the generation of immigrants who started arriving in the early 1960s). Only about 25% of them are ethnic Russians, however. Before the dissolution of the Soviet Union, the overwhelming majority of Russophones in Brighton Beach, Brooklyn in New York City were Russian-speaking Jews. Afterward, the influx from the countries of the former Soviet Union changed the statistics somewhat, with ethnic Russians and Ukrainians immigrating along with some more Russian Jews and Central Asians. According to the United States Census, in 2007 Russian was the primary language spoken in the homes of over 850,000 individuals living in the United States.

examples.annotated_text: Emotion: This is a communication-based theory developed by [dblookup('Affective Events Theory', 'Developed By') -> Howard M. Weiss, Russell Cropanzano] Howard M. Weiss and Russell Cropanzano (1996), that looks at the causes, structures, and consequences of emotional experience (especially in work contexts). This theory suggests that emotions are influenced and caused by events which in turn influence attitudes and behaviors. This theoretical frame also emphasizes time in that human beings experience what they call emotion episodes—a "series of emotional states extended over time and organized around an underlying theme." Weiss and [dblookup('Affective Events Theory', 'Reviewed By') -> Daniel J. Beal] Daniel J. Beal in their article, "Reflections on Affective Events Theory", published in [dblookup('Reflections on Affective Events Theory', 'Published In') -> Research on Emotion in Organizations] Research on Emotion in Organizations in [dblookup('Reflections on Affective Events Theory', 'Publication Year') -> 2005] 2005.

examples.text: Richmond,_Virginia: The site of Richmond had been an important village of the Powhatan Confederacy, and was briefly settled by English colonists from Jamestown in 1609, and in 1610–1611. examples.text: Universal_Studios: Burdened with debt, in 2004 Vivendi Universal sold 80% of Vivendi Universal Entertainment (including the studio and theme parks) to General Electric, parent of NBC. examples.text: Mandolin: Other major bluegrass mandolinists who emerged in the early 1950s and are still active include Jesse McReynolds (of Jim and Jesse) who invented a syncopated banjo-roll-like style called crosspicking—and Bobby Osborne of the Osborne Brothers, who is a master of clarity and sparkling single-note runs. examples.annotated_text: British Empire: In [dblookup('Rhodesia', 'Independence Year') -> 1980] 1980, Rhodesia, Britain's last African colony, became the [dblookup('Rhodesia', 'Successor State') -> Zimbabwe] independent nation of Zimbabwe. The New Hebrides achieved independence ( as Vanuatu) in [dblookup('New Hebrides', 'Independence Year') -> 1980] 1980, with Belize following suit in [dblookup('Belize', 'Independence Year') -> 1981] 1981. The passage of the British Nationality Act 1981, which reclassified the remaining Crown colonies as "British Dependent Territories" ([dblookup('British Dependent Territories', 'Renamed To') -> British Overseas Territories] renamed British Overseas Territories in [dblookup('British Overseas Territories', 'Renamed Year') -> 2002] 2002) meant that, aside from a scattering of islands and outposts, the process of decolonisation that had begun after the Second World War was largely complete. In [dblookup('Falkland Islands', 'Invasion Year') -> 1982] 1982, Britain's resolve in defending its remaining overseas territories was tested when [dblookup('Falkland Islands', 'Invasion Country') -> Argentina] Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands, acting on a long-standing claim dating back to the Spanish Empire. Britain's ultimately successful military response to retake the islands during the ensuing [dblookup('Falklands War', 'Outcome') -> Britain successful] Falklands War was viewed by many to have contributed to reversing the downward trend in Britain's status as a world power. The same year, the Canadian government severed its last legal link with Britain by patriating the Canadian constitution from Britain. The 1982 Canada Act passed by the British parliament ended the need for British involvement in changes to the Canadian constitution. Similarly, the Constitution Act [dblookup('New Zealand', 'Constitutional Reform Year') -> 1986] 1986 reformed the constitution of New Zealand to sever its constitutional link with Britain, and the [dblookup('Australia', 'Constitutional Link Severance Year') -> 1986] Australia Act 1986 severed the constitutional link between Britain and the Australian states. examples.text: British_Empire: In 1980, Rhodesia, Britain's last African colony, became the independent nation of Zimbabwe. The New Hebrides achieved independence (as Vanuatu) in 1980, with Belize following suit in 1981. The passage of the British Nationality Act 1981, which reclassified the remaining Crown colonies as "British Dependent Territories" (renamed British Overseas Territories in 2002) meant that, aside from a scattering of islands and outposts the process of decolonisation that had begun after the Second World War was largely complete. In 1982, Britain's resolve in defending its remaining overseas territories was tested when Argentina invaded the Falkland Islands, acting on a long-standing claim that dated back to the Spanish Empire. Britain's ultimately successful military response to retake the islands during the ensuing Falklands War was viewed by many to have contributed to reversing the downward trend in Britain's status as a world power. The same year, the Canadian government severed its last legal link with Britain by patriating the Canadian constitution from Britain. The 1982 Canada Act passed by the British parliament ended the need for British involvement in changes to the Canadian constitution. Similarly, the Constitution Act 1986 reformed the constitution of New Zealand to sever its constitutional link with Britain, and the Australia Act 1986 severed the constitutional link between Britain and the Australian states. In 1984, Brunei, Britain's last remaining Asian protectorate, gained its independence.

examples.annotated_text: Adolescence: Puberty occurs through a long process and begins with a surge in [dblookup('Puberty', 'Initiated By') -> hormone production] hormone production, which in turn causes a number of physical changes. The [dblookup('Male Gonads', 'Hormone Released') -> testosterone] testes primarily release testosterone, and the [dblookup('Female Gonads', 'Hormone Released') -> estrogen] ovaries predominantly dispense estrogen. The production of these hormones increases gradually until sexual maturation is met. Some boys may develop [dblookup('Gynecomastia', 'Cause') -> imbalance of sex hormones, tissue responsiveness, obesity] gynecomastia due to an imbalance of sex hormones, tissue responsiveness, or obesity.
examples.text: Adolescence: Puberty occurs through a long process and begins with a surge in hormone production, which in turn causes a number of physical changes. It is the stage of life characterized by the appearance and development of secondary sex characteristics (for example, a deeper voice and larger adam's apple in boys, and development of breasts and more curved and prominent hips in girls) and a strong shift in hormonal balance towards an adult state. This is triggered by the pituitary gland, which secretes a surge of hormonal agents into the blood stream, initiating a chain reaction to occur. The male and female gonads are subsequently activated, which puts them into a state of rapid growth and development; the triggered gonads now commence the mass production of the necessary chemicals. The testes primarily release testosterone, and the ovaries predominantly dispense estrogen. The production of these hormones increases gradually until sexual maturation is met. Some boys may develop gynecomastia due to an imbalance of sex hormones, tissue responsiveness or obesity.

examples.annotated_text: Canadian_football: The Canadian football field is [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Length') -> 150 yards (137 m)] 150 yards (137 m) long and [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Width') -> 65 yards (59 m)] 65 yards (59 m) wide with end zones [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'End Zone Depth') -> 20 yards (18 m)] 20 yards (18 m) deep, and goal lines [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Distance Between Goal Lines') -> 110 yards (101 m)] 110 yards (101 m) apart. At each goal line is a set of [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Goalpost Height') -> 40-foot-high (12 m)] 40-foot-high (12 m) goalposts, which consist of two uprights joined by an [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Crossbar Length') -> 18 1⁄2-foot-long (5.6 m)] 18 1⁄2-foot-long (5.6 m) crossbar which is [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Crossbar Height Above Ground') -> 10 feet (3 m)] 10 feet (3 m) above the goal line. The goalposts may be [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Goalpost Design') -> H-shaped] H-shaped (both posts fixed in the ground) although in the higher-calibre competitions the [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Preferred High-Calibre Goalpost Design') -> tuning-fork design] tuning-fork design (supported by a single curved post behind the goal line, so that each post starts 10 feet (3 m) above the ground) is preferred. The sides of the field are marked by [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Sideline Markings') -> white sidelines] white sidelines, the goal line is marked in white, and white lines are drawn laterally across the field every [dblookup('Canadian football field', 'Lateral Line Interval') -> 5 yards (4.6 m)] 5 yards (4.6 m) from the goal line. examples.text: Canadian_football: The Canadian football field is 150 yards (137 m) long and 65 yards (59 m) wide with end zones 20 yards (18 m) deep, and goal lines 110 yards (101 m) apart. At each goal line is a set of 40-foot-high (12 m) goalposts, which consist of two uprights joined by an 18 1⁄2-foot-long (5.6 m) crossbar which is 10 feet (3 m) above the goal line. The sides of the field are marked by white sidelines, the goal line is marked in white, and white lines are drawn laterally across the field every 5 yards (4.6 m) from the goal line. These lateral lines are called "yard lines" and often marked with the distance in yards from and an arrow pointed toward the nearest goal line. In previous decades, arrows were not used and every yard line was usually marked with the distance to the goal line, including the goal line itself which was marked with a "0"; in most stadiums today, the 10-, 20-, 30-, 40-, and 50-yard lines are marked with numbers, with the goal line sometimes being marked with a "G". The centre (55-yard) line usually is marked with a "C". "Hash marks" are painted in white, parallel to the yardage lines, at 1 yard (0.9 m) intervals, 24 yards (21.9 m) from the sidelines. On fields that have a surrounding running track, such as Commonwealth Stadium, Molson Stadium, and many universities, the end zones are often cut off in the corners to accommodate the track. In 2014, Edmonton placed turf over the track to create full end zones. This was particularly common among U.S.-based teams during the CFL's American expansion, where few American stadiums were able to accommodate the much longer and noticeably wider CFL field.

examples.text: Translation: When a historic document survives only in translation, the original having been lost, researchers sometimes undertake back-translation in an effort to reconstruct the original text. An example involves the novel The Saragossa Manuscript by the Polish aristocrat Jan Potocki (1761–1815), who wrote the novel in French and anonymously published fragments in 1804 and 1813–14. Portions of the original French-language manuscript were subsequently lost; however, the missing fragments survived in a Polish translation that was made by Edmund Chojecki in 1847 from a complete French copy, now lost. French-language versions of the complete Saragossa Manuscript have since been produced, based on extant French-language fragments and on French-language versions that have been back-translated from Chojecki’s Polish version.

examples.annotated_text: Mandolin: The mandolin's popularity in the United States was spurred by the success of a group of touring young European musicians known as the Estudiantina Figaro, or in the United States, simply the "Spanish Students." Ironically, this ensemble did not play mandolins but rather [dblookup('Estudiantina Figaro', 'Instruments Played') -> bandurrias] bandurrias, which are also small, double-strung instruments that resemble the mandolin. The success of the Figaro Spanish Students spawned other groups who imitated their musical style and costumes. An Italian musician, [dblookup('Carlo Curti', 'Occupation') -> musician] Carlo Curti, hastily started a musical ensemble after seeing the Figaro Spanish Students perform; his group of Italian born Americans called themselves the [dblookup('Carlo Curti', 'Musical Ensemble Name') -> Original Spanish Students] "Original Spanish Students," counting on the American public to not know the difference between the [dblookup('Original Spanish Students', 'Instruments Used') -> Italian mandolins] Spanish bandurrias and Italian mandolins. The imitators' use of mandolins helped to generate enormous public interest in an instrument previously relatively unknown in the United States.
examples.text: Mandolin: The mandolin's popularity in the United States was spurred by the success of a group of touring young European musicians known as the Estudiantina Figaro, or in the United States, simply the "Spanish Students." The group landed in the U.S. on January 2, 1880 in New York City, and played in Boston and New York to wildly enthusiastic crowds. Ironically, this ensemble did not play mandolins but rather bandurrias, which are also small, double-strung instruments that resemble the mandolin. The success of the Figaro Spanish Students spawned other groups who imitated their musical style and costumes. An Italian musician, Carlo Curti, hastily started a musical ensemble after seeing the Figaro Spanish Students perform; his group of Italian born Americans called themselves the "Original Spanish Students," counting on the American public to not know the difference between the Spanish bandurrias and Italian mandolins. The imitators' use of mandolins helped to generate enormous public interest in an instrument previously relatively unknown in the United States.

examples.annotated_text: Intellectual_property: In the context of trademarks, this expansion has been driven by international efforts to harmonise the definition of "trademark", as exemplified by the [dblookup('Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights', 'Ratified In') -> 1994] Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights ratified in 1994, which formalized regulations for [dblookup('Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights', 'Regulate') -> Intellectual Property Rights] IP rights that had been handled by common law, or not at all, in member states. Pursuant to [dblookup('TRIPs', 'Definition of Trademark') -> Any sign capable of distinguishing products or services] TRIPs, any sign which is "capable of distinguishing" the products or services of one business from the products or services of another business is capable of constituting a trademark.
examples.text: Intellectual_property: In the context of trademarks, this expansion has been driven by international efforts to harmonise the definition of "trademark", as exemplified by the Agreement on Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights ratified in 1994, which formalized regulations for IP rights that had been handled by common law, or not at all, in member states. examples.annotated_text: Financial crisis of 2007–08: Rapid increases in a number of commodity prices followed the collapse in the housing bubble. The [dblookup('Price of Oil', 'Increase From 2007 To 2008') -> nearly tripled from $50 to $147] price of oil nearly tripled from $50 to $147 from early 2007 to 2008, before plunging as the financial crisis began to take hold in late 2008. Experts debate the causes, with some attributing it to speculative flow of money from housing and other investments into commodities, some to [dblookup('Financial Crisis of 2007-08', 'Possible Causes') -> monetary policy, scarcity feeling] monetary policy, and some to the increasing feeling of raw materials scarcity in a fast-growing world, leading to long positions taken on those markets, such as Chinese increasing presence in Africa. An increase in oil prices tends to divert a larger share of consumer spending into gasoline, which creates downward pressure on [dblookup('Oil Importing Countries', 'Economic Impact from Oil Price Increase') -> downward pressure on economic growth] economic growth in oil importing countries, as wealth flows to [dblookup('Oil-Producing States', 'Economic Benefit') -> increased wealth flow] oil-producing states. A pattern of spiking instability in the [dblookup('Price of Oil', 'Instability Period') -> decade leading up to 2008] price of oil over the decade leading up to the price high of 2008 has been recently identified. The destabilizing effects of this price variance have been proposed as a contributory factor in the financial crisis.
examples.text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: Rapid increases in a number of commodity prices followed the collapse in the housing bubble. An increase in oil prices tends to divert a larger share of consumer spending into gasoline, which creates downward pressure on economic growth in oil importing countries, as wealth flows to oil-producing states. A pattern of spiking instability in the price of oil over the decade leading up to the price high of 2008 has been recently identified. examples.annotated_text: Anti-aircraft warfare: German air attacks on the British Isles increased in [dblookup('German Air Attacks', 'Increased In') -> 1915] 1915 and the AA efforts were deemed somewhat ineffective, so a Royal Navy gunnery expert, Admiral Sir Percy Scott, was appointed to make improvements, particularly an integrated AA defence for [dblookup('Integrated AA Defence', 'Focus Area') -> London] London. The air defences were expanded with more RNVR AA guns, 75 mm and 3-inch, the pom-poms being ineffective. The naval 3-inch was also adopted by the [dblookup('Royal Army', 'AA Gun Adopted') -> QF 3 inch 20 cwt (76 mm)] army, the QF 3 inch 20 cwt (76 mm), and a new field mounting was introduced in [dblookup('New Field Mounting Introduction', 'Year') -> 1916] 1916. Since most attacks were at night, searchlights were soon used, and acoustic methods of detection and locating were developed. By December 1916 there were [dblookup('AA Defence Sections', 'Number in Britain') -> 183] 183 AA Sections defending Britain (most with the 3-inch), [dblookup('AA Defence Sections', 'Number with BEF in France') -> 74] 74 with the BEF in France and [dblookup('AA Defence Sections', 'Number in the Middle East') -> 10] 10 in the Middle East.
examples.text: Anti-aircraft_warfare: German air attacks on the British Isles increased in 1915 and the AA efforts were deemed somewhat ineffective, so a Royal Navy gunnery expert, Admiral Sir Percy Scott, was appointed to make improvements, particularly an integrated AA defence for London. The air defences were expanded with more RNVR AA guns, 75 mm and 3-inch, the pom-poms being ineffective. The naval 3-inch was also adopted by the army, the QF 3 inch 20 cwt (76 mm), a new field mounting was introduced in 1916. Since most attacks were at night, searchlights were soon used, and acoustic methods of detection and locating were developed. By December 1916 there were 183 AA Sections defending Britain (most with the 3-inch), 74 with the BEF in France and 10 in the Middle East.

examples.annotated_text: Himachal_Pradesh: The history of the area that now constitutes Himachal Pradesh dates back to the time when the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Region', 'Ancient Civilization') -> Indus Valley Civilization] Indus valley civilisation flourished between [dblookup('Indus Valley Civilization', 'Flourished Between') -> 2250 and 1750 BCE] 2250 and 1750 BCE. Tribes such as the Koilis, Halis, Dagis, Dhaugris, Dasa, Khasas, Kinnars, and Kirats inhabited the region from the prehistoric era. During the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Region', 'Political Structure During Vedic Period') -> small republics, Janapada] Vedic period, several small republics known as "Janapada" existed which were later conquered by the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Region', 'Conquered By') -> Gupta Empire] Gupta Empire. After a brief period of supremacy by [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Region', 'Supremacy By') -> King Harshavardhana] King Harshavardhana, the region was once again divided into several local powers headed by chieftains, including some [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Region', 'Political Structure Post Harshavardhana') -> Rajput principalities] Rajput principalities. These kingdoms enjoyed a large degree of independence and were invaded by [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Region', 'Invaded By') -> Delhi Sultanate] Delhi Sultanate a number of times. [dblookup('Kangra', 'Conquered By') -> Mahmud Ghaznavi] Mahmud Ghaznavi conquered Kangra at the beginning of the 10th century. [dblookup('Timur', 'Activities in Himachal Pradesh') -> Marched through lower hills, captured forts] Timur and [dblookup('Sikander Lodi', 'Activities in Himachal Pradesh') -> Marching through lower hills, capturing forts] Sikander Lodi also marched through the lower hills of the state and captured a number of forts and fought many battles. Several hill states [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Hill States', 'Acknowledged Mughal Suzerainty') -> Paid tribute to Mughals] acknowledged Mughal suzerainty and paid regular tribute to the Mughals.
examples.text: Himachal_Pradesh: The history of the area that now constitutes Himachal Pradesh dates back to the time when the Indus valley civilisation flourished between 2250 and 1750 BCE. Tribes such as the Koilis, Halis, Dagis, Dhaugris, Dasa, Khasas, Kinnars, and Kirats inhabited the region from the prehistoric era. During the Vedic period, several small republics known as "Janapada" existed which were later conquered by the Gupta Empire. After a brief period of supremacy by King Harshavardhana, the region was once again divided into several local powers headed by chieftains, including some Rajput principalities. These kingdoms enjoyed a large degree of independence and were invaded by Delhi Sultanate a number of times. Mahmud Ghaznavi conquered Kangra at the beginning of the 10th century. Timur and Sikander Lodi also marched through the lower hills of the state and captured a number of forts and fought many battles. Several hill states acknowledged Mughal suzerainty and paid regular tribute to the Mughals.

examples.annotated_text: Clothing: The world of clothing is always changing, as new cultural influences meet technological innovations. Researchers in scientific labs have been developing prototypes for fabrics that can serve functional purposes well beyond their traditional roles, for example, clothes that can automatically [dblookup('Smart Clothing', 'Functionality') -> adjust temperature, repel bullets, project images, generate electricity] adjust their temperature, repel bullets, project images, and generate electricity. Some practical advances already available to consumers are bullet-resistant garments made with kevlar and [dblookup('Fabrics', 'Coating Feature') -> stain-resistant] stain-resistant fabrics that are coated with chemical mixtures that reduce the absorption of liquids.
examples.text: Clothing: The world of clothing is always changing, as new cultural influences meet technological innovations. Researchers in scientific labs have been developing prototypes for fabrics that can serve functional purposes well beyond their traditional roles, for example, clothes that can automatically adjust their temperature, repel bullets, project images, and generate electricity. Some practical advances already available to consumers are bullet-resistant garments made with kevlar and stain-resistant fabrics that are coated with chemical mixtures that reduce the absorption of liquids.

examples.annotated_text: Avicenna: When [dblookup('Ibn Sina', 'Age When Father Died') -> 22 years old] Ibn Sina was 22 years old, he lost his father. The [dblookup('Samanid Dynasty', 'End Year') -> December 1004] Samanid dynasty came to its end in December 1004. Ibn Sina seems to have declined the offers of [dblookup('Mahmud of Ghazni', 'Offer Status to Ibn Sina') -> declined by Ibn Sina] Mahmud of Ghazni, and proceeded westwards to [dblookup('Ibn Sina', 'Destination Post Declining Offer') -> Urgench] Urgench in modern Turkmenistan, where the vizier, regarded as a friend of scholars, gave him a [dblookup('Ibn Sina', 'Monthly Stipend From Vizier') -> small] small monthly stipend. The pay was small, however, so Ibn Sina wandered from place to place through the districts of Nishapur and Merv to the borders of Khorasan, seeking an opening for his talents. [dblookup('Qabus', 'Title and Region') -> Ruler of Tabaristan] Qabus, the generous ruler of Tabaristan, himself a poet and a scholar, with whom Ibn Sina had expected to find asylum, was on about that date [dblookup('Qabus', 'Death Circumstance') -> starved to death by revolted troops] (1012) starved to death by his troops who had revolted. Ibn Sina himself was at this time stricken by a severe illness. Finally, at Gorgan, near the Caspian Sea, Ibn Sina met with a friend, who bought a dwelling near his own house in which Ibn Sina lectured on logic and astronomy. Several of Ibn Sina's treatises were written for this patron; and the [dblookup('Canon of Medicine', 'Commencement Location') -> Hyrcania] commencement of his Canon of Medicine also dates from his stay in Hyrcania.
examples.text: Avicenna: When Ibn Sina was 22 years old, he lost his father. The Samanid dynasty came to its end in December 1004. Ibn Sina seems to have declined the offers of Mahmud of Ghazni, and proceeded westwards to Urgench in modern Turkmenistan, where the vizier, regarded as a friend of scholars, gave him a small monthly stipend. The pay was small, however, so Ibn Sina wandered from place to place through the districts of Nishapur and Merv to the borders of Khorasan, seeking an opening for his talents. Qabus, the generous ruler of Tabaristan, himself a poet and a scholar, with whom Ibn Sina had expected to find asylum, was on about that date (1012) starved to death by his troops who had revolted. Ibn Sina himself was at this time stricken by a severe illness. Finally, at Gorgan, near the Caspian Sea, Ibn Sina met with a friend, who bought a dwelling near his own house in which Ibn Sina lectured on logic and astronomy. Several of Ibn Sina's treatises were written for this patron; and the commencement of his Canon of Medicine also dates from his stay in Hyrcania.

examples.annotated_text: Roman_Republic: In the process known as the [dblookup('Marian Reforms', 'Initiator') -> Gaius Marius] Marian reforms, Roman consul Gaius Marius carried out a programme of reform of the Roman military. In [dblookup('Marian Reforms', 'Year Implemented') -> 107 BC] 107 BC, all citizens, regardless of their wealth or social class, were made eligible for entry into the Roman army. This move formalised and concluded a gradual process that had been growing for centuries, of removing property requirements for military service. The distinction between the three heavy infantry classes, which had already become blurred, had collapsed into a single class of [dblookup('Roman Military', 'Primary Soldier Class After Marian Reforms') -> heavy legionary infantry] heavy legionary infantry. The heavy infantry legionaries were drawn from citizen stock, while [dblookup('Roman Military', 'Light Infantry Composition') -> non-citizens] non-citizens came to dominate the ranks of the light infantry. The army's higher-level officers and commanders were still drawn exclusively from the [dblookup('Roman Military', 'Source of Higher-Level Officers') -> Roman aristocracy] Roman aristocracy.
examples.text: Roman_Republic: In process known as the Marian reforms, Roman consul Gaius Marius carried out a programme of reform of the Roman military. In 107 BC, all citizens, regardless of their wealth or social class, were made eligible for entry into the Roman army. This move formalised and concluded a gradual process that had been growing for centuries, of removing property requirements for military service. The distinction between the three heavy infantry classes, which had already become blurred, had collapsed into a single class of heavy legionary infantry. The heavy infantry legionaries were drawn from citizen stock, while non-citizens came to dominate the ranks of the light infantry. The army's higher-level officers and commanders were still drawn exclusively from the Roman aristocracy.

examples.annotated_text: Eritrea: Eritrea is a [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> United Nations] member of the United Nations, [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> African Union] the African Union, and is an [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Observer Membership') -> Arab League] observing member of the Arab League. The nation holds a [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Committee Seat') -> United Nations Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions] seat on the United Nations' Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions (ACABQ). Eritrea also holds memberships in the [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> International Bank for Reconstruction and Development] International Bank for Reconstruction and Development, [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> International Finance Corporation] International Finance Corporation, [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> International Criminal Police Organization] International Criminal Police Organization (INTERPOL), [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> Non-Aligned Movement] Non-Aligned Movement, [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons] Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> Permanent Court of Arbitration] Permanent Court of Arbitration, and the [dblookup('Eritrea', 'Membership') -> World Customs Organization] World Customs Organization.
examples.text: Eritrea: Eritrea is a member of the United Nations, the African Union, and is an observing member of the Arab League. The nation holds a seat on the United Nations' Advisory Committee on Administrative and Budgetary Questions (ACABQ). Eritrea also holds memberships in the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development, International Finance Corporation, International Criminal Police Organization (INTERPOL), Non-Aligned Movement, Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, Permanent Court of Arbitration, and the World Customs Organization.

examples.annotated_text: Nintendo_Entertainment_System: Nintendo was accused of [dblookup('Nintendo', 'Accusation') -> antitrust behavior] antitrust behavior because of the strict licensing requirements. The [dblookup('United States Department of Justice', 'Probe Involvement') -> Nintendo] United States Department of Justice and several states began probing Nintendo's business practices, leading to the involvement of [dblookup('Nintendo', 'Investigation By') -> Congress, Federal Trade Commission] Congress and the Federal Trade Commission (FTC). The FTC conducted an [dblookup('Federal Trade Commission', 'Investigation Target') -> Nintendo] extensive investigation which included interviewing hundreds of retailers. During the FTC probe, Nintendo changed the terms of its publisher licensing agreements to eliminate the two-year rule and other restrictive terms. Nintendo and the FTC settled the case in [dblookup('Nintendo', 'Settlement Date With FTC') -> April 1991] April 1991, with Nintendo required to send vouchers giving a $5 discount off to a new game, to every person that had purchased a NES title between [dblookup('Nintendo', 'NES Settlement Eligibility Period') -> June 1988 and December 1990] June 1988 and December 1990. GameSpy remarked that Nintendo's punishment was particularly weak given the case's findings, although it has been speculated that the FTC did not want to damage the video game industry in the United States.
examples.text: Nintendo_Entertainment_System: Nintendo was accused of antitrust behavior because of the strict licensing requirements. The United States Department of Justice and several states began probing Nintendo's business practices, leading to the involvement of Congress and the Federal Trade Commission (FTC). The FTC conducted an extensive investigation which included interviewing hundreds of retailers. During the FTC probe, Nintendo changed the terms of its publisher licensing agreements to eliminate the two-year rule and other restrictive terms. Nintendo and the FTC settled the case in April 1991, with Nintendo required to send vouchers giving a $5 discount off to a new game, to every person that had purchased a NES title between June 1988 and December 1990. GameSpy remarked that Nintendo's punishment was particularly weak giving the case's findings, although it has been speculated that the FTC did not want to damage the video game industry in the United States.

examples.annotated_text: Virgil: Possibly as early as the second century AD, Virgil's works were seen as having magical properties and were used for divination. In what became known as the [dblookup('Sortes Vergilianae', 'Practice Based On') -> Virgil's works] Sortes Vergilianae (Virgilian Lots), passages would be selected at random and interpreted to answer questions. In the [dblookup('Virgil', 'Regarded As Magician Century') -> 12th century] 12th century, starting around [dblookup('Virgil', 'Magician Legend Origin') -> Naples] Naples but eventually spreading widely throughout Europe, a tradition developed in which Virgil was regarded as a great magician. Legends about Virgil and his magical powers remained popular for over [dblookup('Virgil', 'Legend Prominence Duration') -> two hundred years] two hundred years, arguably becoming as prominent as his writings themselves. Virgil's legacy in medieval Wales was such that the [dblookup('Virgil', 'Welsh Name') -> Fferyllt or Pheryllt] Welsh version of his name, Fferyllt or Pheryllt, became a generic term for magic-worker, and survives in the modern Welsh word for pharmacist, fferyllydd.
examples.text: Virgil: Possibly as early as the second century AD, Virgil's works were seen as having magical properties and were used for divination. In what became known as the Sortes Vergilianae (Virgilian Lots), passages would be selected at random and interpreted to answer questions. In the 12th century, starting around Naples but eventually spreading widely throughout Europe, a tradition developed in which Virgil was regarded as a great magician. Legends about Virgil and his magical powers remained popular for over two hundred years, arguably becoming as prominent as his writings themselves. Virgil's legacy in medieval Wales was such that the Welsh version of his name, Fferyllt or Pheryllt, became a generic term for magic-worker, and survives in the modern Welsh word for pharmacist, fferyllydd.
