examples.annotated_text: Solar_energy: Solar concentrating technologies such as parabolic dish, trough, and Scheffler reflectors can provide process heat for commercial and industrial applications. The first commercial system was the [dblookup('Solar Total Energy Project', 'Location') -> Shenandoah, Georgia, USA] Solar Total Energy Project (STEP) in Shenandoah, Georgia, USA where a field of [dblookup('Solar Total Energy Project', 'Parabolic Dishes Quantity') -> 114] 114 parabolic dishes provided 50% of the process heating, air conditioning, and electrical requirements for a clothing factory. This grid-connected cogeneration system provided [dblookup('Solar Total Energy Project', 'Electricity Output') -> 400 kW] 400 kW of electricity plus thermal energy in the form of [dblookup('Solar Total Energy Project', 'Steam Output') -> 401 kW] 401 kW steam and [dblookup('Solar Total Energy Project', 'Chilled Water Output') -> 468 kW] 468 kW chilled water, and had a [dblookup('Solar Total Energy Project', 'Thermal Storage Duration') -> one-hour peak load] one-hour peak load thermal storage. Evaporation ponds are shallow pools that concentrate dissolved solids through evaporation. The use of evaporation ponds to obtain salt from seawater is one of the [dblookup('Evaporation Ponds', 'Historic Application') -> oldest applications of solar energy] oldest applications of solar energy. Modern uses include concentrating brine solutions used in leach mining and removing dissolved solids from waste streams. Clothes lines, clotheshorses, and clothes racks dry clothes through evaporation by wind and sunlight without consuming electricity or gas. In some states of the United States, legislation protects the [dblookup('Right to Dry', 'Protected By Legislation') -> United States] "right to dry" clothes. Unglazed transpired collectors (UTC) are perforated sun-facing walls used for preheating ventilation air. UTCs can raise the incoming air temperature up to [dblookup('Unglazed Transpired Collectors', 'Temperature Increase') -> 22 °C (40 °F)] 22 °C (40 °F) and deliver outlet temperatures of [dblookup('Unglazed Transpired Collectors', 'Outlet Temperature Range') -> 45–60 °C (113–140 °F)] 45–60 °C (113–140 °F). The short payback period of transpired collectors ( 3 to 12 years) makes them a more cost-effective alternative than glazed collection systems. As of 2003, over [dblookup('Unglazed Transpired Collectors', 'Systems Installed Worldwide') -> 80] 80 systems with a [dblookup('Unglazed Transpired Collectors', 'Total Collector Area') -> 35,000 square metres (380,000 sq ft)] combined collector area of 35,000 square metres (380,000 sq ft) had been installed worldwide, including an [dblookup('Unglazed Transpired Collectors', 'Collector Area in Costa Rica') -> 860 m2 (9,300 sq ft)] 860 m2 (9,300 sq ft) collector in Costa Rica used for drying coffee beans and a [dblookup('Unglazed Transpired Collectors', 'Collector Area in India') -> 1,300 m2 (14,000 sq ft)] 1,300 m2 (14,000 sq ft) collector in Coimbatore, India, used for drying marigolds.
examples.text: Solar_energy: Solar concentrating technologies such as parabolic dish, trough and Scheffler reflectors can provide process heat for commercial and industrial applications. The first commercial system was the Solar Total Energy Project (STEP) in Shenandoah, Georgia, USA where a field of 114 parabolic dishes provided 50% of the process heating, air conditioning and electrical requirements for a clothing factory. This grid-connected cogeneration system provided 400 kW of electricity plus thermal energy in the form of 401 kW steam and 468 kW chilled water, and had a one-hour peak load thermal storage. Evaporation ponds are shallow pools that concentrate dissolved solids through evaporation. The use of evaporation ponds to obtain salt from sea water is one of the oldest applications of solar energy. Modern uses include concentrating brine solutions used in leach mining and removing dissolved solids from waste streams. Clothes lines, clotheshorses, and clothes racks dry clothes through evaporation by wind and sunlight without consuming electricity or gas. In some states of the United States legislation protects the "right to dry" clothes. Unglazed transpired collectors (UTC) are perforated sun-facing walls used for preheating ventilation air. UTCs can raise the incoming air temperature up to 22 °C (40 °F) and deliver outlet temperatures of 45–60 °C (113–140 °F). The short payback period of transpired collectors (3 to 12 years) makes them a more cost-effective alternative than glazed collection systems. As of 2003, over 80 systems with a combined collector area of 35,000 square metres (380,000 sq ft) had been installed worldwide, including an 860 m2 (9,300 sq ft) collector in Costa Rica used for drying coffee beans and a 1,300 m2 (14,000 sq ft) collector in Coimbatore, India, used for drying marigolds.

The machine was [dblookup('ENIAC', 'Weight') -> 30 tons] huge, weighing 30 tons, using [dblookup('ENIAC', 'Power Consumption') -> 200 kilowatts] 200 kilowatts of electric power and contained [dblookup('ENIAC', 'Components') -> over 18,000 vacuum tubes, 1,500 relays] over 18,000 vacuum tubes, 1,500 relays, and hundreds of thousands of resistors, capacitors, and inductors.
examples.text: Computer: It combined the high speed of electronics with the ability to be programmed for many complex problems. It could add or subtract 5000 times a second, a thousand times faster than any other machine. It also had modules to multiply, divide, and square root. High speed memory was limited to 20 words (about 80 bytes). Built under the direction of John Mauchly and J. Presper Eckert at the University of Pennsylvania, ENIAC's development and construction lasted from 1943 to full operation at the end of 1945. The machine was huge, weighing 30 tons, using 200 kilowatts of electric power and contained over 18,000 vacuum tubes, 1,500 relays, and hundreds of thousands of resistors, capacitors, and inductors.

examples.annotated_text: Sumer: The Semitic [dblookup('Akkadian language', 'First Attested') -> c. 2800 BC] Akkadian language is first attested in [dblookup('Akkadian language', 'First Appearance In') -> names of the kings of Kish] proper names of the kings of Kish c. 2800 BC, preserved in later king lists. There are texts written entirely in [dblookup('Old Akkadian', 'Earliest Texts Date') -> c. 2500 BC] Old Akkadian dating from c. 2500 BC. Use of Old Akkadian was at its peak during [dblookup('Sargon the Great', 'Reign Period') -> c. 2270–2215 BC] the rule of Sargon the Great (c. 2270–2215 BC), but even then most administrative tablets continued to be written in Sumerian, the language used by the scribes. Gelb and Westenholz differentiate three stages of Old Akkadian: that of the pre-Sargonic era, that of the Akkadian empire, and that of the "Neo-Sumerian Renaissance" that followed it. Akkadian and Sumerian coexisted as vernacular languages for about [dblookup('Akkadian and Sumerian', 'Coexistence Period') -> one thousand years] one thousand years, but by around [dblookup('Sumerian Language', 'Literary Language Transition Period') -> c. 1800 BC] 1800 BC, Sumerian was becoming more of a literary language familiar mainly only to scholars and scribes. [dblookup('Thorkild Jacobsen', 'Argument On Continuity') -> Little break between pre- and post-Sargon periods] Thorkild Jacobsen has argued that there is little break in historical continuity between the pre- and post-Sargon periods, and that too much emphasis has been placed on the perception of a "Semitic vs. Sumerian" conflict. However, it is certain that [dblookup('Akkadian Language', 'Imposed On') -> parts of Elam] Akkadian was also briefly imposed on neighboring parts of Elam that were previously conquered by Sargon.
examples.text: Sumer: The Semitic Akkadian language is first attested in proper names of the kings of Kish c. 2800 BC, preserved in later king lists. There are texts written entirely in Old Akkadian dating from c. 2500 BC. Use of Old Akkadian was at its peak during the rule of Sargon the Great (c. 2270–2215 BC), but even then most administrative tablets continued to be written in Sumerian, the language used by the scribes. Gelb and Westenholz differentiate three stages of Old Akkadian: that of the pre-Sargonic era, that of the Akkadian empire, and that of the "Neo-Sumerian Renaissance" that followed it. Akkadian and Sumerian coexisted as vernacular languages for about one thousand years, but by around 1800 BC, Sumerian was becoming more of a literary language familiar mainly only to scholars and scribes. Thorkild Jacobsen has argued that there is little break in historical continuity between the pre- and post-Sargon periods, and that too much emphasis has been placed on the perception of a "Semitic vs. Sumerian" conflict. However, it is certain that Akkadian was also briefly imposed on neighboring parts of Elam that were previously conquered by Sargon.

examples.annotated_text: Textual_criticism: In the English language, the works of [dblookup('William Shakespeare', 'Subject Of') -> Textual Criticism] Shakespeare have been a particularly fertile ground for textual criticism—both because the texts, as transmitted, contain a considerable amount of variation, and because the effort and expense of producing superior editions of his works have always been widely viewed as worthwhile. The principles of textual criticism, although originally developed and refined for works of [dblookup('Textual Criticism', 'Originally Developed For') -> Antiquity, the Bible, Shakespeare] antiquity, the Bible, and Shakespeare, have been applied to many works, extending backwards from the present to the earliest known written documents, in [dblookup('Earliest Known Written Documents', 'Origins') -> Mesopotamia, Egypt] Mesopotamia and Egypt—a period of about five millennia. However, the application of textual criticism to non-religious works does not antedate [dblookup('Non-Religious Textual Criticism', 'Historical Milestone') -> Invention of Printing] the invention of printing. While Christianity has been relatively receptive to textual criticism, application of it to the Jewish ( Masoretic) Torah and the [dblookup('Qur'an', 'Perception By Devout') -> Taboo for Textual Criticism] Qur'an is, to the devout, taboo.
examples.text: Textual_criticism: In the English language, the works of Shakespeare have been a particularly fertile ground for textual criticism—both because the texts, as transmitted, contain a considerable amount of variation, and because the effort and expense of producing superior editions of his works have always been widely viewed as worthwhile. The principles of textual criticism, although originally developed and refined for works of antiquity, the Bible, and Shakespeare, have been applied to many works, extending backwards from the present to the earliest known written documents, in Mesopotamia and Egypt—a period of about five millennia. However, the application of textual criticism to non-religious works does not antedate the invention of printing. While Christianity has been relatively receptive to textual criticism, application of it to the Jewish (Masoretic) Torah and the Qur'an is, to the devout, taboo.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Freemasonry: Relations between Grand Lodges are determined by the concept of Recognition. Each [dblookup('Freemasonry', 'List Maintained By Grand Lodge') -> Recognised Grand Lodges] Grand Lodge maintains a list of other Grand Lodges that it recognises. When two Grand Lodges recognise and are in Masonic communication with each other, they are said to be in amity, and the brethren of each may visit each other's Lodges and interact Masonically. When two Grand Lodges are not in amity, [dblookup('Grand Lodge Interaction Policy', 'Effect of Non-Amity') -> Inter-visitation Restriction] inter-visitation is not allowed. There are many reasons why one Grand Lodge will withhold or withdraw recognition from another, but the two most common are [dblookup('Grand Lodge Recognition Issue', 'Common Reasons for Withholding Recognition') -> Exclusive Jurisdiction, Regularity] Exclusive Jurisdiction and Regularity.
examples.text: Freemasonry: Relations between Grand Lodges are determined by the concept of Recognition. Each Grand Lodge maintains a list of other Grand Lodges that it recognises. When two Grand Lodges recognise and are in Masonic communication with each other, they are said to be in amity, and the brethren of each may visit each other's Lodges and interact Masonically. When two Grand Lodges are not in amity, inter-visitation is not allowed. There are many reasons why one Grand Lodge will withhold or withdraw recognition from another, but the two most common are Exclusive Jurisdiction and Regularity.

examples.annotated_text: BeiDou_Navigation_Satellite_System: Unlike the American GPS, Russian GLONASS, and European Galileo systems [dblookup('Galileo', 'Orbit Type') -> medium Earth orbit], which use medium Earth orbit satellites, [dblookup('BeiDou-1', 'Orbit Type') -> geostationary orbit] BeiDou-1 uses satellites in geostationary orbit. This means that the system does not require a large constellation of satellites, but it also limits the coverage to areas on Earth where the satellites are visible. The area that can be serviced is from [dblookup('BeiDou-1', 'Coverage Longitude Range') -> 70°E to 140°E] longitude 70°E to 140°E and from [dblookup('BeiDou-1', 'Coverage Latitude Range') -> 5°N to 55°N] latitude 5°N to 55°N. A [dblookup('BeiDou-1', 'Frequency') -> 2491.75 MHz] frequency of the system is 2491.75 MHz.
examples.text: BeiDou_Navigation_Satellite_System: Unlike the American GPS, Russian GLONASS, and European Galileo systems, which use medium Earth orbit satellites, BeiDou-1 uses satellites in geostationary orbit. This means that the system does not require a large constellation of satellites, but it also limits the coverage to areas on Earth where the satellites are visible. The area that can be serviced is from longitude 70°E to 140°E and from latitude 5°N to 55°N. A frequency of the system is 2491.75 MHz.

examples.annotated_text: Pain: A number of meta-analyses have found clinical hypnosis to be effective in controlling pain associated with diagnostic and surgical procedures in both adults and children, as well as [dblookup('Clinical Hypnosis', 'Effectiveness For') -> pain associated with cancer and childbirth] pain associated with cancer and childbirth. The authors concluded that "although the findings provide support for the general applicability of hypnosis in the treatment of chronic pain, considerably more research will be needed to fully determine the effects of hypnosis for different chronic-pain conditions."

examples.annotated_text: Microsoft faced criticism particularly from free software supporters for mandating that devices receiving its optional certification for Windows 8 have secure boot enabled by default using a key provided by Microsoft. Concerns were raised that secure boot could prevent or hinder the use of alternate operating systems such as Linux. In a post discussing secure boot on the [dblookup('Building Windows 8 Blog', 'Author') -> Tony Mangefeste] Building Windows 8 blog, Microsoft developer Tony Mangefeste indicated that vendors would provide means to customize secure boot, stating that "At the end of the day, the customer is in control of their PC. Microsoft's philosophy is to provide customers with the best experience first, and allow them to make decisions themselves." Microsoft's certification guidelines for Windows 8 ultimately revealed that [dblookup('Windows 8 Certification Guidelines', 'Vendor Requirement') -> Vendors must provide re-configuration or disablement of secure boot in UEFI firmware] vendors would be required to provide means for users to re-configure or disable secure boot in their device's UEFI firmware. It also revealed that [dblookup('ARM Devices (Windows RT)', 'Secure Boot Mandate') -> Permanently enabled secure boot] ARM devices (Windows RT) would be required to have secure boot permanently enabled, with no way for users to disable it. However, Tom Warren of The Verge noted that other vendors have implemented similar hardware restrictions on their own ARM-based tablet and smartphone products (including those running Microsoft's own Windows Phone platform), but still argued that Microsoft should "keep a consistent approach across ARM and x86, though, not least because of the number of users who'd love to run Android alongside Windows 8 on their future tablets." [dblookup('Windows 8 Certification Guidelines', 'Third-Party Certificate Requirement') -> No mandate] No mandate is made regarding the installation of third-party certificates that would enable running alternative programs.
examples.text: Windows_8: Following the unveiling of Windows 8, Microsoft faced criticism (particularly from free software supporters) for mandating that devices receiving its optional certification for Windows 8 have secure boot enabled by default using a key provided by Microsoft. In a post discussing secure boot on the Building Windows 8 blog, Microsoft developer Tony Mangefeste indicated that vendors would provide means to customize secure boot, stating that "At the end of the day, the customer is in control of their PC. Microsoft's philosophy is to provide customers with the best experience first, and allow them to make decisions themselves." Microsoft's certification guidelines for Windows 8 ultimately revealed that vendors would be required to provide means for users to re-configure or disable secure boot in their device's UEFI firmware. It also revealed that ARM devices (Windows RT) would be required to have secure boot permanently enabled, with no way for users to disable it. However, Tom Warren of The Verge noted that other vendors have implemented similar hardware restrictions on their own ARM-based tablet and smartphone products (including those running Microsoft's own Windows Phone platform), but still argued that Microsoft should "keep a consistent approach across ARM and x86, though, not least because of the number of users who'd love to run Android alongside Windows 8 on their future tablets." No mandate is made regarding the installation of third-party certificates that would enable running alternative programs.

examples.annotated_text: Asphalt: Because of the difficulty of moving crude bitumen through pipelines, non-upgraded bitumen is usually diluted with natural-gas condensate in a form called [dblookup('Non-Upgraded Bitumen', 'Dilution With') -> dilbit] dilbit or with synthetic crude oil, called [dblookup('Non-Upgraded Bitumen', 'Dilution With') -> synbit] synbit. However, to meet international competition, much non-upgraded bitumen is now sold as a blend of multiple grades of bitumen, conventional crude oil, synthetic crude oil, and condensate in a standardized benchmark product such as Western Canadian Select. This sour, heavy crude oil blend is designed to have uniform refining characteristics to compete with internationally marketed heavy oils such as [dblookup('International Heavy Oils', 'Comparable Product 1') -> Mexican Mayan] Mexican Mayan or [dblookup('International Heavy Oils', 'Comparable Product 2') -> Arabian Dubai Crude] Arabian Dubai Crude.

examples.annotated_text: Crucifixion_of_Jesus: In his book [dblookup('The Crucifixion of Jesus', 'Author') -> Frederick Zugibe] The Crucifixion of Jesus, physician and forensic pathologist [dblookup('Frederick Zugibe', 'Occupation') -> physician, forensic pathologist] Frederick Zugibe studied the likely circumstances of the death of Jesus in great detail. examples.annotated_text: Unicode: Characters with diacritical marks can generally be represented either as a [dblookup('Characters with Diacritical Marks', 'Representation Options') -> precomposed character, decomposed sequence] single precomposed character or as a decomposed sequence of a base letter plus one or more non-spacing marks. For example, ḗ (precomposed e with macron and acute above) and ḗ (e followed by the combining macron above and combining acute above) should be rendered identically, both appearing as an e with a macron and acute accent, but in practice, their appearance may vary depending upon what rendering engine and fonts are being used to display the characters. Similarly, underdots, as needed in the romanization of Indic, will often be placed incorrectly[citation needed]. Unicode characters that map to [dblookup('Unicode Characters', 'Precomposed Glyphs Usage') -> many cases] precomposed glyphs can be used in many cases, thus avoiding the problem, but where no precomposed character has been encoded[,] the problem can often be solved by using a specialist Unicode font such as [dblookup('Charis SIL', 'Used For') -> solving rendering issues] Charis SIL that uses Graphite, OpenType, or AAT technologies for advanced rendering features.
examples.text: Unicode: Characters with diacritical marks can generally be represented either as a single precomposed character or as a decomposed sequence of a base letter plus one or more non-spacing marks. For example, ḗ (precomposed e with macron and acute above) and ḗ (e followed by the combining macron above and combining acute above) should be rendered identically, both appearing as an e with a macron and acute accent, but in practice, their appearance may vary depending upon what rendering engine and fonts are being used to display the characters. Similarly, underdots, as needed in the romanization of Indic, will often be placed incorrectly[citation needed]. Unicode characters that map to precomposed glyphs can be used in many cases, thus avoiding the problem, but where no precomposed character has been encoded the problem can often be solved by using a specialist Unicode font such as Charis SIL that uses Graphite, OpenType, or AAT technologies for advanced rendering features.

examples.annotated_text: Hokkien: While most Hokkien morphemes have standard designated characters, they are not always etymological or phono-semantic. Similar-sounding, similar-meaning or rare characters are commonly borrowed or substituted to represent a particular morpheme. Examples include "beautiful" ([dblookup('Beautiful', 'Vernacular Morpheme') -> suí] 美 bí is the literary form), whose vernacular morpheme suí is represented by characters like 媠 (an obsolete character), 婎 (a vernacular reading of this character) and even 水 (transliteration of the sound suí), or "tall" ([dblookup('Tall', 'Literary Form') -> 高] ko is the literary form), whose morpheme kôan is 懸. Common grammatical particles are not exempt; the negation particle m̄ ([dblookup('Negation Particle', 'Representations') -> 毋, 呣, 唔] not) is variously represented by 毋, 呣 or 唔, among others. In other cases, characters are invented to represent a particular morpheme (a common example is the character 𪜶 in, which represents the personal pronoun [dblookup('𪜶', 'Representation') -> "they"] "they"). In addition, some characters have multiple and unrelated pronunciations, adapted to represent Hokkien words. For example, the Hokkien word bah ("meat") has been reduced to the character [dblookup('Meat', 'Character') -> 肉] 肉, which has etymologically unrelated colloquial and literary readings ([dblookup('肉', 'Colloquial Reading') -> he̍k], [dblookup('肉', 'Literary Reading') -> jio̍k] he̍k and jio̍k, respectively). Another case is the word 'to eat,' chia̍h, which is often transcribed in Taiwanese newspapers and media as [dblookup('To Eat', 'Media Transcription Character') -> 呷] 呷 (a Mandarin transliteration, xiā, to approximate the Hokkien term), even though its recommended character in dictionaries is [dblookup('To Eat', 'Dictionary Recommended Character') -> 食] 食.

examples.annotated_text: Madrasa: In 2004, madaris were mainstreamed in 16 Regions nationwide, primarily in Muslim-majority areas in Mindanao under the auspices of the [dblookup('Department of Education (Philippines)', 'Program Sponsor') -> Madaris Mainstreaming] Department of Education (DepEd). While there are state-recognised Islamic schools, such as [dblookup('Ibn Siena Integrated School', 'Location') -> Islamic City of Marawi] Ibn Siena Integrated School in the Islamic City of Marawi, Sarang Bangun LC in Zamboanga and SMIE in Jolo, their Islamic studies programmes initially varied in application and content.

examples.annotated_text: Frédéric Chopin: On 3 December, Chopin complained about his bad health and the incompetence of the doctors in Majorca: "Three doctors have visited me ... The first said I was dead; the second said I was dying; and the third said I was about to die." He also had problems having his [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Piano Type') -> Pleyel piano] Pleyel piano sent to him. It finally arrived from [dblookup('Pleyel Piano', 'Shipment Origin') -> Paris] Paris in December. Chopin wrote to [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Correspondence Recipient') -> Pleyel] Pleyel in [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Preludes Opus Completion Date') -> January 1839] January 1839: "I am sending you my Preludes [(Op. 28)]. I finished them on your little piano, which arrived in the best possible condition in spite of the sea, the bad weather and the Palma customs." Chopin was also able to undertake work on his [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Composition Work') -> Ballade No. 2, Op. 38; two Polonaises, Op. 40; Scherzo No. 3, Op. 39] Ballade No. 2, Op. 38; two Polonaises, Op. 40; and the Scherzo No. 3, Op. 39.
examples.text: Frédéric_Chopin: On 3 December, Chopin complained about his bad health and the incompetence of the doctors in Majorca: "Three doctors have visited me ... The first said I was dead; the second said I was dying; and the third said I was about to die." He also had problems having his Pleyel piano sent to him. It finally arrived from Paris in December. Chopin wrote to Pleyel in January 1839: "I am sending you my Preludes [(Op. 28)]. I finished them on your little piano, which arrived in the best possible condition in spite of the sea, the bad weather and the Palma customs." Chopin was also able to undertake work on his Ballade No. 2, Op. 38; two Polonaises, Op. 40; and the Scherzo No. 3, Op. 39.

examples.text: Sino-Tibetan_relations_during_the_Ming_dynasty: Throughout the following month, the Yongle Emperor and his court showered the Karmapa with presents. examples.annotated_text: Qing_dynasty: The reign of the [dblookup('Qianlong Emperor', 'Reign Period') -> 1735–1796] Qianlong Emperor (1735–1796) saw the apogee and initial decline in prosperity and imperial control. The population [dblookup('Qing Dynasty', 'Population During Qianlong Reign') -> 400 million] rose to some 400 million, but taxes and government revenues were fixed at a low rate, virtually guaranteeing eventual fiscal crisis. Corruption set in, rebels tested government legitimacy, and ruling elites did not change their mindsets in the face of changes in the world system. Following the Opium War, European powers imposed unequal treaties, free trade, extraterritoriality, and treaty ports under foreign control. The [dblookup('Taiping Rebellion', 'Duration') -> 1850–64] Taiping Rebellion (1850–64) and [dblookup('Dungan Revolt', 'Duration') -> 1862–77] Dungan Revolt (1862–77) in Central Asia led to the [dblookup('Taiping Rebellion and Dungan Revolt', 'Casualties') -> 20 million] deaths of some 20 million people. In spite of these disasters, in the [dblookup('Tongzhi Restoration', 'Period') -> 1860s] Tongzhi Restoration of the 1860s, Han Chinese elites rallied to the defense of the Confucian order and the Qing rulers. The initial gains in the [dblookup('Self-Strengthening Movement', 'Impact on Qing Dynasty') -> destroyed in First Sino-Japanese War] Self-Strengthening Movement were destroyed in the [dblookup('First Sino-Japanese War', 'Outcome for Qing Dynasty') -> lost influence over Korea and possession of Taiwan] First Sino-Japanese War of 1895, in which the Qing lost its influence over Korea and the possession of Taiwan. New Armies were organized, but the ambitious [dblookup('Hundred Days\' Reform', 'Year') -> 1898] Hundred Days' Reform of 1898 was turned back by [dblookup('Empress Dowager Cixi', 'Role in Hundred Days\' Reform') -> reversed the reforms] Empress Dowager Cixi, a ruthless but capable leader. When, in response to the violently anti-foreign Yihetuan ("Boxers"), foreign powers invaded China, the [dblookup('Empress Dowager Cixi', 'Response to Boxer Rebellion') -> declared war on foreign powers] Empress Dowager declared war on them, leading to [dblookup('Boxer Rebellion', 'Consequences for Qing Dynasty') -> defeat and flight of Imperial Court to Xi'an] defeat and the flight of the Imperial Court to Xi'an.
examples.text: Qing_dynasty: The reign of the Qianlong Emperor (1735–1796) saw the apogee and initial decline in prosperity and imperial control. The population rose to some 400 million, but taxes and government revenues were fixed at a low rate, virtually guaranteeing eventual fiscal crisis. Corruption set in, rebels tested government legitimacy, and ruling elites did not change their mindsets in the face of changes in the world system. Following the Opium War, European powers imposed unequal treaties, free trade, extraterritoriality and treaty ports under foreign control. The Taiping Rebellion (1850–64) and Dungan Revolt (1862–77) in Central Asia led to the deaths of some 20 million people. In spite of these disasters, in the Tongzhi Restoration of the 1860s, Han Chinese elites rallied to the defense of the Confucian order and the Qing rulers. The initial gains in the Self-Strengthening Movement were destroyed in the First Sino-Japanese War of 1895, in which the Qing lost its influence over Korea and the possession of Taiwan. New Armies were organized, but the ambitious Hundred Days' Reform of 1898 was turned back by Empress Dowager Cixi, a ruthless but capable leader. When, in response to the violently anti-foreign Yihetuan ("Boxers"), foreign powers invaded China, the Empress Dowager declared war on them, leading to defeat and the flight of the Imperial Court to Xi'an.

examples.text: Biodiversity: The term biological diversity was used first by wildlife scientist and conservationist Raymond F. examples.annotated_text: Tuberculosis: A number of medications are being studied for multi drug resistant tuberculosis including: [dblookup('Multi Drug Resistant Tuberculosis', 'Medications Studied') -> bedaquiline, delamanid] bedaquiline and delamanid. examples.annotated_text: Race_(human_categorization): One crucial innovation in reconceptualizing genotypic and phenotypic variation was the [dblookup('C. Loring Brace', 'Field') -> Anthropology] anthropologist C. Loring Brace's observation that such variations, insofar as it is affected by natural selection, slow migration, or genetic drift, are distributed along geographic gradations or clines. In part, this is due to isolation by distance. This point called attention to a problem common to phenotype-based descriptions of races (for example, those based on hair texture and skin color): they ignore a host of other similarities and differences (for example, blood type) that do not correlate highly with the markers for race. Thus, [dblookup('Frank Livingstone', 'Conclusion on Race') -> "there are no races, only clines"] anthropologist Frank Livingstone's conclusion, that since clines cross racial boundaries, "there are no races, only clines".

examples.annotated_text: Predation: Mimicry is a related phenomenon where an organism has a similar appearance to another species. One such example is the drone fly, which looks a lot like a bee, yet is completely harmless as it cannot sting at all. Another example of batesian mimicry is the [dblookup('Io Moth', 'Scientific Name') -> Automeris io] io moth, ( Automeris io), which has markings on its wings that resemble an owl's eyes. When an insectivorous predator disturbs the moth, it reveals its hind wings, temporarily startling the predator and giving it time to escape. Predators may also use mimicry to lure their prey, however. Female fireflies of the genus Photuris, for example, copy the light signals of other species, thereby attracting male fireflies, which are then captured and eaten.

examples.annotated_text: Hydrogen: Hydrogen is the only element that has different names for its isotopes in common use today. The symbols D and T (instead of [dblookup('Deuterium', 'Symbol Alternatives') -> D, 2H] 2H and [dblookup('Tritium', 'Symbol Alternatives') -> T, 3H] 3H) are sometimes used for deuterium and tritium, but the corresponding symbol for protium, P, is already in use for phosphorus and thus is not available for protium. In its nomenclatural guidelines, the [dblookup('International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry', 'Guidance On Isotope Naming') -> Allows D, T, 2H, 3H] International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry allows any of D, T, 2H, and 3H to be used, although 2H and 3H are preferred.

Along the walls there were few doors to access and exit the city, suggesting that [dblookup('Palermo', 'Trade Activity') -> frequent trade] trade even toward the inner part of the island occurred frequently. examples.annotated_text: Separation_of_church_and_state_in_the_United_States: The [dblookup('First Amendment to the United States Constitution', 'Clause') -> Establishment Clause, Free Exercise Clause] first amendment to the US Constitution states "Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof" The two parts, known as the "establishment clause" and the "free exercise clause" respectively, form the textual basis for the [dblookup('Separation of Church and State Doctrine', 'Interpretation By') -> Supreme Court of the United States] Supreme Court's interpretations of the "separation of church and state" doctrine. Three central concepts were derived from the 1st Amendment which became America's doctrine for church-state separation: [dblookup('America\'s Doctrine for Church-State Separation', 'Concepts') -> no coercion in religious matters, no expectation to support a religion against one's will, religious liberty encompasses all religions] no coercion in religious matters, no expectation to support a religion against one's will, and religious liberty encompasses all religions. Approximately 51 percent of the graduates in BYU's class of 2005 were married. This is compared to a national marriage average among college graduates of 11 percent. BYU students on average marry at the age of 22, according to a 2005 study, while the national average age is 25 years for men and 27 years for women.

Most target bacterial functions or growth processes. Those that target the [dblookup('Penicillins', 'Target') -> bacterial cell wall] bacterial cell wall (penicillins and cephalosporins) or the [dblookup('Polymyxins', 'Target') -> cell membrane] cell membrane (polymyxins), or interfere with essential [dblookup('Rifamycins', 'Target') -> bacterial enzymes] bacterial enzymes (rifamycins, lipiarmycins, quinolones, and sulfonamides) have [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Activity Type') -> bactericidal] bactericidal activities. Those that target [dblookup('Macrolides', 'Target') -> protein synthesis] protein synthesis (macrolides, lincosamides, and tetracyclines) are usually [dblookup('Macrolides', 'Activity Type') -> bacteriostatic] bacteriostatic (with the exception of [dblookup('Aminoglycosides', 'Activity Type') -> bactericidal] bactericidal aminoglycosides). Further categorization is based on their [dblookup('Antibacterial Antibiotics', 'Target Specificity') -> target specificity] target specificity. "Narrow-spectrum" antibacterial antibiotics target [dblookup('Narrow-spectrum Antibiotics', 'Target') -> specific types of bacteria] specific types of bacteria, such as Gram-negative or Gram-positive bacteria, whereas [dblookup('Broad-spectrum Antibiotics', 'Effect') -> wide range of bacteria] broad-spectrum antibiotics affect a wide range of bacteria. Following a 40-year hiatus in [dblookup('Antibacterial Antibiotics', 'New Classes Discovered') -> late 2000s and early 2010s] discovering new classes of antibacterial compounds, four new classes of antibacterial antibiotics have been brought into clinical use in the late 2000s and early 2010s: [dblookup('Cyclic Lipopeptides', 'Example') -> daptomycin] cyclic lipopeptides (such as daptomycin), [dblookup('Glycylcyclines', 'Example') -> tigecycline] glycylcyclines (such as tigecycline), [dblookup('Oxazolidinones', 'Example') -> linezolid] oxazolidinones (such as linezolid), and [dblookup('Lipiarmycins', 'Example') -> fidaxomicin] lipiarmycins (such as fidaxomicin).
examples.text: Antibiotics: Antibacterial antibiotics are commonly classified based on their mechanism of action, chemical structure, or spectrum of activity. Most target bacterial functions or growth processes. Those that target the bacterial cell wall (penicillins and cephalosporins) or the cell membrane (polymyxins), or interfere with essential bacterial enzymes (rifamycins, lipiarmycins, quinolones, and sulfonamides) have bactericidal activities. Those that target protein synthesis (macrolides, lincosamides and tetracyclines) are usually bacteriostatic (with the exception of bactericidal aminoglycosides). Further categorization is based on their target specificity. "Narrow-spectrum" antibacterial antibiotics target specific types of bacteria, such as Gram-negative or Gram-positive bacteria, whereas broad-spectrum antibiotics affect a wide range of bacteria. Following a 40-year hiatus in discovering new classes of antibacterial compounds, four new classes of antibacterial antibiotics have been brought into clinical use in the late 2000s and early 2010s: cyclic lipopeptides (such as daptomycin), glycylcyclines (such as tigecycline), oxazolidinones (such as linezolid), and lipiarmycins (such as fidaxomicin).

examples.annotated_text: Molotov%E2%80%93Ribbentrop_Pact: The Finnish and Baltic invasions began a deterioration of [dblookup('Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact', 'Effect On Relations Between Soviets and Germany') -> deterioration] relations between the Soviets and Germany. Stalin's invasions were a severe irritant to Berlin, as the intent to accomplish these was not communicated to the Germans beforehand, and prompted concern that Stalin was seeking to form an anti-German bloc. Molotov's reassurances to the Germans, and the Germans' mistrust, intensified. On [dblookup('Soviet Invasion of Lithuania', 'Date') -> June 16] June 16, as the Soviets invaded Lithuania, but before they had invaded Latvia and Estonia, [dblookup('Joachim von Ribbentrop', 'Action') -> instructed staff to report on Baltic States'] Ribbentrop instructed his staff "to submit a report as soon as possible as to whether in the Baltic States a tendency to seek support from the Reich can be observed or whether an attempt was made to form a bloc."

On June 16, as the Soviets invaded Lithuania, but before they had invaded Latvia and Estonia, Ribbentrop instructed his staff "to submit a report as soon as possible as to whether in the Baltic States a tendency to seek support from the Reich can be observed or whether an attempt was made to form a bloc."

examples.annotated_text: Sahara: The average annual rainfall ranges from very low in the northern and southern fringes of the [dblookup('Sahara', 'Geographic Feature') -> desert] desert to nearly non-existent over the central and eastern parts. The thin northern fringe of the desert receives more winter cloudiness and rainfall due to the arrival of low pressure systems over the Mediterranean Sea along the polar front, although very attenuated by the rain shadow effects of the mountains and the annual [dblookup('Northern Sahara Fringe', 'Annual Average Rainfall Range') -> 100 mm to 250 mm] average rainfall ranges from 100 mm to 250 mm. For example, [dblookup('Biskra', 'Located In') -> Algeria] Biskra, Algeria and [dblookup('Ouarzazate', 'Located In') -> Morocco] Ouarzazate, Morocco are found in this zone. The southern fringe of the desert along the border with the [dblookup('Sahel', 'Border With') -> Sahara] Sahel receives summer cloudiness and rainfall due to the arrival of the Intertropical Convergence Zone from the south, and the annual [dblookup('Southern Sahara Fringe', 'Annual Average Rainfall Range') -> 100 mm to 250 mm] average rainfall ranges from 100 mm to 250 mm. For example, [dblookup('Timbuktu', 'Located In') -> Mali] Timbuktu, Mali and [dblookup('Agadez', 'Located In') -> Niger] Agadez, Niger are found in this zone. The vast central hyper-arid core of the desert is virtually never affected by northerly or southerly atmospheric disturbances and permanently remains under the influence of the strongest anticyclonic weather regime. The annual [dblookup('Central Sahara Core', 'Annual Average Rainfall') -> less than 1 mm] average rainfall can drop to less than 1 mm. In fact, most of the Sahara receives less than [dblookup('Sahara', 'Average Rainfall') -> 20 mm] 20 mm. Of the 9,000,000 km² of desert land in the Sahara, an area of about 2,800,000 km² (about [dblookup('Sahara', 'Area Receiving 10 mm Rainfall Or Less') -> 31%] 31% of the total area) receives an annual average rainfall amount of 10 mm or less, while some 1,500,000 km² (about [dblookup('Sahara', 'Area Receiving 5 mm Rainfall Or Less') -> 17%] 17% of the total area) receive an average of 5 mm or less. The annual average rainfall is virtually zero over a wide area of some 1,000,000 km² in the eastern Sahara comprising deserts of [dblookup('Eastern Sahara', 'Countries Comprising') -> Libya, Egypt, Sudan] Libya, Egypt, and Sudan (Tazirbu, Kufra, Dakhla, Kharga, Farafra, Siwa, Asyut, Sohag, Luxor, Aswan, Abu Simbel, Wadi Halfa) where the long-term mean approximates [dblookup('Eastern Sahara', 'Annual Average Rainfall') -> 0.5 mm] 0.5 mm per year. The rainfall is very unreliable and erratic in the Sahara as it may vary considerably year by year. In full contrast to the negligible annual rainfall amounts, the annual rates of potential [dblookup('Sahara', 'Annual Evaporation Rate') -> 2,500 mm/year to more than 6,000 mm/year] evaporation are extraordinarily high, roughly ranging from 2,500 mm/year to more than 6,000 mm/year in the whole desert. Nowhere else on Earth has air been found as dry and evaporative as in the Sahara region. With such [dblookup('Sahara', 'Evaporative Power') -> high] an evaporative power, the Sahara can only be desiccated and dried out further and the moisture deficit is tremendous.

examples.annotated_text: University_of_Notre_Dame: Notre Dame teams are known as [dblookup('University_of_Notre_Dame', 'Team Nickname') -> Fighting Irish] the Fighting Irish. examples.annotated_text: Miami: Miami is a [dblookup('Miami', 'Location') -> Atlantic coast, southeastern Florida] city located on the Atlantic coast in southeastern Florida and the [dblookup('Miami', 'County Seat Of') -> Miami-Dade County] seat of Miami-Dade County. The 44th-most populated city proper in the United States, with a [dblookup('Miami', 'City Population') -> 430,332] population of 430,332, it is the principal, central, and most populous city of the Miami metropolitan area, and the second most populous metropolis in the Southeastern United States after [dblookup('Southeastern United States', 'Most Populous Metropolis') -> Washington, D.C.] Washington, D.C. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, Miami's metro area is the [dblookup('Miami Metropolitan Area', 'Population Rank US') -> Eighth] eighth-most populous and [dblookup('Miami Metropolitan Area', 'Urban Area Rank US') -> Fourth] fourth-largest urban area in the United States, with a [dblookup('Miami Metropolitan Area', 'Population Estimate') -> 5.5 million] population of around 5.5 million.
examples.text: Miami: Miami (/maɪˈæmi/; Spanish pronunciation: [maiˈami]) is a city located on the Atlantic coast in southeastern Florida and the seat of Miami-Dade County. The 44th-most populated city proper in the United States, with a population of 430,332, it is the principal, central, and most populous city of the Miami metropolitan area, and the second most populous metropolis in the Southeastern United States after Washington, D.C. According to the U.S. Census Bureau, Miami's metro area is the eighth-most populous and fourth-largest urban area in the United States, with a population of around 5.5 million.

examples.annotated_text: Mammal: The deliberate or accidental hybridising of two or more species of closely related animals through captive breeding is a human activity which has been in existence for [dblookup('Human Captive Breeding', 'Existence Duration') -> millennia] millennia and has grown in recent times for economic purposes. The number of successful interspecific [dblookup('Interspecific Mammalian Hybrids', 'Number') -> relatively small] mammalian hybrids is relatively small, although it has come to be known that there is a significant number of naturally occurring hybrids between forms or regional varieties of a single species. These may form zones of gradation known as clines. Indeed, the distinction between some hitherto distinct species can become clouded once it can be shown that they may not only breed but produce fertile offspring. Some hybrid animals exhibit greater strength and resilience than either parent. This is known as [dblookup('Hybrid Animals', 'Phenomenon of Greater Strength') -> hybrid vigor] hybrid vigor. The existence of the [dblookup('Mule', 'Parentage') -> donkey sire; horse dam] mule (donkey sire; horse dam) being used widely as a hardy draught animal throughout ancient and modern history is testament to this. Other well-known examples are the [dblookup('Liger', 'Parentage') -> lion, tiger] lion/tiger hybrid, the liger, which is by far the largest big cat and sometimes used in circuses; and cattle hybrids such as between [dblookup('Cattle Hybrids', 'Parentage') -> European and Indian domestic cattle, domestic cattle and American bison] European and Indian domestic cattle or between domestic cattle and American bison, which are used in the meat industry and marketed as [dblookup('Beefalo', 'Marketed As') -> Beefalo] Beefalo. There is some speculation that the [dblookup('Donkey', 'Speculation of Origin') -> ancient hybridisation between two wild ass species or sub-species] donkey itself may be the result of an ancient hybridisation between two wild ass species or sub-species. Hybrid animals are normally infertile partly because their parents usually have slightly different numbers of chromosomes, resulting in unpaired chromosomes in their cells, which prevents division of sex cells and the gonads from operating correctly, particularly in males. There are exceptions to this rule, especially if the speciation process was relatively recent or incomplete as is the case with many cattle and dog species. Normally behaviour traits, natural hostility, natural ranges and breeding cycle differences maintain the separateness of closely related species and prevent natural hybridisation. However, the widespread disturbances to natural animal behaviours and range caused by [dblookup('Human Activity', 'Impact on Animal Behaviors') -> widespread disturbances] human activity, cities, dumping grounds with food, agriculture, fencing, roads and so on do force animals together which would not normally breed. Clear examples exist between the various [dblookup('Grey Wolf, Coyote, Domestic Dog', 'Region') -> North America] sub-species of grey wolf, coyote and domestic dog in North America. As many birds and mammals imprint on their mother and immediate family from infancy, a practice used by animal hybridizers is to foster a planned parent in a hybridization program with the same species as the one with which they are planned to mate.
examples.text: Mammal: The deliberate or accidental hybridising of two or more species of closely related animals through captive breeding is a human activity which has been in existence for millennia and has grown in recent times for economic purposes. The number of successful interspecific mammalian hybrids is relatively small, although it has come to be known that there is a significant number of naturally occurring hybrids between forms or regional varieties of a single species.[citation needed] These may form zones of gradation known as clines. Indeed, the distinction between some hitherto distinct species can become clouded once it can be shown that they may not only breed but produce fertile offspring. Some hybrid animals exhibit greater strength and resilience than either parent. This is known as hybrid vigor. The existence of the mule (donkey sire; horse dam) being used widely as a hardy draught animal throughout ancient and modern history is testament to this. Other well known examples are the lion/tiger hybrid, the liger, which is by far the largest big cat and sometimes used in circuses; and cattle hybrids such as between European and Indian domestic cattle or between domestic cattle and American bison, which are used in the meat industry and marketed as Beefalo. There is some speculation that the donkey itself may be the result of an ancient hybridisation between two wild ass species or sub-species. Hybrid animals are normally infertile partly because their parents usually have slightly different numbers of chromosomes, resulting in unpaired chromosomes in their cells, which prevents division of sex cells and the gonads from operating correctly, particularly in males. There are exceptions to this rule, especially if the speciation process was relatively recent or incomplete as is the case with many cattle and dog species. Normally behavior traits, natural hostility, natural ranges and breeding cycle differences maintain the separateness of closely related species and prevent natural hybridisation. However, the widespread disturbances to natural animal behaviours and range caused by human activity, cities, dumping grounds with food, agriculture, fencing, roads and so on do force animals together which would not normally breed. Clear examples exist between the various sub-species of grey wolf, coyote and domestic dog in North America. As many birds and mammals imprint on their mother and immediate family from infancy, a practice used by animal hybridizers is to foster a planned parent in a hybridization program with the same species as the one with which they are planned to mate.

examples.annotated_text: Premier_League: In response to concerns that clubs were increasingly passing over young [dblookup('English Football Players', 'Preference Over Foreign Players Concern Date') -> 1999] English players in favor of foreign players, in 1999, the [dblookup('Home Office', 'Action Taken Regarding Work Permits') -> tightened rules for non-EU players] Home Office tightened its rules for granting work permits to players from countries outside of the European Union. A non-EU player applying for the permit must have played for his country in at least [dblookup('Non-EU Player Work Permit', 'Competition Appearance Requirement') -> 75 per cent] 75 per cent of its competitive 'A' team matches for which he was available for selection during the previous two years, and his country must have averaged at least [dblookup('Non-EU Player Work Permit', 'FIFA Ranking Requirement') -> 70th place] 70th place in the official FIFA world rankings over the previous two years. If a player does not meet those criteria, the club wishing to sign him may appeal.

examples.annotated_text: History_of_science: Geology existed as a cloud of isolated, disconnected ideas about rocks, minerals, and landforms long before it became a coherent science. [dblookup('Theophrastus', 'Work On Rocks') -> Peri lithōn] Theophrastus' work on rocks, Peri lithōn, remained authoritative for [dblookup('Peri lithōn', 'Influence Period') -> millennia] millennia: its interpretation of fossils was not overturned until after the Scientific Revolution. Chinese polymath Shen Kua (1031–1095) first formulated hypotheses for the [dblookup('Shen Kua', 'Contribution To Geology') -> process of land formation] process of land formation. Based on his [dblookup('Shen Kua', 'Observation Location') -> geological stratum in a mountain] observation of fossils in a geological stratum in a mountain hundreds of miles from the ocean, he deduced that the land was formed by [dblookup('Shen Kua', 'Process of Land Formation') -> erosion of mountains, deposition of silt] erosion of the mountains and by deposition of silt.
examples.text: History_of_science: Geology existed as a cloud of isolated, disconnected ideas about rocks, minerals, and landforms long before it became a coherent science. Theophrastus' work on rocks, Peri lithōn, remained authoritative for millennia: its interpretation of fossils was not overturned until after the Scientific Revolution. Chinese polymath Shen Kua (1031–1095) first formulated hypotheses for the process of land formation. Based on his observation of fossils in a geological stratum in a mountain hundreds of miles from the ocean, he deduced that the land was formed by erosion of the mountains and by deposition of silt.

examples.annotated_text: [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Academic Position') -> Professor of Vocal Physiology and Elocution] In the following year, Bell became professor of Vocal Physiology and Elocution at the [dblookup('Boston University School of Oratory', 'Notable Faculty') -> Alexander Graham Bell] Boston University School of Oratory. During this period, he alternated between [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Residence Period') -> 1873] Boston and Brantford, spending summers in his Canadian home. At Boston University, Bell was "swept up" by the excitement engendered by the many scientists and inventors residing in the city. He continued his [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Research Focus') -> sound transmission] research in sound and endeavored to find a way to transmit musical notes and articulate speech, but although absorbed by his experiments, he found it difficult to devote enough time to experimentation. While days and evenings were occupied by his teaching and private classes, Bell began to stay awake late into the night, running experiment after experiment in rented facilities at his boarding house. Keeping "night owl" hours, he worried that his [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Concern') -> Discovery of work by others] work would be discovered and took great pains to lock up his notebooks and laboratory equipment. Bell had a [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Laboratory Equipment Security') -> locking table] specially made table where he could place his notes and equipment inside a locking cover. Worse still, his health deteriorated as he suffered severe [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Health Issue') -> headaches] headaches. Returning to Boston in fall 1873, Bell made a [dblookup('Alexander Graham Bell', 'Focus Decision in 1873') -> Concentrate on sound experiments] fateful decision to concentrate on his experiments in sound.

examples.annotated_text: Royal_assent: While royal assent has not been withheld in the [dblookup('United Kingdom', 'Last Withholding of Royal Assent') -> 1708] United Kingdom since 1708, it has often been withheld in [dblookup('British Colonies', 'Royal Assent Withheld By') -> Governors acting on royal instructions] British colonies and former colonies by governors acting on royal instructions. In the United States Declaration of Independence, colonists complained that [dblookup('George III', 'Refusal of Assent to Laws Mentioned In') -> United States Declaration of Independence] George III "has refused his Assent to Laws, the most wholesome and necessary for the public good [and] has forbidden his Governors to pass Laws of immediate and pressing importance, unless suspended in their operation till his Assent should be obtained; and when so suspended, he has utterly neglected to attend to them." Even after colonies such as, [dblookup('Australia', 'Granted Responsible Government') -> Post British Colonization], [dblookup('New Zealand', 'Granted Responsible Government') -> Post British Colonization], [dblookup('Union of South Africa', 'Granted Responsible Government') -> Post British Colonization], and [dblookup('Newfoundland', 'Granted Responsible Government') -> Post British Colonization] were granted responsible government, the British government continued to sometimes advise governors-general on the granting of assent; assent was also occasionally reserved to allow the British government to examine a bill before advising the governor-general.
examples.text: Royal_assent: While royal assent has not been withheld in the United Kingdom since 1708, it has often been withheld in British colonies and former colonies by governors acting on royal instructions. In the United States Declaration of Independence, colonists complained that George III "has refused his Assent to Laws, the most wholesome and necessary for the public good [and] has forbidden his Governors to pass Laws of immediate and pressing importance, unless suspended in their operation till his Assent should be obtained; and when so suspended, he has utterly neglected to attend to them." Even after colonies such as Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the Union of South Africa, and Newfoundland were granted responsible government, the British government continued to sometimes advise governors-general on the granting of assent; assent was also occasionally reserved to allow the British government to examine a bill before advising the governor-general.

examples.annotated_text: Association_football: At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals. For example, the [dblookup('2005–06 English Premier League', 'Average Goals Per Match') -> 2.48] 2005–06 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.48 goals per match. The [dblookup('Laws of the Game (association football)', 'Specified Position') -> goalkeeper] Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved. The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play. examples.annotated_text: Crucifixion_of_Jesus: The assumption of the use of a [dblookup('Crucifixion of Jesus', 'Cross Type') -> two-beamed cross] two-beamed cross does not determine the [dblookup('Crucifixion of Jesus', 'Number of Nails Hypothesis') -> three or four nails] number of nails used in the crucifixion and some theories suggest three nails while others suggest four nails. examples.annotated_text: [dblookup('Richard Feynman', 'Contribution') -> Feynman diagrams] From his diagrams of a small number of particles interacting in spacetime, Feynman could then model all of physics in terms of the spins of those particles and the range of coupling of the fundamental forces. Feynman attempted an explanation of the strong interactions governing nucleons scattering called the parton model. The parton model emerged as a complement to the quark model developed by his Caltech colleague Murray Gell-Mann. The relationship between the two models was murky; Gell-Mann referred to Feynman's partons derisively as "put-ons". In the mid-1960s, physicists believed that quarks were just a bookkeeping device for symmetry numbers, not real particles, as the statistics of the Omega-minus particle, if it were interpreted as three identical strange quarks bound together, seemed impossible if quarks were real. The [dblookup('Stanford Linear Accelerator', 'Experiment') -> deep inelastic scattering experiments] Stanford linear accelerator deep inelastic scattering experiments of the late 1960s showed, analogously to [dblookup('Ernest Rutherford', 'Experiment') -> 1911 alpha particles on gold nuclei] Ernest Rutherford's experiment of scattering alpha particles on gold nuclei in 1911, that nucleons (protons and neutrons) contained point-like particles that scattered electrons. It was natural to identify these with quarks, but Feynman's parton model attempted to interpret the experimental data in a way that did not introduce additional hypotheses. For example, the data showed that some 45% of the energy momentum was carried by [dblookup('Gluons', 'Role In') -> Nucleons] electrically-neutral particles in the nucleon. These electrically-neutral particles are now seen to be the gluons that carry the forces between the quarks and carry also the three-valued color quantum number that solves the Omega-minus problem. Feynman did not dispute the quark model; for example, when the [dblookup('Fifth Quark', 'Discovery Year') -> 1977] fifth quark was discovered in 1977, Feynman immediately pointed out to his students that the discovery implied the existence of a sixth quark, which was discovered in the decade after his death.
examples.text: Richard_Feynman: From his diagrams of a small number of particles interacting in spacetime, Feynman could then model all of physics in terms of the spins of those particles and the range of coupling of the fundamental forces. Feynman attempted an explanation of the strong interactions governing nucleons scattering called the parton model. The parton model emerged as a complement to the quark model developed by his Caltech colleague Murray Gell-Mann. The relationship between the two models was murky; Gell-Mann referred to Feynman's partons derisively as "put-ons". In the mid-1960s, physicists believed that quarks were just a bookkeeping device for symmetry numbers, not real particles, as the statistics of the Omega-minus particle, if it were interpreted as three identical strange quarks bound together, seemed impossible if quarks were real. The Stanford linear accelerator deep inelastic scattering experiments of the late 1960s showed, analogously to Ernest Rutherford's experiment of scattering alpha particles on gold nuclei in 1911, that nucleons (protons and neutrons) contained point-like particles that scattered electrons. It was natural to identify these with quarks, but Feynman's parton model attempted to interpret the experimental data in a way that did not introduce additional hypotheses. For example, the data showed that some 45% of the energy momentum was carried by electrically-neutral particles in the nucleon. These electrically-neutral particles are now seen to be the gluons that carry the forces between the quarks and carry also the three-valued color quantum number that solves the Omega-minus problem. Feynman did not dispute the quark model; for example, when the fifth quark was discovered in 1977, Feynman immediately pointed out to his students that the discovery implied the existence of a sixth quark, which was discovered in the decade after his death.

examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: Victoria's father was [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Father') -> Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn] Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn, the [dblookup('Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn', 'Position in Royal Family') -> fourth son] fourth son of the reigning [dblookup('George III', 'Monarch Title') -> King of the United Kingdom] King of the United Kingdom, [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Paternal Grandfather') -> George III] George III. examples.text: Queen_Victoria: Victoria's father was Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn, the fourth son of the reigning King of the United Kingdom, George III. Until 1817, Edward's niece, Princess Charlotte of Wales, was the only legitimate grandchild of George III. Her death in 1817 precipitated a succession crisis that brought pressure on the Duke of Kent and his unmarried brothers to marry and have children. In 1818 he married Princess Victoria of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, a widowed German princess with two children—Carl (1804–1856) and Feodora (1807–1872)—by her first marriage to the Prince of Leiningen. Her brother Leopold was Princess Charlotte's widower. The Duke and Duchess of Kent's only child, Victoria, was born at 4.15 a.m. on 24 May 1819 at Kensington Palace in London.

examples.annotated_text: Lancashire: Lancashire had a lively culture of choral and classical music, with [dblookup('Lancashire', 'Choral Societies Foundation Period') -> mid-18th century] very large numbers of local church choirs from the 17th century, leading to the foundation of local choral societies from the mid-18th century, often particularly focused on performances of the [dblookup('Lancashire Choral Societies', 'Music Focus') -> Handel and contemporaries] music of Handel and his contemporaries. examples.text: Lancashire: Lancashire had a lively culture of choral and classical music, with very large numbers of local church choirs from the 17th century, leading to the foundation of local choral societies from the mid-18th century, often particularly focused on performances of the music of Handel and his contemporaries. examples.annotated_text: Empiricism: In response to the early-to-mid-17th century "continental rationalism" John Locke (1632–1704) proposed in An Essay Concerning Human Understanding (1689) a very influential view wherein the only knowledge humans can have is a posteriori, i.e., based upon experience. Locke is famously attributed with holding the proposition that the human mind is a tabula rasa, a "blank tablet", in Locke's words "white paper", on which the experiences derived from sense impressions as a person's life proceeds are written. There are [dblookup('John Locke', 'Sources Of Ideas') -> sensation, reflection] two sources of our ideas: sensation and reflection. In both cases, a distinction is made between simple and complex ideas. The former are unanalysable, and are broken down into primary and secondary qualities. Primary qualities are essential for the object in question to be what it is. Without specific primary qualities, an object would not be what it is. For example, an apple is an apple because of the arrangement of its atomic structure. If an apple was structured differently, it would cease to be an apple. Secondary qualities are the sensory information we can perceive from its primary qualities. For example, an apple can be perceived in various colours, sizes, and textures but it is still identified as an apple. Therefore, its primary qualities dictate what the object essentially is, while its secondary qualities define its attributes. Complex ideas combine simple ones, and divide into [dblookup('Complex Ideas', 'Types') -> substances, modes, relations] substances, modes, and relations. According to Locke, our knowledge of things is a perception of ideas that are in accordance or discordance with each other, which is very different from [dblookup('John Locke', 'Contrasted With') -> Descartes] the quest for certainty of Descartes.

examples.annotated_text: Gregorian_calendar: The [dblookup('Gregorian calendar', 'Calendar Type') -> solar calendar] Gregorian calendar is a solar calendar. A regular Gregorian year consists of [dblookup('Gregorian calendar', 'Regular Year Length') -> 365 days] 365 days, but as in the Julian calendar, in a leap year, a [dblookup('Gregorian calendar', 'Leap Year Addition') -> leap day added to February] leap day is added to February. In the Julian calendar a leap year occurs every [dblookup('Julian calendar', 'Leap Year Frequency') -> 4 years] 4 years, but the [dblookup('Gregorian calendar', 'Leap Year Rule') -> omits 3 leap days every 400 years] Gregorian calendar omits 3 leap days every 400 years. In the Julian calendar, this leap day was inserted by doubling [dblookup('Julian calendar', 'Leap Day Date') -> 24 February] 24 February, and the Gregorian reform did not change the date of the leap day. In the modern period, it has become customary to number the days from the beginning of the month, and [dblookup('Gregorian calendar', 'Common Leap Day Date') -> February 29] February 29th is often considered as the leap day. Some churches, notably the Roman Catholic Church, delay February festivals after the 23rd by one day in leap years.
examples.text: Gregorian_calendar: The Gregorian calendar is a solar calendar. A regular Gregorian year consists of 365 days, but as in the Julian calendar, in a leap year, a leap day is added to February. In the Julian calendar a leap year occurs every 4 years, but the Gregorian calendar omits 3 leap days every 400 years. Some churches, notably the Roman Catholic Church, delay February festivals after the 23rd by one day in leap years.

examples.annotated_text: Idealism: Idealism is a term with several related meanings. It comes via [dblookup('Idealism', 'Origin of Term') -> Greek idein] idea from the Greek idein (ἰδεῖν), meaning "to see". The term entered the [dblookup('Idealism', 'English Language Entry Year') -> 1743] English language by 1743. In ordinary use, as when speaking of Woodrow Wilson's political idealism, it generally suggests the priority of ideals, principles, values, and goals over concrete realities. Idealists are understood to represent the world as it might or should be, unlike [dblookup('Idealism', 'Contrasts With') -> pragmatism] pragmatists, who focus on the world as it presently is. In the arts, similarly, idealism affirms imagination and attempts to realize a mental conception of beauty, a standard of perfection, juxtaposed to aesthetic naturalism and realism.

examples.annotated_text: Railway_electrification_system: An early advantage of AC is that the power-wasting resistors used in [dblookup('DC Locomotive', 'Speed Control Mechanism') -> Resistors] DC locomotives for speed control were not needed in an AC locomotive: multiple taps on the transformer can supply a range of voltages. Separate low-voltage transformer windings supply lighting and the motors driving auxiliary machinery. More recently, the development of very high power semiconductors has caused the classic "universal" [dblookup('Universal AC/DC Motor', 'Replacement By') -> Three-phase Induction Motor] AC/DC motor to be largely replaced with the three-phase induction motor fed by a [dblookup('Three-phase Induction Motor', 'Controlled By') -> Variable Frequency Drive] variable frequency drive, a special inverter that varies both frequency and voltage to control motor speed. These drives can run equally well on [dblookup('Variable Frequency Drive', 'Compatibility') -> DC or AC of any frequency] DC or AC of any frequency, and many modern electric locomotives are designed to handle different [dblookup('Modern Electric Locomotive', 'Supply Variability') -> Supply Voltages and Frequencies] supply voltages and frequencies to simplify cross-border operation.
examples.text: Railway_electrification_system: An early advantage of AC is that the power-wasting resistors used in DC locomotives for speed control were not needed in an AC locomotive: multiple taps on the transformer can supply a range of voltages. Separate low-voltage transformer windings supply lighting and the motors driving auxiliary machinery. More recently, the development of very high power semiconductors has caused the classic "universal" AC/DC motor to be largely replaced with the three-phase induction motor fed by a variable frequency drive, a special inverter that varies both frequency and voltage to control motor speed. These drives can run equally well on DC or AC of any frequency, and many modern electric locomotives are designed to handle different supply voltages and frequencies to simplify cross-border operation.

examples.annotated_text: Daylight_saving_time: Conversely, [dblookup('Daylight Saving Time', 'Opposition From') -> farmers] DST can adversely affect farmers, parents of young children, and others whose hours are set by the sun and they have traditionally opposed the practice, although some farmers are neutral. examples.annotated_text: Empiricism: In the extreme empiricism of the [dblookup('Neopositivists', 'Philosophical Position Before 1930s') -> extreme empiricism] neopositivists—at least before the 1930s—any genuinely synthetic assertion must be reducible to an ultimate assertion (or set of ultimate assertions) that expresses direct observations or perceptions. In later years, [dblookup('Rudolf Carnap', 'Philosophical Transition') -> abandoned phenomenalism, adopted rational reconstruction] Carnap and [dblookup('Otto Neurath', 'Philosophical Transition') -> abandoned phenomenalism, adopted rational reconstruction] Neurath abandoned this sort of phenomenalism in favor of a rational reconstruction of knowledge into the language of an objective spatio-temporal physics. That is, instead of translating sentences about physical objects into sense-data, such sentences were to be translated into so-called protocol sentences, for example, "X at location Y and at time T observes such and such." The central theses of [dblookup('Logical Positivism', 'Core Theses') -> verificationism, the analytic-synthetic distinction, reductionism] logical positivism (verificationism, the analytic-synthetic distinction, reductionism, etc.) came under sharp attack after World War II by thinkers such as [dblookup('Nelson Goodman', 'Critique Of') -> Logical Positivism] Nelson Goodman, [dblookup('W.V. Quine', 'Critique Of') -> Logical Positivism] W.V. Quine, [dblookup('Hilary Putnam', 'Critique Of') -> Logical Positivism] Hilary Putnam, [dblookup('Karl Popper', 'Critique Of') -> Logical Positivism] Karl Popper, and [dblookup('Richard Rorty', 'Critique Of') -> Logical Positivism] Richard Rorty. By the [dblookup('Logical Positivism', 'Decline Period') -> late 1960s] late 1960s, it had become evident to most philosophers that the movement had pretty much run its course, though its influence is still significant among contemporary analytic philosophers such as [dblookup('Michael Dummett', 'Philosophical Influence') -> Logical Positivism] Michael Dummett and other anti-realists.
examples.text: Empiricism: In the extreme empiricism of the neopositivists—at least before the 1930s—any genuinely synthetic assertion must be reducible to an ultimate assertion (or set of ultimate assertions) that expresses direct observations or perceptions. In later years, Carnap and Neurath abandoned this sort of phenomenalism in favor of a rational reconstruction of knowledge into the language of an objective spatio-temporal physics. That is, instead of translating sentences about physical objects into sense-data, such sentences were to be translated into so-called protocol sentences, for example, "X at location Y and at time T observes such and such." The central theses of logical positivism (verificationism, the analytic-synthetic distinction, reductionism, etc.) came under sharp attack after World War II by thinkers such as Nelson Goodman, W.V. Quine, Hilary Putnam, Karl Popper, and Richard Rorty. By the late 1960s, it had become evident to most philosophers that the movement had pretty much run its course, though its influence is still significant among contemporary analytic philosophers such as Michael Dummett and other anti-realists.

examples.annotated_text: Guam: The U.S. military has proposed [dblookup('U.S. Military', 'Proposed Project in Guam') -> new aircraft carrier berth] building a new aircraft carrier berth on Guam and [dblookup('U.S. Military', 'Proposed Relocation to Guam') -> 8,600 Marines, 9,000 dependents from Okinawa] moving 8,600 Marines, and 9,000 of their dependents, to Guam from Okinawa, Japan. Including the required construction workers, this buildup would [dblookup('Proposed Military Buildup in Guam', 'Impact on Population') -> increase by 45%] increase Guam's population by 45%. In a February 2010 letter, the [dblookup('United States Environmental Protection Agency', 'Criticism Date') -> February 2010] United States Environmental Protection Agency sharply criticized these plans because of a [dblookup('Guam Military Buildup Criticism', 'Reasons') -> water shortfall, sewage problems, impact on coral reefs] water shortfall, sewage problems and the impact on coral reefs. By 2012, these plans had been [dblookup('Modified Military Buildup Plan for Guam', 'Marines in 2012') -> maximum of 4,800] cut to only have a maximum of 4,800 Marines stationed on the island, two thirds of which would be there on a rotational basis without their dependents.
examples.text: Guam: The U.S. military has proposed building a new aircraft carrier berth on Guam and moving 8,600 Marines, and 9,000 of their dependents, to Guam from Okinawa, Japan. Including the required construction workers, this buildup would increase Guam's population by 45%. In a February 2010 letter, the United States Environmental Protection Agency sharply criticized these plans because of a water shortfall, sewage problems and the impact on coral reefs. By 2012, these plans had been cut to only have a maximum of 4,800 Marines stationed on the island, two thirds of which would be there on a rotational basis without their dependents.

examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: On [dblookup('Victoria, Queen', 'Incident Date') -> 29 May 1842] 29 May 1842, Victoria was riding in a carriage along The Mall, London, when [dblookup('Assassination Attempt on Victoria, Queen', 'Assailant') -> John Francis] John Francis aimed a pistol at her but the gun did not fire; he escaped. The following day, Victoria drove the same route, though faster and with a greater escort, in a deliberate attempt to provoke Francis to take a second aim and catch him in the act. Edward Oxford felt that the attempts were encouraged by his acquittal in 1840. Bean was [dblookup('John William Bean', 'Sentencing') -> 18 months in jail] sentenced to 18 months in jail. In a similar attack in 1849, unemployed Irishman [dblookup('Assassination Attempt on Victoria, Queen', 'Third Assailant') -> William Hamilton] William Hamilton fired a powder-filled pistol at Victoria's carriage as it passed along Constitution Hill, London. In [dblookup('Robert Pate', 'Attack Year') -> 1850] 1850, the Queen did sustain injury when she was assaulted by a possibly insane ex-army officer, [dblookup('Assault on Victoria, Queen', 'Assailant') -> Robert Pate] Robert Pate. As Victoria was riding in a carriage, Pate struck her with his cane, crushing her bonnet and bruising her forehead. Both Hamilton and Pate were [dblookup('William Hamilton', 'Sentencing') -> seven years' transportation] sentenced to seven years' transportation.
examples.text: Queen_Victoria: On 29 May 1842, Victoria was riding in a carriage along The Mall, London, when John Francis aimed a pistol at her but the gun did not fire; he escaped. The following day, Victoria drove the same route, though faster and with a greater escort, in a deliberate attempt to provoke Francis to take a second aim and catch him in the act. As expected, Francis shot at her, but he was seized by plain-clothes policemen, and convicted of high treason. On 3 July, two days after Francis's death sentence was commuted to transportation for life, John William Bean also tried to fire a pistol at the Queen, but it was loaded only with paper and tobacco and had too little charge. Edward Oxford felt that the attempts were encouraged by his acquittal in 1840. Bean was sentenced to 18 months in jail. In a similar attack in 1849, unemployed Irishman William Hamilton fired a powder-filled pistol at Victoria's carriage as it passed along Constitution Hill, London. In 1850, the Queen did sustain injury when she was assaulted by a possibly insane ex-army officer, Robert Pate. As Victoria was riding in a carriage, Pate struck her with his cane, crushing her bonnet and bruising her forehead. Both Hamilton and Pate were sentenced to seven years' transportation.
