examples.annotated_text: Seattle: The Puget Sound Convergence Zone is an important feature of Seattle's weather. In the convergence zone, air arriving from the north meets air flowing in from the south. Both [dblookup('Puget Sound Convergence Zone', 'Airflow Origin') -> Pacific Ocean] streams of air originate over the Pacific Ocean; airflow is split by the [dblookup('Olympic Mountains', 'Geographic Location') -> Seattle's west] Olympic Mountains to Seattle's west, then reunited to the east. When the air currents meet, they are forced upward, resulting in convection. Thunderstorms caused by this activity are usually weak and can occur north and south of town, but Seattle itself rarely receives more than occasional thunder and small hail showers. The Hanukkah Eve Wind Storm in December 2006 is an exception that brought heavy rain and [dblookup('Hanukkah Eve Wind Storm', 'Wind Speed') -> 69 mph (111 km/h)] winds gusting up to 69 mph (111 km/h), an event that was not caused by the Puget Sound Convergence Zone and was widespread across the [dblookup('Hanukkah Eve Wind Storm', 'Affected Region') -> Pacific Northwest] Pacific Northwest.

When the air currents meet, they are forced upward, resulting in convection. examples.annotated_text: Annelid: Since annelids are soft-bodied, their fossils are rare. Polychaetes' fossil record consists mainly of the jaws that some species had and the mineralized tubes that some secreted. Some Ediacaran fossils such as [dblookup('Dickinsonia', 'Resemblance To') -> polychaetes] Dickinsonia in some ways resemble polychaetes, but the similarities are too vague for these fossils to be classified with confidence. The small shelly fossil [dblookup('Cloudina', 'Age Range') -> 549 to 542 million years ago] Cloudina, from 549 to 542 million years ago, has been classified by some authors as an annelid, but by others as a [dblookup('Cloudina', 'Alternative Classification') -> cnidarian] cnidarian (i.e. in the phylum to which jellyfish and sea anemones belong). Until 2008, the earliest fossils widely accepted as annelids were the polychaetes [dblookup('Canadia', 'Era Found') -> early Cambrian] Canadia and [dblookup('Burgessochaeta', 'Era Found') -> early Cambrian] Burgessochaeta, both from Canada's Burgess Shale, formed about 505 million years ago in the early Cambrian. Myoscolex, found in Australia and a little older than the Burgess Shale, was possibly an annelid. However, it lacks some typical annelid features and has features which are not usually found in annelids and some of which are associated with other phyla. Then Simon Conway Morris and John Peel reported [dblookup('Phragmochaeta', 'Discovery Location') -> Sirius Passet] Phragmochaeta from Sirius Passet, about 518 million years old, and concluded that it was [dblookup('Phragmochaeta', 'Significance') -> oldest annelid known] the oldest annelid known to date. There has been vigorous debate about whether the Burgess Shale fossil Wiwaxia was a [dblookup('Wiwaxia', 'Possible Classification 1') -> mollusc] mollusc or an [dblookup('Wiwaxia', 'Possible Classification 2') -> annelid] annelid. Polychaetes diversified in the early Ordovician, about 488 to 474 million years ago. It is not until the early Ordovician that the first annelid jaws are found, thus the crown-group cannot have appeared before this date and probably appeared somewhat later. By the [dblookup('Carboniferous', 'End Period') -> 299 million years ago] end of the Carboniferous, about 299 million years ago, fossils of most of the modern mobile polychaete groups had appeared. Many fossil tubes look like those made by modern sessile polychaetes, but the first tubes clearly produced by polychaetes date from the [dblookup('Jurassic', 'Start Period') -> less than 199 million years ago] Jurassic, less than 199 million years ago.

examples.annotated_text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: For Whitehead, the core of religion was individual. He took special care to note that while religion is often a good influence, it is not necessarily good – an idea which he called a "[dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Concept of Religion Danger') -> Dangerous Delusion]" dangerous delusion (e.g., a religion might encourage the violent extermination of a rival religion's adherents).
examples.text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: For Whitehead the core of religion was individual. While he acknowledged that individuals cannot ever be fully separated from their society, he argued that life is an internal fact for its own sake before it is an external fact relating to others. Whitehead saw religion as a system of general truths that transformed a person's character. He took special care to note that while religion is often a good influence, it is not necessarily good – an idea which he called a "dangerous delusion" (e.g., a religion might encourage the violent extermination of a rival religion's adherents).

examples.text: Zinc: Zinc deficiency is crop plants' most common micronutrient deficiency; it is particularly common in high-pH soils. Zinc-deficient soil is cultivated in the cropland of about half of Turkey and India, a third of China, and most of Western Australia, and substantial responses to zinc fertilization have been reported in these areas. examples.annotated_text: New_Haven,_Connecticut: For over a century, New Haven citizens had fought in the colonial militia alongside regular British forces, as in the [dblookup('New Haven', 'Participation in Wars') -> French and Indian War] French and Indian War. On 23 April 1775, which is still celebrated in New Haven as Powder House Day, the [dblookup('Second Company, Governor\'s Foot Guard', 'Location') -> New Haven] Second Company, Governor's Foot Guard, of New Haven entered the struggle against the [dblookup('New Haven', 'Adversary During American Revolution') -> Governing British Parliament] governing British parliament. Under [dblookup('Benedict Arnold', 'Role at New Haven') -> Captain] Captain Benedict Arnold, they broke into the powder house to arm themselves and began a three-day march to Cambridge, Massachusetts. Other New Haven militia members were on hand to [dblookup('New Haven Militia', 'Action During Washington\'s Stay') -> Escort George Washington] escort George Washington from his overnight stay in New Haven on his way to [dblookup('George Washington', 'Destination in New Haven Story') -> Cambridge] Cambridge. examples.text: New_Haven,_Connecticut: For over a century, New Haven citizens had fought in the colonial militia alongside regular British forces, as in the French and Indian War. As the American Revolution approached, General David Wooster and other influential residents hoped that the conflict with the government in Britain could be resolved short of rebellion. On 23 April 1775, which is still celebrated in New Haven as Powder House Day, the Second Company, Governor's Foot Guard, of New Haven entered the struggle against the governing British parliament. Under Captain Benedict Arnold, they broke into the powder house to arm themselves and began a three-day march to Cambridge, Massachusetts. Other New Haven militia members were on hand to escort George Washington from his overnight stay in New Haven on his way to Cambridge. Contemporary reports, from both sides, remark on the New Haven volunteers' professional military bearing, including uniforms.

examples.annotated_text: Association_football: In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the IFAB experimented with ways of creating a winner without requiring a penalty shootout, which was often seen as an undesirable way to end a match. These involved rules ending a game in extra time early, either when the first goal in extra time was scored ([dblookup('Golden Goal', 'Purpose') -> end a match upon the first goal in extra time] golden goal), or if one team held a lead at the end of the first period of extra time ([dblookup('Silver Goal', 'Purpose') -> end a match if one team leads at the end of the first extra time period] silver goal). Golden goal was used at the [dblookup('FIFA World Cup', 'Golden Goal Usage') -> 1998 and 2002] World Cup in 1998 and 2002. The first World Cup game decided by a golden goal was [dblookup('1998 FIFA World Cup', 'First Golden Goal Decided Match') -> France vs. Paraguay] France's victory over Paraguay in 1998. Germany was the first nation to score a golden goal in a major competition, beating the Czech Republic in the final of Euro 1996. Silver goal was used in [dblookup('UEFA Euro 2004', 'Silver Goal Usage') -> Euro 2004] Euro 2004. Both these experiments have been [dblookup('International Football Association Board', 'Discontinuation Of Methods') -> golden goal, silver goal] discontinued by IFAB.

examples.annotated_text: Geological_history_of_Earth: The most-commonly accepted theory is that these events were triggered by the onset of an [dblookup('Hirnantian Ice Age', 'Historical Period') -> Ice Age] ice age, in the Hirnantian faunal stage that ended the long, stable greenhouse conditions typical of the [dblookup('Ordovician Period', 'Climate Conditions') -> Greenhouse] Ordovician. The ice age was probably not as long-lasting as once thought; study of oxygen isotopes in fossil brachiopods shows that it was probably no longer than [dblookup('Hirnantian Ice Age', 'Duration') -> 0.5 to 1.5 million years] 0.5 to 1.5 million years. The event was preceded by a fall in [dblookup('Ordovician Period', 'Atmospheric Carbon Dioxide Levels') -> 7000ppm to 4400ppm] atmospheric carbon dioxide (from 7000ppm to 4400ppm) which selectively affected the shallow seas where most organisms lived. As the [dblookup('Gondwana', 'Position During Ordovician') -> South Pole] southern supercontinent Gondwana drifted over the South Pole, ice caps formed on it. Evidence of these ice caps have been detected in Upper Ordovician rock strata of North Africa and then-adjacent northeastern South America, which were south-polar locations at the time.

As the southern supercontinent Gondwana drifted over the South Pole, ice caps formed on it. Evidence of these ice caps have been detected in Upper Ordovician rock strata of North Africa and then-adjacent northeastern South America, which were south-polar locations at the time.

examples.annotated_text: Electric_motor: A major turning point in the development of DC machines took place in 1864, when [dblookup('Antonio Pacinotti', 'Contribution To DC Machines') -> described ring armature] Antonio Pacinotti described for the first time the ring armature with its symmetrically grouped coils closed upon themselves and connected to the bars of a commutator, the brushes of which delivered practically non-fluctuating current. The first commercially successful DC motors followed the invention by [dblookup('Zénobe Gramme', 'Invention Based On') -> Pacinotti's ring armature design] Zénobe Gramme who, in [dblookup('Zénobe Gramme', 'Motor Invention Year') -> 1871] 1871, reinvented Pacinotti's design. In [dblookup('Zénobe Gramme', 'Dynamo Motor Demonstration Year') -> 1873] 1873, Gramme showed that his dynamo could be used as a motor, which he demonstrated to great effect at exhibitions in Vienna and Philadelphia by connecting two such DC motors at a distance of up to 2 km away from each other, one as a generator. (See also 1873 : l'expérience décisive [Decisive Workaround].)
examples.text: Electric_motor: A major turning point in the development of DC machines took place in 1864, when Antonio Pacinotti described for the first time the ring armature with its symmetrically grouped coils closed upon themselves and connected to the bars of a commutator, the brushes of which delivered practically non-fluctuating current. The first commercially successful DC motors followed the invention by Zénobe Gramme who, in 1871, reinvented Pacinotti's design. In 1873, Gramme showed that his dynamo could be used as a motor, which he demonstrated to great effect at exhibitions in Vienna and Philadelphia by connecting two such DC motors at a distance of up to 2 km away from each other, one as a generator. (See also 1873 : l'expérience décisive [Decisive Workaround] .)

examples.annotated_text: Memory: The more long term the exposure to stress is, the more impact it may have. However, short term exposure to stress also causes impairment in memory by interfering with the function of the [dblookup('Hippocampus', 'Role In') -> Memory Function] hippocampus. Research shows that subjects placed in a stressful situation for a short amount of time still have [dblookup('Glucocorticoids', 'Effect Of Stress On Levels') -> Increase] blood glucocorticoid levels that have increased drastically when measured after the exposure is completed. When subjects are asked to complete a learning task after short term exposure they have often difficulties. Prenatal stress also hinders the [dblookup('Prenatal Stress', 'Effect On') -> Ability to Learn and Memorize] ability to learn and memorize by disrupting the development of the [dblookup('Hippocampus', 'Development Affected By') -> Prenatal Stress] hippocampus and can lead to [dblookup('Long Term Potentiation', 'Effect Of Prenatal Stress') -> Unestablished] unestablished long term potentiation in the offspring of severely stressed parents. Although the stress is applied prenatally, the [dblookup('Offspring Of Stressed Parents', 'Stress Response') -> Increased Glucocorticoid Levels] offspring show increased levels of glucocorticoids when they are subjected to stress later on in life.
examples.text: Memory: The more long term the exposure to stress is, the more impact it may have. Research shows that subjects placed in a stressful situation for a short amount of time still have blood glucocorticoid levels that have increased drastically when measured after the exposure is completed. examples.annotated_text: Geological_history_of_Earth: The [dblookup('Silurian', 'Geologic Timescale Division') -> major division] Silurian is a major division of the geologic timescale that started [dblookup('Silurian', 'Start Date') -> about 443.8 ± 1.5 Ma] about 443.8 ± 1.5 Ma. During the Silurian, [dblookup('Gondwana', 'Movement During Silurian') -> slow southward drift to high southern latitudes] Gondwana continued a slow southward drift to high southern latitudes, but there is evidence that the Silurian ice caps were [dblookup('Silurian Ice Caps', 'Comparison to Late Ordovician') -> less extensive than those of the late Ordovician glaciation] less extensive than those of the late Ordovician glaciation. The melting of ice caps and glaciers contributed to [dblookup('Silurian Sea Levels', 'Effect of Ice Cap Melting') -> rise] a rise in sea levels, recognizable from the fact that Silurian sediments overlie eroded Ordovician sediments, forming [dblookup('Silurian Sediments', 'Unconformity Formation') -> unconformity] an unconformity. Other cratons and continent fragments drifted together [dblookup('Euramerica', 'Formation Starting Point')] -> near the equator] near the equator, starting the formation of a second supercontinent known as [dblookup('Second Supercontinent Starting Formation', 'Name') -> Euramerica] Euramerica. The vast ocean of [dblookup('Northern Hemisphere', 'Primary Ocean During Silurian') -> Panthalassa] Panthalassa covered most of the northern hemisphere. Other minor oceans include [dblookup('Silurian Minor Oceans', 'Names') -> Proto-Tethys, Paleo-Tethys, Rheic Ocean, seaway of Iapetus Ocean, Ural Ocean] Proto-Tethys, Paleo-Tethys, Rheic Ocean, a seaway of Iapetus Ocean (now in between Avalonia and Laurentia), and newly formed Ural Ocean.
examples.text: Geological_history_of_Earth: The Silurian is a major division of the geologic timescale that started about 443.8 ± 1.5 Ma. During the Silurian, Gondwana continued a slow southward drift to high southern latitudes, but there is evidence that the Silurian ice caps were less extensive than those of the late Ordovician glaciation. The melting of ice caps and glaciers contributed to a rise in sea levels, recognizable from the fact that Silurian sediments overlie eroded Ordovician sediments, forming an unconformity. Other cratons and continent fragments drifted together near the equator, starting the formation of a second supercontinent known as Euramerica. The vast ocean of Panthalassa covered most of the northern hemisphere. Other minor oceans include Proto-Tethys, Paleo-Tethys, Rheic Ocean, a seaway of Iapetus Ocean (now in between Avalonia and Laurentia), and newly formed Ural Ocean.

examples.annotated_text: Central station electricity can often be generated with higher efficiency than a mobile engine/generator. While the efficiency of power plant generation and diesel locomotive generation are roughly the same in the nominal regime, diesel motors decrease in efficiency in non-nominal regimes at low power while if an electric power plant needs to generate less power it will shut down its least efficient generators, thereby increasing efficiency. The [dblookup('Electric Train', 'Energy-Saving Features') -> Regenerative Braking, No Idling Consumption] electric train can save energy (as compared to diesel) by regenerative braking and by not needing to consume energy by idling as diesel locomotives do when stopped or coasting. However, electric rolling stock may run cooling blowers when stopped or coasting, thus consuming energy.

examples.text: United_States_Air_Force: The United States Air Force (USAF) is the aerial warfare service branch of the United States Armed Forces and one of the seven American uniformed services. Initially part of the United States Army, the USAF was formed as a separate branch of the military on 18 September 1947 under the National Security Act of 1947. It is the most recent branch of the U.S. military to be formed, and is the largest and one of the world's most technologically advanced air forces. The USAF articulates its core functions as Nuclear Deterrence Operations, Special Operations, Air Superiority, Global Integrated ISR, Space Superiority, Command and Control, Cyberspace Superiority, Personnel Recovery, Global Precision Attack, Building Partnerships, Rapid Global Mobility and Agile Combat Support.

examples.annotated_text: ASCII: Code [dblookup('ASCII Code 127', 'Official Name') -> delete] 127 is officially named "delete" but the [dblookup('ASCII Code 127', 'Teletype Label') -> rubout] Teletype label was "rubout". Since the original standard did not give detailed interpretation for most control codes, interpretations of this code varied. The original Teletype meaning, and the intent of the [dblookup('ASCII Code 127', 'Standard Intent') -> ignored character] standard, was to make it an ignored character, the same as [dblookup('ASCII', 'Equivalent To Code 127') -> NUL] NUL (all zeroes). This was useful specifically for [dblookup('Purpose of Code 127', 'Use Case') -> paper tape editing] paper tape, because punching the all-ones bit pattern on top of an existing mark would obliterate it. Tapes designed to be "hand edited" could even be produced with spaces of extra NULs (blank tape) so that a block of characters could be "rubbed out" and then replacements put into the empty space.

examples.annotated_text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: Beginning in the late [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Career Shift Start') -> 1910s] 1910s and [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Career Shift End') -> 1920s] early 1920s, [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Field Shift') -> from mathematics to philosophy of science and metaphysics] Whitehead gradually turned his attention from mathematics to philosophy of science, and finally to metaphysics. He developed a [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Metaphysical System Type') -> comprehensive] comprehensive metaphysical system which radically departed from most of western philosophy. Whitehead argued that [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Reality Theory') -> reality consists of processes] reality consists of processes rather than material objects, and that processes are best defined by their relations with other processes, thus rejecting the theory that reality is fundamentally constructed by bits of matter that exist independently of one another. Today Whitehead's philosophical works – particularly [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Notable Work') -> Process and Reality] Process and Reality – are regarded as the [dblookup('Process and Reality', 'Philosophical Influence') -> foundational texts of process philosophy] foundational texts of process philosophy.
examples.text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: Beginning in the late 1910s and early 1920s, Whitehead gradually turned his attention from mathematics to philosophy of science, and finally to metaphysics. examples.annotated_text: Muammar_Gaddafi: On 2 March 1979, the GPC announced the separation of government and revolution, the latter being represented by new [dblookup('Revolutionary Committees', 'Role In Government') -> represented revolution] Revolutionary Committees, who operated in tandem with the [dblookup('People\'s Committees', 'Operational Sectors') -> schools, universities, unions, police, military] People's Committees in schools, universities, unions, the police force, and the military. Dominated by revolutionary zealots, the Revolutionary Committees were led by [dblookup('Revolutionary Committees', 'Led By') -> Mohammad Maghgoub] Mohammad Maghgoub and a Central Coordinating Office, and met with Gaddafi annually. Publishing a weekly magazine [dblookup('Revolutionary Committees', 'Magazine Published') -> The Green March] The Green March (al-Zahf al-Akhdar), in October 1980 they took control of the press. Responsible for perpetuating revolutionary fervour, they performed [dblookup('Revolutionary Committees', 'Security Role') -> ideological surveillance, arrests, trials] ideological surveillance, later adopting a significant security role, making arrests and putting people on trial according to the [dblookup('Law of the Revolution', 'Type of Justice') -> arbitrary, no legal code] "law of the revolution" (qanun al-thawra). With no legal code or safeguards, the administration of revolutionary justice was largely arbitrary and resulted in widespread abuses and the suppression of civil liberties: the "Green Terror."
examples.text: Muammar_Gaddafi: On 2 March 1979, the GPC announced the separation of government and revolution, the latter being represented by new Revolutionary Committees, who operated in tandem with the People's Committees in schools, universities, unions, the police force and the military. Dominated by revolutionary zealots, the Revolutionary Committees were led by Mohammad Maghgoub and a Central Coordinating Office, and met with Gaddafi annually. Publishing a weekly magazine The Green March (al-Zahf al-Akhdar), in October 1980 they took control of the press. Responsible for perpetuating revolutionary fervour, they performed ideological surveillance, later adopting a significant security role, making arrests and putting people on trial according to the "law of the revolution" (qanun al-thawra). With no legal code or safeguards, the administration of revolutionary justice was largely arbitrary and resulted in widespread abuses and the suppression of civil liberties: the "Green Terror."

examples.annotated_text: Ottoman Empire: Suleiman the Magnificent ( 1520–1566) captured [dblookup('Suleiman the Magnificent', 'Captured City') -> Belgrade] Belgrade in 1521, conquered the southern and central parts of the Kingdom of Hungary as part of the Ottoman–Hungarian Wars, and, after his historical victory in the [dblookup('Suleiman the Magnificent', 'Battle of Mohács Victory') -> 1526] Battle of Mohács in 1526, he established [dblookup('Suleiman the Magnificent', 'Influence Area After 1526') -> Turkish rule in the territory of present-day Hungary (except the western part) and other Central European territories] Turkish rule in the territory of present-day Hungary (except the western part) and other Central European territories. He then laid siege to [dblookup('Suleiman the Magnificent', 'First Siege on Vienna') -> 1529] Vienna in 1529, but failed to take the city. examples.text: Ottoman_Empire: Suleiman the Magnificent (1520–1566) captured Belgrade in 1521, conquered the southern and central parts of the Kingdom of Hungary as part of the Ottoman–Hungarian Wars,[not in citation given] and, after his historical victory in the Battle of Mohács in 1526, he established Turkish rule in the territory of present-day Hungary (except the western part) and other Central European territories. examples.annotated_text: Pain: In [dblookup('René Descartes', 'Year of Theory on Pain') -> 1644] 1644, René Descartes theorized that pain was a disturbance that passed down along nerve fibers until the disturbance reached the brain, a development that transformed the perception of pain from a spiritual, mystical experience to a physical, mechanical sensation. Descartes's work, along with Avicenna's, prefigured the 19th-century development of specificity theory. Specificity theory saw pain as "a specific sensation, with its own sensory apparatus independent of touch and other senses". Another theory that came to prominence in the 18th and 19th centuries was intensive theory, which conceived of pain not as a unique sensory modality, but an emotional state produced by stronger than normal stimuli such as intense light, pressure, or temperature. By the mid- 1890s, specificity was backed mostly by physiologists and physicians, and the intensive theory was mostly backed by psychologists. However, after a series of clinical observations by [dblookup('Henry Head', 'Contribution To') -> Pain Specificity Theory] Henry Head and experiments by [dblookup('Max von Frey', 'Contribution To') -> Pain Specificity Theory] Max von Frey, the psychologists migrated to specificity almost en masse, and by century's end, most textbooks on physiology and psychology were presenting pain specificity as fact.

examples.annotated_text: Digimon: [dblookup('Digimon', 'Origin') -> Digi-Eggs] Digimon hatch from types of eggs which are called Digi-Eggs (デジタマ, Dejitama?). In the English iterations of the franchise, there is [dblookup('Digimon', 'Alternate Egg Type') -> Digimental] another type of Digi-Egg that can be used to digivolve, or transform, Digimon. This second type of Digi-Egg is called a Digimental (デジメンタル, Dejimentaru?) in Japanese. [dblookup('Digimental', 'Role in Season 2') -> Major object for Digivolution] This type of Digi-Egg was also featured as a major object throughout season 2 as a way of Digivolution available only to certain characters at certain points throughout the season. They age via a process called [dblookup('Digimon', 'Aging Process') -> Digivolution] "Digivolution," which changes their appearance and increases their powers. The effect of Digivolution, however, is not permanent in the partner Digimon of the main characters in the anime, and Digimon who've digivolved will most of the time revert to their previous form after a battle or if they are too weak to continue. Some Digimon act feral. Most, however, are capable of intelligence and human speech. They are able to digivolve by the use of Digivices that their human partners have. In some cases, as in the first series, the DigiDestined (known as the 'Chosen Children' in the original Japanese) had to find some special items such as [dblookup('DigiDestined', 'Special Items') -> Crests and Tags] crests and tags so the Digimon could digivolve into further stages of evolution known as Ultimate and Mega in the dub.

examples.annotated_text: Liberia: The Republic of Liberia, beginning as a settlement of the American Colonization Society (ACS), declared its [dblookup('Republic of Liberia', 'Independence Declared On') -> July 26, 1847] independence on July 26, 1847. Between January 7, 1822 and the American Civil War, more than [dblookup('Liberia', 'Number of Black American Relocatees') -> 15,000] 15,000 freed and free-born Black Americans from the United States and [dblookup('Liberia', 'Number of Afro-Caribbean Relocatees') -> 3,198] 3,198 Afro-Caribbeans relocated to the settlement. The Black American settlers carried their culture with them to Liberia. The [dblookup('Liberian Constitution', 'Influence') -> United States] Liberian constitution and flag were modeled after the United States. On [dblookup('Joseph Jenkins Roberts', 'Inauguration Date') -> January 3, 1848] January 3, 1848, Joseph Jenkins Roberts, a wealthy free-born Black American from Virginia who settled in Liberia, was elected as [dblookup('Joseph Jenkins Roberts', 'Role') -> Liberia's first president] Liberia's first president after the people proclaimed independence.
examples.text: Liberia: The Republic of Liberia, beginning as a settlement of the American Colonization Society (ACS), declared its independence on July 26, 1847. The Black American settlers carried their culture with them to Liberia. The Liberian constitution and flag were modeled after the United States. In January 3, 1848 Joseph Jenkins Roberts, a wealthy free-born Black American from Virginia who settled in Liberia, was elected as Liberia's first president after the people proclaimed independence.

examples.annotated_text: Annelid: The [dblookup('Annelid', 'Setae Composition') -> β-chitin] setae ("hairs") of annelids project out from the [dblookup('Annelid', 'Setae Location') -> epidermis] epidermis to provide traction and other capabilities. The simplest are unjointed and form paired bundles near the top and bottom of each side of each segment. The [dblookup('Annelid', 'Parapodia Presence') -> presence of parapodia in certain species] parapodia ("limbs") of annelids that have them often bear more complex chetae at their tips – for example, jointed, comb-like or hooked. Chetae are made of moderately flexible [dblookup('Annelid Chetae', 'Composition') -> β-chitin] β-chitin and are formed by follicles, each of which has a chetoblast ("hair-forming") cell at the bottom and muscles that can extend or retract the cheta. The chetoblasts produce chetae by forming microvilli, fine hair-like extensions that increase the area available for secreting the cheta. When the cheta is complete, the microvilli withdraw into the chetoblast, leaving parallel tunnels that run almost the full length of the cheta. Hence [dblookup('Annelid Chetae', 'Structural Difference') -> structurally different from arthropod setae] annelids' chetae are structurally different from the setae ("bristles") of arthropods, which are made of the more rigid [dblookup('Arthropod Setae', 'Composition') -> α-chitin] α-chitin, have a single internal cavity, and are mounted on flexible joints in shallow pits in the cuticle.
examples.text: Annelid: The setae ("hairs") of annelids project out from the epidermis to provide traction and other capabilities. The simplest are unjointed and form paired bundles near the top and bottom of each side of each segment. The parapodia ("limbs") of annelids that have them often bear more complex chetae at their tips – for example jointed, comb-like or hooked. Chetae are made of moderately flexible β-chitin and are formed by follicles, each of which has a chetoblast ("hair-forming") cell at the bottom and muscles that can extend or retract the cheta. The chetoblasts produce chetae by forming microvilli, fine hair-like extensions that increase the area available for secreting the cheta. When the cheta is complete, the microvilli withdraw into the chetoblast, leaving parallel tunnels that run almost the full length of the cheta. Hence annelids' chetae are structurally different from the setae ("bristles") of arthropods, which are made of the more rigid α-chitin, have a single internal cavity, and are mounted on flexible joints in shallow pits in the cuticle.

examples.annotated_text: Sino-Tibetan_relations_during_the_Ming_dynasty: Some scholars note that Tibetan leaders during the Ming frequently engaged in civil war and conducted their own [dblookup('Tibetan Leaders during the Ming Dynasty', 'Diplomatic Relations With') -> Nepal] foreign diplomacy with neighboring states such as Nepal. Some scholars underscore the commercial aspect of the [dblookup('Ming Dynasty', 'Trade Commodity from Tibet') -> horses] Ming-Tibetan relationship, noting the Ming dynasty's shortage of horses for warfare and thus the importance of the horse trade with Tibet. Others argue that the significant religious nature of the relationship of the Ming court with Tibetan lamas is underrepresented in modern scholarship. In hopes of reviving the unique [dblookup('Kublai Khan', 'Religious Association With') -> Drogön Chögyal Phagpa] relationship of the earlier Mongol leader Kublai Khan (r. 1260–1294) and his spiritual superior Drogön Chögyal Phagpa (1235–1280) of the Sakya school of Tibetan Buddhism, the [dblookup('Yongle Emperor', 'Reign') -> 1402–1424] Yongle Emperor (r. 1402–1424) made a concerted effort to build a secular and religious alliance with [dblookup('Deshin Shekpa', 'Position') -> Karmapa of the Karma Kagyu school] Deshin Shekpa (1384–1415), the Karmapa of the Karma Kagyu school. However, the Yongle Emperor's attempts were unsuccessful.
examples.text: Sino-Tibetan_relations_during_the_Ming_dynasty: Some scholars note that Tibetan leaders during the Ming frequently engaged in civil war and conducted their own foreign diplomacy with neighboring states such as Nepal. Some scholars underscore the commercial aspect of the Ming-Tibetan relationship, noting the Ming dynasty's shortage of horses for warfare and thus the importance of the horse trade with Tibet. Others argue that the significant religious nature of the relationship of the Ming court with Tibetan lamas is underrepresented in modern scholarship. In hopes of reviving the unique relationship of the earlier Mongol leader Kublai Khan (r. 1260–1294) and his spiritual superior Drogön Chögyal Phagpa (1235–1280) of the Sakya school of Tibetan Buddhism, the Yongle Emperor (r. 1402–1424) made a concerted effort to build a secular and religious alliance with Deshin Shekpa (1384–1415), the Karmapa of the Karma Kagyu school. However, the Yongle Emperor's attempts were unsuccessful.

examples.text: Iran: In 633 AD, Rashidun Arabs invaded Iran and conquered it by 651 AD, largely converting Iranian people from their indigenous faiths of Manichaeism and Zoroastrianism to Sunni Islam. Arabic replaced Persian as the official language, while Persian remained the language of both ordinary people and of literature. Iran became a major contributor to the Islamic Golden Age, producing many influential scientists, scholars, artists, and thinkers. Establishment of the Safavid Dynasty in 1501, converted the Iranian people from Sunni Islam to Twelver Shia Islam, and made Twelver Shia Islam the official religion of Iran. Safavid conversion of Iran from Sunnism to Shiism marked one of the most important turning points in Iranian and Muslim history. Starting in 1736 under Nader Shah, Iran reached its greatest territorial extent since the Sassanid Empire, briefly possessing what was arguably the most powerful empire at the time. During the 19th century, Iran irrevocably lost swaths of its territories in the Caucasus which made part of the concept of Iran for centuries, to neighboring Imperial Russia. Popular unrest culminated in the Persian Constitutional Revolution of 1906, which established a constitutional monarchy and the country's first Majles (parliament). Following a coup d'état instigated by the U.K. and the U.S. in 1953, Iran gradually became close allies with the United States and the rest of the West, remained secular, but grew increasingly autocratic. Growing dissent against foreign influence and political repression culminated in the 1979 Revolution, which led to the establishment of an Islamic republic on 1 April 1979.

examples.annotated_text: ASCII: When a [dblookup('Teletype Model 33 ASR', 'Feature') -> automatic paper tape reader] Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a Control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving [dblookup('Control-Q', 'Function') -> transmit on] Control-Q (XON, "transmit on") caused the tape reader to resume. This technique became adopted by [dblookup('Control-S and Control-Q', 'Use') -> early computer operating systems] several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique. On some systems [dblookup('Control-S', 'Alternative Pause Mechanism') -> double Control-S] Control-S retains its meaning but Control-Q is replaced by a second Control-S to resume output. The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ Control-R (DC2) and Control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.

examples.annotated_text: Age_of_Enlightenment: John Locke, one of the most influential Enlightenment thinkers, [dblookup('John Locke', 'Philosophical Basis') -> social contract theory] based his governance philosophy in social contract theory, a subject that permeated Enlightenment political thought. The English philosopher [dblookup('Thomas Hobbes', 'Contribution To Political Philosophy') -> Leviathan] Thomas Hobbes ushered in this new debate with his work Leviathan in [dblookup('Leviathan', 'Publication Year') -> 1651] 1651. Hobbes also developed some of the fundamentals of [dblookup('Thomas Hobbes', 'Contributions To') -> European liberal thought] European liberal thought: the right of the individual; the natural equality of all men; the artificial character of the political order (which led to the later distinction between civil society and the state); the view that all legitimate political power must be "representative" and based on the consent of the people; and a liberal interpretation of law which leaves people free to do whatever the law does not explicitly forbid.
examples.text: Age_of_Enlightenment: John Locke, one of the most influential Enlightenment thinkers, based his governance philosophy in social contract theory, a subject that permeated Enlightenment political thought. The English philosopher Thomas Hobbes ushered in this new debate with his work Leviathan in 1651. Hobbes also developed some of the fundamentals of European liberal thought: the right of the individual; the natural equality of all men; the artificial character of the political order (which led to the later distinction between civil society and the state); the view that all legitimate political power must be "representative" and based on the consent of the people; and a liberal interpretation of law which leaves people free to do whatever the law does not explicitly forbid.

examples.annotated_text: Empiricism: This idea was later developed in ancient philosophy by the [dblookup('Empiricism', 'Developed By') -> Stoic school] Stoic school. Stoic epistemology generally emphasized that the mind starts blank, but acquires [dblookup('Stoic Epistemology', 'View On Knowledge Acquisition') -> knowledge impressed by the outside world] knowledge as the outside world is impressed upon it. The doxographer [dblookup('Aetius', 'Role In Stoicism') -> Summarizer of Stoic Views] Aetius summarizes this view as "When a man is born, the Stoics say, he has the commanding part of his soul like a sheet of paper ready for writing upon." Later stoics, such as [dblookup('Sextus of Chaeronea', 'Contribution to Stoicism') -> Continued Empirical Ideas] Sextus of Chaeronea, would continue this idea of empiricism in later Stoic writings as well. As Sextus contends "For every thought comes from sense-perception or not without sense-perception and either from direct experience or not without direct experience" (Against the Professors, 8.56-8).
examples.text: Empiricism: This idea was later developed in ancient philosophy by the Stoic school. Stoic epistemology generally emphasized that the mind starts blank, but acquires knowledge as the outside world is impressed upon it. The doxographer Aetius summarizes this view as "When a man is born, the Stoics say, he has the commanding part of his soul like a sheet of paper ready for writing upon." Later stoics, such as Sextus of Chaeronea, would continue this idea of empiricism in later Stoic writings as well. As Sextus contends "For every thought comes from sense-perception or not without sense-perception and either from direct experience or not without direct experience" (Against the Professors, 8.56-8).

examples.text: Madonna_(entertainer): Madonna also began work on her thirteenth studio album, with collaborators including Avicii, Diplo and Natalia Kills. In December 2014, thirteen demos recorded for the album leaked onto the Internet. She posted in response that half of the tracks would not be used on the final release, while the other half had "changed and evolved". The album, titled Rebel Heart, was released on March 10, 2015. From September 2015, she embarked on the Rebel Heart Tour to promote the album; the tour ended in March 2016 and traveled throughout North America, Europe and Asia and was the singer's first visit to Australia in 23 years, where she also performed a one-off show for her fans. examples.annotated_text: Mosaic: The apse mosaic of the [dblookup('Gelati Monastery', 'Use of Mosaic Began By') -> King David IV] Gelati Monastery is a rare example of mosaic use in Georgia. Began by king David IV and completed by his son [dblookup('Gelati Monastery Mosaic', 'Completed By') -> Demetrius I of Georgia] Demetrius I of Georgia, the fragmentary panel depicts Theotokos flanked by two archangels. The use of mosaic in Gelati attests to some [dblookup('Gelati Monastery Mosaic', 'Cultural Influence') -> Byzantine] Byzantine influence in the country and was a demonstration of the imperial ambition of the Bagrationids. The mosaic covered church could compete in magnificence with the churches of [dblookup('Gelati Monastery', 'Comparable To') -> Churches of Constantinople] Constantinople. Gelati is one of few mosaic creations which survived in Georgia but fragments prove that the early churches of [dblookup('Early Georgian Churches', 'Mosaic Decorated') -> Pitsunda, Tsromi] Pitsunda and Tsromi were also decorated with mosaic as well as other, lesser known sites. The destroyed [dblookup('Pitsunda Cathedral', 'Inspiration For Mosaic Floors') -> Roman prototypes] 6th century mosaic floors in the Pitsunda Cathedral have been inspired by Roman prototypes. In Tsromi the tesserae are still visible on the walls of the [dblookup('Tsromi Church', 'Century Built') -> 7th century] 7th-century church but only faint lines hint at the original scheme. Its central figure was [dblookup('Tsromi Church Mosaic', 'Central Figure') -> Christ] Christ standing and displaying a scroll with Georgian text.
examples.text: Mosaic: The apse mosaic of the Gelati Monastery is a rare example of mosaic use in Georgia. Began by king David IV and completed by his son Demetrius I of Georgia, the fragmentary panel depicts Theotokos flanked by two archangels. The use of mosaic in Gelati attests to some Byzantine influence in the country and was a demonstration of the imperial ambition of the Bagrationids. The mosaic covered church could compete in magnificence with the churches of Constantinople. Gelati is one of few mosaic creations which survived in Georgia but fragments prove that the early churches of Pitsunda and Tsromi were also decorated with mosaic as well as other, lesser known sites. The destroyed 6th century mosaic floors in the Pitsunda Cathedral have been inspired by Roman prototypes. In Tsromi the tesserae are still visible on the walls of the 7th-century church but only faint lines hint at the original scheme. Its central figure was Christ standing and displaying a scroll with Georgian text.

examples.annotated_text: Friedrich_Hayek: In [dblookup('Friedrich Hayek', 'Departure Year from London School of Economics') -> 1950] 1950, Hayek left the [dblookup('London School of Economics', 'Former Faculty Member') -> Friedrich Hayek] London School of Economics for the [dblookup('Friedrich Hayek', 'New Institution in 1950') -> University of Chicago] University of Chicago, where he became a [dblookup('Friedrich Hayek', 'Position at University of Chicago') -> professor in the Committee on Social Thought] professor in the Committee on Social Thought. Hayek's [dblookup('Friedrich Hayek', 'Salary Source at University of Chicago') -> outside foundation] salary was funded not by the university, but by an outside foundation. [dblookup('University of Chicago', 'President in 1950') -> Robert Hutchins] University of Chicago President Robert Hutchins was in the midst of a war with the [dblookup('University of Chicago', 'Conflict Topic in 1950') -> departmental autonomy and control] U. of Chicago faculty over departmental autonomy and control, and Hayek got caught in the middle of that battle. Hutchins had been attempting to force all departments to adopt the neo-Thomist Great Books program of [dblookup('Great Books Program', 'Creator') -> Mortimer Adler] Mortimer Adler, and the U. of Chicago economists were sick of Hutchins' meddling. As the result the Economics department rejected [dblookup('University of Chicago Economics Department', 'Rejection of Hayek Hiring') -> Hutchins' pressure] Hutchins' pressure to hire Hayek, and Hayek became a part of the [dblookup('University of Chicago', 'Friedrich Hayek Affiliation') -> Committee on Social Thought] new Committee on Social Thought.
examples.text: Friedrich_Hayek: In 1950, Hayek left the London School of Economics for the University of Chicago, where he became a professor in the Committee on Social Thought. Hayek's salary was funded not by the university, but by an outside foundation. University of Chicago President Robert Hutchins was in the midst of a war with the U. of Chicago faculty over departmental autonomy and control, and Hayek got caught in the middle of that battle. Hutchins had been attempting to force all departments to adopt the neo-Thomist Great Books program of Mortimer Adler, and the U. of Chicago economists were sick of Hutchins' meddling. As the result the Economics department rejected Hutchins' pressure to hire Hayek, and Hayek became a part of the new Committee on Social Thought.

examples.annotated_text: Neptune: Neptune's more varied weather when compared to Uranus is due in part to its [dblookup('Neptune', 'Higher Internal Heating') -> Yes] higher internal heating. Although Neptune lies [dblookup('Neptune', 'Distance Relative to Uranus') -> over 50% further] over 50% further from the Sun than Uranus, and receives only 40% its amount of sunlight, the two planets' [dblookup('Neptune and Uranus', 'Surface Temperature Comparison') -> roughly equal] surface temperatures are roughly equal. The upper regions of Neptune's troposphere reach a low [dblookup('Neptune', 'Lowest Troposphere Temperature') -> 51.8 K (−221.3 °C)] temperature of 51.8 K (−221.3 °C). At a depth where the atmospheric pressure equals [dblookup('Neptune', '1 Bar Temperature') -> 72.00 K (−201.15 °C)] 1 bar (100 kPa), the temperature is 72.00 K (−201.15 °C). Deeper inside the layers of gas, the temperature rises steadily. As with Uranus, the source of this heating is unknown, but the discrepancy is larger: Uranus only radiates 1.1 times as much energy as it receives from the Sun; whereas [dblookup('Neptune', 'Energy Radiation Relative to Solar Reception') -> 2.61 times] Neptune radiates about 2.61 times as much energy as it receives from the Sun. Neptune is the farthest planet from the Sun, yet its [dblookup('Neptune', 'Fastest Planetary Winds') -> Yes] internal energy is sufficient to drive the fastest planetary winds seen in the Solar System. Depending on the thermal properties of its interior, the heat left over from Neptune's formation may be sufficient to explain [dblookup('Neptune', 'Current Heat Flow Explanation') -> Sufficient Internal Heat] its current heat flow, though it is more difficult to simultaneously explain Uranus's lack of internal heat while preserving the apparent similarity between the two planets.
examples.text: Neptune: Neptune's more varied weather when compared to Uranus is due in part to its higher internal heating. Although Neptune lies over 50% further from the Sun than Uranus, and receives only 40% its amount of sunlight, the two planets' surface temperatures are roughly equal. The upper regions of Neptune's troposphere reach a low temperature of 51.8 K (−221.3 °C). At a depth where the atmospheric pressure equals 1 bar (100 kPa), the temperature is 72.00 K (−201.15 °C). Deeper inside the layers of gas, the temperature rises steadily. As with Uranus, the source of this heating is unknown, but the discrepancy is larger: Uranus only radiates 1.1 times as much energy as it receives from the Sun; whereas Neptune radiates about 2.61 times as much energy as it receives from the Sun. Neptune is the farthest planet from the Sun, yet its internal energy is sufficient to drive the fastest planetary winds seen in the Solar System. Depending on the thermal properties of its interior, the heat left over from Neptune's formation may be sufficient to explain its current heat flow, though it is more difficult to simultaneously explain Uranus's lack of internal heat while preserving the apparent similarity between the two planets.

examples.annotated_text: Affirmative_action_in_the_United_States: The category of Native Americans applies to the diverse group of people who lived in North America before European settlement. During the U.S. government's westward expansion, [dblookup('Native Americans', 'Consequence of Westward Expansion') -> Displacement from land] Native Americans were displaced from their land which had been their home for centuries. Instead, they were forced onto reservations which were far smaller and less productive. According to Brest, land belonging to Native Americans was reduced from 138 million acres in [dblookup('Native American Land', 'Size in 1887') -> 138 million acres] 1887 to [dblookup('Native American Land', 'Size in 1934') -> 52 million acres] 52 million acres in 1934. In [dblookup('Native Americans', 'Poverty Rate Year') -> 1990] 1990, the poverty rate for Native Americans was more than triple that of the whites and only [dblookup('Native Americans', 'Bachelor\'s Degree Completion Rate in 1990') -> 9.4%] 9.4% of Native Americans have completed a bachelor's degree as opposed to [dblookup('Whites in the United States', 'Bachelor\'s Degree Completion Rate in 1990') -> 25.2%] 25.2% of whites and [dblookup('African Americans', 'Bachelor\'s Degree Completion Rate in 1990') -> 12.2%] 12.2% of African Americans.
examples.text: Affirmative_action_in_the_United_States: The category of Native American applies to the diverse group of people who lived in North America before European settlement. During the U.S. government's westward expansion, Native Americans were displaced from their land which had been their home for centuries. In 1990, the poverty rate for Native Americans was more than triple that of the whites and only 9.4% of Native Americans have completed a bachelor's degree as opposed to 25.2% of whites and 12.2% of African Americans.

examples.text: House_music: Derrick May a.k.a. examples.annotated_text: Czech_language: Czech syntax has a [dblookup('Czech_language', 'Basic Sentence Structure') -> subject–verb–object] subject–verb–object sentence structure. In practice, however, word order is flexible and used for topicalization and focus. Although Czech has a [dblookup('Czech_language', 'Passive Construction Type') -> periphrastic passive] periphrastic passive construction (like English), colloquial word-order changes frequently produce the passive voice. For example, to change "Peter killed Paul" to "Paul was killed by Peter" the order of subject and object is inverted: Petr zabil Pavla ("Peter killed Paul") becomes "Paul, Peter killed" (Pavla zabil Petr). Pavla is in the [dblookup('Pavla', 'Case') -> accusative] accusative case, the grammatical object (in this case, the victim) of the verb.
examples.text: Czech_language: Czech syntax has a subject–verb–object sentence structure. In practice, however, word order is flexible and used for topicalization and focus. Although Czech has a periphrastic passive construction (like English), colloquial word-order changes frequently produce the passive voice. For example, to change "Peter killed Paul" to "Paul was killed by Peter" the order of subject and object is inverted: Petr zabil Pavla ("Peter killed Paul") becomes "Paul, Peter killed" (Pavla zabil Petr). Pavla is in the accusative case, the grammatical object (in this case, the victim) of the verb.

examples.annotated_text: [dblookup('Kievan Rus', 'Ethnic Controversy') -> Varangians or Slavs] Controversy persists over whether the Rus’ were Varangians (Vikings) or Slavs. This uncertainty is due largely to a paucity of contemporary sources. Attempts to address this question instead rely on archaeological evidence, the accounts of foreign observers, legends and literature from centuries later. To some extent, the controversy is related to the [dblookup('Rus', 'Connection to Modern States') -> foundation myths of modern states] foundation myths of modern states in the region. According to the "Normanist" view, the Rus' were [dblookup('Normanist Theories', 'Ethnic Origin') -> Scandinavians] Scandinavians, while Russian and Ukrainian nationalist historians generally argue that the Rus' were themselves [dblookup('Nationalist Theories', 'Ethnic Origin') -> Slavs] Slavs. Normanist theories focus on the earliest written source for the East Slavs, the [dblookup('Russian Primary Chronicle', 'Significance in Normanist Theories') -> earliest written source for East Slavs] Russian Primary Chronicle, although even this account was not produced until the 12th century. Nationalist accounts have suggested that the Rus' were present before the arrival of the Varangians, noting that only a handful of Scandinavian words can be found in modern Russian and that Scandinavian names in the early chronicles were soon replaced by Slavic names. Nevertheless, archaeological evidence from the area suggests that a [dblookup('Scandinavian Archaeological Evidence', 'Presence') -> Scandinavian population during the 10th century] Scandinavian population was present during the 10th century at the latest. On balance, it seems likely that the Rus' proper were a small minority of Scandinavians who formed an elite ruling class, while the great majority of their subjects were Slavs. Considering the linguistic arguments mounted by nationalist scholars, if the proto-Rus' were Scandinavians, they must have quickly become [dblookup('Proto-Rus Assimilation', 'Cultural Adaptation') -> nativized] nativized, adopting Slavic languages and other cultural practices.

To some extent the controversy is related to the foundation myths of modern states in the region. According to the "Normanist" view, the Rus' were Scandinavians, while Russian and Ukrainian nationalist historians generally argue that the Rus' were themselves Slavs. Normanist theories focus on the earliest written source for the East Slavs, the Russian Primary Chronicle, although even this account was not produced until the 12th century. Nationalist accounts have suggested that the Rus' were present before the arrival of the Varangians, noting that only a handful of Scandinavian words can be found in modern Russian and that Scandinavian names in the early chronicles were soon replaced by Slavic names. Nevertheless, archaeological evidence from the area suggests that a Scandinavian population was present during the 10th century at the latest. On balance, it seems likely that the Rus' proper were a small minority of Scandinavians who formed an elite ruling class, while the great majority of their subjects were Slavs. Considering the linguistic arguments mounted by nationalist scholars, if the proto-Rus' were Scandinavians, they must have quickly become nativized, adopting Slavic languages and other cultural practices.

examples.annotated_text: Madrasa: However, in English, the term madrasah usually refers to [dblookup('Madrasah', 'Typical Focus') -> Islamic institutions] the specifically Islamic institutions. A typical Islamic school usually offers two courses of study: a [dblookup('Madrasah', 'Course Offered') -> ḥifẓ course] ḥifẓ course teaching memorization of the Qur'an (the person who commits the entire Qurʼan to memory is called a [dblookup('Person Memorizing Qur\'an', 'Title') -> ḥāfiẓ] ḥāfiẓ); and an [dblookup('Madrasah', 'Course Leading To') -> ʻālim course] ʻālim course leading the candidate to become an accepted scholar in the community. A regular curriculum includes courses in [dblookup('Madrasah', 'Curriculum Includes') -> Arabic, tafsir, sharīʻah, hadiths, mantiq, Muslim history] Arabic, tafsir (Qur'anic interpretation), sharīʻah (Islamic law), hadiths (recorded sayings and deeds of Muhammad), mantiq (logic), and Muslim history. In the Ottoman Empire, during the Early Modern Period, the study of hadiths was introduced by [dblookup('Study of Hadiths', 'Introduced By') -> Süleyman I] Süleyman I. Depending on the educational demands, some madaris also offer additional advanced courses in [dblookup('Madrasah', 'Additional Courses') -> Arabic literature, English, foreign languages, science, world history] Arabic literature, English and other foreign languages, as well as science and world history. Ottoman madaris along with religious teachings also taught "styles of writing, grammary, syntax, poetry, composition, natural sciences, political sciences, and etiquette."
examples.text: Madrasa: However, in English, the term madrasah usually refers to the specifically Islamic institutions. A typical Islamic school usually offers two courses of study: a ḥifẓ course teaching memorization of the Qur'an (the person who commits the entire Qurʼan to memory is called a ḥāfiẓ); and an ʻālim course leading the candidate to become an accepted scholar in the community. A regular curriculum includes courses in Arabic, tafsir (Qur'anic interpretation), sharīʻah (Islamic law), hadiths (recorded sayings and deeds of Muhammad), mantiq (logic), and Muslim history. In the Ottoman Empire, during the Early Modern Period, the study of hadiths was introduced by Süleyman I. Depending on the educational demands, some madaris also offer additional advanced courses in Arabic literature, English and other foreign languages, as well as science and world history. Ottoman madaris along with religious teachings also taught "styles of writing, grammary, syntax, poetry, composition, natural sciences, political sciences, and etiquette."

examples.annotated_text: A new device for granting [dblookup('Royal Assent', 'Device Created During Reign') -> King Henry VIII] assent was created during the reign of King Henry VIII. In 1542, Henry sought to execute his fifth wife, [dblookup('Henry VIII', 'Spouse Accused of Adultery') -> Catherine Howard] Catherine Howard, whom he accused of committing adultery; the execution was to be authorized not after a trial but by a [dblookup('Catherine Howard', 'Execution Authorized By') -> bill of attainder] bill of attainder, to which he would have to personally assent after listening to the entire text. Henry decided that "the repetition of so grievous a Story and the recital of so infamous a crime" in his presence "might reopen a Wound already closing in the Royal Bosom". Therefore, parliament inserted a clause into the [dblookup('Act of Attainder', 'Clause for Assent by Commissioners') -> 1542] Act of Attainder, providing that assent granted by Commissioners "is and ever was and ever shall be, as good" as assent granted by the sovereign personally. The procedure was used only five times during the 16th century, but more often during the [dblookup('Royal Assent by Commissioners', 'Most Used Centuries') -> 17th, 18th] 17th and 18th centuries, especially when George III's health began to deteriorate. [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Last Personal Assent Year') -> 1854] Queen Victoria became the last monarch to personally grant assent in 1854.
examples.text: Royal_assent: A new device for granting assent was created during the reign of King Henry VIII. In 1542, Henry sought to execute his fifth wife, Catherine Howard, whom he accused of committing adultery; the execution was to be authorised not after a trial but by a bill of attainder, to which he would have to personally assent after listening to the entire text. Henry decided that "the repetition of so grievous a Story and the recital of so infamous a crime" in his presence "might reopen a Wound already closing in the Royal Bosom". Therefore, parliament inserted a clause into the Act of Attainder, providing that assent granted by Commissioners "is and ever was and ever shall be, as good" as assent granted by the sovereign personally. The procedure was used only five times during the 16th century, but more often during the 17th and 18th centuries, especially when George III's health began to deteriorate. Queen Victoria became the last monarch to personally grant assent in 1854.

examples.annotated_text: To_Kill_a_Mockingbird: The origin of Tom Robinson is less clear, although many have speculated that his character was inspired by several models. When Lee was 10 years old, a white woman near Monroeville accused a black man named Walter Lett of raping her. The story and the trial were covered by [dblookup('Harper Lee', 'Father\'s Occupation') -> newspaper editor] her father's newspaper which reported that [dblookup('Walter Lett', 'Trial Outcome') -> convicted and sentenced to death] Lett was convicted and sentenced to death. After a series of letters appeared claiming Lett had been falsely accused, [dblookup('Walter Lett', 'Sentence Outcome') -> commuted to life in prison] his sentence was commuted to life in prison. He died there of [dblookup('Walter Lett', 'Cause of Death') -> tuberculosis] tuberculosis in [dblookup('Walter Lett', 'Year of Death') -> 1937] 1937. Scholars believe that Robinson's difficulties reflect the notorious [dblookup('Scottsboro Boys', 'Case Description') -> nine black men convicted of raping two white women on negligible evidence] case of the Scottsboro Boys, in which nine black men were convicted of raping two white women on negligible evidence. However, in 2005, [dblookup('Harper Lee', 'Statement About Inspiration') -> Scottsboro case served same purpose] Lee stated that she had in mind something less sensational, although the Scottsboro case served "the same purpose" to display Southern prejudices. [dblookup('Emmett Till', 'Related Event') -> murder for flirting with a white woman] Emmett Till, a black teenager who was murdered for flirting with a white woman in Mississippi in 1955, and whose death is credited as a catalyst for the Civil Rights Movement, is also considered a model for Tom Robinson.
examples.text: To_Kill_a_Mockingbird: The origin of Tom Robinson is less clear, although many have speculated that his character was inspired by several models. When Lee was 10 years old, a white woman near Monroeville accused a black man named Walter Lett of raping her. The story and the trial were covered by her father's newspaper which reported that Lett was convicted and sentenced to death. After a series of letters appeared claiming Lett had been falsely accused, his sentence was commuted to life in prison. He died there of tuberculosis in 1937. Scholars believe that Robinson's difficulties reflect the notorious case of the Scottsboro Boys, in which nine black men were convicted of raping two white women on negligible evidence. However, in 2005, Lee stated that she had in mind something less sensational, although the Scottsboro case served "the same purpose" to display Southern prejudices. Emmett Till, a black teenager who was murdered for flirting with a white woman in Mississippi in 1955, and whose death is credited as a catalyst for the Civil Rights Movement, is also considered a model for Tom Robinson.

examples.annotated_text: Electric_motor: A commutator is a mechanism used to [dblookup('Commutator', 'Function') -> switch input of DC machines and certain AC machines] switch the input of most DC machines and certain AC machines consisting of slip ring segments insulated from each other and from the electric motor's shaft. The motor's [dblookup('Electric Motor', 'Current in Armature Supplied By') -> stationary brushes] armature current is supplied through the stationary brushes in contact with the revolving commutator, which causes required current reversal. In light of significant advances in the past few decades due to improved technologies in electronic controller, sensorless control, induction motor, and permanent magnet motor fields, electromechanically commutated motors are increasingly being displaced by [dblookup('Electromechanically Commutated Motors', 'Displaced By') -> externally commutated induction and permanent-magnet motors] externally commutated induction and permanent-magnet motors.
examples.text: Electric_motor: A commutator is a mechanism used to switch the input of most DC machines and certain AC machines consisting of slip ring segments insulated from each other and from the electric motor's shaft. The motor's armature current is supplied through the stationary brushes in contact with the revolving commutator, which causes required current reversal and applies power to the machine in an optimal manner as the rotor rotates from pole to pole. In absence of such current reversal, the motor would brake to a stop. In light of significant advances in the past few decades due to improved technologies in electronic controller, sensorless control, induction motor, and permanent magnet motor fields, electromechanically commutated motors are increasingly being displaced by externally commutated induction and permanent-magnet motors.

examples.annotated_text: Montana: Average annual [dblookup('Montana', 'Average Annual Precipitation') -> 15 inches (380 mm)] precipitation is 15 inches (380 mm), but great variations are seen. The mountain ranges block the moist Pacific air, holding moisture in the western valleys, and creating rain shadows to the east. [dblookup('Heron, Montana', 'Annual Precipitation') -> 34.70 inches (881 mm)] Heron, in the west, receives the most precipitation, 34.70 inches (881 mm). On the eastern (leeward) side of a mountain range, the valleys are much drier; [dblookup('Lonepine, Montana', 'Annual Precipitation') -> 11.45 inches (291 mm)] Lonepine averages 11.45 inches (291 mm), and [dblookup('Deer Lodge, Montana', 'Annual Precipitation') -> 11.00 inches (279 mm)] Deer Lodge 11.00 inches (279 mm) of precipitation. The mountains themselves can receive over 100 inches (2,500 mm), for example the [dblookup('Grinnell Glacier', 'Annual Precipitation') -> 105 inches (2,700 mm)] Grinnell Glacier in Glacier National Park gets 105 inches (2,700 mm). An [dblookup('Belfry, Montana', 'Minimum Annual Precipitation') -> 6.59 inches (167 mm)] area southwest of Belfry averaged only 6.59 inches (167 mm) over a sixteen-year period. Most of the larger cities get [dblookup('Montana', 'Average Annual Snowfall in Cities') -> 30 to 50 inches (0.76 to 1.27 metres)] 30 to 50 inches or 0.76 to 1.27 metres of snow each year. Mountain ranges themselves can accumulate [dblookup('Montana Mountains', 'Average Annual Snowfall') -> 300 inches (7.62 metres)] 300 inches or 7.62 metres of snow during a winter. Heavy snowstorms may occur any time from September through May, though most snow falls from [dblookup('Montana', 'Peak Snowfall Months') -> November to March] November to March.

examples.annotated_text: Slavs: In the Western Balkans, [dblookup('South Slavs', 'Historical Interactions') -> intermarried with Germanic Gepids, Avar invaders] South Slavs and Germanic Gepids intermarried with Avar invaders, eventually producing a Slavicized population. In Central Europe, the Slavs intermixed with [dblookup('Central European Slavs', 'Intermixed With') -> Germanic, Celtic] Germanic and Celtic, while the [dblookup('Eastern Slavs', 'Interacted With') -> Uralic, Scandinavian] eastern Slavs encountered Uralic and Scandinavian peoples. [dblookup('Scandinavians', 'Role In Early Rus Formation') -> Involved in early Rus' state, Slavicized] Scandinavians (Varangians) and Finnic peoples were involved in the early formation of the Rus' state but were completely Slavicized after a century. Some [dblookup('Finno-Ugric Tribes', 'Assimilated Into') -> expanding Rus population] Finno-Ugric tribes in the north were also absorbed into the expanding Rus population. At the time of the [dblookup('Magyar Migration', 'Regions Affected') -> present-day Hungary] Magyar migration, the present-day Hungary was inhabited by [dblookup('Present-day Hungary', 'Inhabited By Before Magyars') -> Slavs, Romano-Dacians] Slavs, numbering about 200,000, and by Romano-Dacians who were either assimilated or enslaved by the Magyars. In the 11th and 12th centuries, constant incursions by nomadic Turkic tribes, such as the Kipchaks and the Pechenegs, caused a massive migration of East Slavic populations to the safer, heavily forested regions of the north. In the Middle Ages, groups of Saxon ore miners settled in medieval Bosnia, Serbia and Bulgaria where they were Slavicized.
examples.text: Slavs: In the Western Balkans, South Slavs and Germanic Gepids intermarried with Avar invaders, eventually producing a Slavicized population.[citation needed] In Central Europe, the Slavs intermixed with Germanic and Celtic, while the eastern Slavs encountered Uralic and Scandinavian peoples. examples.annotated_text: Brain: The two neurotransmitters that are used most widely in the [dblookup('Vertebrate Brain', 'Primary Neurotransmitters') -> glutamate, gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA)] vertebrate brain are glutamate, which almost always exerts excitatory effects on target neurons, and gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), which is almost always inhibitory. Neurons using these transmitters can be found in nearly every part of the brain. Because of their ubiquity, [dblookup('Drugs', 'Effects On Neurotransmitters') -> glutamate, GABA] drugs that act on glutamate or GABA tend to have broad and powerful effects. Some general anesthetics act by [dblookup('General Anesthetics', 'Primary Action') -> reducing glutamate effects] reducing the effects of glutamate; most tranquilizers exert their sedative effects by [dblookup('Tranquilizers', 'Primary Action') -> enhancing GABA effects] enhancing the effects of GABA.

examples.text: Oklahoma: Oklahoma is the 20th largest state in the United States, covering an area of 69,898 square miles (181,035 km2), with 68,667 square miles (177847 km2) of land and 1,281 square miles (3,188 km2) of water. examples.annotated_text: Modern history: Much of the fighting in [dblookup('World War I', 'Major Battle Area') -> Western Front] World War I took place along the Western Front, within a system of opposing manned trenches and fortifications (separated by a "No man's land") running from the [dblookup('Western Front', 'Geographical Extent') -> North Sea to the border of Switzerland] North Sea to the border of Switzerland. On the [dblookup('World War I', 'Eastern Battle Area') -> Eastern Front] Eastern Front, the vast eastern plains and limited rail network prevented a trench warfare stalemate from developing, although the scale of the conflict was just as large. Hostilities also occurred on and under the sea and—for the first time—from the air. More than [dblookup('World War I', 'Military Casualties') -> 9 million soldiers] 9 million soldiers died on the various battlefields, and nearly that many more in the participating countries' home fronts on account of food shortages and genocide committed under the cover of various civil wars and internal conflicts. Notably, more people died of the [dblookup('World War I', 'Coinciding Health Crisis') -> worldwide influenza outbreak] worldwide influenza outbreak at the end of the war and shortly after than died in the hostilities. The [dblookup('1918 Influenza Pandemic', 'Contributing Factors') -> unsanitary conditions, severe overcrowding, wartime propaganda, soldier migration] unsanitary conditions engendered by the war, severe overcrowding in barracks, wartime propaganda interfering with public health warnings, and migration of so many soldiers around the world helped the outbreak become a pandemic.
examples.text: Modern_history: Much of the fighting in World War I took place along the Western Front, within a system of opposing manned trenches and fortifications (separated by a "No man's land") running from the North Sea to the border of Switzerland. On the Eastern Front, the vast eastern plains and limited rail network prevented a trench warfare stalemate from developing, although the scale of the conflict was just as large. Hostilities also occurred on and under the sea and—for the first time—from the air. The unsanitary conditions engendered by the war, severe overcrowding in barracks, wartime propaganda interfering with public health warnings, and migration of so many soldiers around the world helped the outbreak become a pandemic.

examples.annotated_text: Aspirated_consonant: They are unaspirated for almost all speakers when immediately following word-initial s, as in spill, still, skill. After an s elsewhere in a word they are normally [dblookup('Aspirated Consonants', 'Usual State After Word-Internal S') -> unaspirated] unaspirated as well, except sometimes in compound words. When the consonants in a cluster like st are analyzed as belonging to different morphemes (heteromorphemic), [dblookup('Aspirated Consonants', 'State In Heteromorphemic Cluster') -> aspirated] the stop is aspirated, but when they are analyzed as belonging to one morpheme, [dblookup('Aspirated Consonants', 'State In Single Morpheme Cluster') -> unaspirated] the stop is unaspirated. For instance, distend has unaspirated [t] since it is not analyzed as two morphemes, but [dblookup('Word Example', 'State In Distaste') -> aspirated tʰ] distaste has an aspirated middle [tʰ] because it is analyzed as dis- + taste and the word taste has an [dblookup('Word Taste', 'Initial Consonant State') -> aspirated t] aspirated initial t.
examples.text: Aspirated_consonant: They are unaspirated for almost all speakers when immediately following word-initial s, as in spill, still, skill. After an s elsewhere in a word they are normally unaspirated as well, except sometimes in compound words. When the consonants in a cluster like st are analyzed as belonging to different morphemes (heteromorphemic) the stop is aspirated, but when they are analyzed as belonging to one morpheme the stop is unaspirated.[citation needed] For instance, distend has unaspirated [t] since it is not analyzed as two morphemes, but distaste has an aspirated middle [tʰ] because it is analyzed as dis- + taste and the word taste has an aspirated initial t.

examples.text: Armenians: Art historian Hravard Hakobyan notes that "Artsakh carpets occupy a special place in the history of Armenian carpet-making." examples.annotated_text: Premier League: Managers in the Premier League are involved in the [dblookup('Premier League Managers', 'Responsibilities') -> training, team selection, player acquisition] day-to-day running of the team, including the training, team selection, and player acquisition. examples.text: Premier_League: Managers in the Premier League are involved in the day-to-day running of the team, including the training, team selection, and player acquisition. examples.annotated_text: [dblookup('On the Origin of Species', 'Author') -> Charles Darwin] The book aroused international interest and a widespread debate, with no sharp line between scientific issues and ideological, social, and religious implications. Much of the initial reaction was hostile, but Darwin had to be taken seriously as a [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Reputation Status') -> prominent and respected name in science] prominent and respected name in science. There was much less controversy than had greeted the 1844 publication Vestiges of Creation, which had been rejected by scientists, but had influenced a wide public readership into believing that nature and human society were governed by natural laws. The Origin of Species as a book of wide general interest became associated with ideas of social reform. Its proponents made full use of a surge in the [dblookup('On the Origin of Species', 'Promotion Method') -> publication of review journals] publication of review journals, and it was given more popular attention than almost any other scientific work, though it failed to match the continuing sales of Vestiges. Darwin's book legitimised scientific discussion of evolutionary mechanisms, and the newly coined term [dblookup('Darwinism', 'Origin') -> On the Origin of Species] Darwinism was used to cover the whole range of evolutionism, not just his own ideas. By the mid- 1870s, evolutionism was triumphant.
examples.text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: The book aroused international interest and a widespread debate, with no sharp line between scientific issues and ideological, social and religious implications. The Origin of Species as a book of wide general interest became associated with ideas of social reform. Its proponents made full use of a surge in the publication of review journals, and it was given more popular attention than almost any other scientific work, though it failed to match the continuing sales of Vestiges. Darwin's book legitimised scientific discussion of evolutionary mechanisms, and the newly coined term Darwinism was used to cover the whole range of evolutionism, not just his own ideas. By the mid-1870s, evolutionism was triumphant.
