examples.annotated_text: Labour_Party_(UK): [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Role') -> Prime Minister of the United Kingdom] Clement Attlee's government proved one of the most radical British governments of the 20th century, enacting [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Economic Policies') -> Keynesian economic policies] Keynesian economic policies, presiding over a policy of [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Nationalization Policy') -> nationalising major industries and utilities] nationalizing major industries and utilities including the [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Nationalised Industries') -> Bank of England, coal mining, steel industry, electricity, gas, inland transport] Bank of England, coal mining, the steel industry, electricity, gas, and inland transport (including railways, road haulage, and canals). It [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Social Policy Development') -> developed "cradle to grave" welfare state] developed and implemented the "cradle to grave" welfare state conceived by the economist [dblookup('William Beveridge', 'Influence On') -> British welfare state] William Beveridge. To this day, the party considers the [dblookup('National Health Service', 'Established In') -> 1948] 1948 creation of Britain's publicly funded National Health Service (NHS) under health minister [dblookup('Aneurin Bevan', 'Role in NHS') -> Health Minister] Aneurin Bevan its proudest achievement. Attlee's government also began the process of [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Colonial Policy') -> dismantling the British Empire] dismantling the British Empire when it [dblookup('India and Pakistan', 'Independence Granted By') -> Clement Attlee] granted independence to India and Pakistan in [dblookup('India and Pakistan', 'Independence Year') -> 1947] 1947, followed by [dblookup('Burma (Myanmar) and Ceylon (Sri Lanka)', 'Independence Year') -> 1948] Burma (Myanmar) and Ceylon (Sri Lanka) the following year. At a secret meeting in [dblookup('Clement Attlee', 'Nuclear Development Decision Year') -> January 1947] January 1947, Attlee and six cabinet ministers, including [dblookup('Ernest Bevin', 'Position') -> Foreign Secretary] Foreign Secretary Ernest Bevin, decided to proceed with the development of [dblookup('British Nuclear Weapons Programme', 'Initiated By') -> Clement Attlee, Ernest Bevin] Britain's nuclear weapons programme, in opposition to the [dblookup('Labour Party (UK)', 'Internal Stance on Nuclear Weapons') -> pacifist, anti-nuclear] pacifist and anti-nuclear stances of a large element inside the Labour Party.
examples.text: Labour_Party_(UK): Clement Attlee's proved one of the most radical British governments of the 20th century, enacting Keynesian economic policies, presiding over a policy of nationalising major industries and utilities including the Bank of England, coal mining, the steel industry, electricity, gas, and inland transport (including railways, road haulage and canals). It developed and implemented the "cradle to grave" welfare state conceived by the economist William Beveridge. To this day, the party considers the 1948 creation of Britain's publicly funded National Health Service (NHS) under health minister Aneurin Bevan its proudest achievement. Attlee's government also began the process of dismantling the British Empire when it granted independence to India and Pakistan in 1947, followed by Burma (Myanmar) and Ceylon (Sri Lanka) the following year. At a secret meeting in January 1947, Attlee and six cabinet ministers, including Foreign Secretary Ernest Bevin, decided to proceed with the development of Britain's nuclear weapons programme, in opposition to the pacifist and anti-nuclear stances of a large element inside the Labour Party.

examples.annotated_text: Intellectual_property: Trade secret misappropriation is different from violations of other intellectual property laws, since by definition trade secrets are secret, while patents and registered copyrights and trademarks are [dblookup('Patents', 'Availability') -> publicly available] publicly available. In the United States, [dblookup('Trade Secrets', 'Protection Under') -> state law] trade secrets are protected under state law, and states have nearly universally adopted the [dblookup('Uniform Trade Secrets Act', 'Adoption By States') -> nearly universal] Uniform Trade Secrets Act. The United States also has [dblookup('Trade Secrets', 'Federal Law') -> Economic Espionage Act of 1996] federal law in the form of the Economic Espionage Act of 1996 (18 U.S.C. §§ 1831–1839), which makes the theft or misappropriation of a trade secret a [dblookup('Trade Secret Misappropriation', 'Criminal Status') -> federal crime] federal crime. This law contains two provisions criminalizing two sorts of activity. The first, [dblookup('18 U.S.C. § 1831(a)', 'Criminalizes') -> theft of trade secrets to benefit foreign powers] 18 U.S.C. § 1831(a), criminalizes the theft of trade secrets to benefit foreign powers. The second, [dblookup('18 U.S.C. § 1832', 'Criminalizes') -> theft for commercial or economic purposes] 18 U.S.C. § 1832, criminalizes their theft for commercial or economic purposes. (The statutory penalties are different for the two offenses.) In Commonwealth common law jurisdictions, [dblookup('Trade Secrets', 'Legal Status in Commonwealth') -> equitable right] confidentiality and trade secrets are regarded as an equitable right rather than a property right, but penalties for theft are roughly the same as the United States.
examples.text: Intellectual_property: Trade secret misappropriation is different from violations of other intellectual property laws, since by definition trade secrets are secret, while patents and registered copyrights and trademarks are publicly available. In the United States, trade secrets are protected under state law, and states have nearly universally adopted the Uniform Trade Secrets Act. The United States also has federal law in the form of the Economic Espionage Act of 1996 (18 U.S.C. §§ 1831–1839), which makes the theft or misappropriation of a trade secret a federal crime. This law contains two provisions criminalizing two sorts of activity. The first, 18 U.S.C. § 1831(a), criminalizes the theft of trade secrets to benefit foreign powers. The second, 18 U.S.C. § 1832, criminalizes their theft for commercial or economic purposes. (The statutory penalties are different for the two offenses.) In Commonwealth common law jurisdictions, confidentiality and trade secrets are regarded as an equitable right rather than a property right but penalties for theft are roughly the same as the United States.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Symbiosis: Some symbiotic relationships are [dblookup('Symbiotic Relationships', 'Obligate Example') -> lichens] obligate, meaning that both symbionts entirely depend on each other for survival. For example, many lichens consist of [dblookup('Lichens', 'Components') -> fungal and photosynthetic symbionts] fungal and photosynthetic symbionts that cannot live on their own. Others are [dblookup('Symbiotic Relationships', 'Facultative Example') -> facultative] facultative (optional): they can, but do not have to live with the other organism.

examples.annotated_text: An MP3 file is made up of MP3 frames, which consist of a [dblookup('MP3 Frame', 'Components') -> header, data block] header and a data block. This sequence of frames is called an [dblookup('MP3 Frames', 'Collection Term') -> elementary stream] elementary stream. Due to the "byte reservoir", frames are not independent items and cannot usually be extracted on arbitrary frame boundaries. The MP3 Data blocks contain the (compressed) audio information in terms of [dblookup('MP3 Data Blocks', 'Content Type') -> frequencies, amplitudes] frequencies and amplitudes. The diagram shows that the MP3 Header consists of a [dblookup('MP3 Header', 'Components') -> sync word, MPEG indicator, layer indicator] sync word, which is used to identify the beginning of a valid frame. This is followed by a bit indicating that this is the MPEG standard and two bits that indicate that layer 3 is used; hence MPEG-1 Audio Layer 3 or MP3. After this, the values will differ, depending on the MP3 file. ISO/IEC 11172-3 defines the range of values for each section of the header along with the specification of the header. Most MP3 files today contain ID3 metadata, which precedes or follows the MP3 frames, as noted in the diagram.

examples.annotated_text: Liberia: In [dblookup('American Colonization Society', 'Initiated Colonization Year') -> 1822] 1822, the American Colonization Society began sending African-American volunteers to the Pepper Coast to [dblookup('American Colonization Society', 'Purpose of Colonization') -> establish a colony for freed African Americans] establish a colony for freed African Americans. By [dblookup('American Colonization Society', 'Migration By Year') -> 1867] 1867, the ACS (and state-related chapters) had assisted in the migration of more than [dblookup('American Colonization Society', 'Migrants Number') -> 13,000] 13,000 African Americans to [dblookup('Destination of American Colonization Society', 'Destination Country') -> Liberia] Liberia. These free African Americans and their descendants married within their community and came to identify as [dblookup('African Americans in Liberia', 'Ethnic Identity') -> Americo-Liberians] Americo-Liberians. Many were of mixed race and educated in [dblookup('Americo-Liberians', 'Cultural Influence') -> American culture] American culture; they did not identify with the [dblookup('Americo-Liberians', 'Distinction From') -> indigenous natives of the tribes] indigenous natives of the tribes they encountered. They intermarried largely within the colonial community, developing an ethnic group that had a cultural tradition infused with [dblookup('Americo-Liberians', 'Cultural Characteristics') -> American notions of political republicanism and Protestant Christianity] American notions of political republicanism and Protestant Christianity.
examples.text: Liberia: In 1822, the American Colonization Society began sending African-American volunteers to the Pepper Coast to establish a colony for freed African Americans. By 1867, the ACS (and state-related chapters) had assisted in the migration of more than 13,000 African Americans to Liberia. These free African Americans and their descendants married within their community and came to identify as Americo-Liberians. Many were of mixed race and educated in American culture; they did not identify with the indigenous natives of the tribes they encountered. They intermarried largely within the colonial community, developing an ethnic group that had a cultural tradition infused with American notions of political republicanism and Protestant Christianity.

examples.annotated_text: States_of_Germany: The municipalities have two major policy responsibilities. First, they administer programs authorized by the [dblookup('Federal Republic of Germany', 'Government Levels') -> federal government] federal or [dblookup('States of Germany', 'Government Levels') -> state government] state government. Such programs typically relate to youth, schools, public health, and social assistance. Second, Article 28(2) of the Basic Law guarantees the municipalities "the right to regulate on their own responsibility all the affairs of the local community within the limits set by law." Under this broad statement of competence, local governments can justify a wide range of activities. For instance, many municipalities [dblookup('Municipal Activities in Germany', 'Economic Development') -> develop industrial trading estates] develop and expand the economic infrastructure of their communities through the development of industrial trading estates.

examples.annotated_text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: Darwin's barnacle studies convinced him that variation arose constantly and not just in response to changed circumstances. In [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Beagle-Related Writing Completion Year') -> 1854] 1854, he completed the last part of his Beagle-related writing and began working full-time on [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Primary Focus After 1854') -> Evolution] evolution. His thinking changed from the view that species formed in isolated populations only, as on islands, to an emphasis on [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Emphasis on Speciation') -> Speciation without isolation] speciation without isolation; that is, he saw increasing specialization within large stable populations as continuously exploiting new ecological niches. He conducted empirical research focusing on difficulties with his theory. He studied the developmental and anatomical differences between different breeds of many domestic animals, became actively involved in [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Involvement in Breeding') -> Fancy pigeon breeding] fancy pigeon breeding, and experimented (with the help of his son Francis) on ways that plant seeds and animals might disperse across oceans to colonize distant islands. By [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Sophistication of Theory Year') -> 1856] 1856, his theory was much more sophisticated, with a mass of supporting evidence.
examples.text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: Darwin's barnacle studies convinced him that variation arose constantly and not just in response to changed circumstances. In 1854, he completed the last part of his Beagle-related writing and began working full-time on evolution. His thinking changed from the view that species formed in isolated populations only, as on islands, to an emphasis on speciation without isolation; that is, he saw increasing specialisation within large stable populations as continuously exploiting new ecological niches. He conducted empirical research focusing on difficulties with his theory. He studied the developmental and anatomical differences between different breeds of many domestic animals, became actively involved in fancy pigeon breeding, and experimented (with the help of his son Francis) on ways that plant seeds and animals might disperse across oceans to colonise distant islands. By 1856, his theory was much more sophisticated, with a mass of supporting evidence.

examples.annotated_text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, [dblookup('United States', 'Current Account Deficit Increase') -> $650 billion] the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from [dblookup('United States', 'Current Account Deficit as Percentage of GDP 1996') -> 1.5%] 1.5% to [dblookup('United States', 'Current Account Deficit as Percentage of GDP 2004') -> 5.8%] 5.8% of GDP. Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from [dblookup('United States Current Account Deficit', 'Primary Surplus Sources') -> Emerging economies in Asia, Oil-exporting nations] countries running trade surpluses. These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations. The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the [dblookup('United States', 'Deficit and Surplus Balance Requirement') -> Current account deficit, Capital account surplus] U.S.) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount. Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the [dblookup('United States', 'Foreign Capital Inflow Purpose') -> Finance imports] U.S. to finance its imports.

However, the ratings rebounded for the [dblookup('American Idol', 'Season Seven Finale Viewership Rank') -> third most-watched finale] season seven finale with the excitement over the battle of the Davids, and improved over season six as the series' third most watched finale. The strong finish of season seven also helped [dblookup('Fox Television Network', 'Most Watched Network Rank') -> first time since its inception] Fox become the most watched TV network in the country for the first time since its inception, a first ever in American television history for a non-Big Three major broadcast network. examples.text: American_Idol: The loss of viewers continued into season seven. The premiere was down 11% among total viewers, and the results show in which Kristy Lee Cook was eliminated delivered its lowest-rated Wednesday show among the 18–34 demo since the first season in 2002. However, the ratings rebounded for the season seven finale with the excitement over the battle of the Davids, and improved over season six as the series' third most watched finale. examples.annotated_text: Antibiotics: Antibiotics are screened for [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Screening Purpose') -> negative effects on humans or other mammals] any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are usually considered [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'General Safety Assessment') -> safe and most are well tolerated] safe and most are well tolerated. However, some antibiotics have been associated with [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Potential Side Effects') -> range of adverse side effects] a range of adverse side effects. Side-effects range from mild to very serious depending on the [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Factors Influencing Side Effects') -> antibiotics used, microbial organisms targeted, individual patient] antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Side Effects Causes') -> pharmacological or toxicological properties, hypersensitivity reactions, anaphylaxis] pharmacological or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or may involve hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. Safety profiles of [dblookup('Newer Antibiotics', 'Safety Profile Status') -> not as well established] newer drugs are often not as well established as for those that have a long history of use. Adverse effects range from [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Adverse Effects Example') -> fever, nausea, major allergic reactions, photodermatitis, anaphylaxis] fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side-effects include [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Common Side Effect') -> diarrhea] diarrhea, resulting from disruption of the species composition in the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in [dblookup('Clostridium difficile', 'Overgrowth Cause') -> disruption of intestinal flora by antibiotics] overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibacterials can also affect the [dblookup('Antibiotics', 'Effect On Vaginal Flora') -> may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida] vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side-effects can result from [dblookup('Antibiotics and Other Drugs', 'Potential Interaction Risk') -> elevated risk of tendon damage] interaction with other drugs, such as elevated risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have hypothesized that the [dblookup('Indiscriminate Use of Antibiotics', 'Associated Risk') -> alteration of host microbiota] indiscriminate use of antibiotics alter the host microbiota and this has been associated with [dblookup('Altered Microbiota', 'Related Health Issues') -> chronic disease] chronic disease.
examples.text: Antibiotics: Antibiotics are screened for any negative effects on humans or other mammals before approval for clinical use, and are usually considered safe and most are well tolerated. However, some antibiotics have been associated with a range of adverse side effects. Side-effects range from mild to very serious depending on the antibiotics used, the microbial organisms targeted, and the individual patient. Side effects may reflect the pharmacological or toxicological properties of the antibiotic or may involve hypersensitivity reactions or anaphylaxis. Safety profiles of newer drugs are often not as well established as for those that have a long history of use. Adverse effects range from fever and nausea to major allergic reactions, including photodermatitis and anaphylaxis. Common side-effects include diarrhea, resulting from disruption of the species composition in the intestinal flora, resulting, for example, in overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria, such as Clostridium difficile. Antibacterials can also affect the vaginal flora, and may lead to overgrowth of yeast species of the genus Candida in the vulvo-vaginal area. Additional side-effects can result from interaction with other drugs, such as elevated risk of tendon damage from administration of a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid. Some scientists have hypothesized that the indiscriminate use of antibiotics alter the host microbiota and this has been associated with chronic disease.

examples.annotated_text: Textual_criticism: The process of selectio resembles [dblookup('Selectio', 'Comparison To') -> eclectic textual criticism] eclectic textual criticism, but applied to a restricted set of hypothetical [dblookup('Selectio', 'Application To') -> hyparchetypes] hyparchetypes. The steps of examinatio and emendatio resemble [dblookup('Examinatio and Emendatio', 'Comparison To') -> copy-text editing] copy-text editing. In fact, the other techniques can be seen as special cases of [dblookup('Other Techniques', 'Special Case Of') -> stemmatics] stemmatics in which a rigorous family history of the text cannot be determined but only approximated. If it seems that one manuscript is by far the best text, then copy text editing is appropriate, and if it seems that a group of manuscripts are good, then [dblookup('Group of Manuscripts', 'Proper Method') -> eclecticism] eclecticism on that group would be proper.

If it seems that one manuscript is by far the best text, then copy text editing is appropriate, and if it seems that a group of manuscripts are good, then eclecticism on that group would be proper.

examples.annotated_text: Predation: An alternative view offered by [dblookup('Richard Dawkins', 'Perspective On Predation') -> form of competition] Richard Dawkins is of predation as a form of competition: the genes of both the predator and prey are competing for the body (or 'survival machine') of the prey organism. This is best understood in the context of the [dblookup('Gene-centered view of evolution', 'Associated With') -> Richard Dawkins] gene centered view of evolution. Another manner in which predation and competition are connected is throughout [dblookup('Intraguild Predation', 'Definition') -> predation where predators kill and eat other predators at the same trophic level] intraguild predation. Intraguild predators are those that kill and eat other predators of different species at the same trophic level, and thus that are potential competitors.

examples.annotated_text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: Evolution had less obvious applications to anatomy and morphology, and at first had little impact on the research of the anatomist [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Profession') -> Anatomist] Thomas Henry Huxley. Despite this, [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Support For') -> Darwin on evolution] Huxley strongly supported Darwin on evolution; though he called for experiments to show whether natural selection could form new species, and questioned if Darwin's gradualism was sufficient without sudden leaps to cause speciation. Huxley wanted [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Advocacy For') -> Secular Science] science to be secular, without religious interference, and his article in the April [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Westminster Review Article Date') -> 1860] 1860 Westminster Review promoted [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Advocacy For') -> Scientific Naturalism] scientific naturalism over natural theology, praising Darwin for "extending the domination of Science over regions of thought into which she has, as yet, hardly penetrated" and coining the term [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Coining Of Term') -> Darwinism] "Darwinism" as part of his efforts to secularise and professionalise science. Huxley gained influence, and initiated the [dblookup('Thomas Henry Huxley', 'Founding Of') -> X Club] X Club, which used the journal [dblookup('X Club', 'Use Of Journal') -> Nature] Nature to promote evolution and naturalism, shaping much of late Victorian science. Later, the German morphologist [dblookup('Ernst Haeckel', 'Profession') -> Morphologist] Ernst Haeckel would convince Huxley that comparative anatomy and palaeontology could be used to reconstruct evolutionary genealogies.
examples.text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: Evolution had less obvious applications to anatomy and morphology, and at first had little impact on the research of the anatomist Thomas Henry Huxley. Despite this, Huxley strongly supported Darwin on evolution; though he called for experiments to show whether natural selection could form new species, and questioned if Darwin's gradualism was sufficient without sudden leaps to cause speciation. Huxley wanted science to be secular, without religious interference, and his article in the April 1860 Westminster Review promoted scientific naturalism over natural theology, praising Darwin for "extending the domination of Science over regions of thought into which she has, as yet, hardly penetrated" and coining the term "Darwinism" as part of his efforts to secularise and professionalise science. Huxley gained influence, and initiated the X Club, which used the journal Nature to promote evolution and naturalism, shaping much of late Victorian science. Later, the German morphologist Ernst Haeckel would convince Huxley that comparative anatomy and palaeontology could be used to reconstruct evolutionary genealogies.

examples.annotated_text: Eton_College: Until 18 December 2010, Eton College was an exempt charity under English law (Charities Act 1993, Schedule 2). Under the provisions of the [dblookup('Eton College', 'Charity Act') -> Charities Act 2006], it is now an [dblookup('Eton College', 'Current Charity Status') -> excepted charity] excepted charity, and fully registered with the [dblookup('Eton College', 'Regulatory Body') -> Charities Commission] Charities Commission, and is now one of the [dblookup('Eton College', 'Charity Ranking in UK') -> 100 largest charities] 100 largest charities in the UK. As a charity, it benefits from [dblookup('Eton College', 'Tax Benefit') -> substantial tax breaks] substantial tax breaks. It was calculated by the late David Jewell, former Master of Haileybury, that in [dblookup('Eton College', 'Tax Savings per Pupil in 1992') -> £1,945] 1992 such tax breaks saved the School about £1,945 per pupil per year, although he had no direct connection with the School. This subsidy has declined since the 2001 abolition by the Labour Government of state-funded scholarships (formerly known as "assisted places") to independent schools. However, no child attended Eton on this scheme, meaning that the actual level of state assistance to the School has always been lower. Eton's retiring Head Master, [dblookup('Tony Little', 'Position') -> Head Master of Eton College] Tony Little, has claimed that the benefits that Eton provides to the local community free of charge (use of its facilities, etc.) have a higher value than the tax breaks it receives as a result of its charitable status. The fee for the academic year [dblookup('Eton College', 'Fee 2010-2011') -> £29,862] 2010–2011 was £29,862 (approximately US$48,600 or €35,100 as of March 2011), although the sum is considerably lower for those pupils on bursaries and scholarships.
examples.text: Eton_College: Until 18 December 2010, Eton College was an exempt charity under English law (Charities Act 1993, Schedule 2). Under the provisions of the Charities Act 2006, it is now an excepted charity, and fully registered with the Charities Commission, and is now one of the 100 largest charities in the UK. As a charity, it benefits from substantial tax breaks. It was calculated by the late David Jewell, former Master of Haileybury, that in 1992 such tax breaks saved the School about £1,945 per pupil per year, although he had no direct connection with the School. This subsidy has declined since the 2001 abolition by the Labour Government of state-funded scholarships (formerly known as "assisted places") to independent schools. However, no child attended Eton on this scheme, meaning that the actual level of state assistance to the School has always been lower. Eton's retiring Head Master, Tony Little, has claimed that the benefits that Eton provides to the local community free of charge (use of its facilities, etc.) have a higher value than the tax breaks it receives as a result of its charitable status. The fee for the academic year 2010–2011 was £29,862 (approximately US$48,600 or €35,100 as of March 2011), although the sum is considerably lower for those pupils on bursaries and scholarships.

examples.annotated_text: British_Empire: The British Empire comprised the dominions, colonies, protectorates, mandates and other territories ruled or administered by the [dblookup('British Empire', 'Ruling Entity') -> United Kingdom] United Kingdom. It originated with the overseas possessions and trading posts established by [dblookup('British Empire', 'Originating Nation') -> England] England between the late 16th and early 18th centuries. At its height, it was [dblookup('British Empire', 'Historical Status') -> largest empire in history] the largest empire in history and, for over a century, was the foremost global power. By [dblookup('British Empire', 'Peak Year') -> 1922] 1922, the British Empire held sway over about [dblookup('British Empire', 'Population at Peak') -> 458 million people] 458 million people, one-fifth of the world's population at the time, and covered more than [dblookup('British Empire', 'Area at Peak') -> 13,000,000 sq mi] 13,000,000 sq mi (33,670,000 km2), almost a quarter of the Earth's total land area. As a result, [dblookup('British Empire', 'Cultural Influence') -> widespread political, legal, linguistic, cultural legacy] its political, legal, linguistic and cultural legacy is widespread. At the peak of its power, the phrase [dblookup('British Empire', 'Famous Phrase') -> the empire on which the sun never sets] "the empire on which the sun never sets" was often used to describe the British Empire, because its expanse around the globe meant that the sun was always shining on at least one of its territories.
examples.text: British_Empire: The British Empire comprised the dominions, colonies, protectorates, mandates and other territories ruled or administered by the United Kingdom. It originated with the overseas possessions and trading posts established by England between the late 16th and early 18th centuries. At its height, it was the largest empire in history and, for over a century, was the foremost global power. By 1922 the British Empire held sway over about 458 million people, one-fifth of the world's population at the time, and covered more than 13,000,000 sq mi (33,670,000 km2), almost a quarter of the Earth's total land area. As a result, its political, legal, linguistic and cultural legacy is widespread. At the peak of its power, the phrase "the empire on which the sun never sets" was often used to describe the British Empire, because its expanse around the globe meant that the sun was always shining on at least one of its territories.

examples.text: Samurai: By the end of the 12th century, samurai became almost entirely synonymous with bushi, and the word was closely associated with the middle and upper echelons of the warrior class. examples.annotated_text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: In September 2008, the crisis hit its most critical stage. There was the equivalent of a [dblookup('Financial Crisis of 2007-2008', 'Event') -> bank run on the money market funds] bank run on the money market funds, which frequently invest in commercial paper issued by corporations to fund their operations and payrolls. Withdrawal from money markets were [dblookup('Money Market Withdrawals', 'Amount During Crisis Week') -> $144.5 billion] $144.5 billion during one week, versus [dblookup('Money Market Withdrawals', 'Amount Prior Week') -> $7.1 billion] $7.1 billion the week prior. This interrupted the ability of corporations to rollover (replace) their short-term debt. The U.S. government responded by extending insurance for money market accounts analogous to bank deposit insurance via a temporary guarantee and with [dblookup('Federal Reserve', 'Programs During Financial Crisis 2007-2008') -> programs to purchase commercial paper] Federal Reserve programs to purchase commercial paper. The [dblookup('TED Spread', 'Record Level on October 10, 2008') -> 4.65%] TED spread, an indicator of perceived credit risk in the general economy, spiked up in July 2007, remained volatile for a year, then spiked even higher in [dblookup('TED Spread', 'Spike Month') -> September 2008] September 2008, reaching a record 4.65% on [dblookup('TED Spread', 'Record Date') -> October 10, 2008] October 10, 2008.
examples.text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: In September 2008, the crisis hit its most critical stage. There was the equivalent of a bank run on the money market funds, which frequently invest in commercial paper issued by corporations to fund their operations and payrolls. Withdrawal from money markets were $144.5 billion during one week, versus $7.1 billion the week prior. This interrupted the ability of corporations to rollover (replace) their short-term debt. The U.S. government responded by extending insurance for money market accounts analogous to bank deposit insurance via a temporary guarantee and with Federal Reserve programs to purchase commercial paper. The TED spread, an indicator of perceived credit risk in the general economy, spiked up in July 2007, remained volatile for a year, then spiked even higher in September 2008, reaching a record 4.65% on October 10, 2008.

examples.annotated_text: Serbo-Croatian: In addition, like most [dblookup('Shtokavian dialect', 'Language Family') -> Slavic languages] Slavic languages, the Shtokavian verb also has one of two aspects: perfective or imperfective. Most verbs come in pairs, with the perfective verb being created out of the imperfective by adding a prefix or making a stem change. The [dblookup('Shtokavian imperfective aspect', 'Indicative Actions') -> unfinished, in progress, repetitive] imperfective aspect typically indicates that the action is unfinished, in progress, or repetitive; while the [dblookup('Shtokavian perfective aspect', 'Indicative Actions') -> completed, instantaneous, limited duration] perfective aspect typically denotes that the action was completed, instantaneous, or of limited duration. Some Štokavian tenses (namely, aorist and imperfect) favor a particular aspect (but they are rarer or absent in Čakavian and Kajkavian). Actually, aspects "compensate" for the relative lack of tenses, because aspect of the verb determines whether the act is completed or in progress in the referred time.

examples.annotated_text: Clothing: Scientists are still debating when people started wearing clothes. Ralf Kittler, Manfred Kayser and Mark Stoneking, anthropologists at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology, have conducted a genetic analysis of human body lice that suggests [dblookup('Clothing Origin Hypothesis', 'Estimated Date') -> 170,000 years ago] clothing originated quite recently, around 170,000 years ago. Body lice is an indicator of clothes-wearing, since most humans have sparse body hair, and lice thus require human clothing to survive. Their research suggests the [dblookup('Invention of Clothing', 'Coincided With') -> Northward Migration of Homo sapiens] invention of clothing may have coincided with the northward migration of modern Homo sapiens away from the warm climate of Africa, thought to have begun between 50,000 and 100,000 years ago. However, a [dblookup('Clothing Origin Hypothesis', 'Alternate Estimated Date') -> 540,000 years ago] second group of researchers using similar genetic methods estimate that clothing originated around 540,000 years ago (Reed et al. 2004. PLoS Biology 2(11): e340). For now, the [dblookup('Origin of Clothing', 'Resolution Status') -> Unresolved] date of the origin of clothing remains unresolved.[citation needed]
examples.text: Clothing: Scientists are still debating when people started wearing clothes. Ralf Kittler, Manfred Kayser and Mark Stoneking, anthropologists at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology, have conducted a genetic analysis of human body lice that suggests clothing originated quite recently, around 170,000 years ago. Body lice is an indicator of clothes-wearing, since most humans have sparse body hair, and lice thus require human clothing to survive. Their research suggests the invention of clothing may have coincided with the northward migration of modern Homo sapiens away from the warm climate of Africa, thought to have begun between 50,000 and 100,000 years ago. However, a second group of researchers using similar genetic methods estimate that clothing originated around 540,000 years ago (Reed et al. 2004. PLoS Biology 2(11): e340). For now, the date of the origin of clothing remains unresolved.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Political_philosophy: These theorists were driven by two basic questions: one, by what right or need do people form states; and two, what the best form for a state could be. These fundamental questions involved a conceptual distinction between the concepts of "state" and "government." It was decided that "state" would refer to a [dblookup('State', 'Definition') -> set of enduring institutions through which power is distributed and justified] set of enduring institutions through which power would be distributed and its use justified. The term "government" would refer to a [dblookup('Government', 'Definition') -> specific group of people who occupy state institutions and create laws] specific group of people who occupied the institutions of the state, and create the laws and ordinances by which the people, themselves included, would be bound. This conceptual distinction continues to operate in political science, although some political scientists, philosophers, historians and cultural anthropologists have argued that most political action in any given society occurs outside of its state, and that there are [dblookup('Political Societies', 'Without States') -> societies not organized into states] societies that are not organized into states that nevertheless must be considered in political terms. As long as the concept of natural order was not introduced, the social sciences could not [dblookup('Social Sciences', 'Evolution Dependency') -> evolve independently of theistic thinking] evolve independently of theistic thinking. Since the cultural revolution of the 17th century in England, which spread to [dblookup('Cultural Revolution', 'Spread To') -> France and the rest of Europe] France and the rest of Europe, society has been considered subject to [dblookup('Society', 'Subject To') -> natural laws akin to the physical world] natural laws akin to the physical world.
examples.text: Political_philosophy: These theorists were driven by two basic questions: one, by what right or need do people form states; and two, what the best form for a state could be. These fundamental questions involved a conceptual distinction between the concepts of "state" and "government." It was decided that "state" would refer to a set of enduring institutions through which power would be distributed and its use justified. The term "government" would refer to a specific group of people who occupied the institutions of the state, and create the laws and ordinances by which the people, themselves included, would be bound. This conceptual distinction continues to operate in political science, although some political scientists, philosophers, historians and cultural anthropologists have argued that most political action in any given society occurs outside of its state, and that there are societies that are not organized into states that nevertheless must be considered in political terms. As long as the concept of natural order was not introduced, the social sciences could not evolve independently of theistic thinking. Since the cultural revolution of the 17th century in England, which spread to France and the rest of Europe, society has been considered subject to natural laws akin to the physical world.

examples.annotated_text: Idealism: Friedrich Nietzsche argued that [dblookup('Immanuel Kant', 'Critique By') -> Friedrich Nietzsche] Kant commits an agnostic tautology and does not offer a satisfactory answer as to the source of a philosophical right to such-or-other metaphysical claims; he ridicules his pride in tackling "the most difficult thing that could ever be undertaken on behalf of metaphysics." The famous "thing-in-itself" was called a product of philosophical habit, which seeks to introduce a grammatical subject: because wherever there is cognition, there must be a thing that is cognized and allegedly it must be added to ontology as a being (whereas, to Nietzsche, only the world as ever-changing appearances can be assumed). Yet he attacks the [dblookup('Arthur Schopenhauer', 'Critique By') -> Friedrich Nietzsche] idealism of Schopenhauer and [dblookup('René Descartes', 'Critique By') -> Friedrich Nietzsche] Descartes with an argument similar to [dblookup('Immanuel Kant', 'Critique Of Descartes') -> Critique of the latter] Kant's critique of the latter (see above).
examples.text: Idealism: Friedrich Nietzsche argued that Kant commits an agnostic tautology and does not offer a satisfactory answer as to the source of a philosophical right to such-or-other metaphysical claims; he ridicules his pride in tackling "the most difficult thing that could ever be undertaken on behalf of metaphysics." The famous "thing-in-itself" was called a product of philosophical habit, which seeks to introduce a grammatical subject: because wherever there is cognition, there must be a thing that is cognized and allegedly it must be added to ontology as a being (whereas, to Nietzsche, only the world as ever changing appearances can be assumed). Yet he attacks the idealism of Schopenhauer and Descartes with an argument similar to Kant's critique of the latter (see above).

examples.annotated_text: Ashkenazi_Jews: A 2001 study by [dblookup('Nebel et al.', 'Study Conclusion') -> Shared paternal Near Eastern ancestries among Jewish populations] Nebel et al. showed that both [dblookup('Ashkenazi Jews', 'Paternal Ancestry') -> Near Eastern] Ashkenazi and Sephardic Jewish populations share the same overall paternal Near Eastern ancestries. In comparison with data available from other relevant populations in the region, Jews were found to be more closely related to groups in the north of the [dblookup('Ashkenazi Jews', 'Close Ancestral Relation') -> Fertile Crescent] Fertile Crescent. The authors also report on Eu 19 (R1a) chromosomes, which are very frequent in Central and Eastern Europeans (54%–60%) at elevated frequency ( 12.7%) in Ashkenazi Jews. They hypothesized that the differences among Ashkenazim Jews could reflect low-level [dblookup('Ashkenazi Jews', 'Possible Gene Flow From') -> European populations] gene flow from surrounding European populations and/or genetic drift during isolation. A later 2005 study by [dblookup('Nebel et al.', '2005 Study Finding') -> 11.5% of male Ashkenazim belonging to R1a1a (M17+)] Nebel et al., found a similar level of 11.5% of male Ashkenazim belonging to R1a1a (M17+), the dominant Y-chromosome haplogroup in Central and Eastern Europeans.
examples.text: Ashkenazi_Jews: A 2001 study by Nebel et al. showed that both Ashkenazi and Sephardic Jewish populations share the same overall paternal Near Eastern ancestries. In comparison with data available from other relevant populations in the region, Jews were found to be more closely related to groups in the north of the Fertile Crescent. The authors also report on Eu 19 (R1a) chromosomes, which are very frequent in Central and Eastern Europeans (54%–60%) at elevated frequency (12.7%) in Ashkenazi Jews. They hypothesized that the differences among Ashkenazim Jews could reflect low-level gene flow from surrounding European populations and/or genetic drift during isolation. A later 2005 study by Nebel et al., found a similar level of 11.5% of male Ashkenazim belonging to R1a1a (M17+), the dominant Y-chromosome haplogroup in Central and Eastern Europeans.

examples.annotated_text: Mammal: The word "mammal" is modern, from the scientific name [dblookup('Mammal', 'Scientific Name Coined By') -> Mammalia] Mammalia coined by [dblookup('Mammalia', 'Coined By') -> Carl Linnaeus] Carl Linnaeus in [dblookup('Mammalia', 'Coined In Year') -> 1758] 1758, derived from the Latin [dblookup('Mammalia', 'Derived From Latin Term') -> mamma] mamma ("teat, pap"). All female mammals nurse their young with milk, which is secreted from special glands, the mammary glands. According to [dblookup('Mammal Species of the World', 'Number of Known Species in 2006') -> 5,416] Mammal Species of the World, 5,416 species were known in 2006. These were grouped in [dblookup('Mammal Species of the World', 'Number of Genera in 2006') -> 1,229] 1,229 genera, [dblookup('Mammal Species of the World', 'Number of Families in 2006') -> 153] 153 families and [dblookup('Mammal Species of the World', 'Number of Orders in 2006') -> 29] 29 orders. In 2008, the [dblookup('IUCN', 'Global Mammal Assessment Year') -> 2008] IUCN completed a five-year, 1,700-scientist Global Mammal Assessment for its [dblookup('IUCN Red List', 'Accepted Species Count in 2008') -> 5,488] IUCN Red List, which counted 5,488 accepted species.
examples.text: Mammal: The word "mammal" is modern, from the scientific name Mammalia coined by Carl Linnaeus in 1758, derived from the Latin mamma ("teat, pap"). All female mammals nurse their young with milk, which is secreted from special glands, the mammary glands. According to Mammal Species of the World, 5,416 species were known in 2006. These were grouped in 1,229 genera, 153 families and 29 orders. In 2008 the IUCN completed a five-year, 1,700-scientist Global Mammal Assessment for its IUCN Red List, which counted 5,488 accepted species.

examples.annotated_text: Bird: A dearth of field observations limits our knowledge, but intraspecific conflicts are known to sometimes result in injury or death. The screamers ([dblookup('Screamers', 'Scientific Family Name') -> Anhimidae] Anhimidae), some jacanas ( Jacana, Hydrophasianus), the spur-winged goose ([dblookup('Spur-winged Goose', 'Scientific Name') -> Plectropterus] Plectropterus), the torrent duck ([dblookup('Torrent Duck', 'Scientific Name') -> Merganetta] Merganetta) and nine species of lapwing ([dblookup('Lapwings', 'Genera with Weaponized Wing Spurs') -> Vanellus] Vanellus) use a sharp spur on the wing as a weapon. The steamer ducks ([dblookup('Steamer Ducks', 'Genus') -> Tachyeres] Tachyeres), geese and swans ([dblookup('Geese and Swans', 'Subfamily') -> Anserinae] Anserinae), the solitaire ([dblookup('Solitaire', 'Scientific Name') -> Pezophaps] Pezophaps), sheathbills ([dblookup('Sheathbills', 'Genus') -> Chionis] Chionis), some guans ([dblookup('Guans', 'Genus with Weaponized Alular Metacarpal') -> Crax] Crax) and stone curlews ([dblookup('Stone Curlews', 'Genus') -> Burhinus] Burhinus) use a bony knob on the alular metacarpal to punch and hammer opponents. The jacanas [dblookup('Jacanas', 'Species with Blade-like Radius') -> Actophilornis, Irediparra] Actophilornis and Irediparra have an expanded, blade-like radius. The extinct [dblookup('Xenicibis', 'Notable Feature') -> Elongate forelimb and massive hand] Xenicibis was unique in having an elongate forelimb and massive hand which likely functioned in combat or defence as a jointed club or flail. Swans, for instance, may strike with the bony spurs and bite when defending eggs or young.
examples.text: Bird: A dearth of field observations limit our knowledge, but intraspecific conflicts are known to sometimes result in injury or death. The screamers (Anhimidae), some jacanas (Jacana, Hydrophasianus), the spur-winged goose (Plectropterus), the torrent duck (Merganetta) and nine species of lapwing (Vanellus) use a sharp spur on the wing as a weapon. The steamer ducks (Tachyeres), geese and swans (Anserinae), the solitaire (Pezophaps), sheathbills (Chionis), some guans (Crax) and stone curlews (Burhinus) use a bony knob on the alular metacarpal to punch and hammer opponents. The jacanas Actophilornis and Irediparra have an expanded, blade-like radius. The extinct Xenicibis was unique in having an elongate forelimb and massive hand which likely functioned in combat or defence as a jointed club or flail. Swans, for instance, may strike with the bony spurs and bite when defending eggs or young.

examples.annotated_text: Dialect: For example, the Italian and French words for various foods, some family relationships, and body parts are very similar to each other, yet most of those words are completely different in Spanish. Italian [dblookup('Italian Language', 'Auxiliary Verbs') -> avere, essere] "avere" and "essere" as auxiliaries for forming compound tenses are used similarly to French [dblookup('French Language', 'Auxiliary Verbs') -> avoir, être] "avoir" and "être". Spanish only retains [dblookup('Spanish Language', 'Auxiliary Verb') -> haber] "haber" and has done away with "ser" in forming compound tenses. However, when it comes to phonological structures, [dblookup('Italian Language', 'Phonological Change Compared To') -> French Language] Italian and Spanish have undergone less change than French, with the result that some native speakers of Italian and Spanish may attain a degree of mutual comprehension that permits extensive communication.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Nonprofit_organization: In the traditional domain noted in [dblookup('.org', 'Defined In') -> RFC 1591] RFC 1591, .org is for "organizations that didn't fit anywhere else" in the naming system, which implies that it is the proper category for [dblookup('.org', 'For Organizations') -> non-commercial organizations] non-commercial organizations if they are not governmental, educational, or one of the other types with a specific TLD. It is not designated specifically for [dblookup('.org', 'Not Specifically For') -> charitable organizations] charitable organizations or any specific organizational or tax-law status, however; it encompasses anything that is not classifiable as another category. Currently, no restrictions are enforced on registration of [dblookup('.org', 'Registration Restriction') -> none] .com or .org, so one can find organizations of all sorts in either of these domains, as well as other top-level domains including newer, more specific ones which may apply to particular sorts of organizations such as [dblookup('.museum', 'For') -> museums] museums for .museum or [dblookup('.coop', 'For') -> cooperatives] cooperatives for .coop. Organizations might also register by the [dblookup('Organizations', 'Alternative Registration') -> country code top-level domain] appropriate country code top-level domain for their country.
examples.text: Nonprofit_organization: In the traditional domain noted in RFC 1591, .org is for "organizations that didn't fit anywhere else" in the naming system, which implies that it is the proper category for non-commercial organizations if they are not governmental, educational, or one of the other types with a specific TLD. It is not designated specifically for charitable organizations or any specific organizational or tax-law status, however; it encompasses anything that is not classifiable as another category. Currently, no restrictions are enforced on registration of .com or .org, so one can find organizations of all sorts in either of these domains, as well as other top-level domains including newer, more specific ones which may apply to particular sorts of organizations such as .museum for museums or .coop for cooperatives. Organizations might also register by the appropriate country code top-level domain for their country.

examples.annotated_text: Hellenistic period: The Attalid dynasty of Pergamum lasted little longer; [dblookup('Attalid Dynasty', 'Last King') -> Attalus III] a Roman ally until the end, its final king Attalus III died in [dblookup('Attalus III', 'Death Year') -> 133 BC] 133 BC without an heir, and taking the alliance to its natural conclusion, willed [dblookup('Attalus III', 'Bequest') -> Pergamum to the Roman Republic] Pergamum to the Roman Republic. The final Greek resistance came in [dblookup('Mithridatic Wars', 'Outbreak Year') -> 88 BC] 88 BC, when [dblookup('Mithridatic Wars', 'Rebel Leader') -> King Mithridates of Pontus] King Mithridates of Pontus rebelled against Rome, captured Roman-held Anatolia, and massacred up to [dblookup('Mithridatic Wars', 'Massacre Victims') -> 100,000 Romans and Roman allies] 100,000 Romans and Roman allies across Asia Minor. Many Greek cities, including [dblookup('Mithridatic Wars', 'Joining City') -> Athens] Athens, overthrew their Roman puppet rulers and joined him in the Mithridatic wars. When he was driven out of Greece by the [dblookup('Lucius Cornelius Sulla', 'Campaign') -> Siege of Athens] Roman general Lucius Cornelius Sulla, who laid siege to Athens and razed the city. Mithridates was finally defeated by Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (Pompey the Great) in [dblookup('Mithridatic Wars', 'End Year') -> 65 BC] 65 BC. Further ruin was brought to Greece by the [dblookup('Roman Civil Wars', 'Impact On') -> Greece] Roman civil wars, which were partly fought in Greece. Finally, in [dblookup('Greece', 'Annexation Year') -> 27 BC] 27 BC, [dblookup('Augustus', 'Annexation') -> Greece to Roman Empire as Achaea] Augustus directly annexed Greece to the new Roman Empire as the province of Achaea. The struggles with Rome had left Greece [dblookup('Greece', 'Condition Post-Wars') -> depopulated and demoralised] depopulated and demoralised. Nevertheless, Roman rule at least brought an end to warfare, and cities such as Athens, Corinth, Thessaloniki and Patras soon recovered their prosperity.
examples.text: Hellenistic_period: The Attalid dynasty of Pergamum lasted little longer; a Roman ally until the end, its final king Attalus III died in 133 BC without an heir, and taking the alliance to its natural conclusion, willed Pergamum to the Roman Republic. The final Greek resistance came in 88 BC, when King Mithridates of Pontus rebelled against Rome, captured Roman held Anatolia, and massacred up to 100,000 Romans and Roman allies across Asia Minor. Many Greek cities, including Athens, overthrew their Roman puppet rulers and joined him in the Mithridatic wars. When he was driven out of Greece by the Roman general Lucius Cornelius Sulla, who laid siege to Athens and razed the city. Mithridates was finally defeated by Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (Pompey the Great) in 65 BC. Further ruin was brought to Greece by the Roman civil wars, which were partly fought in Greece. Finally, in 27 BC, Augustus directly annexed Greece to the new Roman Empire as the province of Achaea. The struggles with Rome had left Greece depopulated and demoralised. Nevertheless, Roman rule at least brought an end to warfare, and cities such as Athens, Corinth, Thessaloniki and Patras soon recovered their prosperity.

examples.annotated_text: Queen_(band): Before forming Queen, [dblookup('Brian May', 'Band Membership Before Queen') -> Smile] Brian May and [dblookup('Roger Taylor', 'Band Membership Before Queen') -> Smile] Roger Taylor had played together in a band named Smile. [dblookup('Freddie Mercury', 'Birth Name') -> Farrokh "Freddie" Bulsara] Freddie Mercury (then known by his birth name of Farrokh "Freddie" Bulsara) was a fan of Smile and encouraged them to experiment with more elaborate stage and recording techniques. Mercury joined the band in [dblookup('Freddie Mercury', 'Joined Queen') -> 1970] 1970, suggested "Queen" as a new band name, and adopted his familiar stage name. [dblookup('John Deacon', 'Joined Queen') -> Before 1973] John Deacon was recruited prior to recording their eponymous debut album in 1973. Queen first charted in the UK with their [dblookup('Queen', 'First UK Charted Album') -> Queen II] second album, Queen II, in 1974, but it was the release of [dblookup('Queen', 'International Success Album 1') -> Sheer Heart Attack] Sheer Heart Attack later that year and [dblookup('Queen', 'International Success Album 2') -> A Night at the Opera] A Night at the Opera in 1975 which brought them international success. The latter featured "Bohemian Rhapsody", which [dblookup('Bohemian Rhapsody', 'UK Number One Duration') -> Nine weeks] stayed at number one in the UK for nine weeks and popularised the music video. Their 1977 album, [dblookup('Queen', '1977 Album') -> News of the World] News of the World, contained "We Will Rock You" and "We Are the Champions", which have become anthems at sporting events. By the early 1980s, Queen were one of the biggest stadium rock bands in the world. Their performance at [dblookup('Queen', 'Notable Performance') -> 1985 Live Aid] 1985's Live Aid is ranked among the greatest in rock history by various music publications, with a 2005 industry poll ranking it the best. In 1991, [dblookup('Freddie Mercury', 'Year of Death') -> 1991] Mercury died of bronchopneumonia, a complication of AIDS, and Deacon retired in [dblookup('John Deacon', 'Year of Retirement') -> 1997] 1997. Since then, May and Taylor have occasionally performed together, including with [dblookup('Queen', 'Collaboration with Paul Rodgers') -> 2004–09] Paul Rodgers (2004–09) and with [dblookup('Queen', 'Collaboration with Adam Lambert') -> Since 2011] Adam Lambert (since 2011). In November 2014, [dblookup('Queen', '2014 Album') -> Queen Forever] Queen released a new album, Queen Forever, featuring vocals from the late Mercury.
examples.text: Queen_(band): Before forming Queen, Brian May and Roger Taylor had played together in a band named Smile. Freddie Mercury (then known by his birth name of Farrokh "Freddie" Bulsara) was a fan of Smile and encouraged them to experiment with more elaborate stage and recording techniques. Mercury joined the band in 1970, suggested "Queen" as a new band name, and adopted his familiar stage name. John Deacon was recruited prior to recording their eponymous debut album in 1973. Queen first charted in the UK with their second album, Queen II, in 1974, but it was the release of Sheer Heart Attack later that year and A Night at the Opera in 1975 which brought them international success. The latter featured "Bohemian Rhapsody", which stayed at number one in the UK for nine weeks and popularised the music video. Their 1977 album, News of the World, contained "We Will Rock You" and "We Are the Champions", which have become anthems at sporting events. By the early 1980s, Queen were one of the biggest stadium rock bands in the world. Their performance at 1985's Live Aid is ranked among the greatest in rock history by various music publications, with a 2005 industry poll ranking it the best. In 1991, Mercury died of bronchopneumonia, a complication of AIDS, and Deacon retired in 1997. Since then, May and Taylor have occasionally performed together, including with Paul Rodgers (2004–09) and with Adam Lambert (since 2011). In November 2014, Queen released a new album, Queen Forever, featuring vocals from the late Mercury.

examples.annotated_text: Westminster Abbey: Since the coronations in [dblookup('Westminster Abbey', 'First Coronations Year') -> 1066] 1066 of both King Harold and William the Conqueror, coronations of English and British monarchs were held in the abbey. In 1216, Henry III was unable to be crowned in London when he first came to the throne, because the French prince Louis had taken control of the city, and so the king was crowned in [dblookup('Henry III of England', 'Alternative Coronation Venue') -> Gloucester Cathedral] Gloucester Cathedral. This coronation was deemed by the Pope to be improper, and a further coronation was held in the abbey on [dblookup('Henry III of England', 'Westminster Abbey Coronation Date') -> 17 May 1220] 17 May 1220. The Archbishop of Canterbury is the [dblookup('Archbishop of Canterbury', 'Role in Coronation') -> Traditional Cleric] traditional cleric in the coronation ceremony.
examples.text: Westminster_Abbey: Since the coronations in 1066 of both King Harold and William the Conqueror, coronations of English and British monarchs were held in the abbey. In 1216, Henry III was unable to be crowned in London when he first came to the throne, because the French prince Louis had taken control of the city, and so the king was crowned in Gloucester Cathedral. This coronation was deemed by the Pope to be improper, and a further coronation was held in the abbey on 17 May 1220. The Archbishop of Canterbury is the traditional cleric in the coronation ceremony.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Emotion: Attempts are frequently made to regulate emotion according to the conventions of the society and the situation based on many (sometimes conflicting) demands and expectations which originate from various entities. The emotion of anger is in many cultures [dblookup('Anger', 'Discouraged In') -> girls, women] discouraged in girls and women, while fear is [dblookup('Fear', 'Discouraged In') -> boys, men] discouraged in boys and men. Expectations attached to social roles, such as "acting as man" and not as a woman, and the accompanying "feeling rules" contribute to the differences in expression of certain emotions. Some cultures encourage or discourage happiness, [dblookup('Sadness', 'Social Regulation') -> encouraged or discouraged] sadness, or [dblookup('Jealousy', 'Social Regulation') -> encouraged or discouraged] jealousy, and the free expression of the emotion of disgust is [dblookup('Disgust', 'Social Acceptability') -> considered socially unacceptable in most cultures] considered socially unacceptable in most cultures. Some social institutions are seen as based on certain emotion, such as love in the case of contemporary institution of marriage. In advertising, such as health campaigns and political messages, emotional appeals are commonly found. Recent examples include no-smoking health campaigns and [dblookup('Political Campaigns', 'Emphasized Emotion') -> fear of terrorism] political campaigns emphasizing the fear of terrorism.
examples.text: Emotion: Attempts are frequently made to regulate emotion according to the conventions of the society and the situation based on many (sometimes conflicting) demands and expectations which originate from various entities. The emotion of anger is in many cultures discouraged in girls and women, while fear is discouraged in boys and men. Expectations attached to social roles, such as "acting as man" and not as a woman, and the accompanying "feeling rules" contribute to the differences in expression of certain emotions. Some cultures encourage or discourage happiness, sadness, or jealousy, and the free expression of the emotion of disgust is considered socially unacceptable in most cultures. Some social institutions are seen as based on certain emotion, such as love in the case of contemporary institution of marriage. In advertising, such as health campaigns and political messages, emotional appeals are commonly found. Recent examples include no-smoking health campaigns and political campaigns emphasizing the fear of terrorism.

examples.annotated_text: Georgian_architecture: The period saw the growth of a distinct and trained architectural profession; before the mid-century "the high-sounding title, 'architect' was adopted by anyone who could get away with it". But most buildings were still designed by builders and landlords together, and the wide spread of Georgian architecture, and the Georgian styles of design more generally, came from dissemination through pattern books and inexpensive suites of engravings. This contrasted with earlier styles, which were primarily disseminated among craftsmen through the direct experience of the apprenticeship system. Authors such as the prolific William Halfpenny (active 1723–1755) received editions in America as well as Britain. From the mid-18th century, Georgian styles were assimilated into an architectural vernacular that became part and parcel of the training of every architect, designer, builder, carpenter, mason and plasterer, from [dblookup('Georgian Styles', 'Geographical Spread') -> Edinburgh to Maryland] Edinburgh to Maryland.

examples.annotated_text: Computer_security: In 1988, only [dblookup('Internet-connected Computers', 'Number') -> 60,000] 60,000 computers were connected to the Internet, and most were mainframes, minicomputers, and professional workstations. On [dblookup('First Internet Worm', 'Date') -> November 2, 1988] November 2, 1988, many started to slow down because they were running a malicious code that demanded processor time and spread itself to other computers – the first internet "computer worm". The software was traced back to [dblookup('Robert Tappan Morris, Jr.', 'Affiliation') -> Cornell University] 23-year-old Cornell University graduate student [dblookup('Robert Tappan Morris, Jr.', 'Age During Incident') -> 23] Robert Tappan Morris, Jr., who said 'he wanted to count how many machines were connected to [dblookup('Robert Tappan Morris, Jr.', 'Purpose of Worm') -> count internet-connected machines] the Internet'.
examples.text: Computer_security: In 1988, only 60,000 computers were connected to the Internet, and most were mainframes, minicomputers and professional workstations. On November 2, 1988, many started to slow down, because they were running a malicious code that demanded processor time and that spread itself to other computers – the first internet "computer worm". The software was traced back to 23-year-old Cornell University graduate student Robert Tappan Morris, Jr. who said 'he wanted to count how many machines were connected to the Internet'.

examples.annotated_text: Neoclassical_architecture: The first phase of neoclassicism in France is expressed in [dblookup('Neoclassical Architecture in France', 'Early Style') -> Louis XVI style] the "Louis XVI style" of architects like Ange-Jacques Gabriel (Petit Trianon, [dblookup('Petit Trianon', 'Construction Dates') -> 1762–68] 1762–68); the second phase, in the styles called [dblookup('Neoclassical Architecture in France', 'Second Phase Styles') -> Directoire, Empire] Directoire and "Empire", might be characterized by Jean Chalgrin's severe astylar Arc de Triomphe (designed in [dblookup('Arc de Triomphe', 'Design Year') -> 1806] 1806). In England the two phases might be characterized first by the structures of [dblookup('Robert Adam', 'Period of Influence') -> First Phase of Neoclassicism in England] Robert Adam, the second by those of [dblookup('Sir John Soane', 'Period of Influence') -> Second Phase of Neoclassicism in England] Sir John Soane. The interior style in France was initially a Parisian style, the "Goût grec" ("Greek style") not a court style. Only when the young king acceded to the throne in [dblookup('Louis XVI', 'Accession Year') -> 1771] 1771 did [dblookup('Marie Antoinette', 'Influence On Court Style') -> Introduction of Louis XVI style] Marie Antoinette, his fashion-loving Queen, bring the "Louis XVI" style to court.
examples.text: Neoclassical_architecture: The first phase of neoclassicism in France is expressed in the "Louis XVI style" of architects like Ange-Jacques Gabriel (Petit Trianon, 1762–68); the second phase, in the styles called Directoire and "Empire", might be characterized by Jean Chalgrin's severe astylar Arc de Triomphe (designed in 1806). In England the two phases might be characterized first by the structures of Robert Adam, the second by those of Sir John Soane. The interior style in France was initially a Parisian style, the "Goût grec" ("Greek style") not a court style. Only when the young king acceded to the throne in 1771 did Marie Antoinette, his fashion-loving Queen, bring the "Louis XVI" style to court.

examples.annotated_text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: But while Claremont remains the [dblookup('Claremont', 'Role in Whiteheadian Activity') -> most concentrated hub] most concentrated hub of Whiteheadian activity, the place where [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Philosophy Growth Location') -> China] Whitehead's thought currently seems to be growing the most quickly is in China. In order to address the challenges of modernization and industrialization, [dblookup('China', 'Philosophical Blending Initiatives') -> Taoism, Buddhism, Confucianism with Whitehead's philosophy] China has begun to blend traditions of Taoism, Buddhism, and Confucianism with Whitehead's "constructive post-modern" philosophy to create an "ecological civilization." To date, the [dblookup('Chinese Government', 'Educational Initiatives') -> twenty-three university-based centers for Whitehead studies] Chinese government has encouraged the building of twenty-three university-based centers for the study of Whitehead's philosophy, and books by process philosophers John Cobb and [dblookup('David Ray Griffin', 'Works Requirement') -> Chinese graduate students] David Ray Griffin are becoming required reading for Chinese graduate students. Cobb has attributed [dblookup('China', 'Interest Reason in Whitehead Philosophy') -> mutual interdependence of humanity and nature, emphasis on educational system including values] China's interest in process philosophy partly to Whitehead's stress on the mutual interdependence of humanity and nature, as well as his emphasis on an educational system that includes the teaching of values rather than simply bare facts.
examples.text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: But while Claremont remains the most concentrated hub of Whiteheadian activity, the place where Whitehead's thought currently seems to be growing the most quickly is in China. In order to address the challenges of modernization and industrialization, China has begun to blend traditions of Taoism, Buddhism, and Confucianism with Whitehead's "constructive post-modern" philosophy in order to create an "ecological civilization." To date, the Chinese government has encouraged the building of twenty-three university-based centers for the study of Whitehead's philosophy, and books by process philosophers John Cobb and David Ray Griffin are becoming required reading for Chinese graduate students. Cobb has attributed China's interest in process philosophy partly to Whitehead's stress on the mutual interdependence of humanity and nature, as well as his emphasis on an educational system that includes the teaching of values rather than simply bare facts.

examples.annotated_text: Liberal_Party_of_Australia: In South Australia, initially a [dblookup('Liberal and Country League', 'Affiliation') -> Liberal and Country Party] Liberal and Country Party affiliated party, the Liberal and Country League (LCL), mostly led by [dblookup('Liberal and Country League', 'Leader Period 1') -> Premier of South Australia Tom Playford] Premier of South Australia Tom Playford, was in power from the [dblookup('Liberal and Country League', 'Governance Start') -> 1933 election] 1933 election to the [dblookup('Liberal and Country League', 'Governance End') -> 1965 election] 1965 election, though with assistance from an electoral malapportionment, or gerrymander, known as the Playmander. The LCL's [dblookup('Steele Hall', 'Governing Term Start') -> 1968 election] Steele Hall governed for one term from the 1968 election to the [dblookup('Steele Hall', 'Governing Term End') -> 1970 election] 1970 election and during this time began the process of dismantling the Playmander. [dblookup('David Tonkin', 'Leadership Role') -> Leader of the South Australian Division of the Liberal Party of Australia] David Tonkin, as leader of the South Australian Division of the Liberal Party of Australia, became Premier at the [dblookup('David Tonkin', 'Governing Term Start') -> 1979 election] 1979 election for one term, losing office at the [dblookup('David Tonkin', 'Governing Term End') -> 1982 election] 1982 election. The Liberals returned to power at the [dblookup('Liberal Party of Australia', 'Governance Start') -> 1993 election] 1993 election, led by Premiers Dean Brown, John Olsen and Rob Kerin through two terms, until their defeat at the [dblookup('Liberal Party of Australia', 'Governance End') -> 2002 election] 2002 election. They have since remained in opposition under a record five Opposition Leaders.
examples.text: Liberal_Party_of_Australia: In South Australia, initially a Liberal and Country Party affiliated party, the Liberal and Country League (LCL), mostly led by Premier of South Australia Tom Playford, was in power from the 1933 election to the 1965 election, though with assistance from an electoral malapportionment, or gerrymander, known as the Playmander. The LCL's Steele Hall governed for one term from the 1968 election to the 1970 election and during this time began the process of dismantling the Playmander. David Tonkin, as leader of the South Australian Division of the Liberal Party of Australia, became Premier at the 1979 election for one term, losing office at the 1982 election. The Liberals returned to power at the 1993 election, led by Premiers Dean Brown, John Olsen and Rob Kerin through two terms, until their defeat at the 2002 election. They have since remained in opposition under a record five Opposition Leaders.

examples.annotated_text: Computer: The principle of the modern computer was first described by [dblookup('Alan Turing', 'Contribution To Computer Science') -> Principle of the modern computer] mathematician and pioneering computer scientist Alan Turing, who set out the idea in his [dblookup('Alan Turing', 'Notable Work') -> On Computable Numbers] seminal 1936 paper, On Computable Numbers. Turing reformulated [dblookup('Alan Turing', 'Reformulated Work Of') -> Kurt Gödel] Kurt Gödel's 1931 results on the limits of proof and computation, replacing Gödel's universal arithmetic-based formal language with the formal and simple hypothetical devices that became known as [dblookup('Alan Turing', 'Known For') -> Turing machines] Turing machines. examples.text: Computer: The principle of the modern computer was first described by mathematician and pioneering computer scientist Alan Turing, who set out the idea in his seminal 1936 paper, On Computable Numbers. Turing reformulated Kurt Gödel's 1931 results on the limits of proof and computation, replacing Gödel's universal arithmetic-based formal language with the formal and simple hypothetical devices that became known as Turing machines. He proved that some such machine would be capable of performing any conceivable mathematical computation if it were representable as an algorithm. He went on to prove that there was no solution to the Entscheidungsproblem by first showing that the halting problem for Turing machines is undecidable: in general, it is not possible to decide algorithmically whether a given Turing machine will ever halt.

examples.text: History_of_India: The Shunga Empire or Shunga Empire was an ancient Indian dynasty from Magadha that controlled vast areas of the Indian subcontinent from around 187 to 78 BCE. The dynasty was established by Pushyamitra Shunga, after the fall of the Maurya Empire. Its capital was Pataliputra, but later emperors such as Bhagabhadra also held court at Besnagar, modern Vidisha in Eastern Malwa. Pushyamitra Shunga ruled for 36 years and was succeeded by his son Agnimitra. There were ten Shunga rulers. The empire is noted for its numerous wars with both foreign and indigenous powers. They fought battles with the Kalingas, Satavahanas, the Indo-Greeks, and possibly the Panchalas and Mathuras. Art, education, philosophy, and other forms of learning flowered during this period including small terracotta images, larger stone sculptures, and architectural monuments such as the Stupa at Bharhut, and the renowned Great Stupa at Sanchi. The Shunga rulers helped to establish the tradition of royal sponsorship of learning and art. The script used by the empire was a variant of Brahmi and was used to write the Sanskrit language. The Shunga Empire played an imperative role in patronizing Indian culture at a time when some of the most important developments in Hindu thought were taking place.

examples.text: Estonia: The capital of Danish Estonia (Danish: Hertugdømmet Estland) was Reval (Tallinn), founded at the place of Lyndanisse after the invasion of 1219. examples.text: New_Haven,_Connecticut: New Haven has a long tradition of urban planning and a purposeful design for the city's layout.
