examples.annotated_text: Antibiotics: The emergence of resistance of bacteria to antibiotics is a common phenomenon. Emergence of resistance often reflects evolutionary processes that take place during [dblookup('Antibiotic Therapy', 'Effect') -> selection for resistant bacterial strains] antibiotic therapy. The antibiotic treatment may select for bacterial strains with [dblookup('Bacterial Strains', 'Resistance Development') -> physiologically or genetically enhanced capacity] physiologically or genetically enhanced capacity to survive high doses of antibiotics. Under certain conditions, it may result in preferential growth of resistant bacteria, while growth of susceptible bacteria is [dblookup('Susceptible Bacteria', 'Inhibited By') -> antibiotic drug] inhibited by the drug. For example, antibacterial selection for strains having previously acquired antibacterial-resistance genes was demonstrated in [dblookup('Luria–Delbrück Experiment', 'Year') -> 1943] 1943 by the [dblookup('Antibacterial Resistance', 'Historical Experiment') -> Luria–Delbrück experiment] Luria–Delbrück experiment. Antibiotics such as [dblookup('Penicillin', 'Initial Efficacy') -> high efficacy against many bacterial species] penicillin and [dblookup('Erythromycin', 'Initial Efficacy') -> high efficacy against many bacterial species] erythromycin, which used to have a high efficacy against many bacterial species and strains, have become less effective, due to the [dblookup('Bacterial Strains', 'Cause of Resistance Increase') -> increased resistance] increased resistance of many bacterial strains.
examples.text: Antibiotics: The emergence of resistance of bacteria to antibiotics is a common phenomenon. Emergence of resistance often reflects evolutionary processes that take place during antibiotic therapy. The antibiotic treatment may select for bacterial strains with physiologically or genetically enhanced capacity to survive high doses of antibiotics. Under certain conditions, it may result in preferential growth of resistant bacteria, while growth of susceptible bacteria is inhibited by the drug. For example, antibacterial selection for strains having previously acquired antibacterial-resistance genes was demonstrated in 1943 by the Luria–Delbrück experiment. Antibiotics such as penicillin and erythromycin, which used to have a high efficacy against many bacterial species and strains, have become less effective, due to the increased resistance of many bacterial strains.

examples.annotated_text: Zinc: There are many important [dblookup('Organozinc Chemistry', 'Field of Chemistry') -> organozinc compounds] organozinc compounds. Organozinc chemistry is the science of organozinc compounds describing their physical properties, synthesis, and reactions. Among important applications is the [dblookup('Frankland-Duppa Reaction', 'Type of Reaction') -> reaction involving oxalate ester, alkyl halide, zinc, hydrochloric acid] Frankland-Duppa Reaction in which an oxalate ester (ROCOCOOR) reacts with an alkyl halide R'X, zinc, and hydrochloric acid to the α-hydroxycarboxylic esters RR'COHCOOR, the Reformatskii reaction which converts α-halo-esters and aldehydes to β-hydroxy-esters, the [dblookup('Simmons–Smith Reaction', 'Conversion') -> carbenoid to cyclopropane] Simmons–Smith reaction in which the carbenoid (iodomethyl)zinc iodide reacts with alkene (or alkyne) and converts them to cyclopropane, the [dblookup('Organozinc Compounds Addition Reaction', 'Application') -> carbonyl compounds] Addition reaction of organozinc compounds to carbonyl compounds. The Barbier reaction (1899) is the zinc equivalent of the magnesium Grignard reaction and is better of the two. In presence of just about any water the formation of the organomagnesium halide will fail, whereas the Barbier reaction can even take place in water. On the downside organozincs are [dblookup('Organozinc Compounds', 'Nucleophilicity') -> much less nucleophilic than Grignards] much less nucleophilic than Grignards, are expensive and difficult to handle. Commercially available [dblookup('Diorganozinc Compounds', 'Examples') -> dimethylzinc, diethylzinc, diphenylzinc] diorganozinc compounds are dimethylzinc, diethylzinc, and diphenylzinc. In one study the active organozinc compound is obtained from much cheaper [dblookup('Organozinc Compound Synthesis', 'Precursor') -> organobromine precursors] organobromine precursors.
examples.text: Zinc: There are many important organozinc compounds. Organozinc chemistry is the science of organozinc compounds describing their physical properties, synthesis and reactions. Among important applications is the Frankland-Duppa Reaction in which an oxalate ester(ROCOCOOR) reacts with an alkyl halide R'X, zinc and hydrochloric acid to the α-hydroxycarboxylic esters RR'COHCOOR, the Reformatskii reaction which converts α-halo-esters and aldehydes to β-hydroxy-esters, the Simmons–Smith reaction in which the carbenoid (iodomethyl)zinc iodide reacts with alkene(or alkyne) and converts them to cyclopropane, the Addition reaction of organozinc compounds to carbonyl compounds. The Barbier reaction (1899) is the zinc equivalent of the magnesium Grignard reaction and is better of the two. In presence of just about any water the formation of the organomagnesium halide will fail, whereas the Barbier reaction can even take place in water. On the downside organozincs are much less nucleophilic than Grignards, are expensive and difficult to handle. Commercially available diorganozinc compounds are dimethylzinc, diethylzinc and diphenylzinc. In one study the active organozinc compound is obtained from much cheaper organobromine precursors:

examples.annotated_text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: Market strategist [dblookup('Phil Dow', 'Occupation') -> Market Strategist] Phil Dow believes distinctions exist "between the current market malaise" and the Great Depression. He says the [dblookup('Dow Jones', 'Percentage Fall Over 17 Months During Financial Crisis of 2007-2008') -> more than 50%] Dow Jones average's fall of more than 50% over a period of 17 months is similar to a [dblookup('Dow Jones', 'Percentage Fall During Great Depression') -> 54.7%] 54.7% fall in the Great Depression, followed by a total drop of [dblookup('Dow Jones', 'Total Percentage Drop During Great Depression') -> 89%] 89% over the following 16 months. "It's very troubling if you have a mirror image," said Dow. [dblookup('Floyd Norris', 'Occupational Title') -> Chief Financial Correspondent of The New York Times] Floyd Norris, the chief financial correspondent of The New York Times, wrote in a blog entry in [dblookup('Floyd Norris', 'Blog Entry Date on Financial Crisis') -> March 2009] March 2009 that the decline has not been a mirror image of the Great Depression, explaining that although the decline [dblookup('Dow Jones', 'Similar Decline Amounts in Financial Crisis of 2007-2008 and Great Depression') -> nearly the same] amounts were nearly the same at the time, the rates of decline had started much faster in 2007, and that the past year had only ranked [dblookup('Dow Jones', 'Ranking Among Worst Recorded Years for Percentage Drops in Financial Crisis of 2007-2008') -> eighth] eighth among the worst recorded years of percentage drops in the Dow. The past [dblookup('Two-Year Ranking for Dow Jones During Financial Crisis of 2007-2008', 'Ranking') -> third] two years ranked third, however.
examples.text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: Market strategist Phil Dow believes distinctions exist "between the current market malaise" and the Great Depression. He says the Dow Jones average's fall of more than 50% over a period of 17 months is similar to a 54.7% fall in the Great Depression, followed by a total drop of 89% over the following 16 months. "It's very troubling if you have a mirror image," said Dow. Floyd Norris, the chief financial correspondent of The New York Times, wrote in a blog entry in March 2009 that the decline has not been a mirror image of the Great Depression, explaining that although the decline amounts were nearly the same at the time, the rates of decline had started much faster in 2007, and that the past year had only ranked eighth among the worst recorded years of percentage drops in the Dow. The past two years ranked third, however.

examples.annotated_text: Pharmaceutical_industry: In March 2001, 40 [dblookup('Pharmaceutical Companies vs. South Africa', 'Legal Action Type') -> litigation] multi-national pharmaceutical companies brought litigation against [dblookup('Pharmaceutical Companies vs. South Africa', 'Defendant') -> South Africa] South Africa for its Medicines Act, which allowed the generic production of antiretroviral drugs (ARVs) for treating HIV, despite the fact that these drugs were on-patent. HIV was and is an epidemic in [dblookup('HIV Epidemic', 'Country Affected') -> South Africa] South Africa, and ARVs at the time cost between [dblookup('ARV Cost', 'Per Patient Per Year') -> 10,000 to 15,000 USD] 10,000 and 15,000 USD per patient per year. This was unaffordable for most South African citizens, and so the [dblookup('South African Government', 'Action for ARVs') -> committed to affordable pricing] South African government committed to providing ARVs at prices closer to what people could afford. To do so, they would need to ignore the patents on drugs and produce generics within the country (using a compulsory license), or import them from abroad. After international protest in favour of public health rights (including the collection of 250,000 signatures by MSF), the governments of several developed countries (including The Netherlands, Germany, France, and later the US) backed the South African government, and the [dblookup('Pharmaceutical Companies vs. South Africa', 'Case Dropped Date') -> April 2001] case was dropped in April of that year.
examples.text: Pharmaceutical_industry: In March 2001, 40 multi-national pharmaceutical companies brought litigation against South Africa for its Medicines Act, which allowed the generic production of antiretroviral drugs (ARVs) for treating HIV, despite the fact that these drugs were on-patent. HIV was and is an epidemic in South Africa, and ARVs at the time cost between 10,000 and 15,000 USD per patient per year. This was unaffordable for most South African citizens, and so the South African government committed to providing ARVs at prices closer to what people could afford. To do so, they would need to ignore the patents on drugs and produce generics within the country (using a compulsory license), or import them from abroad. After international protest in favour of public health rights (including the collection of 250,000 signatures by MSF), the governments of several developed countries (including The Netherlands, Germany, France, and later the US) backed the South African government, and the case was dropped in April of that year.

examples.annotated_text: A year later, at the height of the 1975 Australian constitutional crisis, the Australian Prime Minister, [dblookup('Gough Whitlam', 'Position During Crisis') -> Prime Minister of Australia] Gough Whitlam, was dismissed from his post by [dblookup('Sir John Kerr', 'Role During Crisis') -> Governor-General of Australia] Governor-General Sir John Kerr, after the [dblookup('Australian Opposition', 'Action During Crisis') -> Rejected Whitlam's budget proposals] Opposition-controlled Senate rejected Whitlam's budget proposals. As Whitlam had a majority in the House of Representatives, Speaker Gordon Scholes appealed to the Queen to reverse Kerr's decision. She declined, stating that [dblookup('Elizabeth II', 'Position on Crisis Intervention') -> Would not interfere in governor-general decisions] she would not interfere in decisions reserved by the Constitution of Australia for the governor-general. The crisis fuelled Australian republicanism.
examples.text: Elizabeth_II: A year later, at the height of the 1975 Australian constitutional crisis, the Australian Prime Minister, Gough Whitlam, was dismissed from his post by Governor-General Sir John Kerr, after the Opposition-controlled Senate rejected Whitlam's budget proposals. As Whitlam had a majority in the House of Representatives, Speaker Gordon Scholes appealed to the Queen to reverse Kerr's decision. She declined, stating that she would not interfere in decisions reserved by the Constitution of Australia for the governor-general. The crisis fuelled Australian republicanism.

examples.annotated_text: Political_corruption: [dblookup('Gombeenism', 'Definition') -> Individual who is dishonest and corrupt for personal gain] Gombeenism refers to an individual who is dishonest and corrupt for the purpose of personal gain, more often through monetary,[dblookup('Parochialism', 'Also Known As') -> Parish Pump Politics] while, parochialism which is also known as parish pump politics, relates to placing local or vanity projects ahead of the national interest. For instance in [dblookup('Irish Politics', 'Criticism By') -> Populist left-wing political parties] Irish politics, populist left wing political parties will often apply these terms to mainstream establishment political parties and will cite the many cases of [dblookup('Corruption in Ireland', 'Examples') -> Irish Banking Crisis] Corruption in Ireland, such as the Irish Banking crisis, which found evidence of [dblookup('Irish Banking Crisis', 'Issues Found') -> Bribery, cronyism, collusion] bribery, cronyism, and collusion, where in some cases politicians who were coming to the end of their political careers would receive a senior management or committee position in a company they had dealings with.

examples.annotated_text: Richard Feynman: In [dblookup('Surely You're Joking, Mr. Feynman!', 'Author') -> Richard Feynman] Surely You're Joking, Mr. Feynman!, he gives advice on the best way to pick up a girl in a hostess bar. At [dblookup('Richard Feynman', 'Affiliation') -> California Institute of Technology] Caltech, he used a nude or topless bar as an office away from his usual office, making sketches or writing physics equations on paper placemats. When the county officials tried to close the place, all visitors except Feynman refused to testify in favor of the bar, fearing that their families or patrons would learn about their visits. Only Feynman accepted, and in court, he affirmed that the bar was a public need, stating that craftsmen, technicians, engineers, common workers, "and a physics professor" frequented the establishment. While the bar lost the court case, it was allowed to remain open as a similar case was pending appeal.

examples.annotated_text: Daylight_saving_time: The war's end swung the pendulum back. Farmers continued to dislike DST, and many countries repealed it after the war. [dblookup('United Kingdom', 'Exception to DST Repeal') -> Retained DST] Britain was an exception: it retained DST nationwide but over the years adjusted transition dates for several reasons, including special rules during the 1920s and 1930s to avoid clock shifts on Easter mornings. The [dblookup('United States', 'DST Repeal Event') -> 1919] US was more typical: Congress repealed DST after 1919. President [dblookup('Woodrow Wilson', 'Opposition to DST Repeal') -> Vetoed repeal twice] Woodrow Wilson, like Willett an avid golfer, vetoed the repeal twice but his second veto was overridden. Only a few [dblookup('US Cities', 'Retained DST Locally After Repeal') -> New York, Chicago, Cleveland] US cities retained DST locally thereafter, including New York so that its financial exchanges could maintain an hour of arbitrage trading with London, and Chicago and Cleveland to keep pace with New York. [dblookup('Warren G. Harding', 'Stance on DST') -> Opposed DST] Wilson's successor Warren G. Harding opposed DST as a "deception". Reasoning that people should instead get up and go to work earlier in the summer, he ordered [dblookup('District of Columbia', '1922 Work Start Time Change') -> 08:00 during summer] District of Columbia federal employees to start work at 08:00 rather than 09:00 during summer 1922. Some businesses followed suit though many others did not; the experiment was not repeated.
examples.text: Daylight_saving_time: The war's end swung the pendulum back. Farmers continued to dislike DST, and many countries repealed it after the war. Britain was an exception: it retained DST nationwide but over the years adjusted transition dates for several reasons, including special rules during the 1920s and 1930s to avoid clock shifts on Easter mornings. The US was more typical: Congress repealed DST after 1919. President Woodrow Wilson, like Willett an avid golfer, vetoed the repeal twice but his second veto was overridden. Only a few US cities retained DST locally thereafter, including New York so that its financial exchanges could maintain an hour of arbitrage trading with London, and Chicago and Cleveland to keep pace with New York. Wilson's successor Warren G. Harding opposed DST as a "deception". Reasoning that people should instead get up and go to work earlier in the summer, he ordered District of Columbia federal employees to start work at 08:00 rather than 09:00 during summer 1922. Some businesses followed suit though many others did not; the experiment was not repeated.

examples.annotated_text: Serbo-Croatian: Nationalists have conflicting views about the language(s). The nationalists among the Croats conflictingly claim either that they speak an entirely separate language from [dblookup('Serbs', 'Language') -> Serbian] Serbs and [dblookup('Bosnians', 'Language') -> Bosnian] Bosnians or that these two peoples have, due to the longer lexicographic tradition among Croats, somehow "borrowed" their [dblookup('Croats', 'Language') -> Croatian] standard languages from them.[citation needed] Bosniak nationalists claim that both [dblookup('Croats', 'Appropriated Language') -> Bosnian] Croats and [dblookup('Serbs', 'Appropriated Language') -> Bosnian] Serbs have "appropriated" the Bosnian language, since Ljudevit Gaj and Vuk Karadžić preferred the Neoštokavian-Ijekavian dialect, widely spoken in [dblookup('Bosnia and Herzegovina', 'Language Influence') -> Neoštokavian-Ijekavian dialect] Bosnia and Herzegovina, as the basis for language standardization, whereas the nationalists among the Serbs claim either that any divergence in the language is artificial, or claim that the [dblookup('Štokavian Dialect', 'Claimed By') -> Serbs] Štokavian dialect is theirs and the [dblookup('Čakavian Dialect', 'Associated With') -> Croats] Čakavian Croats' — in more extreme formulations Croats have "taken" or "stolen" their language from the Serbs.[citation needed]
examples.text: Serbo-Croatian: Nationalists have conflicting views about the language(s). The nationalists among the Croats conflictingly claim either that they speak an entirely separate language from Serbs and Bosnians or that these two peoples have, due to the longer lexicographic tradition among Croats, somehow "borrowed" their standard languages from them.[citation needed] Bosniak nationalists claim that both Croats and Serbs have "appropriated" the Bosnian language, since Ljudevit Gaj and Vuk Karadžić preferred the Neoštokavian-Ijekavian dialect, widely spoken in Bosnia and Herzegovina, as the basis for language standardization, whereas the nationalists among the Serbs claim either that any divergence in the language is artificial, or claim that the Štokavian dialect is theirs and the Čakavian Croats'— in more extreme formulations Croats have "taken" or "stolen" their language from the Serbs.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Law_of_the_United_States: During the 18th and 19th centuries, [dblookup('Federal Law of the United States', 'Focus Areas in 18th and 19th Centuries') -> military, money, foreign relations, tariffs, intellectual property, mail] federal law traditionally focused on areas where there was an express grant of power to the federal government in the federal Constitution, like the military, money, foreign relations (especially international treaties), tariffs, intellectual property (specifically patents and copyrights), and mail. Since the start of the 20th century, broad interpretations of the [dblookup('Constitution of the United States', 'Key Clauses for Law Expansion in 20th Century') -> Commerce and Spending Clauses] Commerce and Spending Clauses of the Constitution have enabled federal law to expand into areas like [dblookup('Federal Law of the United States', 'Expansion Areas in 20th Century') -> aviation, telecommunications, railroads, pharmaceuticals, antitrust, trademarks] aviation, telecommunications, railroads, pharmaceuticals, antitrust, and trademarks. In some areas, like aviation and railroads, the [dblookup('Federal Government of the United States', 'Preempted State Law Areas') -> aviation, railroads] federal government has developed a comprehensive scheme that preempts virtually all state law, while in others, like family law, [dblookup('Federal Government of the United States', 'Interaction of Federal and State Law Example') -> family law] a relatively small number of federal statutes (generally covering interstate and international situations) interacts with a much larger body of state law. In areas like antitrust, trademark, and employment law, there are powerful laws at both the federal and state levels that coexist with each other. In a handful of areas like insurance, [dblookup('Congress of the United States', 'Non-regulated Areas with State Precedence') -> insurance] Congress has enacted laws expressly refusing to regulate them as long as the states have laws regulating them (see, e.g., the [dblookup('McCarran-Ferguson Act', 'Purpose') -> state regulation of insurance] McCarran-Ferguson Act).
examples.text: Law_of_the_United_States: During the 18th and 19th centuries, federal law traditionally focused on areas where there was an express grant of power to the federal government in the federal Constitution, like the military, money, foreign relations (especially international treaties), tariffs, intellectual property (specifically patents and copyrights), and mail. Since the start of the 20th century, broad interpretations of the Commerce and Spending Clauses of the Constitution have enabled federal law to expand into areas like aviation, telecommunications, railroads, pharmaceuticals, antitrust, and trademarks. In some areas, like aviation and railroads, the federal government has developed a comprehensive scheme that preempts virtually all state law, while in others, like family law, a relatively small number of federal statutes (generally covering interstate and international situations) interacts with a much larger body of state law. In areas like antitrust, trademark, and employment law, there are powerful laws at both the federal and state levels that coexist with each other. In a handful of areas like insurance, Congress has enacted laws expressly refusing to regulate them as long as the states have laws regulating them (see, e.g., the McCarran-Ferguson Act).

examples.annotated_text: University: Examining the influence of humanism on scholars in medicine, mathematics, astronomy, and physics may suggest that [dblookup('Humanism', 'Role In') -> scientific revolution] humanism and universities were a strong impetus for the scientific revolution. Although the connection between humanism and the scientific discovery may very well have begun within the confines of the university, the connection has been commonly perceived as having been severed by the changing nature of science during the scientific revolution. Historians such as [dblookup('Richard S. Westfall', 'Argument About') -> university traditionalism inhibiting scientific progress] Richard S. Westfall have argued that the overt traditionalism of universities inhibited attempts to re-conceptualize nature and knowledge and caused an indelible tension between universities and scientists. This resistance to changes in science may have been a significant factor in driving many [dblookup('Scientists', 'Move To') -> private benefactors, princely courts, scientific societies] scientists away from the university and toward private benefactors, usually in princely courts, and associations with newly forming scientific societies.
examples.text: University: Examining the influence of humanism on scholars in medicine, mathematics, astronomy and physics may suggest that humanism and universities were a strong impetus for the scientific revolution. Although the connection between humanism and the scientific discovery may very well have begun within the confines of the university, the connection has been commonly perceived as having been severed by the changing nature of science during the scientific revolution. Historians such as Richard S. Westfall have argued that the overt traditionalism of universities inhibited attempts to re-conceptualize nature and knowledge and caused an indelible tension between universities and scientists. This resistance to changes in science may have been a significant factor in driving many scientists away from the university and toward private benefactors, usually in princely courts, and associations with newly forming scientific societies.

examples.annotated_text: Sichuan: On [dblookup('Sichuan Transportation Bureau', 'Announcement Date for Sui-Yu Expressway Completion') -> November 3, 2007] 3 November 2007, the Sichuan Transportation Bureau announced that the [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Construction Duration') -> three years] Sui-Yu Expressway was completed after three years of construction. After completion of the Chongqing section of the road, the [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Length in Kilometers') -> 36.64] 36.64 km (22.77 mi) expressway connected Cheng-Nan Expressway and formed the [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Significance') -> shortest expressway from Chengdu to Chongqing] shortest expressway from Chengdu to Chongqing. The new expressway is [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Shorter Than Pre-existing Road by Kilometers') -> 50] 50 km (31 mi) shorter than the pre-existing road between Chengdu and Chongqing; thus journey time between the two cities was reduced by an [dblookup('Chengdu to Chongqing New Journey Time', 'Reduction') -> hour] hour, now taking [dblookup('Chengdu to Chongqing New Journey Time', 'Duration') -> two and a half hours] two and a half hours. The Sui-Yu Expressway is a [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Number of Lanes') -> four lane] four lane overpass with a [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Speed Limit in km/h') -> 80] speed limit of 80 km/h (50 mph). The total [dblookup('Sui-Yu Expressway', 'Investment Amount') -> 1.045 billion yuan] investment was 1.045 billion yuan.
examples.text: Sichuan: On 3 November 2007, the Sichuan Transportation Bureau announced that the Sui-Yu Expressway was completed after three years of construction. After completion of the Chongqing section of the road, the 36.64 km (22.77 mi) expressway connected Cheng-Nan Expressway and formed the shortest expressway from Chengdu to Chongqing. The new expressway is 50 km (31 mi) shorter than the pre-existing road between Chengdu and Chongqing; thus journey time between the two cities was reduced by an hour, now taking two and a half hours. The Sui-Yu Expressway is a four lane overpass with a speed limit of 80 km/h (50 mph). The total investment was 1.045 billion yuan.

examples.annotated_text: Dog: Although it is said that the "dog is man's best friend" regarding 17–24% of dogs in the [dblookup('Dog', 'Domestication Rate Developed Countries') -> 17-24%] developed countries, in the [dblookup('Dog', 'Feral Status In Developing World') -> feral, village or community dogs] developing world they are feral, village or community dogs, with pet dogs uncommon. These live their lives as scavengers and have never been owned by humans, with one study showing their [dblookup('Feral Dogs', 'Common Response To Strangers') -> run away (52%), respond with aggression (11%)] most common response when approached by strangers was to run away (52%) or respond with aggression (11%). We know little about these dogs, nor about the dogs that live in developed countries that are [dblookup('Dogs in Developed Countries', 'Non-Pet Status') -> feral, stray, or in shelters] feral, stray or are in shelters, yet the great majority of modern research on dog cognition has focused on pet dogs living in human homes.
examples.text: Dog: Although it is said that the "dog is man's best friend" regarding 17–24% of dogs in the developed countries, in the developing world they are feral, village or community dogs, with pet dogs uncommon. These live their lives as scavengers and have never been owned by humans, with one study showing their most common response when approached by strangers was to run away (52%) or respond with aggression (11%). We know little about these dogs, nor about the dogs that live in developed countries that are feral, stray or are in shelters, yet the great majority of modern research on dog cognition has focused on pet dogs living in human homes.

examples.annotated_text: Hellenistic_period: The level of Hellenistic achievement in astronomy and engineering is impressively shown by the [dblookup('Antikythera mechanism', 'Era') -> Hellenistic] Antikythera mechanism (150–100 BC). It is a 37-gear mechanical computer which computed the motions of the Sun and Moon, including lunar and solar eclipses predicted on the basis of [dblookup('Antikythera mechanism', 'Astronomical Knowledge Source') -> Babylonian] astronomical periods believed to have been learned from the Babylonians. Devices of this sort are not found again until the 10th century, when a simpler eight-geared luni-solar calculator incorporated into an astrolabe was described by the Persian scholar, [dblookup('Luni-solar calculator', 'Described By') -> Al-Biruni] Al-Biruni. Similarly complex devices were also developed by other Muslim engineers and astronomers during the [dblookup('Muslim Engineers and Astronomers', 'Era of Similar Devices Development') -> Middle Ages] Middle Ages.
examples.text: Hellenistic_period: The level of Hellenistic achievement in astronomy and engineering is impressively shown by the Antikythera mechanism (150–100 BC). It is a 37-gear mechanical computer which computed the motions of the Sun and Moon, including lunar and solar eclipses predicted on the basis of astronomical periods believed to have been learned from the Babylonians. Devices of this sort are not found again until the 10th century, when a simpler eight-geared luni-solar calculator incorporated into an astrolabe was described by the Persian scholar, Al-Biruni.[not in citation given] Similarly complex devices were also developed by other Muslim engineers and astronomers during the Middle Ages.[not in citation given]

examples.annotated_text: Affirmative_action_in_the_United_States: In the US, a prominent form of racial preferences relates to [dblookup('Affirmative Action in the United States', 'Area Focus') -> access to education] access to education, particularly admission to universities and other forms of higher education. Race, ethnicity, native language, social class, geographical origin, parental attendance of the university in question (legacy admissions), and/or gender are sometimes taken into account when [dblookup('Universities in the United States', 'Admission Assessment Criteria') -> race, ethnicity, native language, social class, geographical origin, parental attendance, gender] the university assesses an applicant's grades and test scores. Individuals can also be [dblookup('Individuals in the United States', 'Scholarship Criteria') -> race, ethnicity, native language, social class, geographical origin, parental attendance, gender] awarded scholarships and have fees paid on the basis of criteria listed above. In 1978, the [dblookup('Bakke v. Regents', 'Court Ruling Year') -> 1978] Supreme Court ruled in Bakke v. Regents that public universities (and other government institutions) [dblookup('Bakke v. Regents', 'Prohibition On') -> specific numerical targets based on race] could not set specific numerical targets based on race for admissions or employment. The [dblookup('Supreme Court of the United States', 'Decision on Race-Based Diversity Measures') -> goals and timetables for diversity] Court said that "goals" and "timetables" for diversity could be set instead.
examples.text: Affirmative_action_in_the_United_States: In the US, a prominent form of racial preferences relates to access to education, particularly admission to universities and other forms of higher education. Race, ethnicity, native language, social class, geographical origin, parental attendance of the university in question (legacy admissions), and/or gender are sometimes taken into account when the university assesses an applicant's grades and test scores. Individuals can also be awarded scholarships and have fees paid on the basis of criteria listed above. In 1978, the Supreme Court ruled in Bakke v. Regents that public universities (and other government institutions) could not set specific numerical targets based on race for admissions or employment. examples.annotated_text: Separation_of_church_and_state_in_the_United_States: Subsequent to this [dblookup('Supreme Court of the United States', 'Decision Related To') -> Establishment Clause] decision, the [dblookup('Supreme Court of the United States', 'Test Applied For Establishment Clause') -> Lemon Test] Supreme Court has applied a three-pronged test to determine whether government action comports with the Establishment Clause, known as the "Lemon Test". First, the law or policy must have been adopted with a neutral or non-religious purpose. Second, the principle or primary effect must be one that neither advances nor inhibits religion. Third, the statute or policy must not result in an "excessive entanglement" of government with religion. (The decision in Lemon v. Kurtzman hinged upon the conclusion that the government benefits were flowing disproportionately to Catholic schools, and that Catholic schools were an integral component of the Catholic Church's religious mission, thus the policy involved the state in an "excessive entanglement" with religion.) Failure to meet any of these criteria is a proof that the statute or policy in question violates the Establishment Clause.

examples.annotated_text: Korean_War: On 15 October 1950, [dblookup('Meeting of Truman and MacArthur', 'Location') -> Wake Island] President Truman and General MacArthur met at Wake Island in the mid-Pacific Ocean. To President Truman, MacArthur speculated there was little risk of Chinese intervention in Korea, and that the [dblookup('General MacArthur', 'Chinese Intervention View') -> PRC's opportunity for aiding the KPA had lapsed] PRC's opportunity for aiding the KPA had lapsed. He believed the PRC had some 300,000 soldiers in Manchuria, and [dblookup('PRC', 'Yalu River Military Presence') -> 100,000–125,000 soldiers] some 100,000–125,000 soldiers at the Yalu River. He further concluded that, although half of those forces might cross south, "if the Chinese tried to get down to Pyongyang, there would be the greatest slaughter" without air force protection.

These are rights-driven groups that organize themselves in order to achieve some sort of self-determination and the preservation of their culture for their peoples. Organizations like the Coordinator of Indigenous Organizations of the Amazon River Basin and the Indian Council of South America are examples of movements that are breaking the barrier of borders in order to obtain rights for Amazonian indigenous populations everywhere. Similar movements for indigenous rights can also be seen in Canada and the United States, with movements like the International Indian Treaty Council and the accession of native Indian group into the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization.

examples.annotated_text: Religion_in_ancient_Rome: Lucan depicts Sextus Pompeius, the doomed son of Pompey the Great, as convinced "the gods of heaven knew too little" and awaiting the Battle of Pharsalus by consulting with the Thessalian witch Erichtho, who practices necromancy and inhabits deserted graves, feeding on rotting corpses. examples.annotated_text: Galicia_(Spain): The Castro culture ('Culture of the Castles') developed during the [dblookup('Castro Culture', 'Development Period') -> Iron Age] Iron Age and flourished during the [dblookup('Castro Culture', 'Flourished Period') -> second half of the first millennium BC] second half of the first millennium BC. It is usually considered a [dblookup('Castro Culture', 'Origin') -> local evolution of the Atlantic Bronze Age] local evolution of the Atlantic Bronze Age, with later developments and influences and overlapping into the Roman era. Geographically, it corresponds to the people Roman called Gallaeci, which were composed by a large series of nations or tribes, among them the [dblookup('Gallaeci', 'Tribes') -> Artabri, Bracari, Limici, Celtici, Albiones, Lemavi] Artabri, Bracari, Limici, Celtici, Albiones, and Lemavi. They were capable fighters: [dblookup('Gallaeci', 'Described As') -> most difficult foes] Strabo described them as the most difficult foes the Romans encountered in conquering Lusitania, while [dblookup('Gallaeci', 'Spirit Described By') -> warlike spirit] Appian mentions their warlike spirit, noting that the women bore their weapons side by side with their men, frequently preferring death to captivity. According to [dblookup('Gallaeci', 'Cultural Identification By') -> Pomponius Mela] Pomponius Mela, all the inhabitants of the coastal areas were [dblookup('Coastal Inhabitants of Galicia', 'Cultural Identity') -> Celtic people] Celtic people.
examples.text: Galicia_(Spain): The Castro culture ('Culture of the Castles') developed during the Iron Age, and flourished during the second half of the first millennium BC. It is usually considered a local evolution of the Atlantic Bronze Age, with later developments and influences and overlapping into the Roman era. Geographically, it corresponds to the people Roman called Gallaeci, which were composed by a large series of nations or tribes, among them the Artabri, Bracari, Limici, Celtici, Albiones and Lemavi. According to Pomponius Mela all the inhabitants of the coastal areas were Celtic people.

examples.annotated_text: Eritrea: The [dblookup('Culture of Eritrea', 'Influenced By') -> Red Sea coast] culture of Eritrea has been largely shaped by the country's location on the Red Sea coast. One of the most recognizable parts of Eritrean culture is the [dblookup('Eritrean Culture', 'Notable Tradition') -> coffee ceremony] coffee ceremony. Coffee ( Ge'ez ቡን būn) is offered when visiting friends, during festivities, or as a daily staple of life. During the coffee ceremony, there are traditions that are upheld. The coffee is served in three rounds: the first brew or round is called [dblookup('First Coffee Round', 'Name in Tigrinya') -> awel] awel in Tigrinya meaning first, the second round is called [dblookup('Second Coffee Round', 'Name in Tigrinya') -> kalaay] kalaay meaning second, and the third round is called [dblookup('Third Coffee Round', 'Name in Tigrinya') -> bereka] bereka meaning "to be blessed". examples.annotated_text: Matter: A source of definition difficulty in relativity arises from two definitions of mass in common use, one of which is formally equivalent to [dblookup('Total Energy Mass', 'Dependence') -> observer dependent] total energy (and is thus observer dependent), and the other of which is referred to as rest mass or invariant mass and is [dblookup('Rest Mass', 'Dependence') -> observer independent] independent of the observer. Only "rest mass" is loosely equated with matter (since it can be weighed). Invariant mass is usually applied in physics to unbound systems of particles. However, energies which contribute to the "invariant mass" may be weighed also in special circumstances, such as when a system that has invariant mass is confined and has no net momentum (as in the box example above). Thus, a photon with no mass may (confusingly) still add [dblookup('Photon', 'Contribution to System Mass') -> adds mass] mass to a system in which it is trapped. The same is true of the kinetic energy of particles, which by definition is not part of their rest mass, but which does add rest mass to systems in which these particles reside (an example is the [dblookup('Kinetic Energy', 'Mass Contribution') -> adds rest mass] mass added by the motion of gas molecules of a bottle of gas, or by the thermal energy of any hot object).

examples.annotated_text: Separation_of_church_and_state_in_the_United_States: In [dblookup('Epperson v. Arkansas', 'Case Citation') -> 393 U.S. 97 (1968)] Epperson v. Arkansas, 393 U.S. 97 (1968), the [dblookup('United States Supreme Court', 'Considered Law') -> Arkansas law on teaching evolution] Supreme Court considered an Arkansas law that made it a crime "to teach the theory or doctrine that mankind ascended or descended from a lower order of animals," or "to adopt or use in any such institution a textbook that teaches" this theory in any school or university that received public funds. The court's opinion, written by [dblookup('Epperson v. Arkansas', 'Opinion Written By') -> Justice Abe Fortas] Justice Abe Fortas, ruled that the Arkansas law violated "the constitutional prohibition of state laws respecting an establishment of religion or prohibiting the free exercise thereof." The overriding fact is that Arkansas' law selects from the body of knowledge a particular segment which it proscribes for the sole reason that it is deemed to conflict with a particular religious doctrine; that is, with a particular interpretation of the Book of Genesis by a particular religious group." The court held that the [dblookup('Establishment Clause', 'Role In Epperson v. Arkansas') -> prohibits state advancement of religion] Establishment Clause prohibits the state from advancing any religion, and that "[T]he state has no legitimate interest in protecting any or all religions from views distasteful to them."

examples.annotated_text: Data_compression: The most powerful used method works by comparing each frame in the video with the previous one. If the frame contains areas where nothing has moved, the system simply issues a short command that copies that part of the previous frame, bit-for-bit, into the next one. If sections of the frame move in a simple manner, the compressor emits a (slightly longer) command that tells the decompressor to shift, rotate, lighten, or darken the copy. This longer command still remains much shorter than intraframe compression. Interframe compression works well for programs that will simply be played back by the viewer, but can cause problems if the video sequence needs to be edited.

examples.text: Liberal_Party_of_Australia: Menzies ran strongly against Labor's plans to nationalise the Australian banking system and, following victory in the 1949 election, secured a double dissolution election for April 1951, after the Labor-controlled Senate refused to pass his banking legislation. The Liberal-Country Coalition was returned with control of the Senate. examples.annotated_text: Tuberculosis: TB [dblookup('Tuberculosis', 'Infection Origin') -> pulmonary alveoli] infection begins when the mycobacteria reach the pulmonary alveoli, where they invade and replicate within endosomes of [dblookup('Tuberculosis', 'Target Cell') -> alveolar macrophages] alveolar macrophages. Macrophages identify the bacterium as foreign and attempt to eliminate it by phagocytosis. During this process, the bacterium is enveloped by the macrophage and stored temporarily in a membrane-bound vesicle called a [dblookup('Phagocytosis Process', 'Intermediate Structure') -> phagosome] phagosome. The phagosome then combines with a lysosome to create a phagolysosome. In the phagolysosome, the cell attempts to use reactive oxygen species and acid to kill the bacterium. However, [dblookup('Mycobacterium tuberculosis', 'Protective Feature') -> thick, waxy mycolic acid capsule] M. tuberculosis has a thick, waxy mycolic acid capsule that protects it from these toxic substances. M. tuberculosis is [dblookup('Mycobacterium tuberculosis', 'Reproductive Ability') -> reproduce inside macrophage] able to reproduce inside the macrophage and will eventually kill the immune cell.

However, M. tuberculosis has a thick, waxy mycolic acid capsule that protects it from these toxic substances. M. tuberculosis is able to reproduce inside the macrophage and will eventually kill the immune cell.

examples.text: Antarctica: The first semi-permanent inhabitants of regions near Antarctica (areas situated south of the Antarctic Convergence) were British and American sealers who used to spend a year or more on South Georgia, from 1786 onward. examples.annotated_text: Mandolin: Many adaptations of the instrument have been done to cater to the special needs of [dblookup('Mandolin', 'Usage In Music Genre') -> Indian Carnatic music] Indian Carnatic music. examples.text: Mandolin: Many adaptations of the instrument have been done to cater to the special needs of Indian Carnatic music. In Indian classical music and Indian light music, the mandolin, which bears little resemblance to the European mandolin, is usually tuned E-B-E-B. As there is no concept of absolute pitch in Indian classical music, any convenient tuning maintaining these relative pitch intervals between the strings can be used. Another prevalent tuning with these intervals is C-G-C-G, which corresponds to Sa-Pa-Sa-Pa in the Indian carnatic classical music style. This tuning corresponds to the way violins are tuned for carnatic classical music. This type of mandolin is also used in Bhangra, dance music popular in Punjabi culture.

examples.annotated_text: Green: Green can communicate safety to proceed, as in traffic lights. Green and red were standardized as the colors of international railroad signals in the 19th century. The [dblookup('First Traffic Light', 'Erected Location') -> Houses of Parliament in London] first traffic light, using green and red gas lamps, was erected in 1868 in front of the Houses of Parliament in London. It exploded the following year, injuring the policeman who operated it. In 1912, the [dblookup('First Modern Electric Traffic Lights', 'Installed Location') -> Salt Lake City, Utah] first modern electric traffic lights were put up in Salt Lake City, Utah. Red was chosen largely because of its [dblookup('Red Light', 'Characteristics') -> high visibility, association with danger] high visibility, and its association with danger, while green was chosen largely because it could not be mistaken for red. Today green lights universally [dblookup('Green Lights', 'Universal Signal') -> system is turned on and working] signal that a system is turned on and working as it should. In many video games, green signifies both [dblookup('Green', 'Significance in Video Games') -> health, completed objectives] health and completed objectives, opposite red.
examples.text: Green: Green can communicate safety to proceed, as in traffic lights. Green and red were standardized as the colors of international railroad signals in the 19th century. The first traffic light, using green and red gas lamps, was erected in 1868 in front of the Houses of Parliament in London. It exploded the following year, injuring the policeman who operated it. In 1912, the first modern electric traffic lights were put up in Salt Lake City, Utah. Red was chosen largely because of its high visibility, and its association with danger, while green was chosen largely because it could not be mistaken for red. Today green lights universally signal that a system is turned on and working as it should. In many video games, green signifies both health and completed objectives, opposite red.

examples.annotated_text: Neolithic: In [dblookup('Southeast Europe', 'First Agrarian Societies Appeared In') -> 7th millennium BC] southeast Europe, agrarian societies first appeared in the 7th millennium BC, attested by [dblookup('Earliest Farming Sites', 'Discovered Location') -> Vashtëmi, southeastern Albania] one of the earliest farming sites of Europe, discovered in Vashtëmi, southeastern Albania and dating back to [dblookup('Earliest Farming Sites', 'Date') -> 6,500 BC] 6,500 BC. Anthropomorphic figurines have been found in the [dblookup('Anthropomorphic Figurines', 'Earliest Appearance in Balkans') -> 6000 BC] Balkans from 6000 BC, and in [dblookup('Anthropomorphic Figurines', 'Earliest Appearance in Central Europe') -> c. 5800 BC] Central Europe by c. 5800 BC (La Hoguette). Among the earliest cultural complexes of this area are the [dblookup('Sesklo culture', 'Location') -> Thessaly] Sesklo culture in Thessaly, which later expanded in the Balkans giving rise to Starčevo-Körös (Cris), Linearbandkeramik, and Vinča. Through a combination of cultural diffusion and migration of peoples, the Neolithic traditions spread west and northwards to reach northwestern Europe by around [dblookup('Neolithic Traditions Spread', 'Reached Northwestern Europe By') -> 4500 BC] 4500 BC. The Vinča culture may have created the earliest system of writing, the [dblookup('Earliest System of Writing', 'Vinča Signs') -> Vinča signs] Vinča signs, though archaeologist Shan Winn believes they most likely represented pictograms and ideograms rather than a truly developed form of writing. The Cucuteni-Trypillian culture built enormous settlements in Romania, Moldova, and Ukraine from [dblookup('Cucuteni-Trypillian Culture', 'Time Period') -> 5300 to 2300 BC] 5300 to 2300 BC. The megalithic temple complexes of Ġgantija on the Mediterranean island of Gozo (in the [dblookup('Ġgantija Temple Complex', 'Location') -> Maltese archipelago] Maltese archipelago) and of Mnajdra (Malta) are notable for their gigantic Neolithic structures, the oldest of which date back to [dblookup('Ġgantija and Mnajdra', 'Earliest Structures Date') -> c. 3600 BC] c. 3600 BC. The Hypogeum of Ħal-Saflieni, Paola, Malta, is a subterranean structure excavated c. 2500 BC; originally a sanctuary, it became a necropolis, the only prehistoric underground temple in the world, showing a degree of artistry in stone sculpture unique in prehistory to the [dblookup('Ħal-Saflieni', 'Unique Artistic Region') -> Maltese islands] Maltese islands. After 2500 BC, the [dblookup('Maltese Islands', 'Depopulation Period') -> After 2500 BC] Maltese Islands were depopulated for several decades until the arrival of a new influx of Bronze Age immigrants, a culture that [dblookup('Bronze Age Culture', 'Funeral Practice') -> cremated its dead] cremated its dead and introduced smaller megalithic structures called dolmens to Malta. In most cases, there are small chambers here, with the cover made of a large slab placed on upright stones. They are claimed to belong to a population certainly different from that which built the previous megalithic temples. It is presumed the population arrived from [dblookup('Bronze Age Immigrants', 'Origin') -> Sicily] Sicily because of the similarity of Maltese dolmens to some small constructions found in the [dblookup('Sicily', 'Geographical Characteristic') -> largest island of the Mediterranean Sea] largest island of the Mediterranean Sea.
examples.text: Neolithic: In southeast Europe agrarian societies first appeared in the 7th millennium BC, attested by one of the earliest farming sites of Europe, discovered in Vashtëmi, southeastern Albania and dating back to 6,500 BC. Anthropomorphic figurines have been found in the Balkans from 6000 BC, and in Central Europe by c. 5800 BC (La Hoguette). Among the earliest cultural complexes of this area are the Sesklo culture in Thessaly, which later expanded in the Balkans giving rise to Starčevo-Körös (Cris), Linearbandkeramik, and Vinča. Through a combination of cultural diffusion and migration of peoples, the Neolithic traditions spread west and northwards to reach northwestern Europe by around 4500 BC. The Vinča culture may have created the earliest system of writing, the Vinča signs, though archaeologist Shan Winn believes they most likely represented pictograms and ideograms rather than a truly developed form of writing. The Cucuteni-Trypillian culture built enormous settlements in Romania, Moldova and Ukraine from 5300 to 2300 BC. The megalithic temple complexes of Ġgantija on the Mediterranean island of Gozo (in the Maltese archipelago) and of Mnajdra (Malta) are notable for their gigantic Neolithic structures, the oldest of which date back to c. 3600 BC. The Hypogeum of Ħal-Saflieni, Paola, Malta, is a subterranean structure excavated c. 2500 BC; originally a sanctuary, it became a necropolis, the only prehistoric underground temple in the world, and showing a degree of artistry in stone sculpture unique in prehistory to the Maltese islands. After 2500 BC, the Maltese Islands were depopulated for several decades until the arrival of a new influx of Bronze Age immigrants, a culture that cremated its dead and introduced smaller megalithic structures called dolmens to Malta. In most cases there are small chambers here, with the cover made of a large slab placed on upright stones. They are claimed to belong to a population certainly different from that which built the previous megalithic temples. It is presumed the population arrived from Sicily because of the similarity of Maltese dolmens to some small constructions found in the largest island of the Mediterranean sea.

examples.annotated_text: Vacuum: Vacuum is space [dblookup('Vacuum', 'Definition') -> void of matter] void of matter. The word stems from the [dblookup('Vacuum', 'Etymology Source') -> Latin adjective vacuus] Latin adjective vacuus for "vacant" or "void". An approximation to such vacuum is a region with [dblookup('Vacuum', 'Characteristic') -> gaseous pressure much less than atmospheric pressure] a gaseous pressure much less than atmospheric pressure. Physicists often discuss ideal test results that would occur in a perfect vacuum, which they sometimes simply call "vacuum" or free space, and use the term [dblookup('Partial Vacuum', 'Definition') -> actual imperfect vacuum] partial vacuum to refer to an actual imperfect vacuum as one might have in a laboratory or in space. In engineering and applied physics on the other hand, vacuum refers to any space in which the pressure is lower than atmospheric pressure. The Latin term in vacuo is used to describe an object as being in what would otherwise be a vacuum.

examples.annotated_text: Presbyterianism: In the late 1800s, Presbyterian missionaries established a presence in what is now [dblookup('Presbyterianism', 'Region of Influence') -> northern New Mexico] northern New Mexico. In some cases, the converts left towns and villages to establish their own neighboring villages. However, there are still stalwart [dblookup('Stalwart Presbyterians', 'Presence') -> Presbyterian churches in northern New Mexico] Presbyterians and Presbyterian churches in the area.

examples.annotated_text: Montana: As white settlers began populating [dblookup('Montana', 'Settler Influx Period') -> 1850s-1870s] Montana from the 1850s through the 1870s, disputes with Native Americans ensued, primarily over land ownership and control. The treaty was [dblookup('Hellgate Treaty', 'Ratified In') -> 1859] ratified in 1859. While the treaty established what later became the [dblookup('Flathead Indian Reservation', 'Established By') -> Hellgate Treaty] Flathead Indian Reservation, trouble with interpreters and confusion over the terms of the treaty led whites to believe that the Bitterroot Valley was opened to settlement, but the tribal nations disputed those provisions. examples.annotated_text: Baptists: As early as the late [dblookup('Black Baptists', 'Separate Churches Established In') -> 18th century] 18th century, black Baptists began to organize separate churches, associations, and mission agencies, especially in the northern states. Not only did blacks set up some independent congregations in the South before the American Civil War, freedmen quickly separated from white congregations and associations after the war. They wanted to be free of white supervision. In [dblookup('Consolidated American Baptist Convention', 'Formation Year') -> 1866] 1866, the Consolidated American Baptist Convention, formed from black Baptists of the South and West, helped southern associations set up black state conventions, which they did in [dblookup('Black State Conventions', 'Established In States') -> Alabama, Arkansas, Virginia, North Carolina, Kentucky] Alabama, Arkansas, Virginia, North Carolina, and Kentucky. In [dblookup('Foreign Mission Convention', 'Formation Year') -> 1880] 1880, black state conventions united in the national Foreign Mission Convention to support black Baptist missionary work. Two other national black conventions were formed, and in [dblookup('National Baptist Convention', 'Formation Year') -> 1895] 1895 they united as the [dblookup('National Baptist Convention', 'Significance') -> largest black religious organization, second largest Baptist organization] National Baptist Convention. This organization later went through its own changes, spinning off other conventions. It is the largest black religious organization and the second largest Baptist organization in the world. Baptists are numerically most dominant in the Southeast. In [dblookup('Pew Research Center\'s Religious Landscape Survey', 'Year') -> 2007] 2007, the Pew Research Center's Religious Landscape Survey found that 45% of all African-Americans identify with Baptist denominations, with the vast majority of those being within the historically black tradition.
examples.text: Baptists: As early as the late 18th century, black Baptists began to organize separate churches, associations and mission agencies, especially in the northern states. Not only did blacks set up some independent congregations in the South before the American Civil War, freedmen quickly separated from white congregations and associations after the war. They wanted to be free of white supervision. In 1866 the Consolidated American Baptist Convention, formed from black Baptists of the South and West, helped southern associations set up black state conventions, which they did in Alabama, Arkansas, Virginia, North Carolina, and Kentucky. In 1880 black state conventions united in the national Foreign Mission Convention, to support black Baptist missionary work. Two other national black conventions were formed, and in 1895 they united as the National Baptist Convention. This organization later went through its own changes, spinning off other conventions. It is the largest black religious organization and the second largest Baptist organization in the world. Baptists are numerically most dominant in the Southeast. In 2007, the Pew Research Center's Religious Landscape Survey found that 45% of all African-Americans identify with Baptist denominations, with the vast majority of those being within the historically black tradition.

examples.annotated_text: Infrared: Heat is [dblookup('Heat', 'Nature') -> energy in transit] energy in transit that flows due to a [dblookup('Heat', 'Flows Due To') -> temperature difference] temperature difference. Unlike heat transmitted by thermal conduction or thermal convection, thermal radiation can propagate through a vacuum. Thermal radiation is characterized by a [dblookup('Thermal Radiation', 'Characterized By') -> particular spectrum of many wavelengths] particular spectrum of many wavelengths that is associated with emission from an object, due to the vibration of its molecules at a given temperature. Thermal radiation can be emitted from objects at any wavelength, and at very high temperatures such radiations are associated with spectra far above the infrared, extending into visible, ultraviolet, and even X-ray regions (i.e., the solar corona). Thus, the popular association of infrared radiation with thermal radiation is only a [dblookup('Infrared Radiation', 'Association With') -> coincidence with typical surface temperatures of Earth] coincidence based on typical (comparatively low) temperatures often found near the surface of planet Earth.

examples.annotated_text: Bermuda: The island experienced large-scale [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Immigration Increase') -> 20th century] immigration over the 20th century, especially after the [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Significant Immigration Period') -> Second World War] Second World War. Bermuda has a [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Population Diversity') -> diverse population] diverse population including both those with relatively deep roots in Bermuda extending back for centuries, and newer communities whose ancestry results from recent immigration, especially from [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Significant Source of Immigration') -> Britain, North America, West Indies, Portuguese Atlantic islands] Britain, North America, the West Indies, and the Portuguese Atlantic islands (especially the Azores), although these groups are steadily merging. About 46% of the population [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'Bermudian Ancestry Percentage 2010') -> 46%] identified themselves with Bermudian ancestry in 2010, which was [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'Bermudian Ancestry Decrease') -> 51% (2000 census)] a decrease from the 51% who did so in the 2000 census. Those identifying with [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'British Ancestry Percentage 2010') -> 11%] British ancestry dropped by 1% to 11% (although those [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'Largest Non-Native Group') -> born in Britain] born in Britain remain the largest non-native group at 3,942 persons). The number of people born in [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'Canadian Born Percentage Decrease') -> 13%] Canada declined by 13%. Those who reported [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'West Indian Ancestry Percentage 2010') -> 13%] West Indian ancestry were 13%. The number of people born in the West Indies actually [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'West Indies Born Increase') -> 538] increased by 538. A significant segment of the population is of [dblookup('Bermuda Population', 'Portuguese Ancestry Percentage') -> 10%] Portuguese ancestry (10%), the result of immigration over the past 160 years, of whom [dblookup('Bermuda Portuguese Population', 'Residency Status Percentage') -> 79%] 79% have residency status.
examples.text: Bermuda: The island experienced large-scale immigration over the 20th century, especially after the Second World War. Bermuda has a diverse population including both those with relatively deep roots in Bermuda extending back for centuries, and newer communities whose ancestry results from recent immigration, especially from Britain, North America, the West Indies, and the Portuguese Atlantic islands (especially the Azores), although these groups are steadily merging. About 46% of the population identified themselves with Bermudian ancestry in 2010, which was a decrease from the 51% who did so in the 2000 census. Those identifying with British ancestry dropped by 1% to 11% (although those born in Britain remain the largest non-native group at 3,942 persons). The number of people born in Canada declined by 13%. Those who reported West Indian ancestry were 13%. The number of people born in the West Indies actually increased by 538. examples.annotated_text: Switzerland: Switzerland's ecosystems can be particularly fragile, because the many delicate valleys separated by high mountains often form unique ecologies. The mountainous regions themselves are also vulnerable, with a rich range of plants not found at other altitudes, and experience some pressure from visitors and grazing. The climatic, geological and topographical conditions of the alpine region make for a very fragile ecosystem that is particularly sensitive to climate change. Nevertheless, according to [dblookup('Switzerland', 'Environmental Performance Index Rank in 2014') -> 1st] the 2014 Environmental Performance Index, Switzerland ranks first among [dblookup('Environmental Performance Index', 'Total Nations Ranked in 2014') -> 132] 132 nations in safeguarding the environment, due to its high scores on [dblookup('Switzerland', 'Environmental Public Health Score') -> high] environmental public health, its heavy reliance on renewable sources of energy ( hydropower and geothermal energy), and its control of [dblookup('Switzerland', 'Greenhouse Gas Emissions Control') -> effective] greenhouse gas emissions.

examples.annotated_text: Annelid: The basic [dblookup('Annelid', 'Structural Feature') -> multiple segments] annelid form consists of multiple segments. Each segment has the same sets of [dblookup('Annelid', 'Organ Distribution') -> same sets of organs per segment] organs and, in most polychaetes, has a pair of [dblookup('Polychaetes', 'Locomotion Feature') -> parapodia] parapodia that many species use for locomotion. [dblookup('Annelid', 'Segment Separation') -> septa] Septa separate the segments of many species, but are poorly defined or absent in others, and [dblookup('Echiura', 'Segmentation') -> no obvious segmentation] Echiura and Sipuncula show no obvious signs of segmentation. In species with well-developed [dblookup('Annelid', 'Well-developed Segment Features') -> septa] septa, the blood circulates entirely within blood vessels, and the vessels in segments near the front ends of these species are often built up with [dblookup('Annelid', 'Circulatory Feature') -> muscles that act as hearts] muscles that act as hearts. The septa of such species also enable them to [dblookup('Annelid', 'Locomotion Mechanism') -> change the shapes of individual segments] change the shapes of individual segments, which facilitates movement by [dblookup('Annelid', 'Locomotion Type') -> peristalsis] peristalsis ("ripples" that pass along the body) or by [dblookup('Annelid', 'Locomotion Enhancement') -> undulations] undulations that improve the effectiveness of the parapodia. In species with incomplete septa or none, [dblookup('Annelid', 'Alternate Blood Circulation') -> blood circulates through main body cavity] the blood circulates through the main body cavity without any kind of pump, and there is a wide range of [dblookup('Annelid', 'Locomotory Techniques') -> various techniques] locomotory techniques – some burrowing species turn their pharynges inside out to drag themselves through the sediment.
examples.text: Annelid: The basic annelid form consists of multiple segments. Each segment has the same sets of organs and, in most polychaetes, has a pair of parapodia that many species use for locomotion. Septa separate the segments of many species, but are poorly defined or absent in others, and Echiura and Sipuncula show no obvious signs of segmentation. In species with well-developed septa, the blood circulates entirely within blood vessels, and the vessels in segments near the front ends of these species are often built up with muscles that act as hearts. The septa of such species also enable them to change the shapes of individual segments, which facilitates movement by peristalsis ("ripples" that pass along the body) or by undulations that improve the effectiveness of the parapodia. In species with incomplete septa or none, the blood circulates through the main body cavity without any kind of pump, and there is a wide range of locomotory techniques – some burrowing species turn their pharynges inside out to drag themselves through the sediment.

examples.annotated_text: Plymouth: The 1971 Local Government White Paper proposed [dblookup('Local Government White Paper 1971', 'Proposed Action') -> abolishing county boroughs] abolishing county boroughs, which would have left Plymouth, a town of 250,000 people, being administered from a council based at the [dblookup('Plymouth', 'Proposed Administrator Location') -> Exeter] smaller Exeter, on the other side of the county. This led to Plymouth lobbying for the creation of a [dblookup('Plymouth', 'Proposed New County') -> Tamarside] Tamarside county, to include Plymouth, Torpoint, Saltash, and the rural hinterland. The [dblookup('Tamarside County Campaign', 'Outcome') -> unsuccessful] campaign was not successful, and Plymouth ceased to be a county borough on [dblookup('Plymouth', 'County Borough Status End Date') -> 1 April 1974] 1 April 1974 with responsibility for [dblookup('Plymouth', 'Transferred Responsibilities to Devon County Council') -> education, social services, highways, and libraries] education, social services, highways, and libraries transferred to Devon County Council. All powers returned when the city [dblookup('Plymouth', 'Unitary Authority Start Date') -> 1 April 1998] became a unitary authority on 1 April 1998 under recommendations of the [dblookup('Banham Commission', 'Recommendation') -> Plymouth unitary authority status] Banham Commission.
examples.text: Plymouth: The 1971 Local Government White Paper proposed abolishing county boroughs, which would have left Plymouth, a town of 250,000 people, being administered from a council based at the smaller Exeter, on the other side of the county. This led to Plymouth lobbying for the creation of a Tamarside county, to include Plymouth, Torpoint, Saltash, and the rural hinterland. The campaign was not successful, and Plymouth ceased to be a county borough on 1 April 1974 with responsibility for education, social services, highways and libraries transferred to Devon County Council. All powers returned when the city become a unitary authority on 1 April 1998 under recommendations of the Banham Commission.

examples.annotated_text: Hindu_philosophy: In Indian philosophy, [dblookup('Yoga', 'Philosophical School Classification') -> āstika philosophical schools] Yoga is among other things, the name of one of the six āstika philosophical schools. The epistemology of the [dblookup('Yoga', 'Pramanas Utilized') -> pratyakṣa, anumāṇa, śabda] Yoga school, like the Sāmkhya school, relies on three of six prāmaṇas as the means of gaining reliable knowledge: pratyakṣa (perception), anumāṇa (inference) and śabda (āptavacana, word/testimony of reliable sources).

examples.annotated_text: Association_football: The [dblookup('Referee', 'Authority Over') -> players, substitutes, substituted players] referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card). A second yellow card at the same game leads to a [dblookup('Second Yellow Card', 'Consequences') -> red card] red card, and therefore to a dismissal. A player given a yellow card is [dblookup('Yellow Card', 'Common Term') -> booked] said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in his official notebook. If a player has been dismissed, [dblookup('Dismissed Player', 'Substitution Rules') -> no substitute can be brought on] no substitute can be brought on in their place. Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad. In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences. A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute or substituted player. Non-players such as managers and support staff [dblookup('Non-Players', 'Card Rule') -> cannot be shown yellow or red card] cannot be shown the yellow or red card, but may be expelled from the technical area if they fail to conduct themselves in a responsible manner.

examples.annotated_text: War_on_Terror: The [dblookup('Obama Administration', 'Reengagement in Iraq Date') -> 10 August 2014] Obama administration began to reengage in Iraq with a series of airstrikes aimed at ISIS beginning on 10 August 2014. On 9 September 2014 President Obama said that he had the [dblookup('Barack Obama', 'Claimed Authority for Action Against ISIL') -> 2001 Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists] authority he needed to take action to destroy the militant group known as the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant, citing the 2001 Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists, and thus did not require additional approval from Congress. The following day on 10 September 2014 [dblookup('Barack Obama', 'Speech Date on ISIL Strategy') -> 10 September 2014] President Barack Obama made a televised speech about ISIL, which he stated "Our objective is clear: We will degrade, and ultimately destroy, ISIL through a comprehensive and sustained counter-terrorism strategy". examples.annotated_text: Gregorian_calendar: The Council of Trent approved a plan in 1563 for correcting the calendrical errors, requiring that the date of the vernal equinox be restored to that which it held at the time of the [dblookup('First Council of Nicaea', 'Date of Vernal Equinox Reference') -> 325] First Council of Nicaea in 325 and that an alteration to the calendar be designed to prevent future drift. This would allow for a more consistent and accurate scheduling of the feast of Easter. In 1577, a Compendium was sent to expert mathematicians outside the reform commission for comments. Some of these experts, including [dblookup('Giambattista Benedetti', 'Position on Easter Computation') -> True motions of the sun and moon] Giambattista Benedetti and [dblookup('Giuseppe Moleto', 'Position on Easter Computation') -> True motions of the sun and moon] Giuseppe Moleto, believed Easter should be computed from the true motions of the sun and moon, rather than using a tabular method, but these recommendations were not adopted. The reform adopted was a modification of a proposal made by the [dblookup('Aloysius Lilius', 'Contribution') -> Calendar Reform Proposal] Calabrian doctor Aloysius Lilius (or Lilio).
examples.text: Gregorian_calendar: The Council of Trent approved a plan in 1563 for correcting the calendrical errors, requiring that the date of the vernal equinox be restored to that which it held at the time of the First Council of Nicaea in 325 and that an alteration to the calendar be designed to prevent future drift. This would allow for a more consistent and accurate scheduling of the feast of Easter. In 1577, a Compendium was sent to expert mathematicians outside the reform commission for comments. Some of these experts, including Giambattista Benedetti and Giuseppe Moleto, believed Easter should be computed from the true motions of the sun and moon, rather than using a tabular method, but these recommendations were not adopted. The reform adopted was a modification of a proposal made by the Calabrian doctor Aloysius Lilius (or Lilio).

examples.annotated_text: Nutrition: It is possible with protein combinations of two incomplete protein sources (e.g., rice and beans) to make a complete protein source, and characteristic combinations are the basis of distinct cultural cooking traditions. The amino acids remaining after such conversion are discarded.

examples.annotated_text: Film_speed: For digital photo cameras ("digital still cameras"), an exposure index (EI) rating—commonly called ISO setting—is specified by the [dblookup('Exposure Index (EI)', 'Specification Source') -> Manufacturer] manufacturer such that the sRGB image files produced by the camera will have a lightness similar to what would be obtained with film of the same EI rating at the same exposure. The usual design is that the camera's parameters for interpreting the sensor data values into sRGB values are fixed, and a number of different EI choices are accommodated by varying the sensor's signal gain in the analog realm, prior to conversion to digital. Some camera designs provide at least some EI choices by [dblookup('Signal Gain Variation', 'Alternative Use Case') -> Digital Realm Adjustment] adjusting the sensor's signal gain in the digital realm. A few camera designs also provide EI adjustment through a choice of lightness parameters for the interpretation of sensor data values into sRGB; this variation allows different tradeoffs between the range of highlights that can be captured and the amount of noise introduced into the shadow areas of the photo.

examples.annotated_text: Separation_of_powers_under_the_United_States_Constitution: Strict separation of powers did not operate in The United Kingdom, the political structure of which served in most instances as a model for the government created by the U.S. Constitution. Under the UK Westminster system, based on parliamentary sovereignty and responsible government, Parliament (consisting of the Sovereign (King-in-Parliament), House of Lords and House of Commons) was the supreme lawmaking authority. The executive branch acted in the name of the King ("His Majesty's Government"), as did the judiciary. The King's Ministers were in most cases members of one of the two Houses of Parliament, and the Government needed [dblookup('United Kingdom Government', 'Requirement') -> majority support in House of Commons] to sustain the support of a majority in the House of Commons. One minister, the Lord Chancellor, was at the same time the sole judge in the Court of Chancery and the presiding officer in the House of Lords. Therefore, it may be seen that the three branches of British government often violated the strict principle of separation of powers, even though there were many occasions when the different branches of the government disagreed with each other. Some U.S. states did not observe [dblookup('Separation Of Powers', 'Observed By') -> U.S. states in 18th century] a strict separation of powers in the 18th century. In New Jersey, the [dblookup('Governor of New Jersey', 'Additional Roles') -> member of state's highest court, presiding officer of legislature] Governor also functioned as a member of the state's highest court and as the presiding officer of one house of the New Jersey Legislature. The [dblookup('President of Delaware', 'Additional Role') -> member of the Court of Appeals] President of Delaware was a member of the Court of Appeals; the presiding officers of the two houses of the state legislature also served in the executive department as Vice Presidents. In both Delaware and Pennsylvania, members of the executive council served at the same time as judges. On the other hand, many southern states explicitly required separation of powers., [dblookup('Virginia', 'Government Principle') -> separate and distinct branches], [dblookup('North Carolina', 'Government Principle') -> separate and distinct branches] and [dblookup('Georgia', 'Government Principle') -> separate and distinct branches] Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina and Georgia all kept the branches of government "separate and distinct."

examples.text: Samurai: Created by Takashi Okazaki, Afro Samurai was initially a doujinshi, or manga series, which was then made into an animated series by Studio Gonzo. In 2007 the animated series debuted on American cable television on the Spike TV channel (Denison, 2010). The series was produced for American viewers which “embodies the trend... comparing hip-hop artists to samurai warriors, an image some rappers claim for themselves (Solomon, 2009). Jackson, “Afro is the second-strongest fighter in a futuristic, yet, still feudal Japan and seeks revenge upon the gunman who killed his father” (King 2008).
