examples.annotated_text: Tuvalu: From [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'Economic Performance Years') -> 1996 to 2002] 1996 to 2002, Tuvalu was one of the best-performing Pacific Island economies and achieved an [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'Average GDP Growth Rate 1996-2002') -> 5.6% per annum] average real gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate of 5.6% per annum. Since 2002 economic growth has [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'GDP Growth Rate 2008') -> 1.5%] slowed, with GDP growth of 1.5% in 2008. Tuvalu was exposed to rapid rises in world prices of fuel and food in 2008, with the level of [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'Inflation Rate 2008') -> 13.4%] inflation peaking at 13.4%. The [dblookup('International Monetary Fund', 'Tuvalu Report Year') -> 2010] International Monetary Fund 2010 Report on Tuvalu estimates that Tuvalu experienced [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'GDP Growth 2010') -> zero] zero growth in its 2010 GDP, after the economy contracted by about [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'GDP Contraction 2009') -> 2%] 2% in 2009. On [dblookup('International Monetary Fund', 'Tuvalu Article IV Consultation Date') -> August 5, 2012] 5 August 2012, the Executive Board of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) concluded the Article IV consultation with Tuvalu, and assessed the economy of Tuvalu: "A slow recovery is underway in Tuvalu, but there are important risks. GDP grew in 2011 for the first time since the global financial crisis, led by the private retail sector and education spending. We expect growth to rise slowly". The IMF [dblookup('International Monetary Fund', 'Tuvalu Country Report Year') -> 2014] 2014 Country Report noted that real GDP growth in Tuvalu had been volatile averaging only [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'Average GDP Growth Rate Past Decade') -> 1 percent] 1 percent in the past decade. The 2014 Country Report describes economic growth prospects as generally positive as the result of large revenues from [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'Revenue Source 2014') -> fishing licenses] fishing licenses, together with substantial [dblookup('Tuvalu', 'Foreign Aid Contribution 2014') -> substantial] foreign aid.
examples.text: Tuvalu: From 1996 to 2002, Tuvalu was one of the best-performing Pacific Island economies and achieved an average real gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate of 5.6% per annum. The International Monetary Fund 2010 Report on Tuvalu estimates that Tuvalu experienced zero growth in its 2010 GDP, after the economy contracted by about 2% in 2009. On 5 August 2012, the Executive Board of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) concluded the Article IV consultation with Tuvalu, and assessed the economy of Tuvalu: "A slow recovery is underway in Tuvalu, but there are important risks. examples.annotated_text: Humanism: The humanists' close study of Latin literary texts soon enabled them to discern historical differences in the writing styles of different periods. By analogy with what they saw as decline of Latin, they applied the principle of [dblookup('Humanism', 'Key Principle') -> ad fontes] ad fontes, or back to the sources, across broad areas of learning, seeking out manuscripts of Patristic literature as well as pagan authors. In [dblookup('Lorenzo Valla', 'Significant Year') -> 1439] 1439, while employed in [dblookup('Lorenzo Valla', 'Place of Employment') -> Naples] Naples at the court of [dblookup('Alfonso V of Aragon', 'Title') -> King of Aragon] Alfonso V of Aragon (at the time engaged in a dispute with the Papal States) the humanist [dblookup('Lorenzo Valla', 'Occupation') -> Humanist, Philologist] Lorenzo Valla used stylistic textual analysis, now called [dblookup('Stylistic Textual Analysis', 'Modern Term') -> Philology] philology, to prove that [dblookup('Donation of Constantine', 'Proven Status') -> 8th-century forgery] the Donation of Constantine, which purported to confer temporal powers on the Pope of Rome, was an 8th-century forgery. For the next 70 years, however, neither Valla nor any of his contemporaries thought to apply the techniques of philology to other controversial manuscripts in this way. Instead, after the fall of the [dblookup('Byzantine Empire', 'Fall Year') -> 1453] Byzantine Empire to the Turks in 1453, which brought a flood of Greek Orthodox refugees to Italy, humanist scholars increasingly turned to the study of [dblookup('Humanism', 'Subjects of Study Post-1453') -> Neoplatonism, Hermeticism] Neoplatonism and Hermeticism, hoping to bridge the differences between the Greek and Roman Churches, and even between Christianity itself and the non-Christian world. The refugees brought with them Greek manuscripts, not only of Plato and Aristotle, but also of the Christian Gospels, previously unavailable in the Latin West.
examples.text: Humanism: The humanists' close study of Latin literary texts soon enabled them to discern historical differences in the writing styles of different periods. By analogy with what they saw as decline of Latin, they applied the principle of ad fontes, or back to the sources, across broad areas of learning, seeking out manuscripts of Patristic literature as well as pagan authors. In 1439, while employed in Naples at the court of Alfonso V of Aragon (at the time engaged in a dispute with the Papal States) the humanist Lorenzo Valla used stylistic textual analysis, now called philology, to prove that the Donation of Constantine, which purported to confer temporal powers on the Pope of Rome, was an 8th-century forgery. For the next 70 years, however, neither Valla nor any of his contemporaries thought to apply the techniques of philology to other controversial manuscripts in this way. Instead, after the fall of the Byzantine Empire to the Turks in 1453, which brought a flood of Greek Orthodox refugees to Italy, humanist scholars increasingly turned to the study of Neoplatonism and Hermeticism, hoping to bridge the differences between the Greek and Roman Churches, and even between Christianity itself and the non-Christian world. The refugees brought with them Greek manuscripts, not only of Plato and Aristotle, but also of the Christian Gospels, previously unavailable in the Latin West.

examples.annotated_text: Gene: Prior to Mendel's work, the dominant theory of heredity was [dblookup('Blending Inheritance', 'Heredity Concept') -> blending inheritance] one of blending inheritance, which suggested that each parent contributed fluids to the fertilisation process and that the traits of the parents blended and mixed to produce the offspring. [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Developed Theory') -> Pangenesis] Charles Darwin developed a theory of inheritance he termed pangenesis, which used the term [dblookup('Pangenesis', 'Key Concept') -> gemmule] gemmule to describe hypothetical particles that would mix during reproduction. Although [dblookup('Gregor Mendel', 'Publication Year') -> 1866] Mendel's work was largely unrecognized after its first publication in 1866, it was 'rediscovered' in [dblookup('Mendelian Inheritance', 'Rediscovery Year') -> 1900] 1900 by three European scientists, [dblookup('Hugo de Vries', 'Achievement') -> Rediscovery of Mendelian Inheritance], [dblookup('Carl Correns', 'Achievement') -> Rediscovery of Mendelian Inheritance], and [dblookup('Erich von Tschermak', 'Achievement') -> Rediscovery of Mendelian Inheritance] Hugo de Vries, Carl Correns, and Erich von Tschermak, who claimed to have reached similar conclusions in their own research.
examples.text: Gene: Prior to Mendel's work, the dominant theory of heredity was one of blending inheritance, which suggested that each parent contributed fluids to the fertilisation process and that the traits of the parents blended and mixed to produce the offspring. Charles Darwin developed a theory of inheritance he termed pangenesis, which used the term gemmule to describe hypothetical particles that would mix during reproduction. Although Mendel's work was largely unrecognized after its first publication in 1866, it was 'rediscovered' in 1900 by three European scientists, Hugo de Vries, Carl Correns, and Erich von Tschermak, who claimed to have reached similar conclusions in their own research.

examples.annotated_text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: An 1855 paper on the "introduction" of species, written by [dblookup('Alfred Russel Wallace', 'Published Work In') -> 1855] Alfred Russel Wallace, claimed that patterns in the geographical distribution of living and fossil species could be explained if every new species always came into existence near an already existing, closely related species. [dblookup('Charles Lyell', 'Recognized Implications Of') -> Alfred Russel Wallace's paper] Charles Lyell recognised the implications of Wallace's paper and its possible connection to [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Associated Work') -> Darwin's theory on species] Darwin's work, although Darwin did not, and in a letter written on [dblookup('Charles Lyell', 'Letter Date to Charles Darwin') -> May 1-2, 1856] 1–2 May 1856 Lyell urged Darwin to publish his theory to establish priority. Darwin was torn between the desire to set out a full and convincing account and the pressure to quickly produce a short paper. He met Lyell, and in correspondence with [dblookup('Joseph Dalton Hooker', 'Corresponded With') -> Charles Darwin] Joseph Dalton Hooker affirmed that he did not want to expose his ideas to review by an editor as would have been required to publish in an academic journal. He began a "sketch" account on [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Started Sketch') -> May 14, 1856] 14 May 1856, and by July had decided to produce a full technical treatise on species. His theory including the principle of divergence was complete by [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Theory Completion Date') -> September 5, 1857] 5 September 1857 when he sent [dblookup('Asa Gray', 'Recipient of Darwin\'s Abstract') -> Asa Gray] Asa Gray a brief but detailed abstract of his ideas.
examples.text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: An 1855 paper on the "introduction" of species, written by Alfred Russel Wallace, claimed that patterns in the geographical distribution of living and fossil species could be explained if every new species always came into existence near an already existing, closely related species. Charles Lyell recognised the implications of Wallace's paper and its possible connection to Darwin's work, although Darwin did not, and in a letter written on 1–2 May 1856 Lyell urged Darwin to publish his theory to establish priority. Darwin was torn between the desire to set out a full and convincing account and the pressure to quickly produce a short paper. He met Lyell, and in correspondence with Joseph Dalton Hooker affirmed that he did not want to expose his ideas to review by an editor as would have been required to publish in an academic journal. He began a "sketch" account on 14 May 1856, and by July had decided to produce a full technical treatise on species. His theory including the principle of divergence was complete by 5 September 1857 when he sent Asa Gray a brief but detailed abstract of his ideas.

examples.annotated_text: Wood: The single most revealing property of [dblookup('Wood', 'Quality Indicator') -> specific gravity] wood as an indicator of wood quality is specific gravity (Timell 1986), as both pulp yield and lumber strength are determined by it. Upon drying, [dblookup('Wood', 'Effect of Drying') -> shrinks and its density increases] wood shrinks and its density increases. In very high-risk scenarios, inhibitors of the platelet glycoprotein αIIbβ3a receptor such as eptifibatide or tirofiban may be used.

examples.text: Guam: Believed to be a stowaway on a U.S. military transport near the end of World War II, the brown tree snake (Boiga irregularis) was accidentally introduced to Guam, that previously had no native species of snake. examples.text: Liberia: Following a peak in growth in 1979, the Liberian economy began a steady decline due to economic mismanagement following the 1980 coup. Burke was not merely presenting a peace agreement to Parliament; rather, he stepped forward with four reasons against using force, carefully reasoned. He laid out his objections in an orderly manner, focusing on one before moving to the next. 

His first concern was that [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Concern About') -> Use of Force Temporary] the use of force would have to be temporary, and that the uprisings and objections to British governance in America would not be. Second, [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Concern About') -> Uncertainty of British Victory] Burke worried about the uncertainty surrounding whether Britain would win a conflict in America. "An armament", Burke said, "is not a victory". 

Third, Burke brought up the [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Concern About') -> Impairment from Scorched Earth Tactics] issue of impairment; it would do the British Government no good to engage in a scorched earth war and have the object they desired (America) become damaged or even useless. The American colonists could always retreat into the mountains, but the land they left behind would most likely be unusable, whether by accident or design. 

The fourth and final reason to avoid the use of force was [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Concern About') -> Lack of Experience] experience; the British had never attempted to rein in an unruly colony by force, and they did not know if it could be done, let alone accomplished thousands of miles away from home. Not only were all of these concerns reasonable, but some turned out to be [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Description Of Concerns') -> Prophetic] prophetic – the American colonists did not surrender, even when things looked extremely bleak, and the British were ultimately unsuccessful in their attempts to win a war fought on American soil.

Second, Burke worried about the uncertainty surrounding whether Britain would win a conflict in America. "An armament", Burke said, "is not a victory". Third, Burke brought up the issue of impairment; it would do the British Government no good to engage in a scorched earth war and have the object they desired (America) become damaged or even useless. The American colonists could always retreat into the mountains, but the land they left behind would most likely be unusable, whether by accident or design. The fourth and final reason to avoid the use of force was experience; the British had never attempted to rein in an unruly colony by force, and they did not know if it could be done, let alone accomplished thousands of miles away from home. Not only were all of these concerns reasonable, but some turned out to be prophetic – the American colonists did not surrender, even when things looked extremely bleak, and the British were ultimately unsuccessful in their attempts to win a war fought on American soil.

examples.annotated_text: Imperial_College_London: The Great Exhibition was organised by [dblookup('The Great Exhibition', 'Organiser 1') -> Prince Albert], [dblookup('The Great Exhibition', 'Organiser 2') -> Henry Cole], [dblookup('The Great Exhibition', 'Organiser 3') -> Francis Fuller] and other members of the [dblookup('The Great Exhibition', 'Organising Society') -> Royal Society for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce]. examples.text: Imperial_College_London: The Great Exhibition was organised by Prince Albert, Henry Cole, Francis Fuller and other members of the Royal Society for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce. examples.annotated_text: Thuringia: Since the Protestant Reformation, the most [dblookup('Thuringia', 'Prominent Christian Denomination Since Reformation') -> Lutheranism] prominent Christian denomination in Thuringia has been Lutheranism. During the [dblookup('Thuringia', 'Church Membership Policy During GDR Period') -> discouraged] GDR period, church membership was discouraged and has continued shrinking since the reunification in [dblookup('Thuringia', 'Reunification Year') -> 1990] 1990. Today over two-thirds of the population is [dblookup('Thuringia', 'Non-Religious Population Proportion in 2009') -> over 68.2%] non-religious. The [dblookup('Evangelical Church in Germany', 'Largest Protestant Population in Thuringia in 2009') -> 24.0%] Protestant Evangelical Church in Germany has had the largest number of members in the state, adhered to by 24.0% of the population in 2009. Members of the [dblookup('Catholic Church', 'Population in Thuringia in 2009') -> 7.8%] Catholic Church formed 7.8% of the population, while [dblookup('Thuringia', 'Non-Religious or Other Faiths Population in 2009') -> 68.2%] 68.2% of Thuringians were non-religious or adhere to other faiths. The highest [dblookup('Protestant Concentrations in Thuringia', 'Location') -> southern and western Thuringia] Protestant concentrations are in the small villages of southern and western Thuringia, whereas the bigger cities are [dblookup('Non-Religious Population in Thuringian Cities', 'Proportion in Gera') -> up to 88%] even more non-religious (up to 88% in Gera). [dblookup('Catholic Regions in Thuringia', 'Location') -> Eichsfeld, Rhön Mountains around Geisa] Catholic regions are the Eichsfeld in the northwest and parts of the Rhön Mountains around Geisa in the southwest. Protestant church membership is [dblookup('Protestant Church Membership Trend in Thuringia', 'Current Trend') -> shrinking rapidly] shrinking rapidly, whereas the [dblookup('Catholic Church Population Stability in Thuringia', 'Reason') -> Catholic migration from Poland, Southern Europe, West Germany] Catholic Church is somewhat more stable because of Catholic migration from Poland, Southern Europe and West Germany. Other religions play no significant role in Thuringia. There are only a [dblookup('Muslim Population in Thuringia', 'Size') -> few thousand] few thousand Muslims (largely migrants) and about [dblookup('Jewish Population in Thuringia', 'Size') -> 750] 750 Jews (mostly migrants from Russia) living in Thuringia. Furthermore, there are some [dblookup('Orthodox Communities in Thuringia', 'Origin') -> Eastern European migrants] Orthodox communities of Eastern European migrants and some traditional Protestant Free churches in Thuringia without any societal influence.
examples.text: Thuringia: Since the Protestant Reformation, the most prominent Christian denomination in Thuringia has been Lutheranism. During the GDR period, church membership was discouraged and has continued shrinking since the reunification in 1990. Today over two thirds of the population is non-religious. The Protestant Evangelical Church in Germany has had the largest number of members in the state, adhered to by 24.0% of the population in 2009. Members of the Catholic Church formed 7.8% of the population, while 68.2% of Thuringians were non-religious or adhere to other faiths. The highest Protestant concentrations are in the small villages of southern and western Thuringia, whereas the bigger cities are even more non-religious (up to 88% in Gera). Catholic regions are the Eichsfeld in the northwest and parts of the Rhön Mountains around Geisa in the southwest. Protestant church membership is shrinking rapidly, whereas the Catholic Church is somewhat more stable because of Catholic migration from Poland, Southern Europe and West Germany. Other religions play no significant role in Thuringia. There are only a few thousand Muslims (largely migrants) and about 750 Jews (mostly migrants from Russia) living in Thuringia. Furthermore, there are some Orthodox communities of Eastern European migrants and some traditional Protestant Free churches in Thuringia without any societal influence.

examples.annotated_text: Insect: Many adult insects use [dblookup('Insects', 'Number of Legs') -> six] six legs for walking and have adopted a [dblookup('Insects', 'Typical Gait') -> tripedal gait] tripedal gait. The tripedal gait allows for [dblookup('Tripedal Gait', 'Characteristics') -> rapid walking, stable stance] rapid walking while always having a stable stance and has been [dblookup('Tripedal Gait', 'Studied In') -> cockroaches] studied extensively in cockroaches. The legs are used in alternate triangles touching the ground. For the first step, the middle right leg and the front and rear left legs are in contact with the ground and move the insect forward, while the front and rear right leg and the middle left leg are lifted and moved forward to a new position. When they touch the ground to form a new stable triangle, the other legs can be lifted and brought forward in turn and so on. The purest form of the tripedal gait is seen in [dblookup('Insects', 'Gait at High Speeds') -> tripedal gait] insects moving at high speeds. However, this type of locomotion is not rigid and [dblookup('Insects', 'Gait Adaptability') -> adaptable] insects can adapt a variety of gaits. For example, when moving slowly, turning, or avoiding obstacles, four or more feet may be touching the ground. Insects can also adapt their gait to cope with the [dblookup('Insects', 'Coping with Limb Loss') -> adaptable gait] loss of one or more limbs.
examples.text: Insect: Many adult insects use six legs for walking and have adopted a tripedal gait. The tripedal gait allows for rapid walking while always having a stable stance and has been studied extensively in cockroaches. The legs are used in alternate triangles touching the ground. For the first step, the middle right leg and the front and rear left legs are in contact with the ground and move the insect forward, while the front and rear right leg and the middle left leg are lifted and moved forward to a new position. When they touch the ground to form a new stable triangle the other legs can be lifted and brought forward in turn and so on. The purest form of the tripedal gait is seen in insects moving at high speeds. However, this type of locomotion is not rigid and insects can adapt a variety of gaits. For example, when moving slowly, turning, or avoiding obstacles, four or more feet may be touching the ground. Insects can also adapt their gait to cope with the loss of one or more limbs.

examples.annotated_text: Rule_of_law: In countries such as [dblookup('China', 'Economic Transition Factor') -> Transition to a market economy] China and [dblookup('Vietnam', 'Economic Transition Factor') -> Transition to a market economy] Vietnam, the transition to a market economy has been a major factor in a move toward the rule of law, because a rule of law is important to [dblookup('Rule of Law', 'Importance For') -> Foreign investors, Economic development] foreign investors and to economic development. It remains unclear whether the rule of law in countries like China and Vietnam will be limited to commercial matters or will spill into other areas as well, and if so whether that spillover will enhance prospects for related values such as [dblookup('Prospects for Rule of Law Spillover', 'Related Values') -> Democracy, Human rights] democracy and human rights. The [dblookup('Rule of Law', 'Discussion in China') -> Legal scholars, Politicians] rule of law in China has been widely discussed and debated by both legal scholars and politicians in China.
examples.text: Rule_of_law: In countries such as China and Vietnam, the transition to a market economy has been a major factor in a move toward the rule of law, because a rule of law is important to foreign investors and to economic development. examples.annotated_text: Gamal_Abdel_Nasser: On 18 June 1953, the [dblookup('Republic of Egypt', 'Established As Republic') -> 1953] monarchy was abolished and the Republic of Egypt declared, with [dblookup('Republic of Egypt', 'First President') -> Naguib] Naguib as its first president. According to Aburish, after assuming power, Nasser and the Free Officers expected to become the "guardians of the people's interests" against the monarchy and the pasha class while leaving the day-to-day tasks of government to civilians. They asked former prime minister [dblookup('Ali Maher', 'Reappointed As Prime Minister Date') -> 1953] Ali Maher to accept reappointment to his previous position, and to form an all-civilian cabinet. The Free Officers then governed as the [dblookup('Revolutionary Command Council', 'First Chairman') -> Naguib] Revolutionary Command Council (RCC) with Naguib as chairman and [dblookup('Revolutionary Command Council', 'Vice-Chairman Nasser Term Start') -> 1953] Nasser as vice-chairman. Relations between the RCC and Maher grew tense, however, as the latter viewed many of Nasser's schemes—agrarian reform, abolition of the monarchy, reorganization of political parties—as too radical, culminating in Maher's resignation on [dblookup('Ali Maher', 'Resignation Date') -> September 7, 1953] 7 September. Naguib assumed the additional role of prime minister, and Nasser that of deputy prime minister. In September, the [dblookup('Egypt', 'Agrarian Reform Law Implemented By') -> Revolutionary Command Council] Agrarian Reform Law was put into effect. In Nasser's eyes, this law [dblookup('Agrarian Reform Law (Egypt)', 'Significance') -> RCC identity, coup to revolution] gave the RCC its own identity and transformed the coup into a revolution.
examples.text: Gamal_Abdel_Nasser: On 18 June 1953, the monarchy was abolished and the Republic of Egypt declared, with Naguib as its first president. According to Aburish, after assuming power, Nasser and the Free Officers expected to become the "guardians of the people's interests" against the monarchy and the pasha class while leaving the day-to-day tasks of government to civilians. They asked former prime minister Ali Maher to accept reappointment to his previous position, and to form an all-civilian cabinet. The Free Officers then governed as the Revolutionary Command Council (RCC) with Naguib as chairman and Nasser as vice-chairman. Relations between the RCC and Maher grew tense, however, as the latter viewed many of Nasser's schemes—agrarian reform, abolition of the monarchy, reorganization of political parties—as too radical, culminating in Maher's resignation on 7 September. Naguib assumed the additional role of prime minister, and Nasser that of deputy prime minister. In September, the Agrarian Reform Law was put into effect. In Nasser's eyes, this law gave the RCC its own identity and transformed the coup into a revolution.

Some electric railways have their [dblookup('Electric Railways', 'Power Source Type') -> dedicated generating stations] own dedicated generating stations and transmission lines but most [dblookup('Electric Railways', 'Common Power Purchase Source') -> electric utility] purchase power from an electric utility. The railway usually provides its own [dblookup('Electric Railways', 'Infrastructure Components') -> distribution lines, switches, transformers] distribution lines, switches and transformers.
examples.text: Railway_electrification_system: Electric railways use electric locomotives to haul passengers or freight in separate cars or electric multiple units, passenger cars with their own motors. examples.text: Hokkien: Hokkien, especially Taiwanese, is sometimes written in the Latin script using one of several alphabets. examples.annotated_text: Royal_Dutch_Shell: Downstream operations, which now also include the [dblookup('Royal_Dutch_Shell', 'Chemicals Business Inclusion') -> downstream operations] chemicals business, generates a third of Shell's profits worldwide and is known for its [dblookup('Royal_Dutch_Shell', 'Petrol Stations Number') -> more than 40,000] global network of more than 40,000 petrol stations and its [dblookup('Royal_Dutch_Shell', 'Oil Refineries Count') -> 47] 47 oil refineries. examples.text: Royal_Dutch_Shell: Downstream operations, which now also includes the chemicals business, generates a third of Shell's profits worldwide and is known for its global network of more than 40,000 petrol stations and its 47 oil refineries. In the 1990s, this paradigm began to change, and the independence of operating companies around the world was gradually reduced. Today, virtually all of Shell's operations in various businesses are much more directly managed from London and The Hague. examples.annotated_text: Orthodox_Judaism: Politically, Orthodox Jews, given their variety of movements and affiliations, tend not to conform easily to the standard left-right political spectrum, with one of the key differences between the movements stemming from the groups' attitudes to Zionism. Generally speaking, of the three key strands of Orthodox Judaism, Haredi Orthodox and Hasidic Orthodox Jews are at best ambivalent towards the [dblookup('Haredi Orthodox Judaism', 'View On') -> Zionism] ideology of Zionism and the creation of the State of Israel, and there are many groups and organisations who are outspokenly anti-Zionistic, seeing the ideology of Zionism as diametrically opposed to the [dblookup('Orthodox Judaism', 'View On') -> Teaching of the Torah] teaching of the Torah, and the [dblookup('State of Israel', 'Perceived Characteristics') -> Militarism, Nationalism] Zionist administration of the State of Israel, with its emphasis on militarism and nationalism, as destructive of the Judaic way of life.
examples.text: Orthodox_Judaism: Politically, Orthodox Jews, given their variety of movements and affiliations, tend not to conform easily to the standard left-right political spectrum, with one of the key differences between the movements stemming from the groups' attitudes to Zionism. Generally speaking, of the three key strands of Orthodox Judaism, Haredi Orthodox and Hasidic Orthodox Jews are at best ambivalent towards the ideology of Zionism and the creation of the State of Israel, and there are many groups and organisations who are outspokenly anti-Zionistic, seeing the ideology of Zionism as diametrically opposed to the teaching of the Torah, and the Zionist administration of the State of Israel, with its emphasis on militarism and nationalism, as destructive of the Judaic way of life.

examples.annotated_text: <pitch_(music): Pitch is an [dblookup('Pitch_(music)', 'Type') -> Auditory Sensation] auditory sensation in which a listener assigns musical tones to relative positions on a musical scale based primarily on their [dblookup('Pitch_(music)', 'Basis') -> Perception of Frequency of Vibration] perception of the frequency of vibration. Pitch is closely related to [dblookup('Pitch_(musical)', 'Relation To') -> Frequency] frequency, but the two are not equivalent. Frequency is an [dblookup('Frequency', 'Attribute Type') -> Objective, Scientific Attribute] objective, scientific attribute that can be measured. Pitch is each person's [dblookup('Pitch_(music)', 'Nature') -> Subjective Perception of Sound] subjective perception of a sound, which cannot be directly measured.
examples.text: Pitch_(music): Pitch is an auditory sensation in which a listener assigns musical tones to relative positions on a musical scale based primarily on their perception of the frequency of vibration. Pitch is closely related to frequency, but the two are not equivalent. Frequency is an objective, scientific attribute that can be measured. Pitch is each person's subjective perception of a sound, which cannot be directly measured. However, this does not necessarily mean that most people won't agree on which notes are higher and lower.

examples.annotated_text: Mandolin: The transition from the mandolino to the mandolin began around [dblookup('Mandolin', 'Transition Began') -> 1744] 1744 with the designing of the metal-string mandolin by the [dblookup('Metal-string Mandolin', 'Designed By') -> Vinaccia family] Vinaccia family, 3 brass strings and one of gut, using friction tuning pegs on a fingerboard that sat "flush" with the sound table. The mandolin grew in popularity over the next [dblookup('Mandolin', 'Period of Growing Popularity') -> 60 years] 60 years, in the streets where it was used by young men courting and by street musicians, and in the concert hall. After the Napoleonic Wars of [dblookup('Napoleonic Wars', 'End Year') -> 1815] 1815, however, its popularity began to fall. The [dblookup('19th Century', 'Prominent Mandolin Players') -> Bartolomeo Bortolazzi, Pietro Vimercati] 19th century produced some prominent players, including Bartolomeo Bortolazzi of Venice and Pietro Vimercati. However, professional virtuosity was in decline, and the mandolin music changed as the mandolin became a folk instrument; "the large repertoire of notated instrumental music for the mandolino and the mandoline was completely forgotten". The export market for mandolins from Italy dried up around [dblookup('Mandolin Export Market', 'Decline Year') -> 1815] 1815, and when Carmine de Laurentiis wrote a mandolin method in [dblookup('Carmine de Laurentiis', 'Mandolin Method Published') -> 1874] 1874, the Music World magazine wrote that the mandolin was "out of date." Salvador Léonardi mentioned this decline in his [dblookup('Salvador Léonardi', 'Publication Year') -> 1921] 1921 book, Méthode pour Banjoline ou Mandoline-Banjo, saying that the mandolin had been declining in popularity from previous times.
examples.text: Mandolin: The transition from the mandolino to the mandolin began around 1744 with the designing of the metal-string mandolin by the Vinaccia family, 3 brass strings and one of gut, using friction tuning pegs on a fingerboard that sat "flush" with the sound table. The mandolin grew in popularity over the next 60 years, in the streets where it was used by young men courting and by street musicians, and in the concert hall. After the Napoleonic Wars of 1815, however, its popularity began to fall. The 19th century produced some prominent players, including Bartolomeo Bortolazzi of Venice and Pietro Vimercati. However, professional virtuosity was in decline, and the mandolin music changed as the mandolin became a folk instrument; "the large repertoire of notated instrumental music for the mandolino and the mandoline was completely forgotten". The export market for mandolins from Italy dried up around 1815, and when Carmine de Laurentiis wrote a mandolin method in 1874, the Music World magazine wrote that the mandolin was "out of date." Salvador Léonardi mentioned this decline in his 1921 book, Méthode pour Banjoline ou Mandoline-Banjo, saying that the mandolin had been declining in popularity from previous times.

examples.annotated_text: Modern_history: The Second Sino-Japanese War had seen tensions rise between [dblookup('Imperial Japan', 'Tension With') -> United States] Imperial Japan and the United States; events such as the [dblookup('Panay incident', 'Impact On') -> American public opinion against Japan] Panay incident and the [dblookup('Nanking Massacre', 'Impact On') -> American public opinion against Japan] Nanking Massacre turned American public opinion against Japan. With the [dblookup('French Indochina', 'Occupation By') -> Imperial Japan] occupation of French Indochina in the years [dblookup('French Indochina Occupation', 'Years') -> 1940–41] 1940–41, and with the continuing war in China, the [dblookup('United States', 'Embargo On') -> Imperial Japan] United States placed embargoes on Japan of strategic materials such as scrap metal and oil, which were vitally needed for the war effort. The Japanese were faced with the option of either [dblookup('Imperial Japan', 'Decision Options') -> withdrawing from China or seizing new sources of raw materials] withdrawing from China and losing face or seizing and securing new sources of raw materials in the resource-rich, European-controlled colonies of South East Asia—specifically [dblookup('British Malaya', 'Target Of') -> Imperial Japan] British Malaya and the [dblookup('Dutch East Indies', 'Target Of') -> Imperial Japan] Dutch East Indies (modern-day Indonesia). In [dblookup('Imperial Japan', 'Tripartite Pact Year') -> 1940] 1940, Imperial Japan signed the [dblookup('Tripartite Pact', 'Members') -> Nazi Germany, Fascist Italy, Imperial Japan] Tripartite Pact with Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy.
examples.text: Modern_history: The Second Sino-Japanese War had seen tensions rise between Imperial Japan and the United States; events such as the Panay incident and the Nanking Massacre turned American public opinion against Japan. With the occupation of French Indochina in the years of 1940–41, and with the continuing war in China, the United States placed embargoes on Japan of strategic materials such as scrap metal and oil, which were vitally needed for the war effort. The Japanese were faced with the option of either withdrawing from China and losing face or seizing and securing new sources of raw materials in the resource-rich, European-controlled colonies of South East Asia—specifically British Malaya and the Dutch East Indies (modern-day Indonesia). In 1940, Imperial Japan signed the Tripartite Pact with Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy.

examples.annotated_text: Textual_criticism: Since the canons of criticism are highly susceptible to interpretation, and at times even contradict each other, they may be employed to justify a result that fits the textual critic's aesthetic or theological agenda. Starting in the [dblookup('Textual Criticism', '19th Century Developments') -> more rigorous methods] 19th century, scholars sought more rigorous methods to guide editorial judgment. Best-text editing (a complete rejection of eclecticism) became one extreme. [dblookup('Stemmatics', 'Characteristics') -> eclectic] Stemmatics and [dblookup('Copy-text Editing', 'Characteristics') -> eclectic] copy-text editing – while both eclectic, in that they permit the editor to select readings from multiple sources – sought to reduce subjectivity by establishing one or a few witnesses presumably as being favored by "objective" criteria. The citing of sources used, and alternate readings, and the use of original text and images helps readers and other critics determine to an extent the depth of research of the critic, and to independently verify their work.

examples.annotated_text: Cotton: During the [dblookup('American Civil War', 'Effect On') -> American cotton exports] American Civil War, American cotton exports slumped due to a Union blockade on Southern ports, and also because of a strategic decision by the [dblookup('Confederate Government', 'Tactic In') -> cutting exports] Confederate government to cut exports, hoping to force Britain to recognize the Confederacy or enter the war. This prompted the main purchasers of cotton, [dblookup('Cotton Purchasers', 'During American Civil War') -> Britain, France] Britain and France, to turn to [dblookup('Egyptian Cotton', 'Alternative Source For') -> Britain, France] Egyptian cotton. British and French traders invested heavily in [dblookup('Egypt', 'Foreign Investment In') -> cotton plantations] cotton plantations. The Egyptian government of [dblookup('Isma'il Pasha', 'Position') -> Viceroy] Viceroy Isma'il took out substantial loans from [dblookup('Egyptian Government', 'Lenders') -> European bankers and stock exchanges] European bankers and stock exchanges. After the American Civil War ended in [dblookup('American Civil War', 'End Year') -> 1865] 1865, British and French traders abandoned [dblookup('Egyptian Cotton', 'Post-Civil War Status') -> abandoned by British and French traders] Egyptian cotton and returned to cheap American exports,[citation needed] sending Egypt into a [dblookup('Egypt', 'Economic Status Post-Civil War') -> deficit spiral] deficit spiral that led to the country declaring [dblookup('Egypt', 'Bankruptcy Declaration Year') -> 1876] bankruptcy in 1876, a key factor behind Egypt's [dblookup('Egypt', 'British Occupation Year') -> 1882] occupation by the British Empire in 1882.
examples.text: Cotton: During the American Civil War, American cotton exports slumped due to a Union blockade on Southern ports, and also because of a strategic decision by the Confederate government to cut exports, hoping to force Britain to recognize the Confederacy or enter the war. This prompted the main purchasers of cotton, Britain and France, to turn to Egyptian cotton. British and French traders invested heavily in cotton plantations. The Egyptian government of Viceroy Isma'il took out substantial loans from European bankers and stock exchanges. After the American Civil War ended in 1865, British and French traders abandoned Egyptian cotton and returned to cheap American exports,[citation needed] sending Egypt into a deficit spiral that led to the country declaring bankruptcy in 1876, a key factor behind Egypt's occupation by the British Empire in 1882.

examples.annotated_text: Printed_circuit_board: At the [dblookup('Printed Circuit Board', 'Significance of Tg') -> glass transition temperature] glass transition temperature, the resin in the composite softens and significantly increases thermal expansion; exceeding [dblookup('Printed Circuit Board', 'Effects of Exceeding Tg') -> mechanical overload] Tg then exerts mechanical overload on the board components - e.g. the joints and the vias. Below Tg the thermal expansion of the resin roughly matches copper and glass, above it gets significantly higher. As the reinforcement and copper confine the board along the plane, virtually all volume expansion projects to the thickness and stresses the plated-through holes. Repeated soldering or other exposition to higher temperatures can cause [dblookup('Printed Circuit Board', 'Consequence of High Temperature Exposure') -> failure of the plating] failure of the plating, especially with thicker boards; [dblookup('Printed Circuit Board', 'Requirement for Thick Boards') -> high Tg matrix] thick boards therefore require high Tg matrix.

examples.annotated_text: Queen Victoria: Victoria later described her [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Childhood Description') -> rather melancholy] childhood as "rather melancholy". Her [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Mother') -> Duchess of Kent] mother was extremely protective, and Victoria was raised largely isolated from other children under the so-called [dblookup('Kensington System', 'Developed By') -> Duchess of Kent, Sir John Conroy] "Kensington System", an elaborate set of rules and protocols devised by the Duchess and her ambitious and domineering comptroller, [dblookup('Kensington System', 'Key Figure') -> Sir John Conroy] Sir John Conroy, who was rumoured to be the Duchess's lover. The system prevented the princess from meeting people whom her mother and Conroy deemed undesirable (including most of her father's family), and was designed to render her weak and dependent upon them. The Duchess avoided the court because she was scandalised by the presence of King William's bastard children, and perhaps prompted the emergence of [dblookup('Victorian Morality', 'Emergence Promoted By') -> Duchess of Kent] Victorian morality by insisting that her daughter avoid any appearance of sexual impropriety. Victoria shared a bedroom with [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Shared Bedroom With') -> Duchess of Kent] her mother every night, studied with private tutors to a regular timetable, and spent her play-hours with [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Childhood Companions') -> dolls, King Charles spaniel Dash] her dolls and her King Charles spaniel, Dash. Her lessons included [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Languages Studied') -> French, German, Italian, Latin] French, German, Italian, and Latin, but she spoke only [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Home Language') -> English] English at home.
examples.text: Queen_Victoria: Victoria later described her childhood as "rather melancholy". Her mother was extremely protective, and Victoria was raised largely isolated from other children under the so-called "Kensington System", an elaborate set of rules and protocols devised by the Duchess and her ambitious and domineering comptroller, Sir John Conroy, who was rumoured to be the Duchess's lover. The system prevented the princess from meeting people whom her mother and Conroy deemed undesirable (including most of her father's family), and was designed to render her weak and dependent upon them. The Duchess avoided the court because she was scandalised by the presence of King William's bastard children, and perhaps prompted the emergence of Victorian morality by insisting that her daughter avoid any appearance of sexual impropriety. Victoria shared a bedroom with her mother every night, studied with private tutors to a regular timetable, and spent her play-hours with her dolls and her King Charles spaniel, Dash. Her lessons included French, German, Italian, and Latin, but she spoke only English at home.

examples.annotated_text: Himachal_Pradesh: Himachal Pradesh is governed through a [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh', 'Government System') -> parliamentary system of representative democracy] parliamentary system of representative democracy, a feature the state shares with other Indian states. [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh', 'Voting System') -> Universal suffrage] Universal suffrage is granted to residents. The legislature consists of elected members and special office bearers such as the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Legislature', 'Special Office Bearers') -> Speaker, Deputy Speaker] Speaker and the Deputy Speaker who are elected by the members. Assembly meetings are presided over by the Speaker or the Deputy Speaker in the Speaker's absence. The judiciary is composed of the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh', 'Judiciary Head Court') -> Himachal Pradesh High Court] Himachal Pradesh High Court and a system of lower courts. Executive authority is vested in the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh', 'Executive Authority') -> Council of Ministers headed by the Chief Minister] Council of Ministers headed by the Chief Minister, although the titular head of government is the [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh', 'Titular Head of Government') -> Governor] Governor. The [dblookup('Governor of Himachal Pradesh', 'Appointed By') -> President of India] Governor is the head of state appointed by the President of India. The leader of the party or coalition with a majority in the Legislative Assembly is appointed as the Chief Minister by the Governor, and the Council of Ministers are appointed by the Governor on the advice of the Chief Minister. The [dblookup('Council of Ministers of Himachal Pradesh', 'Reports To') -> Legislative Assembly] Council of Ministers reports to the Legislative Assembly. The Assembly is [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Legislative Assembly', 'Chamber Type') -> unicameral] unicameral with [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Legislative Assembly', 'Number of Members') -> 68] 68 Members of the Legislative Assembly (MLA). Terms of office run for [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh Legislative Assembly', 'Term Length') -> 5 years] 5 years, unless the Assembly is dissolved prior to the completion of the term. Auxiliary authorities known as [dblookup('Himachal Pradesh', 'Local Government System') -> panchayats] panchayats, for which local body elections are regularly held, govern local affairs.
examples.text: Himachal_Pradesh: Himachal Pradesh is governed through a parliamentary system of representative democracy, a feature the state shares with other Indian states. Universal suffrage is granted to residents. The legislature consists of elected members and special office bearers such as the Speaker and the Deputy Speaker who are elected by the members. Assembly meetings are presided over by the Speaker or the Deputy Speaker in the Speaker's absence. The judiciary is composed of the Himachal Pradesh High Court and a system of lower courts. Executive authority is vested in the Council of Ministers headed by the Chief Minister, although the titular head of government is the Governor. The Governor is the head of state appointed by the President of India. The leader of the party or coalition with a majority in the Legislative Assembly is appointed as the Chief Minister by the Governor, and the Council of Ministers are appointed by the Governor on the advice of the Chief Minister. The Council of Ministers reports to the Legislative Assembly. The Assembly is unicameral with 68 Members of the Legislative Assembly (MLA). Terms of office run for 5 years, unless the Assembly is dissolved prior to the completion of the term. examples.annotated_text: Empiricism: Around the beginning of the 20th century, [dblookup('William James', 'Coined Term') -> radical empiricism] William James (1842–1910) coined the term "radical empiricism" to describe an offshoot of his form of pragmatism, which he argued could be dealt with separately from his pragmatism – though in fact the two concepts are intertwined in James's published lectures. James maintained that the empirically observed "directly apprehended universe needs ... no extraneous trans-empirical connective support", by which he meant to rule out the perception that there can be any value added by seeking supernatural explanations for natural phenomena. James's "radical empiricism" is thus not radical in the context of the term "empiricism", but is instead [dblookup('Radical Empiricism', 'Consistency With') -> modern use of the term "empirical"] fairly consistent with the modern use of the term "empirical". (His method of argument in arriving at this view, however, still readily encounters debate within philosophy even today.)

At the time in which Vasari was writing, Italy had experienced a century of building in the Classical architectural vocabulary revived in the Renaissance and seen as evidence of a new Golden Age of learning and refinement.

examples.annotated_text: Sanskrit: Sanskrit has greatly [dblookup('Sanskrit', 'Influence On') -> languages of India] influenced the languages of India that grew from its vocabulary and grammatical base; for instance, Hindi is a "Sanskritised register" of the Khariboli dialect. Words originating in Sanskrit are estimated at roughly [dblookup('Sanskrit', 'Vocabulary Contribution To Modern Indo-Aryan Languages') -> fifty percent] fifty percent of the vocabulary of modern Indo-Aryan languages, as well as the literary forms of [dblookup('Malayalam', 'Vocabulary Contribution From Sanskrit') -> fifty percent] Malayalam and [dblookup('Kannada', 'Vocabulary Contribution From Sanskrit') -> fifty percent] Kannada. examples.annotated_text: Lighting: [dblookup('Compact Fluorescent Lamps', 'Alternative Name') -> CFLs] Compact fluorescent lamps (aka 'CFLs') use less power to supply the same amount of light as an [dblookup('Compact Fluorescent Lamps', 'Power Efficiency Compared To Incandescent') -> one fifth to one quarter] incandescent lamp, however they contain [dblookup('Compact Fluorescent Lamps', 'Contains Hazardous Material') -> mercury] mercury which is a dispose hazard. Due to the ability to reduce electric consumption, many organizations have undertaken measures to encourage the adoption of CFLs. Some electric utilities and local governments [dblookup('Electric Utilities and Local Governments', 'Encouragement Measures for CFLs') -> subsidized or provided free] have subsidized CFLs or provided them free to customers as a means of reducing electric demand. One of the simplest and quickest ways for a household or business to become more energy efficient is to adopt CFLs as the main lamp source, as suggested by the [dblookup('Alliance for Climate Protection', 'Recommendation on Energy Efficiency') -> adoption of CFLs] Alliance for Climate Protection. Unlike incandescent lamps CFL's need a little time to 'warm up' and reach full brightness. Care should be taken when selecting CFL's because not all of them are suitable for dimming.

examples.annotated_text: Separation_of_powers_under_the_United_States_Constitution: Richard Nixon used national security as a basis for his [dblookup('Richard Nixon', 'Expansions of Power') -> national security] expansion of power. He asserted, for example, that "the inherent power of the President to safeguard the security of the nation" authorized him to [dblookup('Richard Nixon', 'Action Without Warrant') -> order a wiretap without a judge's warrant] order a wiretap without a judge's warrant. Nixon also asserted that [dblookup('Richard Nixon', 'Claimed Protection') -> executive privilege] "executive privilege" shielded him from all legislative oversight; furthermore, he impounded federal funds. In the specific cases aforementioned, however, the [dblookup('United States Supreme Court', 'Ruling Against') -> Nixon] Supreme Court ruled against Nixon. This was also because of an ongoing criminal investigation into the [dblookup('Richard Nixon', 'Related Scandal') -> Watergate tapes] Watergate tapes, even though they acknowledged the general need for executive privilege. Since then, [dblookup('Richard Nixon', 'Influence On Successors') -> assertion of executive privilege and national security interests] Nixon's successors have sometimes asserted that they may act in the interests of national security or that executive privilege shields them from Congressional oversight. Though such claims have in general been more limited than Nixon's, one may still conclude that the [dblookup('United States Presidency', 'Power Augmentation Since') -> eighteenth and nineteenth centuries] presidency's power has been greatly augmented since the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.
examples.text: Separation_of_powers_under_the_United_States_Constitution: Richard Nixon used national security as a basis for his expansion of power. He asserted, for example, that "the inherent power of the President to safeguard the security of the nation" authorized him to order a wiretap without a judge's warrant. Nixon also asserted that "executive privilege" shielded him from all legislative oversight; furthermore, he impounded federal funds (that is to say, he refused to spend money that Congress had appropriated for government programs). In the specific cases aforementioned, however, the Supreme Court ruled against Nixon. This was also because of an ongoing criminal investigation into the Watergate tapes, even though they acknowledged the general need for executive privilege. Since then, Nixon's successors have sometimes asserted that they may act in the interests of national security or that executive privilege shields them from Congressional oversight. Though such claims have in general been more limited than Nixon's, one may still conclude that the presidency's power has been greatly augmented since the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.

examples.annotated_text: Electric_motor: A [dblookup('Servomotor', 'Primary Purpose') -> position-control or speed-control feedback control system] servomotor is a motor, very often sold as a complete module, which is used within a position-control or speed-control feedback control system mainly control valves, such as motor-operated control valves. Servomotors are used in applications such as [dblookup('Servomotor', 'Applications') -> machine tools, pen plotters, process systems] machine tools, pen plotters, and other process systems. Motors intended for use in a servomechanism must have well-documented characteristics for [dblookup('Servomotor', 'Required Characteristics') -> speed, torque, power] speed, torque, and power. The speed vs. torque curve is quite important and is high ratio for a servomotor. Dynamic response characteristics such as [dblookup('Servomotor', 'Dynamic Response Characteristics') -> winding inductance, rotor inertia] winding inductance and rotor inertia are also important; these factors limit the overall performance of the servomechanism loop. Large, powerful, but slow-responding servo loops may use conventional AC or DC motors and drive systems with position or speed feedback on the motor. As dynamic response requirements increase, more specialized motor designs such as coreless motors are used. AC motors' superior power density and acceleration characteristics compared to that of DC motors tends to favor PM synchronous, BLDC, induction, and SRM drive applications.

examples.annotated_text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by Richard M. Bowen III on events during his [dblookup('Richard M. Bowen III', 'Position') -> Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup] tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup (where he was [dblookup('Richard M. Bowen III', 'Responsibility') -> over 220 professional underwriters] responsible for over 220 professional underwriters) suggests that by the final years of the [dblookup('U.S. Housing Bubble', 'Collapse Period') -> 2006–2007] U.S. housing bubble (2006–2007), the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic. His testimony stated that by [dblookup('Citigroup', 'Defective Mortgages Percentage 2006') -> 60%] 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citi from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents) – this, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citi's standards. Moreover, during [dblookup('Citigroup', 'Defective Mortgages Percentage 2007') -> over 80%] 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased... to over 80% of production".
examples.text: Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308: Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by Richard M. Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup (where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters) suggests that by the final years of the U.S. housing bubble (2006–2007), the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic. Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased... to over 80% of production".

examples.annotated_text: Heian_period: Despite [dblookup('Fujiwara', 'Influence On Imperial Authority') -> usurpation] their usurpation of imperial authority, the Fujiwara presided over a period of [dblookup('Fujiwara', 'Cultural Contribution') -> cultural and artistic flowering] cultural and artistic flowering at the imperial court and among the aristocracy. There was great interest in graceful poetry and vernacular literature. Two types of phonetic Japanese script: [dblookup('Katakana', 'Characteristics') -> simplified script using parts of Chinese characters] katakana, a simplified script that was developed by using parts of Chinese characters, was abbreviated to [dblookup('Hiragana', 'Writing Style') -> cursive syllabary] hiragana, a cursive syllabary with a distinct writing method that was uniquely Japanese. [dblookup('Hiragana', 'Cultural Influence') -> Rise in vernacular literature] Hiragana gave written expression to the spoken word and, with it, to the rise in Japan's famous vernacular literature, much of it written by court women who had not been trained in Chinese as had their male counterparts. Three late tenth century and early eleventh century women presented their views of life and romance at the Heian court in [dblookup('Kagerō Nikki', 'Author') -> "the mother of Fujiwara Michitsuna"] Kagerō Nikki by "the mother of Fujiwara Michitsuna", [dblookup('The Pillow Book', 'Author') -> Sei Shōnagon] The Pillow Book by Sei Shōnagon and [dblookup('The Tale of Genji', 'Author') -> Murasaki Shikibu] The Tale of Genji by Murasaki Shikibu. [dblookup('Fujiwara', 'Influence On Art') -> Indigenous art flourishing] Indigenous art also flourished under the Fujiwara after centuries of imitating Chinese forms. [dblookup('Yamato-e', 'Characteristics') -> Vividly colored Japanese style paintings] Vividly colored yamato-e, Japanese style paintings of court life and stories about temples and shrines became common in the mid- and late Heian periods, setting patterns for [dblookup('Japanese Art', 'Heian Period Influence') -> Persistent art patterns] Japanese art to this day.
examples.text: Heian_period: Despite their usurpation of imperial authority, the Fujiwara presided over a period of cultural and artistic flowering at the imperial court and among the aristocracy. There was great interest in graceful poetry and vernacular literature. Two types of phonetic Japanese script: katakana, a simplified script that was developed by using parts of Chinese characters, was abbreviated to hiragana, a cursive syllabary with a distinct writing method that was uniquely Japanese. Hiragana gave written expression to the spoken word and, with it, to the rise in Japan's famous vernacular literature, much of it written by court women who had not been trained in Chinese as had their male counterparts. Three late tenth century and early eleventh century women presented their views of life and romance at the Heian court in Kagerō Nikki by "the mother of Fujiwara Michitsuna", The Pillow Book by Sei Shōnagon and The Tale of Genji by Murasaki Shikibu. Indigenous art also flourished under the Fujiwara after centuries of imitating Chinese forms. Vividly colored yamato-e, Japanese style paintings of court life and stories about temples and shrines became common in the mid- and late Heian periods, setting patterns for Japanese art to this day.

Most Han Chinese migrants were not evicted as they went over the Great Wall and Willow Palisade. During the eighteenth century, [dblookup('Han Chinese Farmers', 'Land Cultivated in Manchuria by 18th Century') -> 500,000 hectares privately, 203,583 hectares of estates and Banner lands] Han Chinese farmed 500,000 hectares of privately owned land in Manchuria and 203,583 hectares of lands which were part of courtier stations, noble estates, and Banner lands. In garrisons and towns in Manchuria, [dblookup('Han Chinese', 'Percentage of Population in Manchurian Towns During Qing') -> 80%] Han Chinese made up 80% of the population.

examples.annotated_text: Xbox 360: The [dblookup('Xbox 360', 'Advantage Over Competitors') -> High profile game releases] Xbox 360's advantage over its competitors was due to the release of high profile titles from both first party and third party developers. By [dblookup('Xbox 360', 'Software Attach Rate in March 2008') -> 7.5 games per console in the US, 7.0 games in Europe] March 2008, the Xbox 360 had reached a software attach rate of 7.5 games per console in the US; the rate was 7.0 in Europe, while its competitors were 3.8 (PS3) and 3.5 (Wii), according to Microsoft. As well as enjoying [dblookup('Xbox 360', 'Exclusive Games') -> Halo franchise, Gears of War] exclusives such as additions to the Halo franchise and Gears of War, the Xbox 360 has managed to gain a [dblookup('Xbox 360', 'Simultaneous Game Releases With PS3') -> Devil May Cry, Ace Combat, Virtua Fighter, Grand Theft Auto IV, Final Fantasy XIII, Tekken 6, Metal Gear Solid: Rising, L.A. Noire] simultaneous release of titles that were initially planned to be PS3 exclusives, including Devil May Cry, Ace Combat, Virtua Fighter, Grand Theft Auto IV, Final Fantasy XIII, Tekken 6, Metal Gear Solid: Rising, and L.A. Noire. In addition, [dblookup('Xbox 360', '2006-2007 Game Version Superiority') -> Considered superior to PS3 versions] Xbox 360 versions of cross-platform games were generally considered superior to their PS3 counterparts in 2006 and 2007, due in part to the difficulties of programming for the PS3.
examples.text: Xbox_360: The Xbox 360's advantage over its competitors was due to the release of high profile titles from both first party and third party developers. The 2007 Game Critics Awards honored the platform with 38 nominations and 12 wins – more than any other platform. By March 2008, the Xbox 360 had reached a software attach rate of 7.5 games per console in the US; the rate was 7.0 in Europe, while its competitors were 3.8 (PS3) and 3.5 (Wii), according to Microsoft. Noire. In addition, Xbox 360 versions of cross-platform games were generally considered superior to their PS3 counterparts in 2006 and 2007, due in part to the difficulties of programming for the PS3.

examples.annotated_text: Baptists: Baptist missionary work in [dblookup('Baptists', 'Missionary Work Started In') -> Canada] Canada began in the British colony of [dblookup('British Colony', 'Missionary Work Started In') -> Nova Scotia] Nova Scotia (present day Nova Scotia and New Brunswick) in [dblookup('Baptists', 'Missionary Work Started Year') -> 1760s] the 1760s. The first official record of a Baptist church in Canada was that of the [dblookup('Horton Baptist Church', 'Location') -> Wolfville, Nova Scotia] Horton Baptist Church (now Wolfville) in Wolfville, Nova Scotia on [dblookup('Horton Baptist Church', 'Established Date') -> October 29, 1778] 29 October 1778. The church was established with the assistance of [dblookup('Horton Baptist Church', 'Established With Assistance Of') -> Henry Alline] the New Light evangelist Henry Alline. Many of Alline's followers, after his death, would convert and strengthen the Baptist presence in the Atlantic region. Two major groups of Baptists formed the basis of the churches in the Maritimes. These were referred to as [dblookup('Baptists in the Maritimes', 'Major Groups') -> Regular Baptist (Calvinistic), Free Will Baptists] Regular Baptist (Calvinistic in their doctrine) and Free Will Baptists.
examples.text: Baptists: Baptist missionary work in Canada began in the British colony of Nova Scotia (present day Nova Scotia and New Brunswick) in the 1760s. The first official record of a Baptist church in Canada was that of the Horton Baptist Church (now Wolfville) in Wolfville, Nova Scotia on 29 October 1778. Many of Alline's followers, after his death, would convert and strengthen the Baptist presence in the Atlantic region.[page needed] Two major groups of Baptists formed the basis of the churches in the Maritimes. These were referred to as Regular Baptist (Calvinistic in their doctrine) and Free Will Baptists.

examples.annotated_text: Intellectual_property: Law professor, writer, and political activist [dblookup('Lawrence Lessig', 'Criticism Of') -> Analogy between intellectual property and physical property] Lawrence Lessig, along with many other copyleft and free software activists, has criticized the implied analogy with physical property (like land or an automobile). They argue such an analogy fails because physical property is generally rivalrous while intellectual works are non-rivalrous (that is, if one makes a copy of a work, the enjoyment of the copy does not prevent enjoyment of the original). Other arguments along these lines claim that unlike the situation with tangible property, there is no natural scarcity of a particular idea or information: once it exists at all, it can be re-used and duplicated indefinitely without such re-use diminishing the original. [dblookup('Stephan Kinsella', 'Objection To') -> Intellectual property as implying scarcity] Stephan Kinsella has objected to intellectual property on the grounds that the word "property" implies scarcity, which may not be applicable to ideas.

Other makers from the Loar period and earlier include [dblookup('Lyon and Healy', 'Mandolin Manufacturing Era') -> Loar period and earlier] Lyon and Healy, Vega and Larson Brothers. Some notable modern American carved mandolin manufacturers include, in addition to Kay, [dblookup('Gibson', 'Mandolin Manufacturing Type') -> carved] Gibson, Weber, Monteleone and [dblookup('Collings', 'Mandolin Manufacturing Type') -> carved] Collings. Mandolins from other countries include The Loar (China), [dblookup('Santa, Rosa', 'Country Of Manufacture') -> China] Santa, Rosa (China), Michael Kelly (Korea), [dblookup('Eastman', 'Country Of Manufacture') -> China] Eastman (China), Kentucky (China), Heiden (Canada), Gilchrist (Australia) and Morgan Monroe (China).

examples.annotated_text: Predation: Among predators, there is a large degree of [dblookup('Predators', 'Specialization') -> specialization] specialization. Many predators specialize in hunting only one species of prey. Others are more [dblookup('Predators', 'Behavior Type') -> opportunistic] opportunistic and will kill and eat almost anything (examples: humans, leopards, dogs and alligators). The specialists are usually particularly well suited to capturing their preferred prey. The prey, in turn, are often equally suited to escape that predator. This is called [dblookup('Predation', 'Related Concept') -> evolutionary arms race] an evolutionary arms race and tends to keep the [dblookup('Evolutionary Arms Race', 'Effect') -> equilibrium of populations] populations of both species in equilibrium. Some predators specialize in certain classes of prey, not just single species. Some will switch to other prey (with varying degrees of success) when the preferred target is extremely scarce, and they may also resort to [dblookup('Predators', 'Alternative Diet') -> scavenging, herbivorous diet] scavenging or a herbivorous diet if possible.[citation needed]
examples.text: Predation: Among predators there is a large degree of specialization. Many predators specialize in hunting only one species of prey. Others are more opportunistic and will kill and eat almost anything (examples: humans, leopards, dogs and alligators). The specialists are usually particularly well suited to capturing their preferred prey. The prey in turn, are often equally suited to escape that predator. This is called an evolutionary arms race and tends to keep the populations of both species in equilibrium. Some predators specialize in certain classes of prey, not just single species. Some will switch to other prey (with varying degrees of success) when the preferred target is extremely scarce, and they may also resort to scavenging or a herbivorous diet if possible.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: War_on_Terror: On the morning of [dblookup('September 11 attacks', 'Date') -> September 11, 2001] 11 September 2001, 19 men affiliated with [dblookup('September 11 attacks', 'Perpetrator') -> al-Qaeda] al-Qaeda hijacked four airliners all bound for California. Once the hijackers assumed control of the airliners, they told the passengers that they had the bomb on board and would spare the lives of passengers and crew once their demands were met – no passenger and crew actually suspected that they would use the airliners as suicide weapons since it had never happened before in history. The hijackers – members of [dblookup('Hijackers', 'Cell Affiliation') -> al-Qaeda's Hamburg cell] al-Qaeda's Hamburg cell – intentionally crashed [dblookup('September 11 attacks', 'Targeted Buildings') -> Twin Towers] two airliners into the Twin Towers of the World Trade Center in [dblookup('World Trade Center', 'Location') -> New York City] New York City. Both buildings collapsed within two hours from fire damage related to the crashes, destroying nearby buildings and damaging others. The hijackers crashed a third airliner into [dblookup('September 11 attacks', 'Pentagon Attack Location') -> Pentagon] the Pentagon in [dblookup('Pentagon', 'Location') -> Arlington County, Virginia] Arlington County, Virginia, just outside [dblookup('Arlington County', 'Proximity To') -> Washington D.C.] Washington D.C. The fourth plane crashed into a field near [dblookup('United Airlines Flight 93', 'Crash Site') -> Shanksville, Pennsylvania] Shanksville, Pennsylvania, after some of its passengers and flight crew attempted to retake control of the plane, which the hijackers had redirected toward Washington D.C., to target the [dblookup('September 11 attacks', 'Intended Targets') -> White House, U.S. Capitol] White House, or the U.S. Capitol. No flights had survivors. A total of [dblookup('September 11 attacks', 'Total Fatalities') -> 2,977] 2,977 victims and the 19 hijackers perished in the attacks.
examples.text: War_on_Terror: On the morning of 11 September 2001, 19 men affiliated with al-Qaeda hijacked four airliners all bound for California. Once the hijackers assumed control of the airliners, they told the passengers that they had the bomb on board and would spare the lives of passengers and crew once their demands were met – no passenger and crew actually suspected that they would use the airliners as suicide weapons since it had never happened before in history. The hijackers – members of al-Qaeda's Hamburg cell – intentionally crashed two airliners into the Twin Towers of the World Trade Center in New York City. Both buildings collapsed within two hours from fire damage related to the crashes, destroying nearby buildings and damaging others. The hijackers crashed a third airliner into the Pentagon in Arlington County, Virginia, just outside Washington D.C. The fourth plane crashed into a field near Shanksville, Pennsylvania, after some of its passengers and flight crew attempted to retake control of the plane, which the hijackers had redirected toward Washington D.C., to target the White House, or the U.S. Capitol. No flights had survivors. A total of 2,977 victims and the 19 hijackers perished in the attacks.

examples.annotated_text: Kanye West: West's fifth album, My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy, has been noted by writers for its [dblookup('My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy', 'Style') -> maximalist aesthetic] maximalist aesthetic and its incorporation of elements from West's previous four albums. examples.annotated_text: Copper: [dblookup('Copper', 'In Use Since') -> At least 10,000 years] Copper has been in use at least 10,000 years, but [dblookup('Copper', 'Percent Extracted Since 1900') -> More than 95%] more than 95% of all copper ever mined and smelted has been extracted since 1900, and [dblookup('Copper', 'Percent Extracted In Last 24 Years') -> More than 50%] more than half was extracted in only the last 24 years. As with many natural resources, the [dblookup('Copper', 'Total Amount On Earth') -> Around 10^14 tons] total amount of copper on Earth is vast (around 10^14 tons just in the top kilometer of Earth's crust, or about 5 million years' worth at the current rate of extraction). However, only a tiny fraction of these reserves is economically viable, given present-day prices and technologies. Various estimates of existing copper reserves available for mining vary from [dblookup('Copper Reserves', 'Estimated Longevity') -> 25 to 60 years] 25 years to 60 years, depending on core assumptions such as the growth rate. [dblookup('Copper', 'Recycling Importance') -> Major source in modern world] Recycling is a major source of copper in the modern world. Because of these and other factors, the future of copper production and supply is the subject of much debate, including the concept of peak copper, analogous to peak oil.
examples.text: Copper: Copper has been in use at least 10,000 years, but more than 95% of all copper ever mined and smelted has been extracted since 1900, and more than half was extracted in only the last 24 years. As with many natural resources, the total amount of copper on Earth is vast (around 1014 tons just in the top kilometer of Earth's crust, or about 5 million years' worth at the current rate of extraction). However, only a tiny fraction of these reserves is economically viable, given present-day prices and technologies. Recycling is a major source of copper in the modern world. Because of these and other factors, the future of copper production and supply is the subject of much debate, including the concept of peak copper, analogous to peak oil.

examples.annotated_text: Infrared: High, cold ice clouds such as Cirrus or Cumulonimbus show up bright white, lower [dblookup('Clouds', 'Type Based on Altitude') -> Stratus, Stratocumulus] warmer clouds such as Stratus or Stratocumulus show up as grey with intermediate clouds shaded accordingly. Hot [dblookup('Land Surfaces', 'Appearance in Infrared') -> dark-grey or black] land surfaces will show up as dark-grey or black. One [dblookup('Infrared Imagery', 'Disadvantage') -> Similar temperature of low cloud and surface] disadvantage of infrared imagery is that low cloud such as stratus or fog can be a similar temperature to the surrounding land or sea surface and does not show up. However, using the difference in brightness of the IR4 channel (10.3–11.5 µm) and the [dblookup('Near-Infrared Channel', 'Wavelength Range') -> 1.58–1.64 µm] near-infrared channel (1.58–1.64 µm), low cloud can be distinguished, producing a fog satellite picture. The main [dblookup('Infrared Imagery', 'Advantage') -> Nighttime imaging capability] advantage of infrared is that images can be produced at night, allowing a continuous sequence of weather to be studied.
examples.text: Infrared: High, cold ice clouds such as Cirrus or Cumulonimbus show up bright white, lower warmer clouds such as Stratus or Stratocumulus show up as grey with intermediate clouds shaded accordingly. Hot land surfaces will show up as dark-grey or black. One disadvantage of infrared imagery is that low cloud such as stratus or fog can be a similar temperature to the surrounding land or sea surface and does not show up. However, using the difference in brightness of the IR4 channel (10.3–11.5 µm) and the near-infrared channel (1.58–1.64 µm), low cloud can be distinguished, producing a fog satellite picture. The main advantage of infrared is that images can be produced at night, allowing a continuous sequence of weather to be studied.

examples.annotated_text: Law_of_the_United_States: The actual substance of English law was formally "received" into the United States in several ways. First, all [dblookup('U.S. States', 'Reception Statutes Status') -> all except Louisiana] U.S. states except Louisiana have enacted "reception statutes" which generally state that the common law of England (particularly judge-made law) is the law of the state to the extent that it is not repugnant to domestic law or indigenous conditions. Some reception statutes impose a specific cutoff date for reception, such as the date of a colony's founding, while others are deliberately vague. Thus, contemporary U.S. courts often cite pre-Revolution cases when discussing the evolution of an ancient judge-made common law principle into its modern form, such as the heightened duty of care traditionally imposed upon common carriers.

examples.annotated_text: Hanover: Another point of interest is the Old Town. In the centre are the large Marktkirche ( Church St. Georgii et Jacobi, preaching venue of the bishop of the Lutheran Landeskirche Hannovers) and the Old Town Hall. Nearby are the Leibniz House, the Nolte House, and the Beguine Tower. A very nice quarter of the Old Town is the Kreuz-Church-Quarter around the Kreuz Church with many nice little lanes. Nearby is the old royal sports hall, now called the Ballhof theatre. On the edge of the Old Town are the Market Hall, the Leine Palace, and the ruin of the Aegidien Church which is now a monument to the victims of war and violence. Through the Marstall Gate you arrive at the bank of the river Leine, where the world-famous Nanas of [dblookup('Nanas of Niki de Saint-Phalle', 'Location') -> river Leine] Niki de Saint-Phalle are located. They are part of the Mile of Sculptures, which starts from Trammplatz, leads along the river bank, crosses Königsworther Square, and ends at the entrance of the Georgengarten. Near the Old Town is the district of Calenberger Neustadt where the Catholic Basilica Minor of St. Clemens, the Reformed Church and the Lutheran Neustädter Hof- und Stadtkirche St. Johannis are located.
