examples.annotated_text: Copper: Copper, [dblookup('Copper', 'Group In Periodic Table') -> 11] silver and gold are in group 11 of the periodic table, and they share certain attributes: they have one s-orbital electron on top of a filled d-electron shell and are characterized by [dblookup('Copper', 'Key Characteristics') -> high ductility, high electrical conductivity] high ductility and electrical conductivity. The filled d-shells in these elements do not contribute much to the interatomic interactions, which are dominated by the s-electrons through [dblookup('Copper', 'Type Of Bonding') -> metallic bonds] metallic bonds. Unlike metals with incomplete d-shells, [dblookup('Copper', 'Bonding Characteristics') -> lacks covalent character, relatively weak metallic bonds] metallic bonds in copper are lacking a covalent character and are relatively weak. This explains the low hardness and high ductility of single crystals of copper. At the macroscopic scale, introduction of extended defects to the crystal lattice, such as grain boundaries, hinders flow of the material under applied stress, thereby increasing its hardness. For this reason, [dblookup('Copper', 'Common Form Supplied') -> fine-grained polycrystalline form] copper is usually supplied in a fine-grained polycrystalline form, which has greater strength than monocrystalline forms.
examples.text: Copper: Copper, silver and gold are in group 11 of the periodic table, and they share certain attributes: they have one s-orbital electron on top of a filled d-electron shell and are characterized by high ductility and electrical conductivity. The filled d-shells in these elements do not contribute much to the interatomic interactions, which are dominated by the s-electrons through metallic bonds. Unlike metals with incomplete d-shells, metallic bonds in copper are lacking a covalent character and are relatively weak. This explains the low hardness and high ductility of single crystals of copper. At the macroscopic scale, introduction of extended defects to the crystal lattice, such as grain boundaries, hinders flow of the material under applied stress, thereby increasing its hardness. For this reason, copper is usually supplied in a fine-grained polycrystalline form, which has greater strength than monocrystalline forms.

examples.annotated_text: Serbo-Croatian: Like most [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Language Family') -> Slavic languages] Slavic languages, there are mostly [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Grammatical Genders Count') -> three] three genders for nouns: masculine, feminine, and neuter, a distinction which is still present even in the [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Plural Gender Distinction') -> yes] plural (unlike Russian and, in part, the [dblookup('Čakavian Dialect', 'Plural Gender Distinction') -> partial] Čakavian dialect). They also have [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Number System') -> singular and plural] two numbers: singular and plural. However, some consider there to be [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Alternate Number System') -> three numbers: singular, dual, paucal] three numbers (paucal or dual, too), since (still preserved in closely related [dblookup('Slovene Language', 'Paucal Number System') -> yes] Slovene) after two (dva, dvije/dve), three (tri) and four (četiri), and all numbers ending in them (e.g. twenty-two, ninety-three, one hundred four) the genitive singular is used, and after all other numbers five (pet) and up, the genitive plural is used. (The number one [jedan] is treated as [dblookup('Number One in Serbo-Croatian', 'Grammatical Treatment') -> adjective] an adjective.) Adjectives are placed [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Adjective Placement') -> before noun] in front of the noun they modify and must [dblookup('Serbo-Croatian', 'Adjective Agreement') -> case and number] agree in both case and number with it.
examples.text: Serbo-Croatian: Like most Slavic languages, there are mostly three genders for nouns: masculine, feminine, and neuter, a distinction which is still present even in the plural (unlike Russian and, in part, the Čakavian dialect). They also have two numbers: singular and plural. However, some consider there to be three numbers (paucal or dual, too), since (still preserved in closely related Slovene) after two (dva, dvije/dve), three (tri) and four (četiri), and all numbers ending in them (e.g. twenty-two, ninety-three, one hundred four) the genitive singular is used, and after all other numbers five (pet) and up, the genitive plural is used. examples.annotated_text: Karl_Popper: To [dblookup('Karl Popper', 'Philosophical Position') -> anti-justificationist] Popper, who was an anti-justificationist, traditional philosophy is misled by the [dblookup('Karl Popper', 'Criticism Of Philosophy') -> false principle of sufficient reason] false principle of sufficient reason. He thinks that no assumption can ever be or needs ever to be justified, so a lack of justification is not a justification for doubt. Instead, theories should be tested and scrutinized. It is not the goal to bless theories with claims of certainty or justification, but to eliminate errors in them. He writes, "there are no such things as good positive reasons; nor do we need such things [...] But [philosophers] obviously cannot quite bring [themselves] to believe that this is my opinion, let alone that it is right" [dblookup('The Philosophy of Karl Popper', 'Page Reference') -> p. 1043] (The Philosophy of Karl Popper, p. 1043).

examples.annotated_text: PlayStation_3: The console was first [dblookup('PlayStation 3', 'Official Announcement Date') -> E3 2005] officially announced at E3 2005, and was [dblookup('PlayStation 3', 'Release Date') -> end of 2006] released at the end of 2006. It was the first console to use Blu-ray Disc as its primary storage medium. The console was the first PlayStation to integrate social gaming services, included it being the first to introduce Sony's social gaming service, PlayStation Network, and its remote connectivity with PlayStation Portable and PlayStation Vita, being able to remote control the console from the devices. In [dblookup('PlayStation 3 Slim', 'Release Date') -> September 2009] September 2009, the Slim model of the PlayStation 3 was released, being lighter and thinner than the original version, which notably featured [dblookup('PlayStation 3 Slim', 'Design Changes') -> redesigned logo and marketing design] a redesigned logo and marketing design, as well as a [dblookup('PlayStation 3 Slim', 'Software Changes') -> minor start-up change] minor start-up change in software. A [dblookup('PlayStation 3 Super Slim', 'Release Date') -> late 2012] Super Slim variation was then released in late 2012, further refining and redesigning the console. As of [dblookup('PlayStation 3', 'Sales Count as of March 2016') -> 85 million units] March 2016, PlayStation 3 has sold 85 million units worldwide. Its successor, the [dblookup('PlayStation 3', 'Successor Console') -> PlayStation 4] PlayStation 4, was released later in [dblookup('PlayStation 4', 'Release Date') -> November 2013] November 2013.
examples.text: PlayStation_3: The console was first officially announced at E3 2005, and was released at the end of 2006. It was the first console to use Blu-ray Disc as its primary storage medium. The console was the first PlayStation to integrate social gaming services, included it being the first to introduce Sony's social gaming service, PlayStation Network, and its remote connectivity with PlayStation Portable and PlayStation Vita, being able to remote control the console from the devices. In September 2009, the Slim model of the PlayStation 3 was released, being lighter and thinner than the original version, which notably featured a redesigned logo and marketing design, as well as a minor start-up change in software. A Super Slim variation was then released in late 2012, further refining and redesigning the console. As of March 2016, PlayStation 3 has sold 85 million units worldwide. Its successor, the PlayStation 4, was released later in November 2013.

examples.annotated_text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: Alfred North Whitehead was [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Birthplace') -> Ramsgate, Kent, England] born in Ramsgate, Kent, England, in [dblookup('Alfred North Whitehead', 'Birth Year') -> 1861] 1861. His father, Alfred Whitehead, was [dblookup('Alfred Whitehead', 'Occupation') -> minister and schoolmaster] a minister and schoolmaster of Chatham House Academy, a successful school for boys established by [dblookup('Thomas Whitehead', 'Founder Of') -> Chatham House Academy] Thomas Whitehead, Alfred North's grandfather. Whitehead himself recalled both of them as being very successful schoolmasters, but that his grandfather was the [dblookup('Thomas Whitehead', 'Reputation') -> more extraordinary man] more extraordinary man. Whitehead's mother was Maria Sarah Whitehead, formerly [dblookup('Maria Sarah Whitehead', 'Former Name') -> Maria Sarah Buckmaster] Maria Sarah Buckmaster. examples.text: Alfred_North_Whitehead: Alfred North Whitehead was born in Ramsgate, Kent, England, in 1861. examples.annotated_text: Biodiversity: In absolute terms, the planet has lost [dblookup('Global Biodiversity', 'Loss Percentage Since 1970') -> 52%] 52% of its biodiversity since 1970 according to a 2014 study by the World Wildlife Fund. The Living Planet Report 2014 claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago". Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, [dblookup('Marine Wildlife', 'Loss Percentage') -> 39%] 39% for the marine wildlife gone, and [dblookup('Freshwater Wildlife', 'Loss Percentage') -> 76%] 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone. Biodiversity took the biggest hit in [dblookup('Latin America', 'Biodiversity Loss Percentage') -> 83%] Latin America, plummeting 83 percent. High-income countries showed a [dblookup('High-Income Countries', 'Biodiversity Change Percentage') -> 10% increase] 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries. This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of the process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.

examples.annotated_text: Royal_assent: The Clerk of the Parliaments, [dblookup('Clerk of the Parliaments', 'Role') -> Official of the House of Lords] an official of the House of Lords, traditionally states a formula in [dblookup('Royal Assent', 'Language of Formula') -> Anglo-Norman Law French] Anglo-Norman Law French, indicating the sovereign's decision. The granting of royal assent to a supply bill is indicated with the words "La Reyne remercie ses bons sujets, accepte leur benevolence, et ainsi le veult", translated as "The Queen thanks her good subjects, accepts their bounty, and wills it so." For other public or private bills, the formula is simply [dblookup('Royal Assent', 'Public/Private Bill Formula') -> "La Reyne le veult"] "La Reyne le veult" ("the Queen wills it"). For personal bills, the phrase is [dblookup('Royal Assent', 'Personal Bill Formula') -> "Soit fait comme il est désiré"] "Soit fait comme il est désiré" ("let it be as it is desired"). The appropriate formula for withholding assent is the euphemistic [dblookup('Royal Assent', 'Withholding Assent Formula') -> "La Reyne s'avisera"] "La Reyne s'avisera" ("the Queen will consider it"). When the sovereign is male, [dblookup('Royal Assent', 'Male Sovereign Formula Alteration') -> "Le Roy"] Le Roy is substituted for La Reyne.
examples.text: Royal_assent: The Clerk of the Parliaments, an official of the House of Lords, traditionally states a formula in Anglo-Norman Law French, indicating the sovereign's decision. The granting of royal assent to a supply bill is indicated with the words "La Reyne remercie ses bons sujets, accepte leur benevolence, et ainsi le veult", translated as "The Queen thanks her good subjects, accepts their bounty, and wills it so." For other public or private bills, the formula is simply "La Reyne le veult" ("the Queen wills it"). For personal bills, the phrase is "Soit fait comme il est désiré" ("let it be as it is desired"). The appropriate formula for withholding assent is the euphemistic "La Reyne s'avisera" ("the Queen will consider it"). When the sovereign is male, Le Roy is substituted for La Reyne.

examples.annotated_text: Cotton: By the 1840s, India was no longer capable of [dblookup('India', 'Cotton Supply Capability Reduction') -> 1840s] supplying the vast quantities of cotton fibers needed by mechanized British factories, while shipping bulky, low-price cotton from India to Britain was time-consuming and expensive. examples.text: Cotton: By the 1840s, India was no longer capable of supplying the vast quantities of cotton fibers needed by mechanized British factories, while shipping bulky, low-price cotton from India to Britain was time-consuming and expensive. This, coupled with the emergence of American cotton as a superior type (due to the longer, stronger fibers of the two domesticated native American species, Gossypium hirsutum and Gossypium barbadense), encouraged British traders to purchase cotton from plantations in the United States and plantations in the Caribbean. examples.text: Virgil: Publius Vergilius Maro (Classical Latin: [ˈpuː.blɪ.ʊs wɛrˈɡɪ.lɪ.ʊs ˈma.roː]; October 15, 70 BC – September 21, 19 BC), usually called Virgil or Vergil /ˈvɜːrdʒᵻl/ in English, was an ancient Roman poet of the Augustan period. He is known for three major works of Latin literature, the Eclogues (or Bucolics), the Georgics, and the epic Aeneid. A number of minor poems, collected in the Appendix Vergiliana, are sometimes attributed to him.

examples.annotated_text: Labour_Party_(UK): The Labour Party's origins lie in the [dblookup('Labour Party (UK)', 'Founded In') -> late 19th century] late 19th century, when it became apparent that there was a need for a new political party to represent the interests and needs of the urban proletariat, a demographic which had increased in number and had recently been given franchise. In addition, several small socialist groups had formed around this time, with the intention of linking the movement to political policies. examples.annotated_text: Crimean War: The war opened in the [dblookup('Crimean War', 'Conflict Region') -> Balkans] Balkans when [dblookup('Crimean War', 'Initial Russian Military Action') -> occupation of provinces in modern Romania] Russian troops occupied provinces in modern Romania and began to cross the Danube. Led by [dblookup('Ottoman Army', 'Commander at Silistra') -> Omar Pasha] Omar Pasha, the Ottomans fought a strong defensive battle and stopped the advance at [dblookup('Battle of Silistra', 'Location') -> Silistra] Silistra. A separate action on the fort town of [dblookup('Siege of Kars', 'Location') -> Kars] Kars in eastern Turkey led to a siege, and a Turkish attempt to reinforce the garrison was destroyed by a [dblookup('Battle of Sinop', 'Defeating Force') -> Russian fleet] Russian fleet at [dblookup('Battle of Sinop', 'Location') -> Sinop] Sinop. Fearing an Ottoman collapse, [dblookup('Crimean War', 'French Involvement Start') -> France] France and the [dblookup('Crimean War', 'British Involvement Start') -> UK] UK rushed forces to [dblookup('Crimean War', 'Initial Allied Landing Site') -> Gallipoli] Gallipoli. They then moved north to [dblookup('Crimean War', 'Allied Movement to Location') -> Varna] Varna in June, arriving just in time for the Russians to abandon Silistra. examples.text: Crimean_War: The war opened in the Balkans when Russian troops occupied provinces in modern Romania and began to cross the Danube. Led by Omar Pasha, the Ottomans fought a strong defensive battle and stopped the advance at Silistra. A separate action on the fort town of Kars in eastern Turkey led to a siege, and a Turkish attempt to reinforce the garrison was destroyed by a Russian fleet at Sinop. Fearing an Ottoman collapse, France and the UK rushed forces to Gallipoli. They then moved north to Varna in June, arriving just in time for the Russians to abandon Silistra. Aside from a minor skirmish at Constanța there was little for the allies to do. Karl Marx quipped that "there they are, the French doing nothing and the British helping them as fast as possible".

examples.annotated_text: Switzerland: The country was historically about evenly balanced between Catholic and Protestant, with a complex patchwork of majorities over most of the country. Geneva converted to Protestantism in 1536, just before [dblookup('John Calvin', 'Arrival In Geneva') -> 1536] John Calvin arrived there. One canton, Appenzell, was officially divided into Catholic and Protestant sections in [dblookup('Appenzell Internal Division', 'Year') -> 1597] 1597. The larger cities and their cantons (Bern, Geneva, Lausanne, Zürich and Basel) used to be predominantly Protestant. Central Switzerland, the Valais, the Ticino, Appenzell Innerrhodes, the Jura, and Fribourg are [dblookup('Central Switzerland and Other Regions', 'Traditional Religious Majority') -> Catholic] traditionally Catholic. The Swiss Constitution of 1848, under the recent impression of the clashes of Catholic vs. Protestant cantons that culminated in the [dblookup('Sonderbundskrieg', 'Historical Event') -> Catholic vs. Protestant cantons clash] Sonderbundskrieg, consciously defines a consociational state, allowing the peaceful co-existence of Catholics and Protestants. A [dblookup('Church and State Separation Initiative', 'Year of Vote') -> 1980] 1980 initiative calling for the [dblookup('Church and State Separation Initiative', 'Result') -> Rejected by 78.9%] complete separation of church and state was rejected by 78.9% of the voters. Some traditionally Protestant cantons and cities nowadays have a slight Catholic majority, not because they were growing in members, quite the contrary, but only because since about 1970 a steadily growing minority became not affiliated with any church or other religious body ( 21.4% in Switzerland, 2012) especially in traditionally Protestant regions, such as [dblookup('Basel-City', 'Percentage Unaffiliated in 2012') -> 42%] Basel-City (42%), [dblookup('Canton of Neuchâtel', 'Percentage Unaffiliated in 2012') -> 38%] canton of Neuchâtel (38%), [dblookup('Canton of Geneva', 'Percentage Unaffiliated in 2012') -> 35%] canton of Geneva (35%), [dblookup('Canton of Vaud', 'Percentage Unaffiliated in 2012') -> 26%] canton of Vaud (26%), or [dblookup('Zürich City', 'Percentage Unaffiliated in 2012 City') -> >25%] Zürich city (city: >25%; [dblookup('Canton of Zürich', 'Percentage Unaffiliated in 2012') -> 23%] canton: 23%).
examples.text: Switzerland: The country was historically about evenly balanced between Catholic and Protestant, with a complex patchwork of majorities over most of the country. Geneva converted to Protestantism in 1536, just before John Calvin arrived there. One canton, Appenzell, was officially divided into Catholic and Protestant sections in 1597. The larger cities and their cantons (Bern, Geneva, Lausanne, Zürich and Basel) used to be predominantly Protestant. Central Switzerland, the Valais, the Ticino, Appenzell Innerrhodes, the Jura, and Fribourg are traditionally Catholic. The Swiss Constitution of 1848, under the recent impression of the clashes of Catholic vs. Protestant cantons that culminated in the Sonderbundskrieg, consciously defines a consociational state, allowing the peaceful co-existence of Catholics and Protestants. A 1980 initiative calling for the complete separation of church and state was rejected by 78.9% of the voters. Some traditionally Protestant cantons and cities nowadays have a slight Catholic majority, not because they were growing in members, quite the contrary, but only because since about 1970 a steadily growing minority became not affiliated with any church or other religious body (21.4% in Switzerland, 2012) especially in traditionally Protestant regions, such as Basel-City (42%), canton of Neuchâtel (38%), canton of Geneva (35%), canton of Vaud (26%), or Zürich city (city: >25%; canton: 23%).

examples.annotated_text: Dwight D. Eisenhower: In [dblookup('Dwight D. Eisenhower', 'Year of Domino Theory Articulation') -> 1954] 1954, Eisenhower articulated the domino theory in his outlook towards communism in Southeast Asia and also in Central America. He believed that if the communists were allowed to prevail in Vietnam, this would cause a succession of countries to fall to communism, from Laos through Malaysia and Indonesia ultimately to India. Likewise, the fall of Guatemala would end with the fall of neighboring Mexico. That year the loss of North Vietnam to the communists and the rejection of his proposed European Defence Community (EDC) were serious defeats, but he remained optimistic in his opposition to the spread of communism, saying "Long faces don't win wars". As he had threatened the French in their rejection of EDC, he afterwards moved to restore [dblookup('Dwight D. Eisenhower', 'Action Towards West Germany') -> restoration as NATO partner] West Germany, as a full NATO partner.

examples.annotated_text: Planck_constant: The "photoelectrons" emitted as a result of the photoelectric effect have a certain [dblookup('Photoelectric Effect', 'Dependent Variable on Frequency') -> kinetic energy] kinetic energy, which can be measured. This kinetic energy (for each photoelectron) is independent of the intensity of the light, but depends linearly on the frequency; and if the frequency is too low (corresponding to a photon energy that is less than the work function of the material), no photoelectrons are emitted at all, unless a plurality of photons, whose energetic sum is greater than the energy of the photoelectrons, acts virtually simultaneously (multiphoton effect). Assuming the frequency is high enough to cause the photoelectric effect, a rise in [dblookup('Photoelectric Effect', 'Effect of Increased Light Intensity') -> more photoelectrons emitted] intensity of the light source causes more photoelectrons to be emitted with the same kinetic energy, rather than the same number of photoelectrons to be emitted with higher kinetic energy.

Global distillation is the [dblookup('Global Distillation', 'Definition') -> process where pesticides are transported from warmer to colder regions] process whereby pesticides are transported from warmer to colder regions of the Earth, in particular the Poles and mountain tops. examples.annotated_text: Immunology: The body’s capability to react to antigen depends on a person's age, antigen type, maternal factors and the area where the antigen is presented. [dblookup('Neonates', 'Physiological Immunodeficiency') -> true] Neonates are said to be in a state of physiological immunodeficiency, because both their innate and adaptive immunological responses are greatly suppressed. Once born, a child’s immune system responds favorably to [dblookup('Newborn Immune Response', 'Antigen Response') -> protein antigens] protein antigens while not as well to [dblookup('Newborn Immune System', 'Weaker Response To') -> glycoproteins, polysaccharides] glycoproteins and polysaccharides. In fact, many of the infections acquired by neonates are caused by [dblookup('Neonate Infections', 'Commonly Caused By') -> Staphylococcus, Pseudomonas] low virulence organisms like Staphylococcus and Pseudomonas. In neonates, [dblookup('Neonate Immune System', 'Opsonic Activity') -> limited] opsonic activity and the ability to activate the complement cascade is very limited. For example, the [dblookup('C3 Level In Newborns', 'Percentage Of Adult Level') -> 65%] mean level of C3 in a newborn is approximately 65% of that found in the adult. [dblookup('Newborn Immune System', 'Phagocytic Activity') -> impaired] Phagocytic activity is also greatly impaired in newborns. This is due to lower opsonic activity, as well as diminished up-regulation of integrin and selectin receptors, which limit the ability of neutrophils to interact with adhesion molecules in the endothelium. Their [dblookup('Neonate Monocytes', 'Characteristics') -> slow, reduced ATP production] monocytes are slow and have a reduced ATP production, which also limits the newborn's phagocytic activity. Although, the number of total [dblookup('Neonate Lymphocyte Count', 'Comparison To Adults') -> higher] lymphocytes is significantly higher than in adults, the [dblookup('Neonate Immunity', 'Impairments') -> cellular, humoral] cellular and humoral immunity is also impaired. Antigen-presenting cells in newborns have a reduced capability to activate T cells. Also, [dblookup('Newborn T Cells', 'Proliferation And Cytokine Production') -> poor proliferation, small cytokine amount] T cells of a newborn proliferate poorly and produce very small amounts of cytokines like [dblookup('Cytokines In Neonates', 'Limited Production') -> IL-2, IL-4, IL-5, IL-12, IFN-g] IL-2, IL-4, IL-5, IL-12, and IFN-g which limits their capacity to activate the humoral response as well as the phagocytic activity of macrophages. B cells develop early during gestation but are not fully active.

examples.annotated_text: YouTube: Both private individuals and large production companies have used YouTube to grow audiences. Independent content creators have built grassroots followings numbering in the thousands at very little cost or effort, while mass retail and radio promotion proved problematic. Concurrently, old media celebrities moved into the website at the invitation of a YouTube management that witnessed early content creators accruing substantial followings, and perceived audience sizes potentially larger than that attainable by television. While YouTube's [dblookup('YouTube', 'Revenue-Sharing Program') -> Partner Program] revenue-sharing "Partner Program" made it possible to earn a substantial living as a video producer—its top five hundred partners each earning more than [dblookup('YouTube Partner Program', 'Top Partners Annual Earnings Range') -> $100,000 to $12 million] $100,000 annually and its ten highest-earning channels grossing from $2.5 million to $12 million—in 2012 CMU business editor characterized YouTube as "a free-to-use... promotional platform for the music labels". In 2013 [dblookup('Forbes', 'Katheryn Thayer Assertion on YouTube') -> Importance of eliciting reactions on social media] Forbes' Katheryn Thayer asserted that digital-era artists' work must not only be of high quality, but must elicit reactions on the YouTube platform and social media. In 2013, [dblookup('YouTube and Vevo', '2013 Artists with Most Views') -> 2.5% of artists categorized as "mega", "mainstream", and "mid-sized"] videos of the 2.5% of artists categorized as "mega", "mainstream" and "mid-sized" received 90.3% of the relevant views on YouTube and Vevo. By early 2013 Billboard had announced that it was factoring YouTube streaming data into calculation of the Billboard Hot 100 and related genre charts.

examples.text: Arsenal_F.C.: Arsenal was the first club from the south of England to join The Football League, in 1893. examples.annotated_text: Infrared: Infrared reflectography, as called by [dblookup('Infrared Reflectography', 'Application By') -> art conservators] art conservators, can be applied to [dblookup('Infrared Reflectography', 'Application On') -> paintings] paintings to reveal underlying layers in a completely non-destructive manner, in particular [dblookup('Infrared Reflectography', 'Reveals') -> underdrawing] the underdrawing or outline drawn by the artist as a guide. This often reveals the artist's use of [dblookup('Infrared Reflectography', 'Detects') -> carbon black] carbon black, which shows up well in reflectograms, as long as it has not also been used in the ground underlying the whole painting. Art conservators are looking to see whether the visible layers of paint differ from the underdrawing or layers in between – such alterations are called pentimenti when made by the original artist. This is very useful information in deciding whether a painting is the prime version by the original artist or a copy, and whether it has been altered by over-enthusiastic restoration work. In general, the more pentimenti the more likely a painting is to be the prime version. It also gives useful insights into [dblookup('Pentimenti', 'Provides Insights Into') -> working practices] working practices.
examples.text: Infrared: Infrared reflectography (fr; it; es), as called by art conservators, can be applied to paintings to reveal underlying layers in a completely non-destructive manner, in particular the underdrawing or outline drawn by the artist as a guide. This often reveals the artist's use of carbon black, which shows up well in reflectograms, as long as it has not also been used in the ground underlying the whole painting. Art conservators are looking to see whether the visible layers of paint differ from the underdrawing or layers in between – such alterations are called pentimenti when made by the original artist. This is very useful information in deciding whether a painting is the prime version by the original artist or a copy, and whether it has been altered by over-enthusiastic restoration work. In general, the more pentimenti the more likely a painting is to be the prime version. It also gives useful insights into working practices.

examples.annotated_text: Greece: Following the assassination of [dblookup('Phillip II of Macedon', 'Successor') -> Alexander III] Phillip II, his son Alexander III ("The Great") assumed the leadership of the [dblookup('Alexander III', 'Leadership Assumed') -> League of Corinth] League of Corinth and launched an invasion of the [dblookup('Alexander III', 'Invaded Empire') -> Persian Empire] Persian Empire with the combined forces of all Greek states in 334 BC. examples.text: Greece: Following the assassination of Phillip II, his son Alexander III ("The Great") assumed the leadership of the League of Corinth and launched an invasion of the Persian Empire with the combined forces of all Greek states in 334 BC. Undefeated in battle, Alexander had conquered the Persian Empire in its entirety by 330 BC. By the time of his death in 323 BC, he had created one of the largest empires in history, stretching from Greece to India. His empire split into several kingdoms upon his death, the most famous of which were the Seleucid Empire, Ptolemaic Egypt, the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom. Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch, Seleucia and the many other new Hellenistic cities in Asia and Africa. Although the political unity of Alexander's empire could not be maintained, it resulted in the Hellenistic civilization and spread the Greek language and Greek culture in the territories conquered by Alexander. Greek science, technology and mathematics are generally considered to have reached their peak during the Hellenistic period.

examples.annotated_text: The_Blitz: A converse popular image arose of [dblookup('British People', 'World War II Image') -> national solidarity] British people in the Second World War: a collection of people locked in national solidarity. This image entered the historiography of the Second World War in the [dblookup('National Solidarity Image', 'Historiography Introduction') -> 1980s and 1990s] 1980s and 1990s, especially after the publication of [dblookup('The Myth of the Blitz', 'Author') -> Angus Calder] Angus Calder's book The Myth of the Blitz (1991). It was evoked by both the right and left political factions in Britain during the [dblookup('Falklands War', 'Nostalgic Narrative Reference') -> Blitz imagery] Falklands War when it was embedded in a nostalgic narrative in which the Second World War represented aggressive British patriotism successfully defending democracy. This imagery of people in the Blitz was and is powerfully portrayed in film, radio, newspapers and magazines. At the time, it was a useful [dblookup('Blitz Imagery', 'Purpose During WWII') -> propaganda tool] propaganda tool for home and foreign consumption. Historians' critical response to this construction focused on what were seen as over-emphasised claims of righteous nationalism and national unity. In the Myth of the Blitz, Calder exposed some of the counter-evidence of anti-social and divisive behaviours. What he saw as the myth—serene national unity—became "historical truth". In particular, [dblookup('World War II Britain', 'Social Issue Highlighted') -> class division] class division was most evident.

examples.annotated_text: Economy_of_Greece: Greece has tended to lag behind its European Union partners in terms of Internet use, with the gap closing rapidly in recent years. examples.annotated_text: Matter: In particle physics and quantum chemistry, [dblookup('Antimatter', 'Composition') -> antiparticles] antimatter is matter that is composed of the antiparticles of those that constitute ordinary matter. If a particle and its antiparticle come into contact with each other, the two annihilate; that is, they may both be converted into other particles with equal energy in accordance with Einstein's equation E = mc^2. These new particles may be high-energy photons (gamma rays) or other particle–antiparticle pairs. The resulting particles are endowed with an amount of kinetic energy equal to the difference between the rest mass of the products of the annihilation and the rest mass of the original particle–antiparticle pair, which is often quite large.

examples.annotated_text: Cotton: GM cotton acreage in India grew at a rapid rate, increasing from [dblookup('GM Cotton in India', 'Acreage in 2002') -> 50,000 hectares] 50,000 hectares in 2002 to [dblookup('GM Cotton in India', 'Acreage in 2011') -> 10.6 million hectares] 10.6 million hectares in 2011. examples.text: Cotton: GM cotton acreage in India grew at a rapid rate, increasing from 50,000 hectares in 2002 to 10.6 million hectares in 2011. examples.annotated_text: Political_corruption: Transparency International, an anti-corruption NGO, pioneered this field with the [dblookup('Corruption Perceptions Index', 'First Released') -> 1995] CPI, first released in 1995. This work is often credited with breaking a taboo and forcing the issue of corruption into high level development policy discourse. Transparency International currently publishes [dblookup('Transparency International', 'Number of Annual Measures') -> three] three measures, updated annually: a CPI (based on aggregating third-party polling of public perceptions of how corrupt different countries are); a [dblookup('Transparency International', 'Publishes') -> Global Corruption Barometer] Global Corruption Barometer (based on a survey of general public attitudes toward and experience of corruption); and a [dblookup('Transparency International', 'Publishes') -> Bribe Payers Index] Bribe Payers Index, looking at the willingness of foreign firms to pay bribes. The [dblookup('Corruption Perceptions Index', 'Popularity') -> best known] Corruption Perceptions Index is the best known of these metrics, though it has drawn much criticism and may be declining in influence. In [dblookup('Government Defence Anti-corruption Index', 'Published Year') -> 2013] 2013 Transparency International published a report on the "Government Defence Anti-corruption Index". This index evaluates the risk of corruption in countries' military sector.
examples.text: Political_corruption: Transparency International, an anti-corruption NGO, pioneered this field with the CPI, first released in 1995. examples.text: Southampton: The city has a particular connection to Cunard Line and their fleet of ships. This was particularly evident on 11 November 2008 when the Cunard liner RMS Queen Elizabeth 2 departed the city for the final time amid a spectacular fireworks display after a full day of celebrations. examples.annotated_text: Red: Red, white, and black were the colors of the German Empire from [dblookup('German Empire', 'Flag Usage Period') -> 1870 to 1918] 1870 to 1918, and as such they came to be [dblookup('German Empire Flag', 'Association') -> German nationalism] associated with German nationalism. In the [dblookup('1920s', 'Nazi Flag Colors Adoption') -> red, white, black] 1920s they were adopted as the colors of the Nazi flag. In [dblookup('Mein Kampf', 'Author') -> Adolf Hitler] Mein Kampf, [dblookup('Adolf Hitler', 'Statement on Flag Colors') -> "revered colors expressive of our homage to the glorious past"] Hitler explained that they were "revered colors expressive of our homage to the glorious past." The red part of the flag was also chosen to [dblookup('Nazi Flag Red', 'Purpose') -> attract attention] attract attention - Hitler wrote: "the new flag ... should prove effective as a large poster" because "in hundreds of thousands of cases a really striking emblem may be the first cause of awakening interest in a movement." The red also [dblookup('Nazi Flag Red', 'Symbolism') -> social program aimed at German workers] symbolized the social program of the Nazis, aimed at German workers. Several designs by a number of different authors were considered, but the one adopted in the end was [dblookup('Nazi Flag Design', 'Designer') -> Adolf Hitler] Hitler's personal design.
examples.text: Red: Red, white, and black were the colors of the German Empire from 1870 to 1918, and as such they came to be associated with German nationalism. In the 1920s they were adopted as the colors of the Nazi flag. In Mein Kampf, Hitler explained that they were "revered colors expressive of our homage to the glorious past." The red part of the flag was also chosen to attract attention - Hitler wrote: "the new flag ... should prove effective as a large poster" because "in hundreds of thousands of cases a really striking emblem may be the first cause of awakening interest in a movement." The red also symbolized the social program of the Nazis, aimed at German workers. Several designs by a number of different authors were considered, but the one adopted in the end was Hitler's personal design.

examples.annotated_text: Imperial_College_London: In September 2014, Professor Stefan Grimm, of the [dblookup('Stefan Grimm', 'Department') -> Department of Medicine] Department of Medicine, was found dead after being threatened with dismissal for failure to raise enough grant money. The [dblookup('Imperial College London', 'Death Announcement Date') -> December 4, 2014] College made its first public announcement of his death on 4 December 2014. Grimm's last email accused his employers of bullying by demanding that he should get grants worth at least [dblookup('Stefan Grimm', 'Grant Expectation') -> £200,000 per year] £200,000 per year. His last email was viewed more than [dblookup('Stefan Grimm', 'Email Views First Four Days') -> 100,000] 100,000 times in the first four days after it was posted. The College has announced an [dblookup('Imperial College London', 'Inquiry Into') -> Stefan Grimm's death] internal inquiry into Stefan Grimm's death. The inquest on his death has not yet reported.
examples.text: Imperial_College_London: In September 2014, Professor Stefan Grimm, of the Department of Medicine, was found dead after being threatened with dismissal for failure to raise enough grant money. The College made its first public announcement of his death on 4 December 2014. Grimm's last email accused his employers of bullying by demanding that he should get grants worth at least £200,000 per year. His last email was viewed more than 100,000 times in the first four days after it was posted. The College has announced an internal inquiry into Stefan Grimm's death. The inquest on his death has not yet reported.

examples.annotated_text: Incandescent_light_bulb: While inert gas reduces filament evaporation, it also conducts heat from the filament, thereby cooling the filament and reducing efficiency. At constant pressure and temperature, the thermal conductivity of a gas depends upon the [dblookup('Gas', 'Factors Influencing Thermal Conductivity') -> molecular weight, cross-sectional area] molecular weight of the gas and the cross-sectional area of the gas molecules. Higher molecular weight gases have lower thermal conductivity, because both the molecular weight is higher and also the cross-sectional area is higher. [dblookup('Xenon Gas', 'Effect on Efficiency') -> improves efficiency] Xenon gas improves efficiency because of its high molecular weight, but is also more expensive, so its use is limited to smaller lamps.

examples.annotated_text: Computer_security: On October 3, 2010, Public Safety Canada unveiled [dblookup('Canada', 'Cyber Security Strategy Name') -> Canada’s Cyber Security Strategy] Canada’s Cyber Security Strategy, following a [dblookup('Speech from the Throne', 'Commitment') -> boost the security of Canadian cyberspace] Speech from the Throne commitment to boost the security of Canadian cyberspace. The aim of the strategy is to [dblookup('Canada’s Cyber Security Strategy', 'Objectives') -> strengthen cyber systems, support economic growth, protect Canadians] strengthen Canada’s "cyber systems and critical infrastructure sectors, support economic growth and protect Canadians as they connect to each other and to the world." [dblookup('Canada’s Cyber Security Strategy', 'Pillars') -> securing government systems, partnering to secure vital cyber systems, helping Canadians be secure] Three main pillars define the strategy: securing government systems, partnering to secure vital cyber systems outside the federal government, and helping Canadians to be secure online. The strategy involves [dblookup('Canada’s Cyber Security Strategy', 'Involvement') -> multiple departments and agencies across the Government of Canada] multiple departments and agencies across the Government of Canada. The [dblookup('Cyber Incident Management Framework for Canada', 'Purpose') -> outlines responsibilities, plans coordinated response] Cyber Incident Management Framework for Canada outlines these responsibilities, and provides a plan for coordinated response between government and other partners in the event of a cyber incident. The [dblookup('Action Plan 2010–2015', 'Purpose') -> ongoing implementation of Canada's Cyber Security Strategy] Action Plan 2010–2015 for Canada's Cyber Security Strategy outlines the ongoing implementation of the strategy.
examples.text: Computer_security: On October 3, 2010, Public Safety Canada unveiled Canada’s Cyber Security Strategy, following a Speech from the Throne commitment to boost the security of Canadian cyberspace. The aim of the strategy is to strengthen Canada’s "cyber systems and critical infrastructure sectors, support economic growth and protect Canadians as they connect to each other and to the world." Three main pillars define the strategy: securing government systems, partnering to secure vital cyber systems outside the federal government, and helping Canadians to be secure online. The strategy involves multiple departments and agencies across the Government of Canada. The Cyber Incident Management Framework for Canada outlines these responsibilities, and provides a plan for coordinated response between government and other partners in the event of a cyber incident. The Action Plan 2010–2015 for Canada's Cyber Security Strategy outlines the ongoing implementation of the strategy.

examples.annotated_text: Han_dynasty: After [dblookup('Han Dynasty', 'Eunuch Involvement Onset') -> 92 AD] 92 AD, the palace eunuchs increasingly involved themselves in court politics, engaging in violent power struggles between the various consort clans of the empresses and empress dowagers, causing the Han's ultimate downfall. Imperial authority was also seriously challenged by large Daoist religious societies which instigated [dblookup('Han Dynasty', 'Rebellions') -> Yellow Turban Rebellion, Five Pecks of Rice Rebellion] the Yellow Turban Rebellion and the Five Pecks of Rice Rebellion. Following the death of [dblookup('Emperor Ling', 'Reign') -> 168–189 AD] Emperor Ling (r. 168–189 AD), the palace eunuchs suffered a wholesale massacre by military officers, allowing members of the aristocracy and military governors to become warlords and divide the empire. When Cao Pi, King of Wei, usurped the throne from Emperor Xian, the [dblookup('Han Dynasty', 'Cessation Date') -> 220 AD] Han dynasty ceased to exist.
examples.text: Han_dynasty: After 92 AD, the palace eunuchs increasingly involved themselves in court politics, engaging in violent power struggles between the various consort clans of the empresses and empress dowagers, causing the Han's ultimate downfall. Imperial authority was also seriously challenged by large Daoist religious societies which instigated the Yellow Turban Rebellion and the Five Pecks of Rice Rebellion. Following the death of Emperor Ling (r. 168–189 AD), the palace eunuchs suffered wholesale massacre by military officers, allowing members of the aristocracy and military governors to become warlords and divide the empire. When Cao Pi, King of Wei, usurped the throne from Emperor Xian, the Han dynasty ceased to exist.

examples.annotated_text: John, King of England: During John's early years, [dblookup('Henry II of England', 'Succession Planning') -> Henry the Young King] Henry attempted to resolve the question of his succession. Henry the Young King had been crowned [dblookup('Henry the Young King', 'Title Obtained Year') -> 1170] King of England in 1170, but was not given any formal powers by [dblookup('Henry the Young King', 'Relationship with') -> Henry II of England] his father; he was also promised [dblookup('Henry the Young King', 'Promised Territories') -> Normandy, Anjou] Normandy and Anjou as part of his future inheritance. Richard was to be appointed the [dblookup('Richard I of England', 'Expected Title') -> Count of Poitou] Count of Poitou with control of [dblookup('Richard I of England', 'Control Over') -> Aquitaine] Aquitaine, whilst Geoffrey was to become the [dblookup('Geoffrey II, Duke of Brittany', 'Title') -> Duke of Brittany] Duke of Brittany. At this time it seemed unlikely that John would ever inherit substantial lands, and he was jokingly nicknamed [dblookup('John, King of England', 'Nickname') -> Lackland] "Lackland" by his father.
examples.text: John,_King_of_England: During John's early years, Henry attempted to resolve the question of his succession. Henry the Young King had been crowned King of England in 1170, but was not given any formal powers by his father; he was also promised Normandy and Anjou as part of his future inheritance. Richard was to be appointed the Count of Poitou with control of Aquitaine, whilst Geoffrey was to become the Duke of Brittany. At this time it seemed unlikely that John would ever inherit substantial lands, and he was jokingly nicknamed "Lackland" by his father.

examples.annotated_text: Copper: There are [dblookup('Copper', 'Number of Isotopes') -> 29] 29 isotopes of [dblookup('Copper', 'Stable Isotopes') -> 63Cu, 65Cu] copper. 63Cu and 65Cu are stable, with [dblookup('63Cu', 'Natural Abundance') -> approximately 69%] 63Cu comprising approximately 69% of naturally occurring copper; they both have [dblookup('63Cu and 65Cu', 'Spin') -> 3/2] a spin of 3/2. The other isotopes are radioactive, with the most stable being [dblookup('67Cu', 'Half-life') -> 61.83 hours] 67Cu with a half-life of 61.83 hours. Seven metastable isotopes have been characterized, with [dblookup('68mCu', 'Half-life') -> 3.8 minutes] 68mCu being the longest-lived with a half-life of 3.8 minutes. Isotopes with a mass number above 64 decay by [dblookup('Isotopes Above 64', 'Decay Mode') -> β−] β−, whereas those with a mass number below 64 decay by [dblookup('Isotopes Below 64', 'Decay Mode') -> β+] β+. 64Cu, which has a half-life of 12.7 hours, decays both ways.
examples.text: Copper: There are 29 isotopes of copper. 63Cu and 65Cu are stable, with 63Cu comprising approximately 69% of naturally occurring copper; they both have a spin of 3⁄2. The other isotopes are radioactive, with the most stable being 67Cu with a half-life of 61.83 hours. Seven metastable isotopes have been characterized, with 68mCu the longest-lived with a half-life of 3.8 minutes. Isotopes with a mass number above 64 decay by β−, whereas those with a mass number below 64 decay by β+. 64Cu, which has a half-life of 12.7 hours, decays both ways.

examples.annotated_text: Economy_of_Greece: Counting shipping as quasi-exports and in terms of monetary value, Greece [dblookup('Greece', 'Global Shipping Rank 2011') -> 4th] ranked 4th globally in [dblookup('Greece', 'Shipping Export Value 2011') -> 17,704.132 million $] 2011 having "exported" shipping services worth 17,704.132 million $; only [dblookup('Countries with Higher Shipping Rank 2011', 'Countries') -> Denmark, Germany, South Korea] Denmark, Germany, and South Korea ranked higher during that year. Similarly, counting shipping services provided to Greece by other countries as quasi-imports and the difference between "exports" and "imports" as a "trade balance", Greece in 2011 [dblookup('Greece', 'Trade Balance Rank 2011') -> 2nd] ranked in the latter second behind Germany, having [dblookup('Greece', 'Shipping Import Value 2011') -> 7,076.605 million US$] "imported" shipping services worth 7,076.605 million US$ and having [dblookup('Greece', 'Shipping Trade Surplus 2011') -> 10,712.342 million US$] run a "trade surplus" of 10,712.342 million US$.
examples.text: Economy_of_Greece: Counting shipping as quasi-exports and in terms of monetary value, Greece ranked 4th globally in 2011 having "exported" shipping services worth 17,704.132 million $; only Denmark, Germany and South Korea ranked higher during that year. Similarly counting shipping services provided to Greece by other countries as quasi-imports and the difference between "exports" and "imports" as a "trade balance", Greece in 2011 ranked in the latter second behind Germany, having "imported" shipping services worth 7,076.605 million US$ and having run a "trade surplus" of 10,712.342 million US$.

examples.annotated_text: Turner Classic Movies: TCM regularly airs a [dblookup('Turner Classic Movies', 'Program') -> Star of the Month] "Star of the Month" throughout the year on Wednesdays starting at 8:00 p.m. Eastern Time, in which most, if not all, feature films from a classic film star are shown during that night's schedule. Hosted by [dblookup('Turner Classic Movies', 'Host') -> Robert Osborne] Robert Osborne, the network also marks the occurrence of a film actor's birthday (either antemortem or posthumously) or recent death with day- or evening-long festivals showcasing several of that artist's best, earliest or least-known pictures; by effect, marathons scheduled in honor of an actor's passing (which are scheduled within a month after their death) pre-empt films originally scheduled to air on that date. TCM also features a [dblookup('Turner Classic Movies', 'Program') -> TCM Guest Programmer] monthly program block called the "TCM Guest Programmer", in which Osborne is joined by celebrity guests responsible for choosing that evening's films (examples of such programmers during 2012 include [dblookup('TCM Guest Programmer', 'Celebrity Guests 2012') -> Jules Feiffer, Anthony Bourdain, Debra Winger, Ellen Barkin, Spike Lee, Regis Philbin, Jim Lehrer] Jules Feiffer, Anthony Bourdain, Debra Winger, Ellen Barkin, Spike Lee, Regis Philbin, and Jim Lehrer); an offshoot of this block featuring Turner Classic Movies employees aired during [dblookup('TCM Guest Programmer', 'Employee Program Date') -> February 2011] February 2011.
examples.text: Turner_Classic_Movies: TCM regularly airs a "Star of the Month" throughout the year on Wednesdays starting at 8:00 p.m. Eastern Time, in which most, if not all, feature films from a classic film star are shown during that night's schedule. Hosted by Robert Osbourne, the network also marks the occurrence of a film actor's birthday (either antemortem or posthumously) or recent death with day- or evening-long festivals showcasting several of that artist's best, earliest or least-known pictures; by effect, marathons scheduled in honor of an actor's passing (which are scheduled within a month after their death) pre-empt films originally scheduled to air on that date. examples.annotated_text: Edmund_Burke: On [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Date of Charge Against Hastings') -> April 4, 1786] 4 April 1786, Burke presented the Commons with the [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Article Name Against Hastings') -> Article of Charge of High Crimes and Misdemeanors] Article of Charge of High Crimes and Misdemeanors against Hastings. The impeachment in Westminster Hall, which did not begin until [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Impeachment Start Date') -> February 14, 1788] 14 February 1788, would be the "first major public discursive event of its kind in England", bringing the morality and duty of [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Theme of Impeachment') -> imperialism] imperialism to the forefront of public perception. Burke already was known for his [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Skills Known For') -> eloquent rhetorical skills] eloquent rhetorical skills and his involvement in the trial only enhanced its [dblookup('Warren Hastings Impeachment', 'Public Impact') -> popularity and significance] popularity and significance. Burke's indictment, fuelled by [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Emotional Approach') -> emotional indignation] emotional indignation, branded Hastings a 'captain-general of iniquity'; who never dined without 'creating a famine'; whose heart was 'gangrened to the core', and who resembled both a 'spider of Hell' and a 'ravenous vulture devouring the carcasses of the dead'. The House of Commons eventually [dblookup('Warren Hastings', 'Result at House of Commons') -> impeached] impeached Hastings, but subsequently, the [dblookup('House of Lords', 'Outcome for Warren Hastings') -> acquitted of all charges] House of Lords acquitted him of all charges.
examples.text: Edmund_Burke: On 4 April 1786, Burke presented the Commons with the Article of Charge of High Crimes and Misdemeanors against Hastings. The impeachment in Westminster Hall, which did not begin until 14 February 1788, would be the "first major public discursive event of its kind in England", bringing the morality and duty of imperialism to the forefront of public perception. Burke already was known for his eloquent rhetorical skills and his involvement in the trial only enhanced its popularity and significance. Burke's indictment, fuelled by emotional indignation, branded Hastings a 'captain-general of iniquity'; who never dined without 'creating a famine'; whose heart was 'gangrened to the core', and who resembled both a 'spider of Hell' and a 'ravenous vulture devouring the carcasses of the dead'. The House of Commons eventually impeached Hastings, but subsequently, the House of Lords acquitted him of all charges.

examples.annotated_text: Architecture: Concurrently, the recent movements of [dblookup('New Urbanism', 'Promotes') -> sustainable approach towards construction] New Urbanism, Metaphoric architecture, and [dblookup('New Classical Architecture', 'Promotes') -> sustainable approach towards construction] New Classical Architecture promote a sustainable approach towards construction, that appreciates and develops [dblookup('New Urbanism', 'Emphasizes On') -> smart growth] smart growth, [dblookup('Metaphoric architecture', 'Appreciates') -> architectural tradition] architectural tradition, and [dblookup('New Classical Architecture', 'Emphasizes On') -> classical design] classical design. examples.text: Architecture: Concurrently, the recent movements of New Urbanism, Metaphoric architecture and New Classical Architecture promote a sustainable approach towards construction, that appreciates and develops smart growth, architectural tradition and classical design. examples.annotated_text: Chihuahua_(state): In the far eastern part of the state the [dblookup('Chihuahua (state)', 'Dominant Region') -> Chihuahuan Desert] Chihuahuan Desert dominates due to low precipitation and extremely high temperatures; some areas of the eastern part of the state are so dry no vegetation is found like the [dblookup('Chihuahua (state)', 'Notable Feature') -> Sand Dunes of Samalayuca] Sand Dunes of Samalayuca. There are two distinctive [dblookup('Chihuahua (state)', 'Climate Zones in Eastern Part') -> Hot Desert (BWh), Cool Desert (BWk)] climate zones found in the eastern part of the state: Hot Desert (BWh) and Cool Desert (BWk) which are differentiated by average annual temperature due to differences in elevation. There is a transition zone in the middle of the state between the two extremely different climates from the east and west; this zone is the [dblookup('Chihuahua (state)', 'Transition Zone in Middle') -> Steppe] Steppe characterized by a compromise between juxtaposed climate zones.
examples.text: Chihuahua_(state): In the far eastern part of the state the Chihuahuan Desert dominates due to low precipitation and extremely high temperatures; some areas of the eastern part of the state are so dry no vegetation is found like the Sand Dunes of Samalayuca. There is a transition zone in the middle of the state between the two extremely different climates from the east and west; this zone is the Steppe characterized by a compromise between juxtaposed climate zones.

examples.annotated_text: Pharmaceutical_industry: In 1937 over [dblookup('Elixir Sulfanilamide Incident', 'Fatalities') -> 100 people] 100 people died after ingesting "Elixir Sulfanilamide" manufactured by [dblookup('Elixir Sulfanilamide', 'Manufacturer') -> S.E. Massengill Company] S.E. Massengill Company of [dblookup('S.E. Massengill Company', 'Location') -> Tennessee] Tennessee. The product was formulated in [dblookup('Elixir Sulfanilamide', 'Toxic Solvent Used') -> diethylene glycol] diethylene glycol, a highly toxic solvent that is now widely used as antifreeze. Under the laws extant at that time, prosecution of the manufacturer was possible only under the technicality that the product had been called an "elixir", which literally implied a solution in ethanol. In response to this episode, the [dblookup('U.S. Congress', 'Legislation Passed In Response') -> Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of 1938] U.S. Congress passed the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of [dblookup('Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act', 'Year Enacted') -> 1938] 1938, which for the first time required pre-market demonstration of safety before a drug could be sold, and explicitly prohibited false therapeutic claims.
examples.text: Pharmaceutical_industry: In 1937 over 100 people died after ingesting "Elixir Sulfanilamide" manufactured by S.E. Massengill Company of Tennessee. The product was formulated in diethylene glycol, a highly toxic solvent that is now widely used as antifreeze. Under the laws extant at that time, prosecution of the manufacturer was possible only under the technicality that the product had been called an "elixir", which literally implied a solution in ethanol. In response to this episode, the U.S. Congress passed the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of 1938, which for the first time required pre-market demonstration of safety before a drug could be sold, and explicitly prohibited false therapeutic claims.

examples.annotated_text: Wood: Some experiments on very resinous [dblookup('Longleaf Pine', 'Strength Increase Due To') -> resin] Longleaf Pine specimens indicate an increase in strength, due to the resin which increases the strength when dry. Such resin-saturated heartwood is called [dblookup('Resin-saturated Heartwood', 'Common Name') -> fat lighter] "fat lighter". Structures built of fat lighter are almost impervious to [dblookup('Fat Lighter Structures', 'Resistance To') -> rot, termites] rot and termites; however, they are [dblookup('Fat Lighter Structures', 'Flammability') -> very flammable] very flammable. Stumps of old longleaf pines are often dug, split into small pieces and sold as [dblookup('Longleaf Pine Stumps', 'Use') -> kindling for fires] kindling for fires. Stumps thus dug may actually remain a century or more since being cut. [dblookup('Spruce Impregnated With Resin', 'Strength Increase') -> resin impregnation] Spruce impregnated with crude resin and dried is also greatly increased in strength thereby.
examples.text: Wood: Some experiments on very resinous Longleaf Pine specimens indicate an increase in strength, due to the resin which increases the strength when dry. Such resin-saturated heartwood is called "fat lighter". Structures built of fat lighter are almost impervious to rot and termites; however they are very flammable. Stumps of old longleaf pines are often dug, split into small pieces and sold as kindling for fires. Stumps thus dug may actually remain a century or more since being cut. examples.annotated_text: History_of_science: In Hellenistic Egypt, the mathematician [dblookup('Euclid', 'Contributions') -> mathematical rigor, definition, axiom, theorem, proof] Euclid laid down the foundations of mathematical rigor and introduced the concepts of definition, axiom, theorem, and proof still in use today in his [dblookup('Euclid', 'Notable Work') -> Elements] Elements, considered the most influential textbook ever written. [dblookup('Archimedes', 'Field') -> Mathematics, Physics] Archimedes, considered one of the greatest mathematicians of all time, is credited with using the [dblookup('Archimedes', 'Mathematical Contribution') -> method of exhaustion] method of exhaustion to calculate the area under the arc of a parabola with the summation of an infinite series, and gave a remarkably accurate approximation of [dblookup('Archimedes', 'Approximation Of') -> Pi] Pi. He is also known in [dblookup('Archimedes', 'Contributions to Physics') -> hydrostatics, statics, lever principle] physics for laying the foundations of hydrostatics, statics, and the explanation of the principle of the lever.
examples.text: History_of_science: In Hellenistic Egypt, the mathematician Euclid laid down the foundations of mathematical rigor and introduced the concepts of definition, axiom, theorem and proof still in use today in his Elements, considered the most influential textbook ever written. Archimedes, considered one of the greatest mathematicians of all time, is credited with using the method of exhaustion to calculate the area under the arc of a parabola with the summation of an infinite series, and gave a remarkably accurate approximation of Pi. He is also known in physics for laying the foundations of hydrostatics, statics, and the explanation of the principle of the lever.

examples.annotated_text: Clothing: Many kinds of clothing are designed to be ironed before they are worn to remove wrinkles. Most modern formal and [dblookup('Semi-Formal Clothing', 'Characteristic') -> requires ironing] semi-formal clothing is in this category (for example, dress shirts and suits). Ironed clothes are believed to look clean, fresh, and neat. Much contemporary [dblookup('Casual Clothing', 'Material Type') -> knit materials] casual clothing is made of knit materials that do not readily wrinkle, and do not require ironing. Some clothing is [dblookup('Permanent Press Clothing', 'Treatment') -> polytetrafluoroethylene coating] permanent press, having been treated with a coating (such as polytetrafluoroethylene) that suppresses wrinkles and creates a smooth appearance without ironing.
examples.text: Clothing: Many kinds of clothing are designed to be ironed before they are worn to remove wrinkles. Most modern formal and semi-formal clothing is in this category (for example, dress shirts and suits). Ironed clothes are believed to look clean, fresh, and neat. Much contemporary casual clothing is made of knit materials that do not readily wrinkle, and do not require ironing. Some clothing is permanent press, having been treated with a coating (such as polytetrafluoroethylene) that suppresses wrinkles and creates a smooth appearance without ironing.

examples.annotated_text: Antibiotics: Antibacterial-resistant strains and species, sometimes referred to as [dblookup('Antibacterial-Resistant Strains', 'Common Name') -> superbugs] "superbugs," now contribute to the emergence of diseases that were for a while well controlled. For example, emergent bacterial strains causing [dblookup('Tuberculosis', 'Bacterial Strain Concern') -> multidrug-resistant tuberculosis (MDR-TB)] tuberculosis (TB) that are resistant to previously effective antibacterial treatments pose many therapeutic challenges. Every year, nearly [dblookup('Multidrug-Resistant Tuberculosis', 'Estimated New Cases Annually Worldwide') -> 500,000] half a million new cases of multidrug-resistant tuberculosis (MDR-TB) are estimated to occur worldwide. For example, [dblookup('NDM-1', 'Type') -> enzyme] NDM-1 is a newly identified enzyme conveying bacterial resistance to a broad range of beta-lactam antibacterials. The United Kingdom's Health Protection Agency has stated that "most isolates with [dblookup('NDM-1', 'Consequence') -> resistance to all standard intravenous antibiotics for severe infections] NDM-1 enzyme are resistant to all standard intravenous antibiotics for treatment of severe infections."
examples.text: Antibiotics: Antibacterial-resistant strains and species, sometimes referred to as "superbugs", now contribute to the emergence of diseases that were for a while well controlled. For example, emergent bacterial strains causing tuberculosis (TB) that are resistant to previously effective antibacterial treatments pose many therapeutic challenges. Every year, nearly half a million new cases of multidrug-resistant tuberculosis (MDR-TB) are estimated to occur worldwide. For example, NDM-1 is a newly identified enzyme conveying bacterial resistance to a broad range of beta-lactam antibacterials. The United Kingdom's Health Protection Agency has stated that "most isolates with NDM-1 enzyme are resistant to all standard intravenous antibiotics for treatment of severe infections."

Yale_University: Yale's secret society buildings (some of which are called "tombs") were built to be private yet unmistakable. A diversity of architectural styles is represented: 

- Berzelius: [dblookup('Berzelius', 'Architect') -> Donn Barber] Donn Barber in an austere cube with classical detailing ([dblookup('Berzelius', 'Completion Year Range') -> 1908 or 1910] erected in 1908 or 1910).
  
- Book and Snake: [dblookup('Book and Snake', 'Architect') -> Louis R. Metcalfe] Louis R. Metcalfe in a Greek Ionic style ([dblookup('Book and Snake', 'Completion Year') -> 1901] erected in 1901).

- Elihu: [dblookup('Elihu', 'Architect') -> unknown] architect unknown but built in a Colonial style (constructed on an early [dblookup('Elihu', 'Foundation Century Origin') -> 17th century] 17th-century foundation although the building is from the [dblookup('Elihu', 'Building Century Origin') -> 18th century] 18th century).

- Mace and Chain: in a late colonial, early Victorian style ([dblookup('Mace and Chain', 'Completion Year') -> 1823] built in 1823). Interior moulding is said to have belonged to [dblookup('Mace and Chain', 'Notable Moulding Owner') -> Benedict Arnold] Benedict Arnold.

- Manuscript Society: [dblookup('Manuscript Society', 'Designer') -> King Lui-Wu] King Lui-Wu with [dblookup('Manuscript Society', 'Landscape Responsible') -> Dan Kniley] Dan Kniley responsible for landscaping and [dblookup('Manuscript Society', 'Brickwork Designer') -> Josef Albers] Josef Albers for the brickwork intaglio mural. Building constructed in a [dblookup('Manuscript Society', 'Architectural Style') -> mid-century modern style] mid-century modern style.

- Scroll and Key: [dblookup('Scroll and Key', 'Architect') -> Richard Morris Hunt] Richard Morris Hunt in a Moorish- or Islamic-inspired Beaux-Arts style ([dblookup('Scroll and Key', 'Completion Year Range') -> 1869-70] erected 1869–70).

- Skull and Bones: possibly [dblookup('Skull and Bones', 'Possible Architect') -> Alexander Jackson Davis or Henry Austin] Alexander Jackson Davis or Henry Austin in an Egypto-Doric style utilizing Brownstone ([dblookup('Skull and Bones', 'First Wing Completion Year') -> 1856] in 1856 the first wing was completed, [dblookup('Skull and Bones', 'Second Wing Completion Year') -> 1903] in 1903 the second wing, [dblookup('Skull and Bones', 'Towers Completion Year') -> 1911] 1911 the Neo-Gothic towers in rear garden were completed).

- St. Elmo: (former tomb) [dblookup('St. Elmo', 'Architect') -> Kenneth M. Murchison] Kenneth M. Murchison, [dblookup('St. Elmo', 'Design Influence') -> Elizabethan manor] designs inspired by Elizabethan manor. Current location, brick colonial.

- Shabtai: [dblookup('Shabtai', 'Completion Year') -> 1882] 1882, the Anderson Mansion built in the [dblookup('Shabtai', 'Architectural Style') -> Second Empire style] Second Empire architectural style.

- Wolf's Head: [dblookup('Wolf's Head', 'Architect') -> Bertram Grosvenor Goodhue] Bertram Grosvenor Goodhue ([dblookup('Wolf's Head', 'Completion Year Range') -> 1923-4] erected 1923-4).

examples.text: Nanjing: Nanjing, one of the nation's most important cities for over a thousand years, is recognized as one of the Four Great Ancient Capitals of China, and had been the world's largest city aggregately for hundreds of years, enjoyed peace and prosperity and beared wars and disasters. Nanjing served as the capital of Eastern Wu, one of the three major states in the Three Kingdoms period (211-280); the Eastern Jin and each of the Southern Dynasties (Liu Song, Southern Qi, Liang and Chen), which successively ruled southern China from 317-589; the Southern Tang, one of the Ten Kingdoms (937-76); the Ming dynasty when, for the first time, all of China was ruled from the city (1368-1421); and the Republic of China (1927–37, 1945–49) prior to its flight to Taiwan during the Chinese Civil War. The city also served as the seat of the rebel Taiping Heavenly Kingdom (1851–64) and the Japanese puppet regime of Wang Jingwei (1940–45) during the Second Sino-Japanese War, and suffered appalling atrocities in both conflicts, including the Nanjing Massacre. It has been serving as the capital city of Jiangsu province after the China was established, and is still the nominal capital of Republic of China that accommodates many of its important heritage sites, including the Presidential Palace and Sun Yat-sen Mausoleum. Nanjing is famous for human historical landscapes, mountains and waters such as Fuzimiao, Ming Palace, Chaotian Palace, Porcelain Tower, Drum Tower, Stone City, City Wall, Qinhuai River, Xuanwu Lake and Purple Mountain. Key cultural facilities include Nanjing Library, Nanjing Museum and Art Museum.

examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: According to one of her [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Biographer') -> Giles St Aubyn] biographers, Giles St Aubyn, Victoria wrote an [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Average Words Written Per Day') -> 2,500] average of 2,500 words a day during her adult life. From July [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Journal Start Date') -> 1832] 1832 until just before her death, she kept a detailed journal, which eventually encompassed [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Journal Volumes') -> 122] 122 volumes. After Victoria's [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Death Year') -> 1901] death, her youngest daughter, [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Literary Executor') -> Princess Beatrice] Princess Beatrice, was appointed her literary executor. Beatrice transcribed and edited the diaries covering Victoria's [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Accession Year') -> 1837] accession onwards, and burned the originals in the process. Despite this destruction, much of the diaries still exist. In addition to Beatrice's edited copy, [dblookup('Queen Victoria's Diaries', 'Transcribed By') -> Lord Esher] Lord Esher transcribed the volumes from 1832 to 1861 before Beatrice destroyed them. Part of Victoria's extensive correspondence has been published in volumes edited by A. C. Benson, Hector Bolitho, George Earle Buckle, Lord Esher, Roger Fulford, and Richard Hough among others.

examples.annotated_text: Somalis: The [dblookup('Somali People', 'Importance of Clan Groupings') -> social units, culture, politics] clan groupings of the Somali people are important social units, and clan membership plays a central part in Somali culture and politics. Clans are [dblookup('Clans in Somali Society', 'Descent Type') -> patrilineal] patrilineal and are often divided into sub-clans, sometimes with many sub-divisions. Tradition holds this general area as an [dblookup('Somali People', 'Ancestral Homeland') -> northern Somalia] ancestral homeland of the Somali people.

examples.annotated_text: Edmund Burke: Although Whig grandees such as [dblookup('William Cavendish-Bentinck, 3rd Duke of Portland', 'Political Affiliation') -> Whig Party] Portland and [dblookup('William Fitzwilliam, 4th Earl Fitzwilliam', 'Political Affiliation') -> Whig Party] Fitzwilliam privately agreed with Burke's Appeal, they wished [dblookup('William Fitzwilliam, 4th Earl Fitzwilliam', 'View On Burke\'s Appeal') -> Agreement with doctrines] he had used more moderate language. Fitzwilliam saw the Appeal as containing "the doctrines I have sworn by, long and long since". Francis Basset, a backbench Whig MP, wrote to Burke: "...though for reasons which I will not now detail I did not then deliver my sentiments, I most perfectly differ from [dblookup('Charles James Fox', 'Opinion On') -> French Revolution] Mr. Fox & from the great Body of opposition on the French Revolution". Burke sent a copy of the Appeal to the king and the [dblookup('George III', 'Reaction To Burke\'s Appeal') -> Read with great satisfaction] king requested a friend to communicate to Burke that he had read it "with great Satisfaction". Burke wrote of its reception: "Not one word from one of our party. They are secretly galled. They agree with me to a title; but they dare not speak out for fear of hurting Fox. ... They leave me to myself; they see that I can do myself justice". Charles Burney viewed it as "a most admirable book—the best & most useful on political subjects that I have ever seen" but believed the differences in the [dblookup('Whig Party', 'Dispute Between Members') -> Edmund Burke and Charles James Fox over French Revolution] Whig Party between Burke and Fox should not be aired publicly.
examples.text: Edmund_Burke: Although Whig grandees such as Portland and Fitzwilliam privately agreed with Burke's Appeal, they wished he had used more moderate language. Burke sent a copy of the Appeal to the king and the king requested a friend to communicate to Burke that he had read it "with great Satisfaction".
