They leave me to myself; they see that I can do myself justice". Charles Burney viewed it as "a most admirable book—the best & most useful on political subjects that I have ever seen" but believed the differences in the Whig Party between Burke and Fox should not be aired publicly.

examples.annotated_text: New_York_City: New York City's [dblookup('New York City', 'Food Culture Influences') -> immigrant history] food culture includes a variety of international cuisines influenced by the city's immigrant history. [dblookup('New York City', 'Cuisines Popularized By') -> Central European, Italian immigrants] Central European and Italian immigrants originally made the city famous for bagels, cheesecake, and New York-style pizza, while [dblookup('New York City', 'Prominent Restaurant Types') -> Chinese, Asian, sandwich joints, trattorias, diners, coffeehouses] Chinese and other Asian restaurants, sandwich joints, trattorias, diners, and coffeehouses have become ubiquitous. Some [dblookup('New York City', 'Number of Licensed Mobile Food Vendors') -> 4,000] 4,000 mobile food vendors licensed by the city, many immigrant-owned, have made [dblookup('New York City', 'Popular Street Foods') -> Middle Eastern foods, falafel, kebabs] Middle Eastern foods such as falafel and kebabs popular examples of modern New York street food. The city is also home to [dblookup('New York City', 'Number of Haute Cuisine Restaurants') -> nearly one thousand] nearly one thousand of the finest and most diverse haute cuisine restaurants in the world, according to Michelin. The [dblookup('New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene', 'Responsibility') -> assigns letter grades to restaurants] New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene assigns letter grades to the city's 24,000 restaurants based upon their inspection results.
examples.text: New_York_City: New York City's food culture includes a variety of international cuisines influenced by the city's immigrant history. Central European and Italian immigrants originally made the city famous for bagels, cheesecake, and New York-style pizza, while Chinese and other Asian restaurants, sandwich joints, trattorias, diners, and coffeehouses have become ubiquitous. Some 4,000 mobile food vendors licensed by the city, many immigrant-owned, have made Middle Eastern foods such as falafel and kebabs popular examples of modern New York street food. The city is also home to nearly one thousand of the finest and most diverse haute cuisine restaurants in the world, according to Michelin. The New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene assigns letter grades to the city's 24,000 restaurants based upon their inspection results.

examples.annotated_text: Central_African_Republic: In [dblookup('Central African Republic', 'Conflict-Stricken Year') -> 2006] 2006, due to ongoing violence, over 50,000 people in the country's northwest were at risk of starvation but this was averted due to assistance from [dblookup('Central African Republic', 'Assistance From') -> United Nations] the United Nations.[citation needed] On 8 January 2008, the [dblookup('United Nations', 'Secretary-General in 2008') -> Ban Ki-Moon] UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-Moon declared that the [dblookup('Central African Republic', 'Eligibility for Peacebuilding Fund') -> 8 January 2008] Central African Republic was eligible to receive assistance from the Peacebuilding Fund. Three priority areas were identified: first, the reform of the security sector; second, the promotion of good governance and the rule of law; and third, the revitalization of communities affected by conflicts. On 12 June 2008, the [dblookup('Central African Republic', 'Request for Peacebuilding Commission Assistance') -> 12 June 2008] Central African Republic requested assistance from the [dblookup('UN Peacebuilding Commission', 'Established Year') -> 2005] UN Peacebuilding Commission, which was set up in 2005 to help countries emerging from conflict avoid devolving back into war or chaos.
examples.text: Central_African_Republic: In 2006, due to ongoing violence, over 50,000 people in the country's northwest were at risk of starvation but this was averted due to assistance from the United Nations.[citation needed] On 8 January 2008, the UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-Moon declared that the Central African Republic was eligible to receive assistance from the Peacebuilding Fund. Three priority areas were identified: first, the reform of the security sector; second, the promotion of good governance and the rule of law; and third, the revitalization of communities affected by conflicts. On 12 June 2008, the Central African Republic requested assistance from the UN Peacebuilding Commission, which was set up in 2005 to help countries emerging from conflict avoid devolving back into war or chaos.

examples.annotated_text: Nutrition: In the US, [dblookup('Dietitians', 'Credentialing Organizations in US') -> Commission for Dietetic Registration, American Dietetic Association] dietitians are registered (RD) or licensed (LD) with the Commission for Dietetic Registration and the American Dietetic Association, and are [dblookup('Dietitians', 'Title Usage Requirement in US') -> educational and experiential prerequisites, national registration or licensure examination] only able to use the title "dietitian," as described by the business and professions codes of each respective state, when they have met specific educational and experiential prerequisites and passed a national registration or licensure examination, respectively. In California, registered dietitians must abide by the "Business and Professions Code of Section 2585-2586.8". Anyone may [dblookup('Nutritionist Title', 'Regulation Status in US') -> unregulated] call themselves a nutritionist, including unqualified dietitians, as this term is unregulated. Most governments provide guidance on nutrition, and some also impose mandatory disclosure/labeling requirements for processed food manufacturers and restaurants to assist consumers in complying with such guidance.

examples.annotated_text: Daylight_saving_time: As with zoneinfo, a user of Microsoft Windows configures DST by specifying the name of a location, and the operating system then consults a table of rule sets that must be updated when DST rules change. Procedures for specifying the name and updating the table vary with release. Updates are not issued for [dblookup('Microsoft Windows', 'Update Policy for DST') -> older versions] older versions of Microsoft Windows. [dblookup('Windows Vista', 'DST Support Limit') -> two start and end rules per time zone setting] Windows Vista supports at most two start and end rules per time zone setting. In a Canadian location observing DST, a single Vista setting supports both 1987–2006 and post-2006 time stamps, but mishandles some older time stamps. Older Microsoft Windows systems [dblookup('Older Microsoft Windows Systems', 'DST Rule Storage') -> single start and end rule per zone] usually store only a single start and end rule for each zone, so that the same Canadian setting reliably supports only post-2006 time stamps.

examples.annotated_text: Near_East: If the British Empire was now going to side with the [dblookup('Russian Empire', 'Alliance During WWI') -> Triple Entente] Russian Empire, the [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Alliance During WWI') -> Triple Alliance] Ottoman Empire had no choice but to cultivate a relationship with the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was supported by the [dblookup('German Empire', 'Alliance During WWI') -> Triple Alliance] German Empire. In a few years these alignments became the [dblookup('Triple Entente', 'Formation Year') -> 1907] Triple Entente and the [dblookup('Triple Alliance', 'Formation Year') -> 1882] Triple Alliance (already formed in 1882), which were in part a cause of [dblookup('World War I', 'Start Year') -> 1914] World War I. By its end in [dblookup('World War I', 'End Year') -> 1918] 1918, three empires were gone, a fourth was about to fall to revolution, and two more, the British and French, were forced to yield in revolutions started under the aegis of their own ideologies.
examples.text: Near_East: If the British Empire was now going to side with the Russian Empire, the Ottoman Empire had no choice but to cultivate a relationship with the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was supported by the German Empire. examples.annotated_text: Adolescence: Because most injuries sustained by adolescents are related to [dblookup('Adolescents', 'Injury Causes') -> risky behavior] risky behavior (car crashes, alcohol, unprotected sex), a great deal of research has been done on the cognitive and emotional processes underlying adolescent risk-taking. In addressing this question, it is important to distinguish whether [dblookup('Adolescents', 'Tendency To Engage In') -> risky behaviors] adolescents are more likely to engage in risky behaviors (prevalence), whether they make risk-related decisions similarly or differently than [dblookup('Comparison Group', 'Decision Making') -> adults] adults (cognitive processing perspective), or whether they use the same processes but value different things and thus arrive at different conclusions. The behavioral decision-making theory proposes that adolescents and adults both weigh the potential rewards and consequences of an action. However, research has shown that [dblookup('Adolescents', 'Emphasis In Decision Making') -> rewards, particularly social rewards] adolescents seem to give more weight to rewards, particularly social rewards, than do adults.
examples.text: Adolescence: Because most injuries sustained by adolescents are related to risky behavior (car crashes, alcohol, unprotected sex), a great deal of research has been done on the cognitive and emotional processes underlying adolescent risk-taking. In addressing this question, it is important to distinguish whether adolescents are more likely to engage in risky behaviors (prevalence), whether they make risk-related decisions similarly or differently than adults (cognitive processing perspective), or whether they use the same processes but value different things and thus arrive at different conclusions. The behavioral decision-making theory proposes that adolescents and adults both weigh the potential rewards and consequences of an action. However, research has shown that adolescents seem to give more weight to rewards, particularly social rewards, than do adults.

examples.annotated_text: Florida: "By May [dblookup('Hernando de Soto', 'Exploration of Florida') -> 1539] 1539, Conquistador Hernando de Soto skirted the coast of Florida, searching for a deep harbor to land. He described seeing a thick wall of red mangroves spread mile after mile, some reaching as high as 70 feet (21 m), with intertwined and elevated roots making landing difficult. Very soon, 'many smokes' appeared 'along the whole coast', billowing against the sky, when the Native ancestors of the Seminole spotted the newcomers and spread the alarm by signal fires". The [dblookup('Spanish', 'Cultural Influence on Florida') -> Christianity, cattle, horses, sheep, Spanish language] Spanish introduced Christianity, cattle, horses, sheep, the Spanish language, and more to Florida. Both the [dblookup('Spanish', 'Settlement in Florida') -> successful and unsuccessful] Spanish and [dblookup('French', 'Settlement in Florida') -> successful and unsuccessful] French established settlements in Florida, with varying degrees of success. In [dblookup('Don Tristán de Luna y Arellano', 'Colony Established Year in Florida') -> 1559] 1559, Don Tristán de Luna y Arellano established a colony at [dblookup('Pensacola', 'Early European Colony Site') -> present-day Pensacola] present-day Pensacola, one of the first European settlements in the continental United States, but it was abandoned by [dblookup('Don Tristán de Luna y Arellano', 'Colony Abandoned Year in Florida') -> 1561] 1561.
examples.text: Florida: "By May 1539, Conquistador Hernando de Soto skirted the coast of Florida, searching for a deep harbor to land. He described seeing a thick wall of red mangroves spread mile after mile, some reaching as high as 70 feet (21 m), with intertwined and elevated roots making landing difficult. Very soon, 'many smokes' appeared 'along the whole coast', billowing against the sky, when the Native ancestors of the Seminole spotted the newcomers and spread the alarm by signal fires". The Spanish introduced Christianity, cattle, horses, sheep, the Spanish language, and more to Florida.[full citation needed] Both the Spanish and French established settlements in Florida, with varying degrees of success. In 1559, Don Tristán de Luna y Arellano established a colony at present-day Pensacola, one of the first European settlements in the continental United States, but it was abandoned by 1561.

examples.annotated_text: Black_people: Black people is a term used in [dblookup('Black People', 'Applicable Regions') -> certain countries] certain countries, often in socially based systems of racial classification or of ethnicity, to describe persons who are perceived to be dark-skinned compared to other given populations. As such, the meaning of the expression varies widely both between and within societies, and depends significantly on context. For many [dblookup('Black People', 'Perception') -> individuals, communities, countries] individuals, communities and countries, "black" is also perceived as a derogatory, outdated, reductive or otherwise unrepresentative label, and as a result is neither used nor defined.
examples.text: Black_people: Black people is a term used in certain countries, often in socially based systems of racial classification or of ethnicity, to describe persons who are perceived to be dark-skinned compared to other given populations. As such, the meaning of the expression varies widely both between and within societies, and depends significantly on context. For many other individuals, communities and countries, "black" is also perceived as a derogatory, outdated, reductive or otherwise unrepresentative label, and as a result is neither used nor defined.

examples.annotated_text: Religion_in_ancient_Rome: The same [dblookup('Religion in Ancient Rome', 'Divine Agencies Role') -> causing and averting disease or harm] divine agencies who caused disease or harm also had the power to avert it, and so might be placated in advance. Divine consideration might be sought to avoid the inconvenient delays of a journey, or encounters with banditry, piracy, and shipwreck, with due gratitude to be rendered on safe arrival or return. In times of great crisis, the [dblookup('Senate of Ancient Rome', 'Authority on Religious Rites') -> decree collective public rites] Senate could decree collective public rites, in which [dblookup('Citizens of Ancient Rome', 'Participation in Religious Processions') -> included women and children] Rome's citizens, including women and children, moved in procession from one temple to the next, supplicating the gods.
examples.text: Religion_in_ancient_Rome: The same divine agencies who caused disease or harm also had the power to avert it, and so might be placated in advance. examples.annotated_text: Heian_period: Poetry, in particular, was a staple of court life. Nobles and ladies-in-waiting were expected to be [dblookup('Heian Period Nobles', 'Skill Expected') -> poetry writing] well versed in the art of writing poetry as a mark of their [dblookup('Heian Period Nobles', 'Social Status Indicator') -> poetry skill] status. Every occasion could call for the writing of a verse, from the birth of a child to the coronation of an emperor, or even a pretty scene of nature. A well-written poem or haiku could easily [dblookup('Heian Period Poetry', 'Social Impact') -> reputation influence] make or break one's reputation, and often was a key part of [dblookup('Heian Period Poetry', 'Role in Society') -> social interaction] social interaction. Almost as important was the choice of [dblookup('Heian Period', 'Cultural Importance') -> calligraphy in poetry] calligraphy, or handwriting, used. The Japanese of this period believed [dblookup('Heian Period Calligraphy', 'Believed Reflection') -> condition of soul] handwriting could reflect the condition of a person's soul: therefore, [dblookup('Heian Period Calligraphy', 'Perception of Poor Writing') -> poor breeding indication] poor or hasty writing could be considered a sign of poor breeding. Whether the script was Chinese or Japanese, good writing and artistic skill was [dblookup('Heian Period', 'Importance of Writing Skill') -> paramount to social reputation] paramount to social reputation when it came to poetry. Sei Shonagon mentions in [dblookup('Sei Shonagon', 'Work Mentioning Calligraphy') -> Pillow Book] her Pillow Book that when a certain courtesan tried to ask her advice about how to write a poem to [dblookup('Empress Sadako', 'Historical Period') -> Heian Period] the empress Sadako, she had to politely rebuke him because his writing was so poor.
examples.text: Heian_period: Poetry, in particular, was a staple of court life. Nobles and ladies-in-waiting were expected to be well versed in the art of writing poetry as a mark of their status. Every occasion could call for the writing of a verse, from the birth of a child to the coronation of an emperor, or even a pretty scene of nature. A well-written poem or haiku could easily make or break one's reputation, and often was a key part of social interaction.Almost as important was the choice of calligraphy, or handwriting, used. The Japanese of this period believed handwriting could reflect the condition of a person's soul: therefore, poor or hasty writing could be considered a sign of poor breeding. Whether the script was Chinese or Japanese, good writing and artistic skill was paramount to social reputation when it came to poetry. Sei Shonagon mentions in her Pillow Book that when a certain courtesan tried to ask her advice about how to write a poem to the empress Sadako, she had to politely rebuke him because his writing was so poor.

examples.text: Raleigh,_North_Carolina: The region also experiences occasional periods of drought, during which the city sometimes has restricted water use by residents. During the late summer and early fall, Raleigh can experience hurricanes. In 1996, Hurricane Fran caused severe damage in the Raleigh area, mostly from falling trees. examples.annotated_text: Nintendo Entertainment System: In Europe and Australia, the system was released to two separate marketing regions. One region consisted of most of mainland Europe (excluding Italy), and distribution there was handled by a number of different companies, with Nintendo responsible for most cartridge releases. Most of this region saw a [dblookup('Nintendo Entertainment System', 'Release Year in Mainland Europe') -> 1986] 1986 release. Mattel handled distribution for the other region, consisting of the United Kingdom, Ireland, Canada, Italy, Australia and New Zealand, starting the [dblookup('Mattel', 'Distribution Start Year') -> 1987] following year. Not until the 1990s did Nintendo's newly created European branch direct distribution throughout Europe.

examples.annotated_text: Kievan_Rus%27: The three brothers— Rurik, [dblookup('Sineus', 'Associated Settlement') -> Beloozero] Sineus, and [dblookup('Truvor', 'Associated Settlement') -> Izborsk] Truvor—established themselves in Novgorod, Beloozero, and Izborsk, respectively. Two of the brothers died, and [dblookup('Rurik', 'Role After Brothers\' Death') -> sole ruler of the territory] Rurik became the sole ruler of the territory and [dblookup('Rurik', 'Dynastic Founder') -> Rurik Dynasty] progenitor of the Rurik Dynasty. A short time later, two of Rurik’s men, [dblookup('Rurik\'s Men', 'Names') -> Askold, Dir] Askold and Dir, asked him for permission to go to Tsargrad (Constantinople). On their way south, they discovered "a small city on a hill," [dblookup('Askold and Dir', 'Captured City') -> Kiev] Kiev, captured it and the surrounding country from the Khazars, populated the region with more [dblookup('Askold and Dir', 'Settler Group') -> Varangians] Varangians, and "established their dominion over the country of the Polyanians."
examples.text: Kievan_Rus%27: The three brothers—Rurik, Sineus, and Truvor—established themselves in Novgorod, Beloozero, and Izborsk, respectively. Two of the brothers died, and Rurik became the sole ruler of the territory and progenitor of the Rurik Dynasty. On their way south, they discovered "a small city on a hill," Kiev, captured it and the surrounding country from the Khazars, populated the region with more Varangians, and "established their dominion over the country of the Polyanians."

examples.annotated_text: Pope_Paul_VI: Pope Paul VI knew the [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Affiliation with Roman Curia') -> Roman Curia] Roman Curia well, having worked there for [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Work Period in Roman Curia') -> 1922 to 1954] a generation from 1922 to 1954. He implemented his [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Reform Implementation') -> in stages] reforms in stages, rather than in one fell swoop. On [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Issued Regulation Date') -> March 1, 1968] 1 March 1968, he issued a regulation, a process that had been initiated by [dblookup('Pius XII', 'Initiated Curia Reform') -> Pius XII] Pius XII and continued by [dblookup('John XXIII', 'Continued Curia Reform') -> John XXIII] John XXIII. On [dblookup('Pontificalis Domus', 'Issued Date') -> March 28, 1968] 28 March, with Pontificalis Domus, and in several additional Apostolic Constitutions in the following years, he revamped the entire Curia, which included [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Curia Reforms Included') -> reduction of bureaucracy, streamlining congregations, broader non-Italian representation] reduction of bureaucracy, streamlining of existing congregations and a broader representation of non-Italians in the curial positions.
examples.text: Pope_Paul_VI: Pope Paul VI knew the Roman Curia well, having worked there for a generation from 1922 to 1954. He implemented his reforms in stages, rather than in one fell swoop. On 1 March 1968, he issued a regulation, a process that had been initiated by Pius XII and continued by John XXIII. On 28 March, with Pontificalis Domus, and in several additional Apostolic Constitutions in the following years, he revamped the entire Curia, which included reduction of bureaucracy, streamlining of existing congregations and a broader representation of non-Italians in the curial positions.

examples.annotated_text: Alsace: The region, as part of Lorraine, was [dblookup('Alsace', 'Historical Affiliation') -> Holy Roman Empire] part of the Holy Roman Empire, and then was gradually [dblookup('Alsace', 'Annexed By') -> France] annexed by France in the [dblookup('Alsace', 'Century of French Annexation') -> 17th century] 17th century, and formalized as one of the [dblookup('Alsace', 'Status in France') -> provinces of France] provinces of France. The Calvinist manufacturing republic of Mulhouse, known as Stadtrepublik Mülhausen, became a part of Alsace after a [dblookup('Mulhouse', 'Integration Date into Alsace') -> January 4, 1798] vote by its citizens on 4 January 1798. Alsace is frequently mentioned with and as part of [dblookup('Alsace', 'Association with') -> Lorraine] Lorraine and the former [dblookup('Alsace', 'Associated Former Duchy') -> Duchy of Lorraine] duchy of Lorraine, since it was a vital part of the duchy, and later because of German possession as the [dblookup('Alsace', 'Imperial Province Name') -> Alsace-Lorraine] imperial province (Alsace-Lorraine, [dblookup('Alsace-Lorraine', 'German Control Period') -> 1871–1918] 1871–1918) was contested in the 19th and 20th centuries. [dblookup('Alsace and Lorraine', 'France-Germany Control Exchanges') -> Four times in 75 years] France and Germany exchanged control of parts of Lorraine (including Alsace) four times in 75 years.
examples.text: Alsace: The region, as part of Lorraine, was part of the Holy Roman Empire, and then was gradually annexed by France in the 17th century, and formalized as one of the provinces of France. The Calvinist manufacturing republic of Mulhouse, known as Stadtrepublik Mülhausen, became a part of Alsace after a vote by its citizens on 4 January 1798. Alsace is frequently mentioned with and as part of Lorraine and the former duchy of Lorraine, since it was a vital part of the duchy, and later because German possession as the imperial province (Alsace-Lorraine, 1871–1918) was contested in the 19th and 20th centuries; France and Germany exchanged control of parts of Lorraine (including Alsace) four times in 75 years.

examples.annotated_text: Armenians: From the 9th to 11th century, Armenian [dblookup('Armenian architecture', 'Revival Period') -> 9th to 11th century] architecture underwent a revival under the patronage of the [dblookup('Armenian architecture', 'Patronage By') -> Bagratid Dynasty] Bagratid Dynasty with a great deal of building done in the area of [dblookup('Armenian architecture', 'Significant Area') -> Lake Van] Lake Van. This included both traditional styles and new innovations. Ornately carved [dblookup('Armenian Khachkars', 'Development Period') -> 9th to 11th century] Armenian Khachkars were developed during this time. Many new cities and churches were built, including a new capital at [dblookup('Bagratid Dynasty', 'New Capital Location') -> Lake Van] Lake Van and a new Cathedral on [dblookup('Bagratid Dynasty', 'Cathedral Location') -> Akdamar Island] Akdamar Island. The Cathedral of Ani was also completed during this dynasty. It was during this time that the first major monasteries, such as [dblookup('Haghpat', 'Construction Period') -> Bagratid Dynasty] Haghpat and [dblookup('Haritchavank', 'Construction Period') -> Bagratid Dynasty] Haritchavank were built. This period was ended by the [dblookup('Seljuk invasion', 'Impact On') -> Armenian architecture revival] Seljuk invasion.
examples.text: Armenians: From the 9th to 11th century, Armenian architecture underwent a revival under the patronage of the Bagratid Dynasty with a great deal of building done in the area of Lake Van, this included both traditional styles and new innovations. Ornately carved Armenian Khachkars were developed during this time. Many new cities and churches were built during this time, including a new capital at Lake Van and a new Cathedral on Akdamar Island to match. The Cathedral of Ani was also completed during this dynasty. It was during this time that the first major monasteries, such as Haghpat and Haritchavank were built. This period was ended by the Seljuk invasion.

examples.annotated_text: Buckingham_Palace: Remodelling of the structure began [dblookup('Buckingham Palace', 'Remodelling Start Year') -> 1762] in 1762. After his accession to the throne in [dblookup('King George IV', 'Accession Year') -> 1820] 1820, King George IV continued the renovation with the idea in mind of a small, comfortable home. While the work was in progress, in 1826, the King decided to modify the house into a palace with the help of his architect [dblookup('Buckingham Palace', 'Architect During George IV Reign') -> John Nash] John Nash. Some furnishings were transferred from [dblookup('Buckingham Palace', 'Furnishings Source') -> Carlton House] Carlton House, and others had been bought in France after the [dblookup('French Revolution', 'Consequences') -> transfer of furnishings] French Revolution. The external façade was designed keeping in mind the [dblookup('Buckingham Palace', 'Design Influence') -> French neo-classical] French neo-classical influence preferred by George IV. The cost of the renovations grew dramatically, and by 1829 the extravagance of Nash's designs resulted in his removal as architect. On the death of George IV in [dblookup('King George IV', 'Death Year') -> 1830] 1830, his younger brother [dblookup('King William IV', 'Role in Buckingham Palace Renovation') -> hired Edward Blore] King William IV hired Edward Blore to finish the work. At one stage, William considered converting the palace into the new Houses of Parliament, after the [dblookup('Palace of Westminster', 'Destruction Year') -> 1834] destruction of the Palace of Westminster by fire in 1834.
examples.text: Buckingham_Palace: Remodelling of the structure began in 1762. After his accession to the throne in 1820, King George IV continued the renovation with the idea in mind of a small, comfortable home. While the work was in progress, in 1826, the King decided to modify the house into a palace with the help of his architect John Nash. Some furnishings were transferred from Carlton House, and others had been bought in France after the French Revolution. The external façade was designed keeping in mind the French neo-classical influence preferred by George IV. The cost of the renovations grew dramatically, and by 1829 the extravagance of Nash's designs resulted in his removal as architect. On the death of George IV in 1830, his younger brother King William IV hired Edward Blore to finish the work. At one stage, William considered converting the palace into the new Houses of Parliament, after the destruction of the Palace of Westminster by fire in 1834.

examples.annotated_text: CDs are susceptible to damage during handling and from environmental exposure. Pits are much closer to the label side of a disc, enabling defects and contaminants on the clear side to be out of focus during playback. Consequently, [dblookup('Compact_disc', 'Damage Prone Area') -> label side] CDs are more likely to suffer damage on the label side of the disc. Scratches on the clear side can be repaired by refilling them with [dblookup('Compact_disc', 'Scratch Repair Methods') -> similar refractive plastic, careful polishing] similar refractive plastic or by careful polishing. The edges of CDs are sometimes incompletely sealed, allowing gases and liquids to corrode the [dblookup('Compact_disc', 'Vulnerable Layer') -> metal reflective layer] metal reflective layer and to interfere with the focus of the laser on the pits. The fungus Geotrichum candidum, found in Belize, has been found to [dblookup('Geotrichum candidum', 'Effect On Compact_disc') -> consume polycarbonate plastic and aluminium] consume the polycarbonate plastic and aluminium found in CDs.
examples.text: Compact_disc: CDs are susceptible to damage during handling and from environmental exposure. Pits are much closer to the label side of a disc, enabling defects and contaminants on the clear side to be out of focus during playback. Consequently, CDs are more likely to suffer damage on the label side of the disc. Scratches on the clear side can be repaired by refilling them with similar refractive plastic or by careful polishing. The edges of CDs are sometimes incompletely sealed, allowing gases and liquids to corrode the metal reflective layer and to interfere with the focus of the laser on the pits. The fungus Geotrichum candidum, found in Belize, has been found to consume the polycarbonate plastic and aluminium found in CDs.

examples.annotated_text: Frédéric_Chopin: Fryderyk may have had some piano instruction from his mother, but his first professional music tutor, from [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Tutored From') -> 1816] 1816 to [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Tutored Until') -> 1821] 1821, was the Czech pianist Wojciech Żywny. His elder sister Ludwika also [dblookup('Ludwika Chopin', 'Music Tutor') -> Wojciech Żywny] took lessons from Żywny, and occasionally played duets with her brother. It quickly became apparent that he was a [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Notable Trait') -> child prodigy] child prodigy. By the age of [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Age Started Public Concerts') -> seven] seven Fryderyk had begun giving public concerts, and in [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Year Composed First Polonaises') -> 1817] 1817 he composed two polonaises, in G minor and B-flat major. His next work, a polonaise in A-flat major of [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Year Composed Polonaise in A-flat major') -> 1821] 1821, dedicated to Żywny, is his [dblookup('Fryderyk Chopin', 'Earliest Surviving Musical Manuscript') -> Polonaise in A-flat major] earliest surviving musical manuscript.
examples.text: Frédéric_Chopin: Fryderyk may have had some piano instruction from his mother, but his first professional music tutor, from 1816 to 1821, was the Czech pianist Wojciech Żywny. His elder sister Ludwika also took lessons from Żywny, and occasionally played duets with her brother. It quickly became apparent that he was a child prodigy. By the age of seven Fryderyk had begun giving public concerts, and in 1817 he composed two polonaises, in G minor and B-flat major. His next work, a polonaise in A-flat major of 1821, dedicated to Żywny, is his earliest surviving musical manuscript.

examples.annotated_text: Affirmative_action_in_the_United_States: In the beginning, racial classifications that identified race were inherently suspect and subject to [dblookup('Racial Classifications', 'Legal Standard') -> strict scrutiny] strict scrutiny. These classifications would only be upheld if [dblookup('Racial Classifications', 'Upheld Condition') -> necessary to promote a compelling governmental interest] necessary to promote a compelling governmental interest. Later the U.S. Supreme Court decided that racial classifications that benefited underrepresented minorities were to only be upheld if necessary and promoted a [dblookup('Racial Classifications Benefitting Minorities', 'Upheld Condition') -> compelling governmental purpose] compelling governmental purpose. (See [dblookup('Richmond v. J.A. Croson Co.', 'Legal Importance') -> Precedent on Racial Classifications] Richmond v. J.A. Croson Co.) There is no clear guidance about when government action is not "compelling", and such rulings are rare.
examples.text: Affirmative_action_in_the_United_States: In the beginning, racial classifications that identified race were inherently suspect and subject to strict scrutiny. These classifications would only be upheld if necessary to promote a compelling governmental interest. Later the U.S. Supreme Court decided that racial classifications that benefited underrepresented minorities were to only be upheld if necessary and promoted a compelling governmental purpose. (See Richmond v. J.A. Croson Co.) There is no clear guidance about when government action is not "compelling", and such rulings are rare.

examples.annotated_text: Myanmar: During [dblookup('Myanmar', 'Involvement in World War II') -> British destruction of infrastructure] World War II, the British destroyed the major government buildings, oil wells and mines for tungsten, tin, lead, and silver to keep them from the Japanese. Myanmar was bombed extensively by both sides. After [dblookup('Myanmar', 'Year of Independence') -> 1948] independence, the country was in ruins with its major infrastructure completely destroyed. After a parliamentary government was formed in 1948, Prime Minister [dblookup('U Nu', 'Prime Ministership Start') -> 1948] U Nu embarked upon a policy of nationalisation and the state was declared the owner of all land. The government also tried to implement a poorly considered [dblookup('Myanmar', 'Economic Plan') -> Eight-Year Plan] Eight-Year plan. By the [dblookup('Myanmar', 'Economic State in 1950s') -> decline in rice and mineral exports] 1950s, rice exports had fallen by two thirds and mineral exports by over 96% (as compared to the pre-World War II period). examples.text: Myanmar: During World War II, the British destroyed the major government buildings, oil wells and mines for tungsten, tin, lead and silver to keep them from the Japanese. Myanmar was bombed extensively by both sides. After independence, the country was in ruins with its major infrastructure completely destroyed. After a parliamentary government was formed in 1948, Prime Minister U Nu embarked upon a policy of nationalisation and the state was declared the owner of all land. The government also tried to implement a poorly considered Eight-Year plan. By the 1950s, rice exports had fallen by two thirds and mineral exports by over 96% (as compared to the pre-World War II period). Plans were partly financed by printing money, which led to inflation.

examples.annotated_text: Political_philosophy: A pair of overlapping political perspectives arising toward the end of the 20th century are republicanism (or neo- or civic-republicanism) and the capability approach. The resurgent republican movement aims to provide an alternate definition of liberty from Isaiah Berlin's positive and negative forms of liberty, namely "liberty as non-domination." Unlike liberals who understand liberty as "non-interference," "non-domination" entails individuals not being subject to the arbitrary will of any other person. To a liberal, a slave who is not interfered with may be free, yet to a republican the mere status as a slave, regardless of how that slave is treated, is objectionable. Prominent republicans include historian Quentin Skinner, jurist Cass Sunstein, and political philosopher Philip Pettit. The [dblookup('Capability Approach', 'Further Developed By') -> Martha Nussbaum] capability approach, pioneered by economists Mahbub ul Haq and Amartya Sen and further developed by legal scholar Martha Nussbaum, understands freedom under allied lines: the real-world ability to act. Both the capability approach and republicanism treat choice as something which must be resourced. In other words, it is not enough to be legally able to do something, but to have the real option of doing it.

examples.annotated_text: Anti-aircraft_warfare: Until the [dblookup('Guided Missiles', 'Became Dominant In Anti-Aircraft Warfare') -> 1950s] 1950s guns firing ballistic munitions were the standard weapon; guided missiles then became dominant, except at the very shortest ranges. examples.annotated_text: Roman_Republic: In [dblookup('Roman Republic', 'Event Year') -> 494 BC] 494 BC, the city was at war with two neighboring tribes. The plebeian soldiers refused to march against the enemy, and instead seceded to the [dblookup('Roman Republic', 'Plebeian Secession Location') -> Aventine Hill] Aventine Hill. The plebeians demanded the right to elect their own officials. The patricians agreed, and the plebeians returned to the battlefield. The plebeians called these new officials "plebeian tribunes". The tribunes would have two assistants, called [dblookup('Tribune Assistants', 'Title') -> plebeian aediles] "plebeian aediles". During the [dblookup('Roman Republic', 'Reforms Century') -> 5th century BC] 5th century BC, a series of reforms were passed. The result of these reforms was that any law passed by the plebeian would have the full force of law. In [dblookup('Roman Republic', 'Censorship Creation Year') -> 443 BC] 443 BC, the censorship was created. From [dblookup('Roman Republic', 'Constitutional Crisis Period') -> 375 BC to 371 BC] 375 BC to 371 BC, the republic experienced a constitutional crisis during which the tribunes used their vetoes to prevent the election of senior magistrates.

The result of these reforms was that any law passed by the plebeian would have the full force of law. In 443 BC, the censorship was created. From 375 BC to 371 BC, the republic experienced a constitutional crisis during which the tribunes used their vetoes to prevent the election of senior magistrates.

examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: Russell's ministry, though Whig, was [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Opinion On Russell\'s Ministry') -> not favoured] not favoured by the Queen. She found particularly offensive the [dblookup('Lord Palmerston', 'Position In Russell\'s Ministry') -> Foreign Secretary] Foreign Secretary, Lord Palmerston, who often acted without consulting the [dblookup('Lord Palmerston', 'Consultative Bodies Ignored') -> Cabinet, Prime Minister, Queen] Cabinet, the Prime Minister, or the Queen. Victoria complained to [dblookup('John Russell', 'Complaints Received From') -> Queen Victoria] Russell that Palmerston sent official dispatches to foreign leaders without her knowledge, but Palmerston was retained in office and continued to act on his own initiative, despite her repeated remonstrances. She found particularly offensive the Foreign Secretary, Lord Palmerston, who often acted without consulting the Cabinet, the Prime Minister, or the Queen. Victoria complained to Russell that Palmerston sent official dispatches to foreign leaders without her knowledge, but Palmerston was retained in office and continued to act on his own initiative, despite her repeated remonstrances. examples.annotated_text: Hellenistic_period: One of the few city states who managed to maintain full independence from the control of any Hellenistic kingdom was Rhodes. With a skilled navy to protect its trade fleets from [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Threat') -> pirates] pirates and an ideal strategic position covering the routes from the east into the Aegean, Rhodes prospered during the [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Period of Prosperity') -> Hellenistic period] Hellenistic period. It became a [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Role') -> center of culture and commerce] center of culture and commerce, its [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Economic Influence') -> coins were widely circulated] coins were widely circulated and its [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Educational Influence') -> philosophical schools] philosophical schools became one of the best in the Mediterranean. After holding out for one year under siege by [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Besieger') -> Demetrius Poliorcetes] Demetrius Poliorcetes (304-305 BCE), the Rhodians built the [dblookup('Rhodians', 'Commemorative Structure') -> Colossus of Rhodes] Colossus of Rhodes to commemorate their victory. They retained their independence by the maintenance of a [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Military Strength') -> powerful navy] powerful navy, by maintaining a carefully [dblookup('Rhodes', 'Diplomatic Policy') -> neutral posture] neutral posture and acting to preserve the balance of power between the major Hellenistic kingdoms.
examples.text: Hellenistic_period: One of the few city states who managed to maintain full independence from the control of any Hellenistic kingdom was Rhodes. With a skilled navy to protect its trade fleets from pirates and an ideal strategic position covering the routes from the east into the Aegean, Rhodes prospered during the Hellenistic period. It became a center of culture and commerce, its coins were widely circulated and its philosophical schools became one of the best in the mediterranean. After holding out for one year under siege by Demetrius Poliorcetes (304-305 BCE), the Rhodians built the Colossus of Rhodes to commemorate their victory. They retained their independence by the maintenance of a powerful navy, by maintaining a carefully neutral posture and acting to preserve the balance of power between the major Hellenistic kingdoms.

examples.annotated_text: Buddhism: Suffering ([dblookup('Dukkha', 'Pāli Term') -> दुक्ख dukkha], [dblookup('Dukkha', 'Sanskrit Term') -> दुःख duḥkha] Pāli: दुक्ख dukkha; Sanskrit दुःख duḥkha) is also a central concept in [dblookup('Buddhism', 'Central Concept') -> Suffering] Buddhism. The word roughly corresponds to a number of terms in English including suffering, pain, unsatisfactoriness, sorrow, affliction, anxiety, dissatisfaction, discomfort, anguish, stress, misery, and frustration. Although the term is often translated as "suffering", its philosophical meaning is more analogous to "disquietude" as in the condition of being disturbed. As such, "suffering" is too narrow a translation with [dblookup('Dukkha', 'Translation Issues') -> negative emotional connotations] "negative emotional connotations" that can give the impression that the Buddhist view is pessimistic, but [dblookup('Buddhism', 'Perspective on View') -> seeks to be realistic] Buddhism seeks to be neither pessimistic nor optimistic, but realistic. In English-language [dblookup('Buddhist Literature', 'Translation Practice') -> often untranslated] Buddhist literature translated from Pāli, "dukkha" is often left untranslated, so as to encompass its full range of meaning.
examples.text: Buddhism: Suffering (Pāli: दुक्ख dukkha; Sanskrit दुःख duḥkha) is also a central concept in Buddhism. The word roughly corresponds to a number of terms in English including suffering, pain, unsatisfactoriness, sorrow, affliction, anxiety, dissatisfaction, discomfort, anguish, stress, misery, and frustration. Although the term is often translated as "suffering", its philosophical meaning is more analogous to "disquietude" as in the condition of being disturbed. As such, "suffering" is too narrow a translation with "negative emotional connotations"[web 9] that can give the impression that the Buddhist view is pessimistic, but Buddhism seeks to be neither pessimistic nor optimistic, but realistic. In English-language Buddhist literature translated from Pāli, "dukkha" is often left untranslated, so as to encompass its full range of meaning.[note 8]

examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: Victoria was physically unprepossessing—she was [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Height') -> no more than five feet tall] stout, dowdy and no more than five feet tall—but she succeeded in projecting a grand image. She experienced [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Public Perception During Widowhood') -> unpopularity] unpopularity during the first years of her widowhood, but was [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Public Perception in 1880s-1890s') -> well liked] well liked during the 1880s and 1890s, when she embodied the empire as a benevolent matriarchal figure. Only after the release of her diary and letters did the extent of her political influence become known to the wider public. Biographies of Victoria written before much of the primary material became available, such as Lytton Strachey's [dblookup('Lytton Strachey', 'Work on Queen Victoria') -> Queen Victoria] Queen Victoria of 1921, are now considered [dblookup('Queen Victoria (by Lytton Strachey)', 'Current Status') -> out of date] out of date. The biographies written by [dblookup('Elizabeth Longford', 'Work on Queen Victoria') -> Biography written in 1964] Elizabeth Longford and [dblookup('Cecil Woodham-Smith', 'Work on Queen Victoria') -> Biography written in 1972] Cecil Woodham-Smith, in 1964 and 1972 respectively, are still widely admired. They, and others, conclude that as a person Victoria was [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Personal Traits') -> emotional, obstinate, honest, and straight-talking] emotional, obstinate, honest, and straight-talking.
examples.text: Queen_Victoria: Victoria was physically unprepossessing—she was stout, dowdy and no more than five feet tall—but she succeeded in projecting a grand image. She experienced unpopularity during the first years of her widowhood, but was well liked during the 1880s and 1890s, when she embodied the empire as a benevolent matriarchal figure. Only after the release of her diary and letters did the extent of her political influence become known to the wider public. Biographies of Victoria written before much of the primary material became available, such as Lytton Strachey's Queen Victoria of 1921, are now considered out of date. The biographies written by Elizabeth Longford and Cecil Woodham-Smith, in 1964 and 1972 respectively, are still widely admired. They, and others, conclude that as a person Victoria was emotional, obstinate, honest, and straight-talking.

examples.annotated_text: Nintendo Entertainment System: For its complete North American release, the Nintendo Entertainment System [dblookup('Nintendo Entertainment System', 'North American Release Bundles') -> Deluxe Set, Control Deck, Action Set, Power Set] was progressively released over the ensuing years in four different bundles: the Deluxe Set, the Control Deck, the Action Set and the Power Set. The [dblookup('Deluxe Set', 'Retail Price') -> US$199.99] Deluxe Set, retailing at US$199.99 (equivalent to $475 in 2016), included [dblookup('Deluxe Set', 'Components Included') -> R.O.B., NES Zapper, two controllers, Gyromite, Duck Hunt] R.O.B., a light gun called the NES Zapper, two controllers, and two Game Paks: Gyromite, and Duck Hunt. The Basic Set, retailing at [dblookup('Basic Set', 'Retail Price Without Game') -> US$89.99] US$89.99 with no game, and [dblookup('Basic Set', 'Retail Price With Super Mario Bros.') -> US$99.99] US$99.99 bundled with "Super Mario Bros." The [dblookup('Action Set', 'Retail Price') -> US$149.99] Action Set, retailing in 1988 for US$149.99, came with [dblookup('Action Set', 'Components Included') -> Control Deck, two game controllers, NES Zapper, Super Mario Bros., Duck Hunt] the Control Deck, two game controllers, an NES Zapper, and a dual Game Pak containing both Super Mario Bros. and Duck Hunt. In [dblookup('Power Set', 'Release Year') -> 1989] 1989, the Power Set included [dblookup('Power Set', 'Components Included') -> console, two game controllers, NES Zapper, Power Pad, Super Mario Bros, Duck Hunt, World Class Track Meet] the console, two game controllers, a NES Zapper, a Power Pad, and a triple Game Pak containing Super Mario Bros, Duck Hunt, and World Class Track Meet. In [dblookup('Sports Set', 'Release Year') -> 1990] 1990, a Sports Set bundle was released, including [dblookup('Sports Set', 'Components Included') -> console, NES Satellite, four game controllers, Super Spike V'Ball, Nintendo World Cup] the console, an NES Satellite infrared wireless multitap adapter, four game controllers, and a dual Game Pak containing Super Spike V'Ball and Nintendo World Cup. Two more bundle packages were later released using the original model NES console. The [dblookup('Challenge Set', 'Release Year') -> 1992] Challenge Set of 1992 included the console, two controllers, and a [dblookup('Challenge Set', 'Game Included') -> Super Mario Bros. 3] Super Mario Bros. 3 Game Pak for a [dblookup('Challenge Set', 'Retail Price') -> US$89.99] retail price of US$89.99. The Basic Set, first released in [dblookup('Basic Set', 'First Release Year') -> 1987] 1987, was repackaged for a retail US$89.99. It included only [dblookup('Repackaged Basic Set', 'Components Included') -> console, two controllers, Official Nintendo Player's Guide] the console and two controllers, and no longer was bundled with a cartridge. examples.text: Nintendo_Entertainment_System: For its complete North American release, the Nintendo Entertainment System was progressively released over the ensuing years in four different bundles: the Deluxe Set, the Control Deck, the Action Set and the Power Set. The Deluxe Set, retailing at US$199.99 (equivalent to $475 in 2016), included R.O.B., a light gun called the NES Zapper, two controllers, and two Game Paks: Gyromite, and Duck Hunt. The Basic Set, retailing at US$89.99 with no game, and US$99.99 bundled with "Super Mario Bros." The Action Set, retailing in 1988 for US$149.99, came with the Control Deck, two game controllers, an NES Zapper, and a dual Game Pak containing both Super Mario Bros. and Duck Hunt. In 1989, the Power Set included the console, two game controllers, a NES Zapper, a Power Pad, and a triple Game Pak containing Super Mario Bros, Duck Hunt, and World Class Track Meet. In 1990, a Sports Set bundle was released, including the console, an NES Satellite infrared wireless multitap adapter, four game controllers, and a dual Game Pak containing Super Spike V'Ball and Nintendo World Cup. Two more bundle packages were later released using the original model NES console. The Challenge Set of 1992 included the console, two controllers, and a Super Mario Bros. 3 Game Pak for a retail price of US$89.99. The Basic Set, first released in 1987, was repackaged for a retail US$89.99. It included only the console and two controllers, and no longer was bundled with a cartridge. Instead, it contained a book called the Official Nintendo Player's Guide, which contained detailed information for every NES game made up to that point.

examples.annotated_text: Asthma: Asthma is [dblookup('Asthma', 'Characterized By') -> recurrent episodes of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, coughing] characterized by recurrent episodes of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing. Sputum may be produced from the lung by coughing but is often hard to bring up. During recovery from an attack, it may appear pus-like due to [dblookup('Asthma', 'Caused By') -> high levels of eosinophils] high levels of white blood cells called eosinophils. Symptoms are usually [dblookup('Asthma', 'Symptom Timing') -> worse at night and early morning] worse at night and in the early morning or in response to exercise or cold air. Some people with asthma rarely experience symptoms, usually [dblookup('Asthma', 'Symptom Trigger') -> specific triggers] in response to triggers, whereas others may have marked and persistent symptoms.
examples.text: Asthma: Asthma is characterized by recurrent episodes of wheezing, shortness of breath, chest tightness, and coughing. Sputum may be produced from the lung by coughing but is often hard to bring up. During recovery from an attack, it may appear pus-like due to high levels of white blood cells called eosinophils. Symptoms are usually worse at night and in the early morning or in response to exercise or cold air. Some people with asthma rarely experience symptoms, usually in response to triggers, whereas others may have marked and persistent symptoms.

examples.annotated_text: Department_store: Ireland developed a strong middle class, especially in the major cities, by the mid-nineteenth century. They were active patrons of department stores. Delany's New Mart was [dblookup('Delany\'s New Mart', 'Opening Year') -> 1853] opened in 1853 in [dblookup('Delany\'s New Mart', 'Location') -> Dublin, Ireland] Dublin, Ireland. Unlike others, Delany's had not evolved gradually from a smaller shop on site. Thus it could claim to be [dblookup('Delany\'s New Mart', 'Significance') -> first purpose-built department store in the world] the first purpose-built department store in the world. The word department store had not been invented at that time and thus it was called the "Monster House". The store was completely [dblookup('Delany\'s New Mart', 'Destruction Year') -> 1916] destroyed in the 1916 Easter Rising, but [dblookup('Delany\'s New Mart', 'Reopening Year') -> 1922] reopened in 1922.
examples.text: Department_store: Ireland developed a strong middle class, especially in the major cities, by the mid-nineteenth century. They were active patrons of department stores. Delany's New Mart was opened in 1853 in Dublin, Ireland. Unlike others, Delany's had not evolved gradually from a smaller shop on site. Thus it could claim to be the first purpose-built Department Store in the world. The word department store had not been invented at that time and thus it was called the "Monster House". The store was completely destroyed in the 1916 Easter Rising, but reopened in 1922.

examples.annotated_text: Napoleon: The initial [dblookup('Napoleonic Wars', 'Campaign Start Date 1806') -> September 1806] military maneuvers began in September 1806. In a notable letter to Marshal Soult detailing the plan for the campaign, Napoleon described the essential features of [dblookup('Napoleon', 'Warfare Strategy') -> Napoleonic warfare] Napoleonic warfare and introduced the phrase [dblookup('Napoleon', 'Introduced Phrase') -> le bataillon-carré] le bataillon-carré ('square battalion'). In the bataillon-carré system, the various corps of the [dblookup('Grande Armée', 'System Used During') -> bataillon-carré] Grande Armée would march uniformly together in close supporting distance. Napoleon invaded Prussia with [dblookup('Napoleon', 'Troop Count in 1806 Invasion') -> 180,000] 180,000 troops, rapidly marching on the right bank of the River Saale. As in previous campaigns, his fundamental objective was to destroy one opponent before reinforcements from another could tip the balance of the war. Upon learning the whereabouts of the Prussian army, the French swung westwards and crossed the Saale with overwhelming force. At the twin battles of [dblookup('Battle of Jena and Auerstedt', 'Date') -> 14 October 1806] Jena and Auerstedt, fought on 14 October, the French convincingly defeated the Prussians and inflicted heavy casualties. With several major commanders dead or incapacitated, the Prussian king proved incapable of effectively commanding the army, which began to quickly disintegrate. In a vaunted pursuit that epitomized the "peak of Napoleonic warfare," according to historian Richard Brooks, the [dblookup('France', 'Captured Soldiers in 1806') -> 140,000] French managed to capture 140,000 soldiers, over [dblookup('France', 'Captured Cannons in 1806') -> 2,000] 2,000 cannons and hundreds of ammunition wagons, all in a single month. Historian David Chandler wrote of the Prussian forces: "Never has the morale of any army been more completely shattered." examples.text: Napoleon: The initial military maneuvers began in September 1806. In a notable letter to Marshal Soult detailing the plan for the campaign, Napoleon described the essential features of Napoleonic warfare and introduced the phrase le bataillon-carré ('square battalion'). In the bataillon-carré system, the various corps of the Grande Armée would march uniformly together in close supporting distance. If any single corps was attacked, the others could quickly spring into action and arrive to help. Napoleon invaded Prussia with 180,000 troops, rapidly marching on the right bank of the River Saale. As in previous campaigns, his fundamental objective was to destroy one opponent before reinforcements from another could tip the balance of the war. Upon learning the whereabouts of the Prussian army, the French swung westwards and crossed the Saale with overwhelming force. At the twin battles of Jena and Auerstedt, fought on 14 October, the French convincingly defeated the Prussians and inflicted heavy casualties. With several major commanders dead or incapacitated, the Prussian king proved incapable of effectively commanding the army, which began to quickly disintegrate. In a vaunted pursuit that epitomized the "peak of Napoleonic warfare," according to historian Richard Brooks, the French managed to capture 140,000 soldiers, over 2,000 cannons and hundreds of ammunition wagons, all in a single month. Historian David Chandler wrote of the Prussian forces: "Never has the morale of any army been more completely shattered." Despite their overwhelming defeat, the Prussians refused to negotiate with the French until the Russians had an opportunity to enter the fight.

examples.annotated_text: Flowering_plant: The apparently sudden appearance of nearly modern flowers in the fossil record initially posed such a problem for the [dblookup('Theory of Evolution', 'Challenges Mentioned By') -> Charles Darwin] theory of evolution that it was called an "abominable mystery" by Charles Darwin. However, the fossil record has considerably grown since the time of Darwin, and recently discovered angiosperm fossils such as [dblookup('Archaefructus', 'Relation To') -> angiosperms] Archaefructus, along with further discoveries of fossil gymnosperms, suggest how angiosperm characteristics may have been acquired in a series of steps. Several groups of extinct gymnosperms, in particular seed ferns, have been proposed as the ancestors of flowering plants, but there is no continuous fossil evidence showing exactly how flowers evolved. Some older fossils, such as the upper Triassic [dblookup('Sanmiguelia', 'Period') -> Triassic] Sanmiguelia, have been suggested. Based on current evidence, some propose that the ancestors of the angiosperms diverged from an unknown group of gymnosperms in the [dblookup('Angiosperms', 'Divergence Period') -> Triassic period] Triassic period (245–202 million years ago). Fossil angiosperm-like pollen from the [dblookup('Angiosperm-like Pollen', 'Origin Period') -> Middle Triassic] Middle Triassic (247.2–242.0 Ma) suggests an older date for their origin. A close relationship between [dblookup('Angiosperms', 'Proposed Relationship') -> gnetophytes] angiosperms and gnetophytes, proposed on the basis of morphological evidence, has more recently been disputed on the basis of molecular evidence that suggest gnetophytes are instead more closely related to other [dblookup('Gnetophytes', 'Relation To') -> gymnosperms] gymnosperms.

However, the fossil record has considerably grown since the time of Darwin, and recently discovered angiosperm fossils such as Archaefructus, along with further discoveries of fossil gymnosperms, suggest how angiosperm characteristics may have been acquired in a series of steps. Several groups of extinct gymnosperms, in particular seed ferns, have been proposed as the ancestors of flowering plants, but there is no continuous fossil evidence showing exactly how flowers evolved. Some older fossils, such as the upper Triassic Sanmiguelia, have been suggested. Based on current evidence, some propose that the ancestors of the angiosperms diverged from an unknown group of gymnosperms in the Triassic period (245–202 million years ago). Fossil angiosperm-like pollen from the Middle Triassic (247.2–242.0 Ma) suggests an older date for their origin. A close relationship between angiosperms and gnetophytes, proposed on the basis of morphological evidence, has more recently been disputed on the basis of molecular evidence that suggest gnetophytes are instead more closely related to other gymnosperms.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Iran: In [dblookup('Iran', 'Name Change Year') -> 1935] 1935, Reza Shah requested the international community to refer to the country by its native name, [dblookup('Iran', 'Native Name') -> Iran] Iran. As the New York Times explained at the time, "At the suggestion of the Persian Legation in Berlin, the Tehran government, on the Persian New Year, Nowruz, March 21, 1935, substituted [dblookup('Iran', 'Official Name Change From') -> Persia] Iran for Persia as the official name of the country." Opposition to the name change led to the reversal of the decision, and [dblookup('Ehsan Yarshater', 'Role') -> Editor of Encyclopædia Iranica] Professor Ehsan Yarshater, editor of Encyclopædia Iranica, propagated a move to use Persia and Iran interchangeably. examples.annotated_text: Memory: Stress has a significant effect on memory formation and learning. In response to stressful situations, the brain releases [dblookup('Stress', 'Associated Hormones and Neurotransmitters') -> glucocorticoids, catecholamines] hormones and neurotransmitters (ex. glucocorticoids and catecholamines) which affect memory encoding processes in the [dblookup('Stress', 'Effect Location') -> Hippocampus] hippocampus. Behavioural research on animals shows that [dblookup('Chronic Stress', 'Effect On') -> Adrenal Hormones Production, Hippocampal Structure in Rats] chronic stress produces adrenal hormones which impact the hippocampal structure in the brains of rats. An experimental study by German cognitive psychologists L. Schwabe and O. Wolf demonstrates how learning under stress also decreases memory recall in humans. In this study, [dblookup('L. Schwabe and O. Wolf Study', 'Sample Size and Characteristics') -> 48 healthy female and male university students] 48 healthy female and male university students participated in either a stress test or a control group. Those randomly assigned to the stress test group had a hand immersed in ice cold water (the reputable SECPT or ‘Socially Evaluated Cold Pressor Test’) for up to three minutes, while being monitored and videotaped. Both the stress and control groups were then presented with [dblookup('L. Schwabe and O. Wolf Study', 'Number Of Words Presented') -> 32 words] 32 words to memorize. Twenty-four hours later, both groups were tested to see how many words they could remember (free recall) as well as how many they could recognize from a larger list of words (recognition performance). The results showed a [dblookup('L. Schwabe and O. Wolf Study', 'Stress Group Recall Decrease') -> 30%] clear impairment of memory performance in the stress test group, who recalled 30% fewer words than the control group. The researchers suggest that [dblookup('Stress During Learning', 'Effect') -> Distracts People, Diverts Attention During Encoding] stress experienced during learning distracts people by diverting their attention during the memory encoding process.
examples.text: Memory: Stress has a significant effect on memory formation and learning. In response to stressful situations, the brain releases hormones and neurotransmitters (ex. glucocorticoids and catecholamines) which affect memory encoding processes in the hippocampus. Behavioural research on animals shows that chronic stress produces adrenal hormones which impact the hippocampal structure in the brains of rats. An experimental study by German cognitive psychologists L. Schwabe and O. Wolf demonstrates how learning under stress also decreases memory recall in humans. In this study, 48 healthy female and male university students participated in either a stress test or a control group. Those randomly assigned to the stress test group had a hand immersed in ice cold water (the reputable SECPT or ‘Socially Evaluated Cold Pressor Test’) for up to three minutes, while being monitored and videotaped. Both the stress and control groups were then presented with 32 words to memorize. Twenty-four hours later, both groups were tested to see how many words they could remember (free recall) as well as how many they could recognize from a larger list of words (recognition performance). The results showed a clear impairment of memory performance in the stress test group, who recalled 30% fewer words than the control group. The researchers suggest that stress experienced during learning distracts people by diverting their attention during the memory encoding process.

examples.annotated_text: Department_store: Although there were a number of department stores in Australia for much of the 20th Century, including chains such as Grace Bros. and Waltons, many disappeared during the 1980s and 1990s. Today Myer and David Jones, located nationally, are practically the national department stores duopoly in [dblookup('Myer', 'Market') -> Australia] Australia. When Russian-born migrant, [dblookup('Sidney Myer', 'Country of Origin') -> Russia] Sidney Myer, came to Australia in 1899 he formed [dblookup('Sidney Myer', 'Co-Founder') -> Elcon Myer] the Myer retail group with his brother, Elcon Myer. In [dblookup('Myer Department Store', 'First Store Opening Year') -> 1900] 1900, they opened the first Myer department store, in [dblookup('Myer Department Store', 'First Store Location') -> Bendigo, Victoria] Bendigo, Victoria. Since then, the Myer retail group has grown to be [dblookup('Myer', 'Significance in Australia') -> largest retailer] Australia's largest retailer. Both, [dblookup('Myer', 'Market Position') -> up-market] Myer and David Jones, are up-market chains, offering a wide variety of products from mid-range names to luxury brands. Other retail chain stores such as [dblookup('Target Australia', 'Relation to American Target') -> Unrelated] Target (unrelated to the American chain of the same name), Venture (now defunct), Kmart and [dblookup('Big W', 'Type') -> discount department store] Big W, also located nationally, are considered to be Australia's discount department stores. Harris Scarfe, though only operating in four states and one territory, is a department store using both the large full-line and small discount department store formats. Most department stores in Australia have their own [dblookup('Australian Department Store', 'Credit Card Offering') -> own credit card companies] credit card companies, each having their own benefits while the discount department stores do not have their own credit card rights.
examples.text: Department_store: Although there were a number of department stores in Australia for much of the 20th Century, including chains such as Grace Bros. and Waltons, many disappeared during the 1980s and 1990s. Today Myer and David Jones, located nationally, are practically the national department stores duopoly in Australia. When Russian-born migrant, Sidney Myer, came to Australia in 1899 he formed the Myer retail group with his brother, Elcon Myer. In 1900, they opened the first Myer department store, in Bendigo, Victoria. Since then, the Myer retail group has grown to be Australia's largest retailer. Both, Myer and David Jones, are up-market chains, offering a wide variety of products from mid-range names to luxury brands. Other retail chain stores such as Target (unrelated to the American chain of the same name), Venture (now defunct), Kmart and Big W, also located nationally, are considered to be Australia's discount department stores. Harris Scarfe, though only operating in four states and one territory, is a department store using both the large full-line and small discount department store formats. Most department stores in Australia have their own credit card companies, each having their own benefits while the discount department stores do not have their own credit card rights.

examples.annotated_text: Qing_dynasty: As the years went by, the three feudal lords and their extensive territories became increasingly autonomous. Finally, in [dblookup('Shang Kexi', 'Petitioned Year') -> 1673] 1673, Shang Kexi petitioned [dblookup('Kangxi Emperor', 'Reign Period') -> 1661-1722] Kangxi for permission to retire to his hometown in Liaodong province and nominated his son as his successor. The young emperor granted his retirement, but denied the heredity of his fief. In reaction, the two other generals decided to petition for their own retirements to test Kangxi's resolve, thinking that he would not risk offending them. The move backfired as the young emperor called their bluff by accepting their requests and [dblookup('Kangxi Emperor', 'Decision on Feudatories') -> ordered the reversion of three fiefdoms to the crown] ordering that all three fiefdoms to be reverted to the crown.

[dblookup('Paul D. MacLean', 'Claim Regarding Emotion and Instinct') -> Emotion competes with more instinctive responses and abstract reasoning] Paul D. MacLean claims that emotion competes with even more instinctive responses, on one hand, and the more abstract reasoning, on the other hand. LeDoux', 'Significant Contributions') -> Neurological advances in emotion research in the 1990s] 1990s by Joseph E. LeDoux and [dblookup('António Damásio', 'Significant Contributions') -> Neurological advances in emotion research in the 1990s] António Damásio.

examples.text: Punjab,_Pakistan: Punjab has the largest economy in Pakistan, contributing most to the national GDP. The province's economy has quadrupled since 1972. examples.annotated_text: Appalachian_Mountains: The Appalachian belt includes, with the ranges enumerated above, the plateaus sloping southward to the Atlantic Ocean in New England, and south-eastward to the border of the coastal plain through the central and southern Atlantic states; and on the north-west, [dblookup('Appalachian Mountains', 'Plateaus Included') -> Allegheny Plateau, Cumberland Plateau] the Allegheny and Cumberland plateaus declining toward [dblookup('Appalachian Mountains', 'Geographical Feature Reached') -> Great Lakes, interior plains] the Great Lakes and the interior plains. A remarkable feature of the belt is the longitudinal chain of broad valleys, including [dblookup('Appalachian Mountains', 'Notable Valley') -> The Great Appalachian Valley] The Great Appalachian Valley, which in the southerly sections divides the mountain system into two unequal portions, but in the northernmost lies west of all the ranges possessing typical Appalachian features, and separates them from the [dblookup('Appalachian Mountains', 'Separated From') -> Adirondack group] Adirondack group. The mountain system has no axis of dominating altitudes, but in every portion the summits rise to rather uniform heights, and, especially in the central section, the various ridges and intermontane valleys have the same trend as the system itself. None of the summits reaches [dblookup('Appalachian Mountains', 'Summits Reaching Perpetual Snow') -> None] the region of perpetual snow.

examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: On 14 January 1858, an Italian refugee from Britain called Orsini attempted to assassinate [dblookup('Napoleon III', 'Assassination Attempted By') -> Orsini] Napoleon III with a bomb made in England. [dblookup('Edward Smith-Stanley, 14th Earl of Derby', 'Prime Minister Term Reinstatement') -> Post-Palmerston resignation] Derby was reinstated as prime minister. [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Visited Location on August 5, 1858') -> French military port of Cherbourg] Victoria and Albert attended the opening of a new basin at the French military port of Cherbourg on 5 August 1858, in an attempt by [dblookup('Napoleon III', 'Reassurance Attempt for Britain') -> Military preparations directed elsewhere] Napoleon III to reassure Britain that his military preparations were directed elsewhere. examples.text: Queen_Victoria: On 14 January 1858, an Italian refugee from Britain called Orsini attempted to assassinate Napoleon III with a bomb made in England. examples.annotated_text: Russian_Soviet_Federative_Socialist_Republic: On December 24, Yeltsin informed the Secretary-General of the United Nations that by agreement of the member states of the CIS [dblookup('Russian Federation', 'Assumed UN Membership From') -> Soviet Union] Russian Federation would assume the membership of the Soviet Union in all UN organs (including permanent membership in the UN Security Council). On December 25—just hours after [dblookup('Mikhail Gorbachev', 'Resigned As President') -> December 25, 1991] Gorbachev resigned as president of the Soviet Union—the Russian SFSR was renamed the [dblookup('Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic', 'Renamed To') -> Russian Federation] Russian Federation (Russia), reflecting that it was now a [dblookup('Russian Federation', 'Became Sovereign State Date') -> December 25, 1991] sovereign state with Yeltsin assuming the [dblookup('Boris Yeltsin', 'Assumed Position Date') -> December 25, 1991] Presidency. examples.text: Russian_Soviet_Federative_Socialist_Republic: On December 24, Yeltsin informed the Secretary-General of the United Nations that by agreement of the member states of the CIS Russian Federation would assume the membership of the Soviet Union in all UN organs (including permanent membership in the UN Security Council). examples.annotated_text: Emotion: Emotions can motivate social interactions and relationships and therefore are directly related with basic physiology, particularly with the [dblookup('Emotions', 'Associated System') -> stress systems] stress systems. This is important because emotions are related to the anti-stress complex, with an oxytocin-attachment system, which plays a major role in bonding. Emotional phenotype temperaments affect social connectedness and fitness in complex social systems (Kurt Kortschal 2013). These characteristics are shared with other species and taxa and are due to the effects of genes and their continuous transmission. Information that is encoded in the DNA sequences provides the blueprint for assembling proteins that make up our cells. Zygotes require genetic information from their [dblookup('Zygotes', 'Require Genetic Information From') -> parental germ cells] parental germ cells, and at every speciation event, heritable traits that have enabled its ancestor to survive and reproduce successfully are passed down along with new traits that could be potentially beneficial to the offspring. In the five million years since [dblookup('Modern Humans and Chimpanzees', 'Genetic Split Time') -> five million years ago] the lineages leading to modern humans and chimpanzees split, only about [dblookup('Human-Chimpanzee Genetic Difference', 'Genetic Material Difference') -> 1.2%] 1.2% of their genetic material has been modified. This suggests that everything that separates us from chimpanzees must be encoded in that very small amount of DNA, including our behaviors. Students that study animal behaviors have only identified intraspecific examples of gene-dependent behavioral phenotypes. In voles (Microtus spp.) [dblookup('Microtus spp.', 'Genetic Differences') -> vasopressin receptor gene] minor genetic differences have been identified in a vasopressin receptor gene that corresponds to major species differences in social organization and the mating system (Hammock & Young 2005). Another potential example with behavioral differences is the FOCP2 gene, which is involved in neural circuitry handling speech and language (Vargha-Khadem et al. 2005). Its present form in humans [dblookup('FOCP2 Gene', 'Human-Chimpanzee Comparison') -> few mutations] differed from that of the chimpanzees by only a few mutations and has been present for about [dblookup('FOCP2 Gene', 'Presence Duration') -> 200,000 years] 200,000 years, coinciding with the beginning of modern humans (Enard et al. 2002). Speech, language, and social organization are all part of the basis for emotions.

The tribe eventually [dblookup('Banu Qaynuqa', 'Surrender To') -> Muhammad] surrendered to Muhammad, who initially wanted to kill the members of Banu Qaynuqa but ultimately yielded to [dblookup('Abdullah ibn Ubayy', 'Influence On') -> Expulsion of Banu Qaynuqa] Abdullah ibn Ubayy's insistence and agreed to expel the Qaynuqa.

examples.annotated_text: Roman_Republic: By [dblookup('First Triumvirate', 'Formation Year') -> 59 BC] 59 BC an unofficial political alliance known as the First Triumvirate was formed between [dblookup('First Triumvirate', 'Members') -> Gaius Julius Caesar, Marcus Licinius Crassus, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus] Gaius Julius Caesar, Marcus Licinius Crassus, and Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus ("Pompey the Great") to share power and influence. After initial successes, he marched his army deep into the desert; but here his army was cut off deep in enemy territory, surrounded and slaughtered at the [dblookup('Battle of Carrhae', 'Outcome') -> Roman defeat] Battle of Carrhae in which Crassus himself perished. The death of Crassus removed some of the balance in the [dblookup('First Triumvirate', 'Dissolution Cause') -> Death of Crassus] Triumvirate and, consequently, Caesar and Pompey began to move apart. While Caesar was fighting in [dblookup('Gaius Julius Caesar', 'Military Campaign Region') -> Gaul] Gaul, Pompey proceeded with a legislative agenda for Rome that revealed that he was at best ambivalent towards Caesar and perhaps now covertly allied with Caesar's political enemies. In [dblookup('Roman Senate', 'Demand Year Against Caesar') -> 51 BC] 51 BC, some Roman senators demanded that Caesar not be permitted to stand for consul unless he turned over control of his armies to the state, which would have left Caesar defenseless before his enemies.
