examples.annotated_text: Antarctica: Antarctica is [dblookup('Antarctica', 'Temperature Compared To Arctic') -> colder] colder than the Arctic for three reasons. First, much of the continent is [dblookup('Antarctica', 'Average Elevation Above Sea Level') -> more than 3,000 m (9,800 ft)] more than 3,000 m (9,800 ft) above sea level, and temperature decreases with elevation in the troposphere. Second, the Arctic Ocean covers the north polar zone: the ocean's [dblookup('Arctic Ocean', 'Temperature Influence') -> relative warmth] relative warmth is transferred through the icepack and prevents temperatures in the Arctic regions from reaching the extremes typical of the land surface of Antarctica. Third, the Earth is at [dblookup('Earth', 'Aphelion Occurrence Month') -> July] aphelion in July (i.e., the Earth is farthest from the Sun in the Antarctic winter), and the Earth is at [dblookup('Earth', 'Perihelion Occurrence Month') -> January] perihelion in January (i.e., the Earth is closest to the Sun in the Antarctic summer). The orbital distance contributes to a [dblookup('Antarctica', 'Winter Temperature Compared To Summer') -> colder] colder Antarctic winter (and a warmer Antarctic summer) but the first two effects have more impact.

examples.annotated_text: Montevideo: [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Named After') -> José Batlle y Ordóñez] Parque Batlle is named in honour of José Batlle y Ordóñez, [dblookup('José Batlle y Ordóñez', 'Presidency Period') -> 1911 to 1915] President of Uruguay from 1911 to 1915. The park was originally proposed by an Act of March 1907, which also projected wide boulevards and avenues. [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Landscape Architect') -> Carlos Thays] French landscape architect, Carlos Thays, began the plantings in [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Plantings Began') -> 1911] 1911. In 1918, the park was [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Name In 1918') -> Parque de los Aliados] named Parque de los Aliados, following the victory of the Allies of World War I. On [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Renaming Date') -> 5 May 1930] 5 May 1930, after significant expansion, it was again renamed as [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Name In 1930') -> Parque Batlle y Ordóñez] Parque Batlle y Ordóñez, in memory of the prominent politician and president, who had [dblookup('José Batlle y Ordóñez', 'Death Year') -> 1929] died in 1929. The park was designated a [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Historic Monument Designation') -> National Historic Monument Park] National Historic Monument Park in 1975. As of [dblookup('Parque Batlle', 'Area As Of 2010') -> 60 hectares (150 acres)] 2010, the park covers an area of 60 hectares (150 acres) and is considered the "lung" of the Montevideo city due to the large variety of trees planted here.
examples.text: Montevideo: Parque Batlle is named in honour of José Batlle y Ordóñez, President of Uruguay from 1911 to 1915. The park was originally proposed by an Act of March 1907, which also projected wide boulevards and avenues. French landscape architect, Carlos Thays, began the plantings in 1911. In 1918, the park was named Parque de los Aliados, following the victory of the Allies of World War I. On 5 May 1930, after significant expansion, it was again renamed as Parque Batlle y Ordóñez, in memory of the prominent politician and president, who had died in 1929. The park was designated a National Historic Monument Park in 1975. As of 2010[update], the park covers an area of 60 hectares (150 acres) and is considered the "lung" of the Montevideo city due to the large variety of trees planted here.

examples.annotated_text: Crimean_War: Frustrated by the wasted effort, and with demands for action from their citizens, the [dblookup('Allied Force (Crimean War)', 'Decision to Attack') -> Sevastopol] allied force decided to attack the center of Russian strength in the Black Sea at [dblookup('Sevastopol', 'Location') -> Crimean peninsula] Sevastopol on the Crimean peninsula. After extended preparations, the forces landed on the peninsula in [dblookup('Allied Force (Crimean War)', 'Landing Date on Crimean Peninsula') -> September 1854] September 1854 and fought their way to a point south of Sevastopol after a series of successful battles. The Russians counterattacked on [dblookup('Battle of Balaclava', 'Date') -> 25 October] 25 October in what became the [dblookup('Battle of Balaclava', 'Outcome') -> Russians repulsed, British Army depleted] Battle of Balaclava and were repulsed, but at the cost of seriously depleting the British Army forces. A second counterattack, ordered personally by [dblookup('Nicholas', 'Role During Crimean War') -> Russian Emperor] Nicholas, was defeated by [dblookup('Omar Pasha', 'Role During Crimean War') -> Commander against Russian counterattack] Omar Pasha. The front settled into a siege and led to horrible conditions for troops on both sides. Smaller actions were carried out in the [dblookup('Crimean War', 'Theaters of Operations') -> Baltic, Caucasus, White Sea, North Pacific] Baltic, the Caucasus, the White Sea and in the North Pacific.
examples.text: Crimean_War: Frustrated by the wasted effort, and with demands for action from their citizens, the allied force decided to attack the center of Russian strength in the Black Sea at Sevastopol on the Crimean peninsula. After extended preparations, the forces landed on the peninsula in September 1854 and fought their way to a point south of Sevastopol after a series of successful battles. The Russians counterattacked on 25 October in what became the Battle of Balaclava and were repulsed, but at the cost of seriously depleting the British Army forces. A second counterattack, ordered personally by Nicholas, was defeated by Omar Pasha. The front settled into a siege and led to horrible conditions for troops on both sides. Smaller actions were carried out in the Baltic, the Caucasus, the White Sea and in the North Pacific.

examples.annotated_text: Treaty: A treaty breach does not automatically suspend or terminate [dblookup('Treaty', 'Relations Affected By Breach') -> treaty relations] treaty relations, however. It depends on how the other parties regard the breach and how they resolve to respond to it. Sometimes [dblookup('Treaty', 'Breach Resolution Mechanism') -> tribunal, independent arbiter] treaties will provide for the seriousness of a breach to be determined by a tribunal or other independent arbiter. An advantage of such an arbiter is that it prevents a party from prematurely and perhaps wrongfully suspending or terminating its own obligations due to another's alleged material breach.

examples.annotated_text: Geography_of_the_United_States: Occasional severe flooding is experienced. There was the [dblookup('Great Mississippi Flood', 'Year') -> 1927] Great Mississippi Flood of 1927, the [dblookup('Great Flood of 1993', 'Year') -> 1993] Great Flood of 1993, and widespread flooding and mudslides caused by the [dblookup('1982-1983 El Niño event', 'Impact Region') -> western United States] 1982-1983 El Niño event in the western United States. Localized flooding can, however, occur anywhere, and mudslides from heavy rain can cause problems in any mountainous area, particularly the [dblookup('Southwest United States', 'Vulnerability') -> mudslides] Southwest. Large stretches of desert shrub in the west can fuel the spread of wildfires. The narrow canyons of many mountain areas in the west and severe thunderstorm activity during the summer lead to [dblookup('Flash Floods', 'Occurrence Region') -> western mountain areas] sometimes devastating flash floods as well, while Nor'Easter snowstorms can bring activity to a halt throughout the Northeast, although heavy snowstorms can occur almost anywhere.

examples.annotated_text: Heresy: The term [dblookup('Heresy', 'Origin Language') -> Greek] heresy is from Greek αἵρεσις originally meant "choice" or "thing chosen", but it came to mean the "party or school of a man's choice" and also referred to that process whereby a young person would examine various philosophies to determine how to live. The word "heresy" is usually used within a [dblookup('Heresy', 'Context') -> Christian, Jewish, Islamic] Christian, Jewish, or Islamic context, and implies slightly different meanings in each. The founder or leader of a heretical movement is called a [dblookup('Heresy', 'Leader Title') -> heresiarch] heresiarch, while individuals who espouse heresy or commit heresy are known as [dblookup('Heresy', 'Individuals Known As') -> heretics] heretics. [dblookup('Heresy', 'Field of Study') -> Heresiology] Heresiology is the study of heresy.

examples.annotated_text: Energy: Sunlight may be stored as [dblookup('Sunlight', 'Contribution To Energy Storage') -> gravitational potential energy] gravitational potential energy after it strikes the Earth, as (for example) water evaporates from oceans and is deposited upon mountains (where, after being released at a hydroelectric dam, it can be used to drive turbines or generators to produce electricity). Sunlight also [dblookup('Sunlight', 'Role In Weather Phenomena') -> drives many weather phenomena] drives many weather phenomena, save those generated by volcanic events. An example of a [dblookup('Hurricane', 'Cause') -> solar-mediated weather event] solar-mediated weather event is a hurricane, which occurs when [dblookup('Hurricane', 'Formation Condition') -> large unstable areas of warm ocean] large unstable areas of warm ocean, heated over months, give up some of their [dblookup('Warm Ocean', 'Energy Type Released') -> thermal energy] thermal energy suddenly to power a few days of violent air movement.
examples.text: Energy: Sunlight may be stored as gravitational potential energy after it strikes the Earth, as (for example) water evaporates from oceans and is deposited upon mountains (where, after being released at a hydroelectric dam, it can be used to drive turbines or generators to produce electricity). An example of a solar-mediated weather event is a hurricane, which occurs when large unstable areas of warm ocean, heated over months, give up some of their thermal energy suddenly to power a few days of violent air movement.

examples.annotated_text: Jews: According to historian Shaye J. D. Cohen, the status of the offspring of mixed marriages was determined patrilineally in the Bible. He brings two likely explanations for the change in [dblookup('Offspring of Mixed Marriages', 'Mishnaic Determination') -> matrilineally] Mishnaic times: first, the Mishnah may have been applying the same logic to mixed marriages as it had applied to other mixtures like Kil'ayim. Thus, a mixed marriage is forbidden as is the union of a horse and a donkey, and in both unions the offspring are judged matrilineally. Second, the Tannaim may have been influenced by Roman law, which dictated that when a parent could not contract a legal marriage, offspring would follow the mother.

examples.annotated_text: : Back in Warsaw that year, Chopin heard Niccolò Paganini play the violin, and composed a set of variations, [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Composed Work') -> Souvenir de Paganini] Souvenir de Paganini. It may have been this experience which encouraged him to commence writing his first [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'First Études Composed') -> 1829–32] Études, (1829–32), exploring the capacities of his own instrument. On 11 August, three weeks after completing his studies at [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Education') -> Warsaw Conservatory] the Warsaw Conservatory, he made his debut in [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Debut Location') -> Vienna] Vienna. He gave two piano concerts and received many favourable reviews—in addition to some commenting (in Chopin's own words) that he was "too delicate for those accustomed to the piano-bashing of local artists". In one of these concerts, he premiered his [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Premiered Work in Vienna') -> Variations on Là ci darem la mano, Op. 2] Variations on Là ci darem la mano, Op. 2 (variations on an aria from [dblookup('Là ci darem la mano', 'Based On') -> Mozart's opera Don Giovanni] Mozart's opera Don Giovanni) for piano and orchestra. He returned to Warsaw in September 1829, where he premiered his [dblookup('Frédéric Chopin', 'Premiere Date of Piano Concerto No. 2') -> 17 March 1830] Piano Concerto No. 2 in F minor, Op. 21 on 17 March 1830.
examples.text: Frédéric_Chopin: Back in Warsaw that year, Chopin heard Niccolò Paganini play the violin, and composed a set of variations, Souvenir de Paganini. It may have been this experience which encouraged him to commence writing his first Études, (1829–32), exploring the capacities of his own instrument. On 11 August, three weeks after completing his studies at the Warsaw Conservatory, he made his debut in Vienna. He gave two piano concerts and received many favourable reviews—in addition to some commenting (in Chopin's own words) that he was "too delicate for those accustomed to the piano-bashing of local artists". In one of these concerts, he premiered his Variations on Là ci darem la mano, Op. 2 (variations on an aria from Mozart's opera Don Giovanni) for piano and orchestra. He returned to Warsaw in September 1829, where he premiered his Piano Concerto No. 2 in F minor, Op. 21 on 17 March 1830.

examples.annotated_text: Gramophone_record: A gramophone record (phonograph record in [dblookup('American English', 'Term for Gramophone Record') -> phonograph record] American English) or vinyl record, commonly known as a "record", is an [dblookup('Gramophone Record', 'Type of Medium') -> analogue sound storage medium] analogue sound storage medium in the form of a flat polyvinyl chloride (previously shellac) disc with an inscribed, modulated spiral groove. The groove usually starts near the periphery and ends near the center of the disc. Phonograph records are generally described by their [dblookup('Phonograph Record', 'Measurement') -> diameter in inches, rotational speed in rpm, time capacity, reproductive quality, audio channels] diameter in inches (12", 10", 7"), the rotational speed in rpm at which they are played (16 2⁄3, 33 1⁄3, 45, 78), and their time capacity resulting from a combination of those parameters (LP – long playing 33 1⁄3 rpm, SP – 78 rpm single, EP – 12-inch single or extended play, 33 or 45 rpm); their reproductive quality or level of fidelity (high-fidelity, orthophonic, full-range, etc.), and the number of audio channels provided (mono, stereo, quad, etc.).

examples.annotated_text: Insect: In addition to the use of sound for communication, a wide range of insects have evolved chemical means for communication. These chemicals, termed [dblookup('Insects', 'Communication Chemicals') -> semiochemicals] semiochemicals, are often derived from plant metabolites include those meant to attract, repel and provide other kinds of information. [dblookup('Semiochemicals', 'Type') -> Pheromones] Pheromones, a type of semiochemical, are used for attracting mates of the opposite sex, for aggregating conspecific individuals of both sexes, for deterring other individuals from approaching, to mark a trail, and to trigger aggression in nearby individuals. Allomonea benefit their producer by the effect they have upon the receiver. [dblookup('Kairomones', 'Effect') -> benefit receiver] Kairomones benefit their receiver instead of their producer. [dblookup('Synomones', 'Effect') -> benefit both producer and receiver] Synomones benefit the producer and the receiver. While some chemicals are targeted at individuals of the same species, others are used for communication across species. The use of scents is especially well known to have developed in [dblookup('Social Insects', 'Developed Communication Method') -> scents] social insects.:96–105

examples.annotated_text: Napoleon: In 1955, the diaries of Napoleon's valet, [dblookup('Napoleon', 'Valet') -> Louis Marchand] Louis Marchand, were published. His description of Napoleon in the months before his death led Sten Forshufvud in a 1961 paper in [dblookup('Sten Forshufvud', 'Paper In') -> Nature] Nature to put forward other causes for his death, including deliberate [dblookup('Napoleon', 'Alternative Death Cause Suggested') -> arsenic poisoning] arsenic poisoning. Arsenic was used as a poison during the era because it was undetectable when administered over a long period. [dblookup('Sten Forshufvud', 'Book Co-Author') -> Ben Weider] Forshufvud, in a [dblookup('Sten Forshufvud and Ben Weider', 'Book Year') -> 1978] 1978 book with Ben Weider, noted that Napoleon's body was found to be remarkably well preserved when moved in [dblookup('Napoleon', 'Body Moved Year') -> 1840] 1840. Arsenic is a strong preservative, and therefore this supported the poisoning hypothesis. Forshufvud and Weider observed that Napoleon had attempted to quench abnormal thirst by drinking large amounts of orgeat syrup that contained cyanide compounds in the almonds used for flavouring.
examples.text: Napoleon: In 1955, the diaries of Napoleon's valet, Louis Marchand, were published. His description of Napoleon in the months before his death led Sten Forshufvud in a 1961 paper in Nature to put forward other causes for his death, including deliberate arsenic poisoning. Arsenic was used as a poison during the era because it was undetectable when administered over a long period. Forshufvud, in a 1978 book with Ben Weider, noted that Napoleon's body was found to be remarkably well preserved when moved in 1840. Arsenic is a strong preservative, and therefore this supported the poisoning hypothesis. Forshufvud and Weider observed that Napoleon had attempted to quench abnormal thirst by drinking large amounts of orgeat syrup that contained cyanide compounds in the almonds used for flavouring.

examples.annotated_text: Airport: An airbase, sometimes referred to as an air station or airfield, provides [dblookup('Airbase', 'Primary Function') -> basing and support of military aircraft] basing and support of military aircraft. examples.annotated_text: Queen_Victoria: Victoria visited mainland Europe regularly for holidays. In 1889, during a stay in Biarritz, she became the [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'First British Monarch to Visit') -> Spain] first reigning monarch from Britain to set foot in Spain when she crossed the border for a brief visit. Instead, the Queen went to [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Visited Ireland Again In') -> 1900] Ireland for the first time since [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Previous Visit to Ireland') -> 1861] 1861, in part to acknowledge the contribution of Irish regiments to the South African war. In July, her [dblookup('Queen Victoria', 'Second Son') -> Alfred] second son Alfred ("Affie") died; "Oh, God! My poor darling Affie gone too", she wrote in her journal. "It is a horrible year, nothing but sadness & horrors of one kind & another."

examples.text: Adolescence: Within the past ten years, the amount of social networking sites available to the public has greatly increased as well as the number of adolescents using them. examples.annotated_text: Elevator: In each case, cables are attached to a hitch plate on top of the cab or may be "underslung" below a cab, and then looped over the drive sheave to a [dblookup('Elevator Cables', 'Counterweight Function') -> counterweight attached to the opposite end] counterweight attached to the opposite end of the cables which reduces the amount of power needed to move the cab. The counterweight is located in the hoist-way and rides a [dblookup('Elevator Counterweight', 'Movement System') -> separate railway system] separate railway system; as the car goes up, the counterweight goes down, and vice versa. This action is powered by the traction machine which is directed by the controller, typically a relay logic or computerized device that directs starting, acceleration, deceleration, and stopping of the elevator cab. The weight of the counterweight is typically equal to the weight of the elevator cab plus [dblookup('Elevator Counterweight', 'Typical Additional Capacity Percentage') -> 40-50%] 40-50% of the capacity of the elevator. The grooves in the drive sheave are specially designed to prevent the cables from slipping. [dblookup('Drive Sheave', 'Function') -> Provides traction] "Traction" is provided to the ropes by the grip of the grooves in the sheave, thereby the name. As the ropes age and the traction grooves wear, some traction is lost and the ropes must be replaced and the sheave repaired or replaced. [dblookup('Sheave and Rope Wear', 'Reduction Method') -> Equal rope tension] Sheave and rope wear may be significantly reduced by ensuring that all ropes have equal tension, thus sharing the load evenly. Rope tension equalization may be achieved using a rope tension gauge, and is a simple way to extend the lifetime of the sheaves and ropes.

examples.annotated_text: Capital_punishment_in_the_United_States: In total, [dblookup('United States', 'Prisoner Exonerations 1973-2015') -> 156] 156 prisoners have been either acquitted, or received pardons or commutations on the basis of possible innocence, between [dblookup('Capital Punishment in the United States', 'Period of Exoneration Recorded') -> 1973-2015] 1973 to 2015. Death penalty opponents often argue that this statistic shows how perilously close states have come to undertaking wrongful executions; proponents point out that the statistic refers only to those exonerated in law, and that the truly innocent may be a smaller number. Statistics likely understate the actual problem of wrongful convictions because once an execution has occurred there is often insufficient motivation and finance to keep a case open, and it becomes unlikely at that point that the miscarriage of justice will ever be exposed.

examples.annotated_text: Supreme_court: In India, the [dblookup('Supreme Court of India', 'Established On') -> January 28, 1950] Supreme Court of India was created on January 28, 1950 after the adoption of the [dblookup('Constitution of India', 'Adoption Led To') -> Establishment of Supreme Court of India] Constitution. Article 141 of the Constitution of India states that the law declared by [dblookup('Supreme Court of India', 'Authority') -> Binding on all Courts in India] the Supreme Court is to be binding on all Courts within the territory of India. It is the highest court in India and has ultimate [dblookup('Supreme Court of India', 'Judicial Authority') -> Interpret the Constitution, Decide questions of national law] judicial authority to interpret the Constitution and decide questions of national law (including local bylaws). The Supreme Court is also vested with the [dblookup('Supreme Court of India', 'Power') -> Judicial review] power of judicial review to ensure the application of the rule of law.
examples.text: Supreme_court: In India, the Supreme Court of India was created on January 28, 1950 after adoption of the Constitution. examples.annotated_text: [dblookup('Financial Crisis of 2007–2008', 'Involvement of Financial Innovation') -> financial products] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing. Examples pertinent to this crisis included: the adjustable-rate mortgage; the bundling of subprime mortgages into mortgage-backed securities (MBS) or collateralized debt obligations (CDO) for sale to investors, a type of securitization; and a form of credit insurance called credit default swaps (CDS). The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis. These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.

examples.annotated_text: Pharmaceutical_industry: While highly effective, the requirement for injection limited the use of [dblookup('Norepinephrine', 'Route of Administration') -> Injection] norepinephrine and orally active derivatives were sought. A structurally similar compound, [dblookup('Ephedrine', 'Discovery By') -> Japanese chemists] ephedrine, was identified by Japanese chemists in the Ma Huang plant and [dblookup('Ephedrine', 'Marketed By') -> Eli Lilly] marketed by Eli Lilly as an oral treatment for [dblookup('Ephedrine', 'Treatment For') -> asthma] asthma. Following the work of Henry Dale and [dblookup('George Barger', 'Workplace') -> Burroughs-Wellcome] George Barger at Burroughs-Wellcome, academic chemist [dblookup('Gordon Alles', 'Achievement') -> Synthesized amphetamine] Gordon Alles synthesized amphetamine and tested it in asthma patients in [dblookup('Amphetamine', 'Tested In') -> 1929] 1929. The drug proved to have only modest anti-asthma effects, but produced sensations of exhilaration and palpitations. [dblookup('Amphetamine', 'Developed By') -> Smith, Kline and French] Amphetamine was developed by Smith, Kline and French as a nasal decongestant under the trade name [dblookup('Amphetamine', 'Trade Name') -> Benzedrine Inhaler] Benzedrine Inhaler. Amphetamine was eventually developed for the [dblookup('Amphetamine', 'Use In') -> narcolepsy, post-encepheletic parkinsonism, mood elevation in depression] treatment of narcolepsy, post-encepheletic parkinsonism, and mood elevation in depression and other psychiatric indications. It received approval as a New and Nonofficial Remedy from the [dblookup('Amphetamine', 'Approval By') -> American Medical Association] American Medical Association for these uses in [dblookup('Amphetamine', 'Approval Year') -> 1937] 1937 and remained in common use for depression until the development of [dblookup('Tricyclic Antidepressants', 'Development Era') -> 1960s] tricyclic antidepressants in the 1960s.
examples.text: Pharmaceutical_industry: While highly effective, the requirement for injection limited the use of norepinephrine[clarification needed] and orally active derivatives were sought. A structurally similar compound, ephedrine, was identified by Japanese chemists in the Ma Huang plant and marketed by Eli Lilly as an oral treatment for asthma. Following the work of Henry Dale and George Barger at Burroughs-Wellcome, academic chemist Gordon Alles synthesized amphetamine and tested it in asthma patients in 1929. The drug proved to have only modest anti-asthma effects, but produced sensations of exhilaration and palpitations. Amphetamine was developed by Smith, Kline and French as a nasal decongestant under the trade name Benzedrine Inhaler. Amphetamine was eventually developed for the treatment of narcolepsy, post-encepheletic parkinsonism, and mood elevation in depression and other psychiatric indications. It received approval as a New and Nonofficial Remedy from the American Medical Association for these uses in 1937 and remained in common use for depression until the development of tricyclic antidepressants in the 1960s.

examples.annotated_text: Digestion: Digestion begins in the [dblookup('Digestion', 'Initial Organ') -> mouth] mouth with the secretion of saliva and its digestive enzymes. Food is formed into a bolus by the mechanical mastication and swallowed into the esophagus from where it enters the [dblookup('Esophagus', 'Leads To') -> stomach] stomach through the action of [dblookup('Esophagus', 'Transport Mechanism') -> peristalsis] peristalsis. Gastric juice contains [dblookup('Gastric Juice', 'Components') -> hydrochloric acid, pepsin] hydrochloric acid and pepsin which would damage the walls of the stomach and [dblookup('Stomach Protection', 'Secretion Involved') -> mucus] mucus is secreted for protection. In the stomach further release of enzymes break down the food further and this is combined with the churning action of the stomach. The partially digested food enters the [dblookup('Digestive Sequence', 'Follows Stomach') -> duodenum] duodenum as a thick semi-liquid chyme. In the small intestine, the larger part of digestion takes place and this is helped by the secretions of [dblookup('Small Intestine', 'Secretion Aids') -> bile, pancreatic juice, intestinal juice] bile, pancreatic juice, and intestinal juice. The intestinal walls are lined with [dblookup('Intestinal Walls', 'Structural Feature') -> villi] villi, and their epithelial cells are covered with numerous [dblookup('Epithelial Cells', 'Surface Feature') -> microvilli] microvilli to improve the absorption of nutrients by increasing the [dblookup('Microvilli', 'Primary Function') -> surface area of the intestine] surface area of the intestine.
examples.text: Digestion: Digestion begins in the mouth with the secretion of saliva and its digestive enzymes. Food is formed into a bolus by the mechanical mastication and swallowed into the esophagus from where it enters the stomach through the action of peristalsis. Gastric juice contains hydrochloric acid and pepsin which would damage the walls of the stomach and mucus is secreted for protection. In the stomach further release of enzymes break down the food further and this is combined with the churning action of the stomach. The partially digested food enters the duodenum as a thick semi-liquid chyme. In the small intestine, the larger part of digestion takes place and this is helped by the secretions of bile, pancreatic juice and intestinal juice. The intestinal walls are lined with villi, and their epithelial cells is covered with numerous microvilli to improve the absorption of nutrients by increasing the surface area of the intestine.

examples.annotated_text: Sichuan: The Sichuan government raised the minimum wage in the province by 12.5 percent at the end of [dblookup('Minimum Wage Change in Sichuan', 'Effective Date') -> December 26, 2007] December 2007. The monthly minimum wage went up from [dblookup('Sichuan Minimum Wage', 'Previous Monthly Rate') -> 400 yuan] 400 to [dblookup('Sichuan Minimum Wage', 'New Monthly Rate') -> 450 yuan] 450 yuan, with a minimum of [dblookup('Sichuan Minimum Wage', 'New Hourly Rate for Part-time') -> 4.9 yuan] 4.9 yuan per hour for part-time work, effective 26 December 2007. The government also reduced the [dblookup('Sichuan Minimum Wage Structure', 'Number of Tiers After Change') -> three] four-tier minimum wage structure to three. The top tier mandates a minimum of [dblookup('Sichuan Top Tier Minimum Wage', 'Monthly Rate') -> 650 yuan] 650 yuan per month, or [dblookup('Sichuan Top Tier Minimum Wage', 'Hourly Rate') -> 7.1 yuan] 7.1 yuan per hour. National law allows each province to set minimum wages independently, but with a floor of 450 yuan per month.
examples.text: Sichuan: The Sichuan government raised the minimum wage in the province by 12.5 percent at the end of December 2007. The monthly minimum wage went up from 400 to 450 yuan, with a minimum of 4.9 yuan per hour for part-time work, effective 26 December 2007. The government also reduced the four-tier minimum wage structure to three. The top tier mandates a minimum of 650 yuan per month, or 7.1 yuan per hour. National law allows each province to set minimum wages independently, but with a floor of 450 yuan per month.

examples.annotated_text: A_cappella: In July 1943, as a result of the [dblookup('American Federation of Musicians', 'Event') -> boycott of US recording studios] American Federation of Musicians boycott of US recording studios, the a cappella vocal group [dblookup('The Song Spinners', 'Achievement') -> had a best-seller with "Comin' In On A Wing And A Prayer"] The Song Spinners had a best-seller with "Comin' In On A Wing And A Prayer". A cappella music attained renewed prominence from the late 1980s onward, spurred by the success of Top 40 recordings by artists such as [dblookup('The Manhattan Transfer', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] The Manhattan Transfer, [dblookup('Bobby McFerrin', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] Bobby McFerrin, [dblookup('Huey Lewis and the News', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] Huey Lewis and the News, [dblookup('All-4-One', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] All-4-One, [dblookup('The Nylons', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] The Nylons, [dblookup('Backstreet Boys', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] Backstreet Boys, and [dblookup('Boyz II Men', 'Role in A Cappella') -> spurred renewed interest] Boyz II Men.[citation needed]
examples.text: A_cappella: In July 1943, as a result of the American Federation of Musicians boycott of US recording studios, the a cappella vocal group The Song Spinners had a best-seller with "Comin' In On A Wing And A Prayer". examples.annotated_text: Samurai: A samurai could take concubines but their backgrounds were checked by [dblookup('Concubines', 'Background Check Authority') -> higher-ranked samurai] higher-ranked samurai. In many cases, taking a concubine was akin to [dblookup('Samurai', 'Concubine Relationship Similarity') -> marriage] a marriage. Kidnapping a concubine, although common in fiction, would have been [dblookup('Kidnapping Concubines', 'Cultural Perception') -> shameful, if not criminal] shameful, if not criminal. If the concubine was a commoner, a messenger was sent with [dblookup('Samurai', 'Betrothal Tradition for Commoner Concubines') -> betrothal money or tax exemption note] betrothal money or a note for exemption of tax to ask for her parents' acceptance. Even though the woman would not be a legal wife, a situation normally considered a demotion, many wealthy merchants believed that being the concubine of a samurai was superior to being the legal wife of a commoner. When a merchant's daughter married a samurai, her family's money erased the samurai's debts, and the samurai's [dblookup('Marriage Between Merchants and Samurai', 'Social Benefit for Merchant Family') -> improved social status of the merchant family] social status improved the standing of the merchant family. If a samurai's commoner concubine gave birth to a son, the son could [dblookup('Inheritance by Samurai's Son with Commoner Concubine', 'Social Status Inheritance') -> inherit his father's social status] inherit his father's social status.
examples.text: Samurai: A samurai could take concubines but their backgrounds were checked by higher-ranked samurai. In many cases, taking a concubine was akin to a marriage. Kidnapping a concubine, although common in fiction, would have been shameful, if not criminal. If the concubine was a commoner, a messenger was sent with betrothal money or a note for exemption of tax to ask for her parents' acceptance. Even though the woman would not be a legal wife, a situation normally considered a demotion, many wealthy merchants believed that being the concubine of a samurai was superior to being the legal wife of a commoner. When a merchant's daughter married a samurai, her family's money erased the samurai's debts, and the samurai's social status improved the standing of the merchant family. If a samurai's commoner concubine gave birth to a son, the son could inherit his father's social status.

Edmund Burke: On [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Vote of Thanks Date') -> June 20, 1794] 20 June 1794, Burke received a vote of thanks from the Commons for his services in the Hastings Trial and he immediately resigned his seat, being replaced by his son Richard. A tragic blow fell upon Burke with the [dblookup('Richard Burke', 'Date of Death') -> August 1794] loss of Richard in August 1794, to whom he was tenderly attached, and in whom he saw signs of promise, which were not patent to others and which, in fact, appear to have been non-existent (though this view may have rather reflected the fact that [dblookup('Richard Burke', 'Contribution To') -> early battle for Catholic emancipation] Richard Burke had worked successfully in the early battle for Catholic emancipation). 

[dblookup('King George III', 'Intended Title for Edmund Burke') -> Earl of Beaconsfield] King George III, whose favour he had gained by his attitude on the French Revolution, wished to create him Earl of Beaconsfield, but the death of his son deprived the opportunity of such an honour and all its attractions, so the only award he would accept was a [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Award Accepted') -> pension of £2,500] pension of £2,500. Even this modest reward was attacked by the [dblookup('Duke of Bedford', 'Opponent of Edmund Burke') -> Duke of Bedford] Duke of Bedford and the [dblookup('Earl of Lauderdale', 'Opponent of Edmund Burke') -> Earl of Lauderdale] Earl of Lauderdale, to whom Burke replied in his [dblookup('Edmund Burke', 'Work') -> Letter to a Noble Lord] Letter to a Noble Lord (1796): "It cannot at this time be too often repeated; line upon line; precept upon precept; until it comes into the currency of a proverb, To innovate is not to reform." He argued that he was rewarded on merit, but the Duke of Bedford received his rewards from inheritance alone, his ancestor being the original pensioner: "Mine was from a mild and benevolent sovereign; his from Henry the Eighth." Burke also hinted at what would happen to such people if their revolutionary ideas were implemented, and included a description of the British constitution.

examples.text: Computer: Purely electronic circuit elements soon replaced their mechanical and electromechanical equivalents, at the same time that digital calculation replaced analog. The engineer Tommy Flowers, working at the Post Office Research Station in London in the 1930s, began to explore the possible use of electronics for the telephone exchange. examples.annotated_text: Franco-Prussian War: The Battle of Wörth (also known as Fröschwiller or Reichshoffen) began when the two armies clashed again on [dblookup('Battle of Wörth', 'Date') -> August 6, 1870] 6 August near Wörth in the town of Fröschwiller, about [dblookup('Fröschwiller', 'Distance From') -> 10 miles from Wissembourg] 10 miles (16 km) from Wissembourg. The Crown Prince of Prussia's 3rd army had, on the quick reaction of his Chief of Staff [dblookup('Crown Prince of Prussia', 'Chief of Staff') -> General von Blumenthal] General von Blumenthal, drawn reinforcements which brought its strength up to [dblookup('Prussian 3rd Army', 'Troop Strength on August 6, 1870') -> 140,000] 140,000 troops. The French had been slowly reinforced and their [dblookup('French Army', 'Troop Strength at Battle of Wörth') -> 35,000] force numbered only 35,000. Although badly outnumbered, the French defended their position just outside Fröschwiller. By afternoon, the Germans had suffered [dblookup('German Casualties at Battle of Wörth', 'Killed or Wounded') -> 10,500] c. 10,500 killed or wounded and the French had lost a similar number of casualties and another [dblookup('French Army', 'Prisoners Taken at Battle of Wörth') -> 9,200] c. 9,200 men taken prisoner, a loss of about 50%. The Germans captured Fröschwiller which sat on a hilltop in the centre of the French line. Having lost any hope for victory and facing a massacre, the French army disengaged and retreated in a westerly direction towards Bitche and Saverne, hoping to join French forces on the other side of the Vosges mountains. The German 3rd army did not pursue the French but remained in Alsace and moved slowly south, attacking and destroying the French garrisons in the vicinity.
examples.text: Franco-Prussian_War: The Battle of Wörth (also known as Fröschwiller or Reichshoffen) began when the two armies clashed again on 6 August near Wörth in the town of Fröschwiller, about 10 miles (16 km) from Wissembourg. The Crown Prince of Prussia's 3rd army had, on the quick reaction of his Chief of Staff General von Blumenthal, drawn reinforcements which brought its strength up to 140,000 troops. By afternoon, the Germans had suffered c. 10,500 killed or wounded and the French had lost a similar number of casualties and another c. 9,200 men taken prisoner, a loss of about 50%. Having lost any hope for victory and facing a massacre, the French army disengaged and retreated in a westerly direction towards Bitche and Saverne, hoping to join French forces on the other side of the Vosges mountains. The German 3rd army did not pursue the French but remained in Alsace and moved slowly south, attacking and destroying the French garrisons in the vicinity.

examples.annotated_text: Mesozoic: The [dblookup('Late Cretaceous', 'Time Span') -> 100 million to 65 million years ago] Late Cretaceous spans from 100 million to 65 million years ago. The Late Cretaceous featured a [dblookup('Late Cretaceous', 'Climate Trend') -> cooling trend] cooling trend that would continue on in the Cenozoic period. Eventually, tropics were restricted to the equator and areas beyond the tropic lines featured extreme seasonal changes in weather. Dinosaurs still thrived as [dblookup('Late Cretaceous', 'Dominant Dinosaur Species') -> Tyrannosaurus, Ankylosaurus, Triceratops, Hadrosaurs] new species such as Tyrannosaurus, Ankylosaurus, Triceratops and Hadrosaurs dominated the food web. In the oceans, [dblookup('Late Cretaceous', 'Dominant Marine Reptile') -> Mosasaurs] Mosasaurs ruled the seas to fill the role of the Ichthyosaurs, and huge plesiosaurs, such as [dblookup('Elasmosaurus', 'Era') -> Late Cretaceous] Elasmosaurus, evolved. Also, the first flowering plants evolved. At the end of the Cretaceous, the [dblookup('Deccan Traps', 'Impact on Environment') -> poisoning the atmosphere] Deccan traps and other volcanic eruptions were poisoning the atmosphere. As this was continuing, it is thought that a [dblookup('Chicxulub Crater', 'Cause') -> large meteor impact] large meteor smashed into earth, creating the Chicxulub Crater in an event known as the [dblookup('K-T Extinction', 'Type') -> fifth mass extinction event] K-T Extinction, the fifth and most recent mass extinction event, in which [dblookup('K-T Extinction', 'Percentage of Life Extinct') -> 75%] 75% of life on earth went extinct, including all non-avian dinosaurs. Everything over 10 kilograms went extinct. The age of the dinosaurs was over.
examples.text: Mesozoic: The Late Cretaceous spans from 100 million to 65 million years ago. The Late Cretaceous featured a cooling trend that would continue on in the Cenozoic period. Eventually, tropics were restricted to the equator and areas beyond the tropic lines featured extreme seasonal changes in weather. Dinosaurs still thrived as new species such as Tyrannosaurus, Ankylosaurus, Triceratops and Hadrosaurs dominated the food web. In the oceans, Mosasaurs ruled the seas to fill the role of the Ichthyosaurs, and huge plesiosaurs, such as Elasmosaurus, evolved. Also, the first flowering plants evolved. At the end of the Cretaceous, the Deccan traps and other volcanic eruptions were poisoning the atmosphere. As this was continuing, it is thought that a large meteor smashed into earth, creating the Chicxulub Crater in an event known as the K-T Extinction, the fifth and most recent mass extinction event, in which 75% of life on earth went extinct, including all non-avian dinosaurs. Everything over 10 kilograms went extinct. The age of the dinosaurs was over.

examples.annotated_text: Circadian_rhythm: [dblookup('Circadian_rhythm', 'Function') -> Anticipate environmental changes] Circadian rhythms allow organisms to anticipate and prepare for precise and regular environmental changes. They thus enable organisms to best capitalize on environmental resources (e.g. light and food) compared to those that cannot predict such availability. It has therefore been suggested that circadian rhythms put organisms at [dblookup('Circadian_rhythm', 'Evolutionary Impact') -> Selective advantage] a selective advantage in evolutionary terms. However, rhythmicity appears to be as important in regulating and coordinating [dblookup('Circadian_rhythm', 'Importance') -> Internal metabolic processes regulation] internal metabolic processes, as in coordinating with the environment. This is suggested by the maintenance (heritability) of [dblookup('Circadian_rhythm', 'Heritability Example') -> Fruit flies] circadian rhythms in fruit flies after several hundred generations in constant laboratory conditions, as well as in [dblookup('Circadian_rhythm', 'Heritability Example') -> Creatures in constant darkness] creatures in constant darkness in the wild, and by [dblookup('Circadian_rhythm', 'Experimental Evidence') -> Quail] the experimental elimination of behavioral, but not physiological, circadian rhythms in quail.
examples.text: Circadian_rhythm: Circadian rhythms allow organisms to anticipate and prepare for precise and regular environmental changes. They thus enable organisms to best capitalize on environmental resources (e.g. light and food) compared to those that cannot predict such availability. It has therefore been suggested that circadian rhythms put organisms at a selective advantage in evolutionary terms. However, rhythmicity appears to be as important in regulating and coordinating internal metabolic processes, as in coordinating with the environment. This is suggested by the maintenance (heritability) of circadian rhythms in fruit flies after several hundred generations in constant laboratory conditions, as well as in creatures in constant darkness in the wild, and by the experimental elimination of behavioral, but not physiological, circadian rhythms in quail.

The latter aided in the defence of their respective territories against attacks by other European powers, Aboriginal peoples, and later American forces during the American Revolutionary War and [dblookup('War of 1812', 'Period') -> 1812-1815] War of 1812, as well as in the [dblookup('Fenian Raids', 'Involved Conflicts') -> Fenian raids] Fenian raids, [dblookup('Red River Rebellion', 'Year') -> 1869-1870] Red River Rebellion, and [dblookup('North-West Rebellion', 'Year') -> 1885] North-West Rebellion. examples.annotated_text: Geological_history_of_Earth: The [dblookup('Devonian Period', 'Time Span') -> 419 to 359 Ma] Devonian spanned roughly from 419 to 359 Ma. The period was a time of [dblookup('Devonian Period', 'Tectonic Activity') -> high] great tectonic activity, as [dblookup('Laurasia', 'Drew Closer To') -> Gondwana] Laurasia and Gondwana drew closer together. The continent [dblookup('Euramerica', 'Created By Collision Of') -> Laurentia, Baltica] Euramerica (or Laurussia) was created in the early Devonian by the collision of Laurentia and Baltica, which rotated into the natural dry zone along the Tropic of Capricorn. In these near-deserts, the [dblookup('Old Red Sandstone', 'Formed In') -> Devonian Period] Old Red Sandstone sedimentary beds formed, made red by the oxidized iron (hematite) characteristic of drought conditions. Near the equator, [dblookup('Pangaea', 'Consolidation Began') -> Devonian Period] Pangaea began to consolidate from the plates containing [dblookup('North America', 'Part Of') -> Pangaea] North America and Europe, further raising the northern Appalachian Mountains and forming the [dblookup('Caledonian Mountains', 'Formed In') -> Devonian Period] Caledonian Mountains in Great Britain and Scandinavia. The southern continents remained tied together in the supercontinent of [dblookup('Gondwana', 'Status During Devonian') -> supercontinent] Gondwana. The remainder of modern Eurasia lay in the Northern Hemisphere. [dblookup('Sea Levels', 'Status During Devonian') -> high] Sea levels were high worldwide, and much of the land lay submerged under shallow seas. The deep, enormous Panthalassa (the "universal ocean") covered the rest of the planet. Other minor oceans were [dblookup('Minor Oceans During Devonian', 'Included') -> Paleo-Tethys, Proto-Tethys, Rheic Ocean, Ural Ocean] Paleo-Tethys, Proto-Tethys, Rheic Ocean, and Ural Ocean (which was closed during the collision with Siberia and Baltica).
examples.text: Geological_history_of_Earth: The Devonian spanned roughly from 419 to 359 Ma. The period was a time of great tectonic activity, as Laurasia and Gondwana drew closer together. The continent Euramerica (or Laurussia) was created in the early Devonian by the collision of Laurentia and Baltica, which rotated into the natural dry zone along the Tropic of Capricorn. In these near-deserts, the Old Red Sandstone sedimentary beds formed, made red by the oxidized iron (hematite) characteristic of drought conditions. Near the equator Pangaea began to consolidate from the plates containing North America and Europe, further raising the northern Appalachian Mountains and forming the Caledonian Mountains in Great Britain and Scandinavia. The southern continents remained tied together in the supercontinent of Gondwana. The remainder of modern Eurasia lay in the Northern Hemisphere. Sea levels were high worldwide, and much of the land lay submerged under shallow seas. The deep, enormous Panthalassa (the "universal ocean") covered the rest of the planet. Other minor oceans were Paleo-Tethys, Proto-Tethys, Rheic Ocean and Ural Ocean (which was closed during the collision with Siberia and Baltica).

examples.annotated_text: Cork_(city): Cork was one of the most rail-oriented cities in Ireland, featuring [dblookup('Cork', 'Number of Stations') -> eight] eight stations at various times. The main route, still much the same today, is from [dblookup('Cork to Dublin Rail Route', 'Start Station') -> Dublin Heuston] Dublin Heuston. Originally terminating on the city's outskirts at [dblookup('Cork to Dublin Rail Route', 'Initial Terminus') -> Blackpool] Blackpool, the route now reaches the city centre terminus of [dblookup('Cork to Dublin Rail Route', 'Current Terminus') -> Kent Station] Kent Station via Glanmire tunnel. Now a [dblookup('Kent Station', 'Current Function') -> through station] through station, the line through Kent connects the towns of [dblookup('Kent Station', 'Connected Towns') -> Cobh, Midleton] Cobh and Midleton east of the city. This also connected to the seaside town of [dblookup('Cork Rail Connection', 'Seaside Towns Connected') -> Youghal] Youghal, until the [dblookup('Youghal Rail Connection', 'Ceased Operation') -> 1980s] 1980s.
examples.text: Cork_(city): Cork was one of the most rail-oriented cities in Ireland, featuring eight stations at various times. The main route, still much the same today, is from Dublin Heuston. Originally terminating on the city's outskirts at Blackpool, the route now reaches the city centre terminus of Kent Station via Glanmire tunnel. Now a through station, the line through Kent connects the towns of Cobh and Midleton east of the city. This also connected to the seaside town of Youghal, until the 1980s.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: Scientific readers were already aware of arguments that species changed through processes that were subject to laws of nature, but the transmutational ideas of [dblookup('Jean-Baptiste Lamarck', 'Idea Referred To') -> Species Transmutation] Lamarck and the vague "law of development" of [dblookup('Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation', 'Concept Referred To') -> Law of Development] Vestiges had not found scientific favour. [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Concept Introduced') -> Natural Selection] Darwin presented natural selection as a scientifically testable mechanism while accepting that other mechanisms such as [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Other Mechanism Referred To') -> Inheritance of Acquired Characters] inheritance of acquired characters were possible. His strategy established that [dblookup('Charles Darwin', 'Scientific Contribution') -> Evolution through Natural Laws] evolution through natural laws was worthy of scientific study, and by 1875, most scientists accepted that evolution occurred but few thought natural selection was significant. Darwin's scientific method was also disputed, with his proponents favouring the empiricism of [dblookup('John Stuart Mill', 'Work Referred To') -> A System of Logic] John Stuart Mill's A System of Logic, while opponents held to the idealist school of [dblookup('William Whewell', 'Work Referred To') -> Philosophy of the Inductive Sciences] William Whewell's Philosophy of the Inductive Sciences, in which investigation could begin with the intuitive truth that species were fixed objects created by design. Early support for Darwin's ideas came from the findings of field naturalists studying biogeography and ecology, including [dblookup('Joseph Dalton Hooker', 'Support Year') -> 1860] Joseph Dalton Hooker in 1860, and [dblookup('Asa Gray', 'Support Year') -> 1862] Asa Gray in 1862. [dblookup('Henry Walter Bates', 'Research Year') -> 1861] Henry Walter Bates presented research in 1861 that explained insect mimicry using natural selection. [dblookup('Alfred Russel Wallace', 'Research Area') -> Malay Archipelago] Alfred Russel Wallace discussed evidence from his Malay archipelago research, including an [dblookup('Alfred Russel Wallace', 'Paper Year') -> 1864] 1864 paper with an evolutionary explanation for the Wallace line.
examples.text: On_the_Origin_of_Species: Scientific readers were already aware of arguments that species changed through processes that were subject to laws of nature, but the transmutational ideas of Lamarck and the vague "law of development" of Vestiges had not found scientific favour. Darwin presented natural selection as a scientifically testable mechanism while accepting that other mechanisms such as inheritance of acquired characters were possible. His strategy established that evolution through natural laws was worthy of scientific study, and by 1875, most scientists accepted that evolution occurred but few thought natural selection was significant. Darwin's scientific method was also disputed, with his proponents favouring the empiricism of John Stuart Mill's A System of Logic, while opponents held to the idealist school of William Whewell's Philosophy of the Inductive Sciences, in which investigation could begin with the intuitive truth that species were fixed objects created by design. Early support for Darwin's ideas came from the findings of field naturalists studying biogeography and ecology, including Joseph Dalton Hooker in 1860, and Asa Gray in 1862. Henry Walter Bates presented research in 1861 that explained insect mimicry using natural selection. Alfred Russel Wallace discussed evidence from his Malay archipelago research, including an 1864 paper with an evolutionary explanation for the Wallace line.

examples.annotated_text: Armenians: Within the diasporan Armenian community, there is an unofficial classification of the different kinds of Armenians. For example, [dblookup('Armenians from Iran', 'Referred As') -> Parskahay] Armenians who originate from Iran are referred to as Parskahay (Պարսկահայ), while [dblookup('Armenians from Lebanon', 'Referred As') -> Lipananahay] Armenians from Lebanon are usually referred to as Lipananahay (Լիբանանահայ). Armenians of the Diaspora are the primary speakers of the [dblookup('Armenian Diaspora', 'Language Dialect Spoken') -> Western Armenian] Western dialect of the Armenian language. This dialect has considerable differences with [dblookup('Eastern Armenian', 'Language Comparison') -> Western Armenian] Eastern Armenian, but speakers of either of the two variations can usually understand each other. [dblookup('Eastern Armenian', 'Primary Diaspora Regions') -> Iran, Ukraine, Russia, Georgia] Eastern Armenian in the diaspora is primarily spoken in Iran and European countries such as Ukraine, Russia, and Georgia (where they form a majority in the Samtskhe-Javakheti province). In diverse communities (such as in Canada and the U.S.) where many different kinds of Armenians live together, there is a tendency for the different groups to cluster together.
examples.text: Armenians: Within the diasporan Armenian community, there is an unofficial classification of the different kinds of Armenians. For example, Armenians who originate from Iran are referred to as Parskahay (Պարսկահայ), while Armenians from Lebanon are usually referred to as Lipananahay (Լիբանանահայ). Armenians of the Diaspora are the primary speakers of the Western dialect of the Armenian language. This dialect has considerable differences with Eastern Armenian, but speakers of either of the two variations can usually understand each other. Eastern Armenian in the diaspora is primarily spoken in Iran and European countries such as Ukraine, Russia, and Georgia (where they form a majority in the Samtskhe-Javakheti province). In diverse communities (such as in Canada and the U.S.) where many different kinds of Armenians live together, there is a tendency for the different groups to cluster together.

examples.annotated_text: Cardinal_(Catholicism): Pope Sixtus V limited the number of cardinals to 70, comprising [dblookup('Cardinals Under Pope Sixtus V', 'Composition') -> six cardinal bishops, 50 cardinal priests, 14 cardinal deacons] six cardinal bishops, 50 cardinal priests, and 14 cardinal deacons. Starting in the pontificate of [dblookup('Pope John XXIII', 'Exceeded Cardinals Limit') -> Yes] Pope John XXIII, that limit has been exceeded. At the start of 1971, [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Cardinal Electors Limit Set') -> 120] Pope Paul VI set the number of cardinal electors at a maximum of 120, but [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'General Cardinals Limit Set') -> None] set no limit on the number of cardinals generally. He also established a maximum age of eighty years for electors. His action deprived twenty-five living cardinals, including the three living cardinals elevated by [dblookup('Pope Pius XI', 'Living Cardinals Deprived of Vote') -> Yes] Pope Pius XI, of the right to participate in a conclave.[citation needed] Popes can dispense from church laws and have sometimes brought the number of cardinals under the age of 80 to more than 120. [dblookup('Pope Paul VI', 'Increased Cardinal Bishops') -> Yes] Pope Paul VI also increased the number of cardinal bishops by giving that rank to patriarchs of the Eastern Catholic Churches.
examples.text: Cardinal_(Catholicism): Pope Sixtus V limited the number of cardinals to 70, comprising six cardinal bishops, 50 cardinal priests, and 14 cardinal deacons. Starting in the pontificate of Pope John XXIII, that limit has been exceeded. At the start of 1971, Pope Paul VI set the number of cardinal electors at a maximum of 120, but set no limit on the number of cardinals generally. He also established a maximum age of eighty years for electors. His action deprived twenty-five living cardinals, including the three living cardinals elevated by Pope Pius XI, of the right to participate in a conclave.[citation needed] Popes can dispense from church laws and have sometimes brought the number of cardinals under the age of 80 to more than 120. Pope Paul VI also increased the number of cardinal bishops by giving that rank to patriarchs of the Eastern Catholic Churches.

examples.annotated_text: One of the problems of the standard electric light bulb is filament notching due to evaporation of the filament. Small variations in resistivity along the filament cause "hot spots" to form at points of higher resistivity; a variation of diameter of only 1% will cause a 25% reduction in service life. These hot spots evaporate faster than the rest of the filament, which increases the resistance at that point—this creates a positive feedback that ends in the familiar tiny gap in an otherwise healthy-looking filament. Irving Langmuir found that an inert gas, instead of vacuum, would retard evaporation. [dblookup('General Service Incandescent Light Bulbs', 'Gas Fill') -> Mixture of argon and nitrogen or krypton] General service incandescent light bulbs over about 25 watts in rating are now filled with a mixture of mostly argon and some nitrogen, or sometimes krypton. Lamps operated on direct current develop random stairstep irregularities on the filament surface which may cut lifespan in half compared to AC operation; [dblookup('Tungsten and Rhenium', 'Use In Lamps') -> Counteract irregularities from DC operation] different alloys of tungsten and rhenium can be used to counteract the effect.
examples.text: Incandescent_light_bulb: One of the problems of the standard electric light bulb is filament notching due to evaporation of the filament. Small variations in resistivity along the filament cause "hot spots" to form at points of higher resistivity; a variation of diameter of only 1% will cause a 25% reduction in service life. These hot spots evaporate faster than the rest of the filament, which increases the resistance at that point—this creates a positive feedback that ends in the familiar tiny gap in an otherwise healthy-looking filament. Irving Langmuir found that an inert gas, instead of vacuum, would retard evaporation. General service incandescent light bulbs over about 25 watts in rating are now filled with a mixture of mostly argon and some nitrogen, or sometimes krypton. Lamps operated on direct current develop random stairstep irregularities on the filament surface which may cut lifespan in half compared to AC operation; different alloys of tungsten and rhenium can be used to counteract the effect.

examples.annotated_text: Alaska: On [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Date') -> March 27, 1964] March 27, 1964, the massive Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Causes Of Destruction') -> tsunamis and landslides] resultant tsunamis and landslides. It was the [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Global Rank By Magnitude') -> second-most-powerful earthquake] second-most-powerful earthquake in the recorded history of the world, with a [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Magnitude') -> 9.2] moment magnitude of 9.2. It was over [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Comparison To Other Earthquake') -> one thousand times more powerful than the 1989 San Francisco earthquake] one thousand times more powerful than the 1989 San Francisco earthquake. The [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Time Of Occurrence') -> 5:36 pm] time of day (5:36 pm), time of year and [dblookup('Good Friday Earthquake', 'Epicenter Location Consideration') -> epicenter's location cited as factors in sparing lives] location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
examples.text: Alaska: On March 27, 1964, the massive Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides. It was the second-most-powerful earthquake in the recorded history of the world, with a moment magnitude of 9.2. It was over one thousand times more powerful than the 1989 San Francisco earthquake. The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.

examples.text: Northwestern_University: Northwestern is a large, residential research university. examples.annotated_text: Classical_music: One major difference between [dblookup('Baroque Music', 'Time Period') -> 1600 to 1750] Baroque music and the [dblookup('Classical Music Era', 'Time Period') -> 1750 to 1820] classical era that followed it is that the types of instruments used in ensembles were much less standardized. Whereas a [dblookup('Classical Music Era', 'Standard Ensemble') -> string quartet] classical era string quartet consists almost exclusively of two violins, a viola, and a cello, a [dblookup('Baroque Music', 'Ensemble Variation') -> diverse instrument groups] Baroque group accompanying a soloist or opera could include one of several different types of keyboard instruments (e.g., [dblookup('Baroque Music', 'Common Keyboard Instruments') -> pipe organ, harpsichord, clavichord] pipe organ, harpsichord, or clavichord), additional stringed chordal instruments (e.g., a lute) and an unspecified number of bass instruments performing the basso continuo bassline, including [dblookup('Baroque Music', 'Basso Continuo Instruments') -> bowed strings, woodwinds, brass instruments] bowed strings, woodwinds, and brass instruments (e.g., a cello, contrabass, viol, bassoon, serpent, etc.).
examples.text: Classical_music: One major difference between Baroque music and the classical era that followed it is that the types of instruments used in ensembles were much less standardized. Whereas a classical era string quartet consists almost exclusively of two violins, a viola and a cello, a Baroque group accompanying a soloist or opera could include one of several different types of keyboard instruments (e.g., pipe organ, harpsichord, or clavichord), additional stringed chordal instruments (e.g., a lute) and an unspecified number of bass instruments performing the basso continuo bassline, including bowed strings, woodwinds and brass instruments (e.g., a cello, contrabass, viol, bassoon, serpent, etc.).

examples.annotated_text: East_Prussia: In [dblookup('Nazi Germany', 'Toponym Alteration Year in East Prussia') -> 1938] 1938 the Nazis altered about one-third of the toponyms of the area, eliminating, Germanizing, or simplifying a number of Old Prussian names, as well as those Polish or Lithuanian names originating from colonists and refugees to Prussia during and after the Protestant Reformation. More than [dblookup('East Prussia', 'Places Renamed By 16 July 1938') -> 1,500] 1,500 places were ordered to be renamed by [dblookup('East Prussia', 'Renaming Decree Date') -> 16 July 1938] 16 July 1938 following a decree issued by [dblookup('Erich Koch', 'Position During Renaming') -> Gauleiter and Oberpräsident] Gauleiter and Oberpräsident Erich Koch and initiated by [dblookup('Toponym Renaming in East Prussia', 'Initiated By') -> Adolf Hitler] Adolf Hitler. Many who would not cooperate with the rulers of [dblookup('Nazi Germany', 'Regime') -> Nazi Germany] were sent to [dblookup('Nazi Germany', 'Use of Concentration Camps') -> concentration camps] and held prisoner there until their [dblookup('Concentration Camps', 'Prisoner Fate') -> death or liberation] death or liberation.
examples.text: East_Prussia: In 1938 the Nazis altered about one-third of the toponyms of the area, eliminating, Germanizing, or simplifying a number of Old Prussian names, as well as those Polish or Lithuanian names originating from colonists and refugees to Prussia during and after the Protestant Reformation. Many who would not cooperate with the rulers of Nazi Germany were sent to concentration camps and held prisoner there until their death or liberation.

examples.annotated_text: University_of_Notre_Dame: Besides its prominence in sports, [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Type') -> large, four-year, highly residential research university] Notre Dame is also a large, four-year, highly residential research University, and is [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Ranking in USA') -> top twenty universities in the United States] consistently ranked among the top twenty universities in the United States and as a [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Reputation') -> major global university] major global university. The latter is known for teaching New Classical Architecture and for [dblookup('Architecture School of University of Notre Dame', 'Award') -> Driehaus Architecture Prize] awarding the globally renowned annual Driehaus Architecture Prize. Notre Dame's graduate program has more than [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Graduate Programs Count') -> 50] 50 master's, doctoral and professional degree programs offered by the five schools, with the addition of the [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Graduate Schools') -> Notre Dame Law School, MD-PhD program with IU Medical School] Notre Dame Law School and a MD-PhD program offered in combination with IU medical School. It maintains a system of libraries, cultural venues, artistic and scientific museums, including [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Libraries and Museums') -> Hesburgh Library, Snite Museum of Art] Hesburgh Library and the Snite Museum of Art. Over [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'On-Campus Housing Percentage') -> 80%] 80% of the university's 8,000 undergraduates live on campus in one of [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Residential Halls Count') -> 29] 29 single-sex residence halls, each with its own traditions, legacies, events and intramural sports teams. The university counts approximately [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Alumni Count') -> 120,000] 120,000 alumni, considered among [dblookup('University of Notre Dame', 'Alumni Network') -> strongest among U.S. colleges] the strongest alumni networks among U.S. colleges.
examples.text: University_of_Notre_Dame: Besides its prominence in sports, Notre Dame is also a large, four-year, highly residential research University, and is consistently ranked among the top twenty universities in the United States  and as a major global university. The undergraduate component of the university is organized into four colleges (Arts and Letters, Science, Engineering, Business) and the Architecture School. The latter is known for teaching New Classical Architecture and for awarding the globally renowned annual Driehaus Architecture Prize. Notre Dame's graduate program has more than 50 master's, doctoral and professional degree programs offered by the five schools, with the addition of the Notre Dame Law School and a MD-PhD program offered in combination with IU medical School. It maintains a system of libraries, cultural venues, artistic and scientific museums, including Hesburgh Library and the Snite Museum of Art. Over 80% of the university's 8,000 undergraduates live on campus in one of 29 single-sex residence halls, each with its own traditions, legacies, events and intramural sports teams. The university counts approximately 120,000 alumni, considered among the strongest alumni networks among U.S. colleges.

examples.annotated_text: Comics: Specialized comics periodicals formats vary greatly in different cultures. [dblookup('Comic Books', 'Primary Format') -> American] Comic books, primarily an American format, are [dblookup('Comic Books', 'Physical Format') -> thin periodicals] thin periodicals usually published in [dblookup('Comic Books', 'Color Format') -> colour] colour. [dblookup('European Comics', 'Publication Frequency') -> monthly or weekly] European and [dblookup('Japanese Comics', 'Publication Frequency') -> weekly] Japanese comics are frequently serialized in magazines—monthly or weekly in Europe, and usually [dblookup('Japanese Comics', 'Color Format') -> black-and-white] black-and-white and weekly in Japan. examples.text: Comics: Specialized comics periodicals formats vary greatly in different cultures. Comic books, primarily an American format, are thin periodicals usually published in colour. examples.annotated_text: Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union: In the first session of the new [dblookup('Congress of People\'s Deputies', 'Initial Session Dates') -> May 25 to June 9, 1989] Congress of People's Deputies, from May 25 to June 9, hardliners retained control but reformers used the legislature as a platform for debate and criticism – which was broadcast live and uncensored. This transfixed the population; nothing like this freewheeling debate had ever been witnessed in the [dblookup('U.S.S.R.', 'Feature') -> Live Uncensored Broadcast of Debate] U.S.S.R. On May 29, [dblookup('Boris Yeltsin', 'Position Acquired') -> Seat on the Supreme Soviet] Yeltsin managed to secure a seat on the Supreme Soviet, and in the summer he formed [dblookup('Inter-Regional Deputies Group', 'Formed By') -> Boris Yeltsin] the first opposition, the Inter-Regional Deputies Group, composed of Russian nationalists and liberals. Composing the final legislative group in the [dblookup('Soviet Union', 'Final Elected Legislative Group Year') -> 1989] Soviet Union, those elected in 1989 played a vital part in [dblookup('Soviet Union', 'Contributions to Final Years') -> Reforms and Breakup] reforms and the eventual breakup of the Soviet Union during the next two years.
examples.text: Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union: In the first session of the new Congress of People's Deputies, from May 25 to June 9, hardliners retained control but reformers used the legislature as a platform for debate and criticism – which was broadcast live and uncensored. This transfixed the population; nothing like this freewheeling debate had ever been witnessed in the U.S.S.R. On May 29, Yeltsin managed to secure a seat on the Supreme Soviet, and in the summer he formed the first opposition, the Inter-Regional Deputies Group, composed of Russian nationalists and liberals. Composing the final legislative group in the Soviet Union, those elected in 1989 played a vital part in reforms and the eventual breakup of the Soviet Union during the next two years.

examples.annotated_text: After a lengthy period of formal racial segregation in the former Confederacy following the Reconstruction Era, and bans on interracial marriage in various parts of the country, more people are openly forming interracial unions. In addition, social conditions have changed and many multiracial people do not believe it is socially advantageous to try to "pass" as white. [dblookup('United States', 'Demographic Change') -> Diverse Immigration] Diverse immigration has brought more mixed-race people into the United States, such as the large population of [dblookup('Hispanics', 'Subgroup') -> Mestizos] Hispanics identifying as mestizos. examples.text: Multiracial_American: After a lengthy period of formal racial segregation in the former Confederacy following the Reconstruction Era, and bans on interracial marriage in various parts of the country, more people are openly forming interracial unions. examples.text: Sahara: The South Saharan steppe and woodlands ecoregion is a narrow band running east and west between the hyper-arid Sahara and the Sahel savannas to the south. examples.text: LaserDisc: By the early 2000s, LaserDisc was completely replaced by DVD in the North American retail marketplace, as neither players nor software were then produced. examples.annotated_text: In the Union of Utrecht of [dblookup('Union of Utrecht', 'Date Signed') -> 20 January 1579] 20 January 1579, [dblookup('Union of Utrecht', 'Religious Rights Granted To') -> Holland, Zeeland] Holland and Zeeland were granted the right to accept only one religion (in practice, [dblookup('Holland and Zeeland', 'Accepted Religion') -> Calvinism] Calvinism). examples.text: Dutch_Republic: In the Union of Utrecht of 20 January 1579, Holland and Zeeland were granted the right to accept only one religion (in practice, Calvinism). examples.annotated_text: East_Prussia: Upon the invitation of [dblookup('Duke Konrad I of Masovia', 'Invited By') -> Duke Konrad I of Masovia] Duke Konrad I of Masovia, the [dblookup('Teutonic Knights', 'Took Possession Of') -> Prussia] Teutonic Knights took possession of Prussia in the [dblookup('Teutonic Knights', 'Took Possession Era') -> 13th century] 13th century and created a monastic state to administer the conquered Old Prussians. examples.text: East_Prussia: Upon the invitation of Duke Konrad I of Masovia, the Teutonic Knights took possession of Prussia in the 13th century and created a monastic state to administer the conquered Old Prussians. Local Old-Prussian (north) and Polish (south) toponyms were gradually Germanised. The Knights' expansionist policies, including occupation of Polish Pomerania with Gdańsk/Danzig and western Lithuania, brought them into conflict with the Kingdom of Poland and embroiled them in several wars, culminating in the Polish-Lithuanian-Teutonic War, whereby the united armies of Poland and Lithuania, defeated the Teutonic Order at the Battle of Grunwald (Tannenberg) in 1410. examples.text: Quran: The proper recitation of the Quran is the subject of a separate discipline named tajwid which determines in detail how the Quran should be recited, how each individual syllable is to be pronounced, the need to pay attention to the places where there should be a pause, to elisions, where the pronunciation should be long or short, where letters should be sounded together and where they should be kept separate, etc. It may be said that this discipline studies the laws and methods of the proper recitation of the Quran and covers three main areas: the proper pronunciation of consonants and vowels (the articulation of the Quranic phonemes), the rules of pause in recitation and of resumption of recitation, and the musical and melodious features of recitation.

examples.annotated_text: Flowering_plant: Agriculture is almost entirely dependent on [dblookup('Angiosperms', 'Dependency On By') -> agriculture] angiosperms, which provide virtually all plant-based food, and also provide a significant amount of livestock feed. Also of high importance are the Solanaceae, or nightshade family (potatoes, tomatoes, and peppers, among others), the [dblookup('Cucurbitaceae', 'Includes') -> pumpkins, melons] Cucurbitaceae, or gourd family (also including pumpkins and melons), the [dblookup('Brassicaceae', 'Includes') -> rapeseed] Brassicaceae, or mustard plant family (including rapeseed and the innumerable varieties of the cabbage species Brassica oleracea), and the [dblookup('Apiaceae', 'Common Name') -> parsley family] Apiaceae, or parsley family. Many of our fruits come from the [dblookup('Rutaceae', 'Includes') -> oranges, lemons, grapefruits] Rutaceae, or rue family (including oranges, lemons, grapefruits, etc.), and the [dblookup('Rosaceae', 'Includes') -> apples, pears, cherries, apricots, plums] Rosaceae, or rose family (including apples, pears, cherries, apricots, plums, etc.).
