examples.annotated_text: Biodiversity: Biodiversity's [dblookup('Biodiversity', 'Relevance To') -> human health] relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss. This issue is closely linked with [dblookup('Biodiversity', 'Link To') -> climate change] the issue of climate change, as many of the anticipated health risks of climate change are associated with changes in biodiversity (e.g., changes in populations and distribution of disease vectors, scarcity of fresh water, impacts on agricultural biodiversity and food resources, etc.). This is because the species most likely to disappear are those that buffer against infectious disease transmission, while surviving species tend to be the ones that increase disease transmission, such as that of [dblookup('West Nile Virus', 'Association With') -> biodiversity loss] West Nile Virus, Lyme disease, and [dblookup('Drew Harvell', 'Affiliation') -> Cornell University] Hantavirus, according to a study co-authored by Felicia Keesing, an ecologist at Bard College, and Drew Harvell, associate director for Environment of the Atkinson Center for a Sustainable Future (ACSF) at Cornell University.
examples.text: Biodiversity: Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss. This issue is closely linked with the issue of climate change, as many of the anticipated health risks of climate change are associated with changes in biodiversity (e.g. changes in populations and distribution of disease vectors, scarcity of fresh water, impacts on agricultural biodiversity and food resources etc.) This is because the species most likely to disappear are those that buffer against infectious disease transmission, while surviving species tend to be the ones that increase disease transmission, such as that of West Nile Virus, Lyme disease and Hantavirus, according to a study done co-authored by Felicia Keesing, an ecologist at Bard College, and Drew Harvell, associate director for Environment of the Atkinson Center for a Sustainable Future (ACSF) at Cornell University.

examples.annotated_text: Norfolk_Island: As a relatively small and isolated oceanic island, Norfolk [dblookup('Norfolk Island', 'Geographic Characteristic') -> isolated oceanic island] has few land birds but a high degree of [dblookup('Norfolk Island', 'Endemic Species Characteristic') -> high degree of endemicity] endemicity among them. Many of the [dblookup('Norfolk Island land birds', 'Extinction Cause') -> massive clearance of native vegetation] endemic species and subspecies have become extinct as a result of massive clearance of the island's native vegetation of subtropical rainforest for agriculture, hunting and persecution as agricultural pests. The birds have also suffered from the introduction of [dblookup('Norfolk Island', 'Introduced Mammals') -> rats, cats, pigs, goats] mammals such as rats, cats, pigs, and goats, as well as from introduced competitors such as [dblookup('Norfolk Island', 'Introduced Competitors') -> common blackbirds, crimson rosellas] common blackbirds and crimson rosellas.
examples.text: Norfolk_Island: As a relatively small and isolated oceanic island, Norfolk has few land birds but a high degree of endemicity among them. Many of the endemic species and subspecies have become extinct as a result of massive clearance of the island's native vegetation of subtropical rainforest for agriculture, hunting and persecution as agricultural pests. The birds have also suffered from the introduction of mammals such as rats, cats, pigs and goats, as well as from introduced competitors such as common blackbirds and crimson rosellas.

examples.annotated_text: Yale_University: In 1966, Yale began discussions with its sister school [dblookup('Yale University', 'Coeducation Merger Proposal') -> Vassar College] Vassar College about merging to foster coeducation at the undergraduate level. Vassar, then all-female and part of the [dblookup('Vassar College', 'Seven Sisters Membership') -> Seven Sisters] Seven Sisters—elite higher education schools that historically served as sister institutions to the Ivy League when the Ivy League still only admitted men—tentatively accepted, but then declined the invitation. Both schools introduced [dblookup('Yale University', 'Year Coeducation Began') -> 1969] coeducation independently in 1969. Amy Solomon was the first woman to register as a Yale undergraduate; she was also the first woman at [dblookup('Amy Solomon', 'First Undergraduate Society at Yale') -> St. Anthony Hall] Yale to join an undergraduate society, St. Anthony Hall. The undergraduate class of [dblookup('Yale University', 'First Coeducational Class Year') -> 1973] 1973 was the first class to have women starting from freshman year; at the time, all undergraduate women were housed in [dblookup('Yale University', 'Initial Female Housing') -> Vanderbilt Hall] Vanderbilt Hall at the south end of Old Campus.[citation needed]
examples.text: Yale_University: In 1966, Yale began discussions with its sister school Vassar College about merging to foster coeducation at the undergraduate level. Vassar, then all-female and part of the Seven Sisters—elite higher education schools that historically served as sister institutions to the Ivy League when the Ivy League still only admitted men—tentatively accepted, but then declined the invitation. Both schools introduced coeducation independently in 1969. Amy Solomon was the first woman to register as a Yale undergraduate; she was also the first woman at Yale to join an undergraduate society, St. Anthony Hall. The undergraduate class of 1973 was the first class to have women starting from freshman year; at the time, all undergraduate women were housed in Vanderbilt Hall at the south end of Old Campus.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Palermo: Being [dblookup('Palermo', 'Administrative Level') -> Sicily's administrative capital] Sicily's administrative capital, Palermo is a centre for much of the region's finance, tourism, and commerce. The economy mainly relies on [dblookup('Palermo', 'Economic Reliance') -> tourism and services] tourism and services, but also has commerce, shipbuilding, and agriculture. The city, however, still has [dblookup('Palermo', 'Challenges') -> high unemployment, high corruption, significant black market] high unemployment levels, high corruption, and a significant black market empire (Palermo being the home of the [dblookup('Palermo', 'Crime Organization') -> Sicilian Mafia] Sicilian Mafia). Even though the city still suffers from widespread corruption, inefficient bureaucracy, and organized crime, the level of crime in Palermo's has gone down dramatically, unemployment has been decreasing and many new, profitable opportunities for growth (especially regarding tourism) have been introduced, making the city safer and better to live in.

examples.annotated_text: Greeks: The total number of Greeks living outside [dblookup('Greeks', 'Countries of Origin') -> Greece, Cyprus] Greece and Cyprus today is a contentious issue. Where Census figures are available, they show around [dblookup('Greeks Outside Greece and Cyprus', 'Census Estimate') -> 3 million] 3 million Greeks outside Greece and Cyprus. Estimates provided by the [dblookup('SAE - World Council of Hellenes Abroad', 'Estimate of Greeks Outside Greece and Cyprus') -> 7 million] SAE - World Council of Hellenes Abroad put the figure at around 7 million worldwide. According to George Prevelakis of [dblookup('George Prevelakis', 'Affiliation') -> Sorbonne University] Sorbonne University, the number is closer to just below [dblookup('George Prevelakis', 'Estimate of Greeks Outside Greece and Cyprus') -> 5 million] 5 million. Integration, intermarriage, and loss of the Greek language influence the self-identification of the Omogeneia. Important centres of the New Greek Diaspora today are [dblookup('New Greek Diaspora', 'Prominent Cities') -> London, New York, Melbourne, Toronto] London, New York, Melbourne, and Toronto. In 2010, the [dblookup('Hellenic Parliament', 'Enacted Law in 2010') -> Law for Diaspora Greeks Voting Rights] Hellenic Parliament introduced a law that enables Diaspora Greeks in Greece to vote in the elections of the Greek state. This law was later [dblookup('Law for Diaspora Greeks Voting Rights', 'Repealed') -> early 2014] repealed in early 2014.
examples.text: Greeks: The total number of Greeks living outside Greece and Cyprus today is a contentious issue. Where Census figures are available, they show around 3 million Greeks outside Greece and Cyprus. Estimates provided by the SAE - World Council of Hellenes Abroad put the figure at around 7 million worldwide. According to George Prevelakis of Sorbonne University, the number is closer to just below 5 million. Integration, intermarriage, and loss of the Greek language influence the self-identification of the Omogeneia. Important centres of the New Greek Diaspora today are London, New York, Melbourne and Toronto. In 2010, the Hellenic Parliament introduced a law that enables Diaspora Greeks in Greece to vote in the elections of the Greek state. This law was later repealed in early 2014.

examples.annotated_text: Utrecht: When the Frankish rulers established the system of feudalism, the Bishops of Utrecht came to exercise worldly power as prince-bishops. The territory of the bishopric not only included the modern [dblookup('Bishopric of Utrecht', 'Modern Province Included') -> Utrecht] province of Utrecht (Nedersticht, 'lower Sticht'), but also extended to the northeast. The [dblookup('Prince-Bishopric of Utrecht', 'Conflict With') -> Counts of Holland, Dukes of Guelders] prince-bishopric was involved in almost continuous conflicts with the Counts of Holland and the Dukes of Guelders. The [dblookup('Veluwe Region', 'Seized By') -> Guelders] Veluwe region was seized by Guelders, but large areas in the modern province of [dblookup('Overijssel', 'Region Retained') -> Oversticht] Overijssel remained as the Oversticht.

examples.annotated_text: Strasbourg: In [dblookup('Strasbourg', 'Council of Europe Seat Since') -> 1949] 1949, the city was chosen to be the [dblookup('Council of Europe', 'Headquarters') -> Strasbourg] seat of the Council of Europe with its European Court of Human Rights and European Pharmacopoeia. Since [dblookup('European Parliament', 'Meeting in Strasbourg Since') -> 1952] 1952, the European Parliament has met in Strasbourg, which was formally [dblookup('Strasbourg', 'Official European Parliament Seat Designation') -> December 1992] designated its official 'seat' at the Edinburgh meeting of the European Council of EU heads of state and government in December 1992. (This position was reconfirmed and given treaty status in the [dblookup('European Parliament', 'Treaty Status') -> 1997 Treaty of Amsterdam] 1997 Treaty of Amsterdam). However, only the (four-day) plenary sessions of the Parliament are held in Strasbourg each month, with all other [dblookup('European Parliament', 'Other Business Conducted In') -> Brussels, Luxembourg] business being conducted in Brussels and Luxembourg. Those sessions take place in the [dblookup('Immeuble Louise Weiss', 'Inauguration Year') -> 1999] Immeuble Louise Weiss, inaugurated in 1999, which houses the [dblookup('Immeuble Louise Weiss', 'Largest Assembly Room') -> Parliamentary Assembly Room] largest parliamentary assembly room in Europe and of any democratic institution in the world. Before that, the EP sessions had to take place in the main Council of Europe building, the [dblookup('Palace of Europe', 'Council of Europe Building') -> Palace of Europe] Palace of Europe, whose unusual inner architecture had become a familiar sight to European TV audiences. In 1992, Strasbourg became the seat of the Franco-German TV channel and movie-production society Arte.
examples.text: Strasbourg: In 1949, the city was chosen to be the seat of the Council of Europe with its European Court of Human Rights and European Pharmacopoeia. Since 1952, the European Parliament has met in Strasbourg, which was formally designated its official 'seat' at the Edinburgh meeting of the European Council of EU heads of state and government in December 1992. (This position was reconfirmed and given treaty status in the 1997 Treaty of Amsterdam). However, only the (four-day) plenary sessions of the Parliament are held in Strasbourg each month, with all other business being conducted in Brussels and Luxembourg. Those sessions take place in the Immeuble Louise Weiss, inaugurated in 1999, which houses the largest parliamentary assembly room in Europe and of any democratic institution in the world. Before that, the EP sessions had to take place in the main Council of Europe building, the Palace of Europe, whose unusual inner architecture had become a familiar sight to European TV audiences. In 1992, Strasbourg became the seat of the Franco-German TV channel and movie-production society Arte.

The name is derived from the encounter of the three federal branches around the plaza: the Executive, represented by the [dblookup('Executive Branch of Brazil', 'Office Building') -> Palácio do Planalto] Palácio do Planalto (presidential office); the Legislative, represented by the [dblookup('Legislative Branch of Brazil', 'Building') -> National Congress] National Congress (Congresso Nacional); and the Judicial branch, represented by the [dblookup('Judicial Branch of Brazil', 'Supreme Court') -> Supreme Federal Court] Supreme Federal Court (Supremo Tribunal Federal). It is a [dblookup('Praça dos Três Poderes', 'Tourist Status') -> tourist attraction] tourist attraction in Brasília, designed by [dblookup('Praça dos Três Poderes', 'Designer 1') -> Lúcio Costa] Lúcio Costa and [dblookup('Praça dos Três Poderes', 'Designer 2') -> Oscar Niemeyer] Oscar Niemeyer as a place where the three branches would meet harmoniously.
examples.text: Bras%C3%ADlia: Praça dos Três Poderes (Portuguese for Square of the Three Powers) is a plaza in Brasília. The name is derived from the encounter of the three federal branches around the plaza: the Executive, represented by the Palácio do Planalto (presidential office); the Legislative, represented by the National Congress (Congresso Nacional); and the Judicial branch, represented by the Supreme Federal Court (Supremo Tribunal Federal). examples.annotated_text: Unicode: Thousands of fonts exist on the market, but fewer than a dozen [dblookup('Pan-Unicode Fonts', 'Approximate Number') -> fewer than a dozen] fonts—sometimes described as "pan-Unicode" fonts—attempt to support the majority of Unicode's character repertoire. Instead, Unicode-based fonts typically focus on supporting only basic ASCII and [dblookup('Unicode-Based Fonts', 'Focus On') -> particular scripts or sets of characters or symbols] particular scripts or sets of characters or symbols. Several reasons justify this approach: applications and documents rarely [dblookup('Applications and Documents', 'Need') -> render characters from more than one or two writing systems] need to render characters from more than one or two writing systems; fonts tend to demand resources in computing environments; and operating systems and applications show increasing intelligence in regard to obtaining glyph information from separate font files as needed, i.e., font substitution. Furthermore, designing a consistent set of rendering instructions for tens of thousands of glyphs constitutes a monumental task; such a venture passes the point of diminishing returns for most typefaces.
examples.text: Unicode: Thousands of fonts exist on the market, but fewer than a dozen fonts—sometimes described as "pan-Unicode" fonts—attempt to support the majority of Unicode's character repertoire. Instead, Unicode-based fonts typically focus on supporting only basic ASCII and particular scripts or sets of characters or symbols. Several reasons justify this approach: applications and documents rarely need to render characters from more than one or two writing systems; fonts tend to demand resources in computing environments; and operating systems and applications show increasing intelligence in regard to obtaining glyph information from separate font files as needed, i.e., font substitution. Furthermore, designing a consistent set of rendering instructions for tens of thousands of glyphs constitutes a monumental task; such a venture passes the point of diminishing returns for most typefaces.

This era also saw more glam-infused American hard rock bands come to the forefront, with both [dblookup('Poison', 'Debut Album') -> Look What the Cat Dragged In] Poison and [dblookup('Cinderella', 'Debut Album') -> Night Songs] Cinderella releasing their multi-platinum début albums in 1986. [dblookup('Van Halen', 'First Album with Sammy Hagar') -> 5150] Van Halen released 5150 (1986), their first album with Sammy Hagar on lead vocals, which was [dblookup('5150', 'US Number One Duration') -> three weeks] number one in the US for three weeks and sold over [dblookup('5150', 'US Sales') -> 6 million copies] 6 million copies. examples.text: Hard_rock: Bon Jovi's third album, Slippery When Wet (1986), mixed hard rock with a pop sensitivity and spent a total of 8 weeks at the top of the Billboard 200 album chart, selling 12 million copies in the US while becoming the first hard rock album to spawn three top 10 singles — two of which reached number one. The album has been credited with widening the audiences for the genre, particularly by appealing to women as well as the traditional male dominated audience, and opening the door to MTV and commercial success for other bands at the end of the decade. Van Halen released 5150 (1986), their first album with Sammy Hagar on lead vocals, which was number one in the US for three weeks and sold over 6 million copies. By the second half of the decade, hard rock had become the most reliable form of commercial popular music in the United States.

examples.text: Red: Red hair varies from a deep burgundy through burnt orange to bright copper. The Portugal–Spain border is [dblookup('Portugal–Spain Border', 'Length') -> 1,214 km (754 mi)] 1,214 km (754 mi) long and considered the longest uninterrupted border within the [dblookup('Portugal–Spain Border', 'Region') -> European Union] European Union. examples.text: Portugal: Portugal (Portuguese: [puɾtuˈɣaɫ]), officially the Portuguese Republic (Portuguese: República Portuguesa), is a country on the Iberian Peninsula, in Southwestern Europe. It is the westernmost country of mainland Europe, being bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the west and south and by Spain to the north and east. The Portugal–Spain border is 1,214 km (754 mi) long and considered the longest uninterrupted border within the European Union. The republic also includes the Atlantic archipelagos of the Azores and Madeira, both autonomous regions with their own regional governments.

examples.annotated_text: Federalism: On one hand, this means that the Belgian political landscape, generally speaking, consists of only two components: the Dutch-speaking population represented by Dutch-language political parties, and the majority populations of Wallonia and Brussels, represented by their French-speaking parties. The [dblookup('Brussels', 'Position In Belgian Federalism') -> third component] Brussels region emerges as a third component. This specific [dblookup('Belgian Federalism', 'Type') -> dual federalism] dual form of federalism, with the special position of Brussels, consequently has a number of political issues—even minor ones—that are being fought out over the Dutch/French-language political division. With such issues, a final decision is possible only in the form of a compromise. This tendency gives this dual federalism model a number of traits that generally are ascribed to confederalism, and makes the future of Belgian federalism contentious.

examples.text: John,_King_of_England: The political turmoil continued. John began to explore an alliance with the French king Philip II, freshly returned from the crusade. John hoped to acquire Normandy, Anjou and the other lands in France held by Richard in exchange for allying himself with Philip. John was persuaded not to pursue an alliance by his mother. Longchamp, who had left England after Walter's intervention, now returned, and argued that he had been wrongly removed as justiciar. When Richard still did not return from the crusade, John began to assert that his brother was dead or otherwise permanently lost. Fighting broke out in England between forces loyal to Richard and those being gathered by John. John's military position was weak and he agreed to a truce; in early 1194 the king finally returned to England, and John's remaining forces surrendered. John retreated to Normandy, where Richard finally found him later that year. Richard declared that his younger brother – despite being 27 years old – was merely "a child who has had evil counsellors" and forgave him, but removed his lands with the exception of Ireland.

examples.annotated_text: Elevator: In most US and Canadian jurisdictions, passenger elevators are required to conform to the [dblookup('American Society of Mechanical Engineers', 'Elevator Standard') -> A17.1 Safety Code for Elevators and Escalators] American Society of Mechanical Engineers' Standard A17.1, Safety Code for Elevators and Escalators. In addition, passenger elevators may be required to conform to the requirements of [dblookup('ASME', 'Existing Elevator Standard') -> A17.3 Standard] A17.3 for existing elevators where referenced by the local jurisdiction. Passenger elevators are tested using the [dblookup('ASME', 'Elevator Testing Standard') -> A17.2 Standard] ASME A17.2 Standard. examples.text: Elevator: In most US and Canadian jurisdictions, passenger elevators are required to conform to the American Society of Mechanical Engineers' Standard A17.1, Safety Code for Elevators and Escalators. examples.annotated_text: Bermuda: The island was administered as an extension of Virginia by the [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Administered By') -> Company of Virginia] Company until 1614. Its spin-off, [dblookup('Somers Isles Company', 'Took Over Administration') -> 1615] the Somers Isles Company, took over in 1615 and managed the colony until [dblookup('Somers Isles Company', 'Charter Revoked') -> 1684] 1684. At that time, the company's charter was revoked, and the [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Administration Taken Over By') -> English Crown] English Crown took over administration. The islands became a [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Became British Colony') -> 1707] British colony following the 1707 unification of the parliaments of Scotland and England, which created the [dblookup('Kingdom of Great Britain', 'Established') -> 1707] Kingdom of Great Britain. After 1949, when Newfoundland became part of Canada, Bermuda was automatically ranked as the [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Oldest Remaining British Overseas Territory After') -> 1949] oldest remaining British Overseas Territory. Since the return of Hong Kong to China in 1997, it is the [dblookup('Bermuda', 'Most Populous British Overseas Territory After') -> 1997] most populous Territory. Its first capital, [dblookup('St. George\'s, Bermuda', 'Established') -> 1612] St. George's, was established in 1612 and is the [dblookup('St. George\'s, Bermuda', 'Oldest Continuously Inhabited English Town in New World') -> True] oldest continuously inhabited English town in the New World.
examples.text: Bermuda: The island was administered as an extension of Virginia by the Company until 1614. Its spin-off, the Somers Isles Company, took over in 1615 and managed the colony until 1684. At that time, the company's charter was revoked, and the English Crown took over administration. The islands became a British colony following the 1707 unification of the parliaments of Scotland and England, which created the Kingdom of Great Britain. After 1949, when Newfoundland became part of Canada, Bermuda was automatically ranked as the oldest remaining British Overseas Territory. Since the return of Hong Kong to China in 1997, it is the most populous Territory. Its first capital, St. George's, was established in 1612 and is the oldest continuously inhabited English town in the New World.

examples.text: Economy_of_Greece: Most of the differences in the revised budget deficit numbers were due to a temporary change of accounting practices by the new government, i.e., recording expenses when military material was ordered rather than received. However, it was the retroactive application of ESA95 methodology (applied since 2000) by Eurostat, that finally raised the reference year (1999) budget deficit to 3.38% of GDP, thus exceeding the 3% limit. This led to claims that Greece (similar claims have been made about other European countries like Italy) had not actually met all five accession criteria, and the common perception that Greece entered the Eurozone through "falsified" deficit numbers.

examples.text: Spectre_(2015_film): In the United Kingdom, the film grossed £4.1 million ($6.4 million) from its Monday preview screenings. It grossed £6.3 million ($9.2 million) on its opening day and then £5.7 million ($8.8 million) on Wednesday, setting UK records for both days. examples.annotated_text: Mammal: When endothermy [dblookup('Endothermy', 'First Appearance in Evolution') -> Uncertain] first appeared in the evolution of mammals is uncertain. Modern monotremes have lower body temperatures and more variable metabolic rates than marsupials and placentals, but there is evidence that some of their ancestors, perhaps including ancestors of the therians, may have had body temperatures like those of modern therians. Some of the evidence found so far suggests that [dblookup('Triassic Cynodonts', 'Metabolic Rates') -> High] Triassic cynodonts had fairly high metabolic rates, but it is not conclusive. For small animals, an insulative covering like fur is necessary for the maintenance of a high and stable body temperature.

examples.annotated_text: Norfolk_Island: It was announced on [dblookup('Norfolk Island', 'Self-Governance Revoked Date') -> March 19, 2015] 19 March 2015 that self-governance for the island would be revoked by the [dblookup('Norfolk Island', 'Governing Entity Post-2015') -> Commonwealth of Australia] Commonwealth and replaced by a local council with the [dblookup('New South Wales', 'Role for Norfolk Island Post-2015') -> Providing services to the island] state of New South Wales providing services to the island. examples.text: Norfolk_Island: It was announced on 19 March 2015 that self-governance for the island would be revoked by the Commonwealth and replaced by a local council with the state of New South Wales providing services to the island. examples.annotated_text: Database: Physically, database servers are dedicated computers that hold the actual databases and run only the DBMS and related software. Database servers are usually [dblookup('Database Servers', 'Typical Configuration') -> multiprocessor computers with generous memory and RAID disk arrays] multiprocessor computers, with generous memory and RAID disk arrays used for [dblookup('RAID', 'Purpose') -> stable storage] stable storage. [dblookup('RAID', 'Used For') -> recovery of data if any disk fails] RAID is used for recovery of data if any of the disks fail. Hardware database accelerators, connected to one or more servers via a high-speed channel, are also used in large volume transaction processing environments. DBMSs are found at the heart of most database applications. DBMSs may be built around a custom multitasking kernel with built-in networking support, but modern DBMSs typically rely on a standard operating system to provide these functions. Before the inception of [dblookup('SQL', 'Introduction Impact') -> standardized method for data fetching and structuring] Structured Query Language (SQL), the data recovered was disparate, redundant, and disorderly, since there was no proper method to fetch it and arrange it in a concrete structure.

examples.text: Detroit: Lafayette Park is a revitalized neighborhood on the city's east side, part of the Ludwig Mies van der Rohe residential district. examples.annotated_text: Communications_in_Somalia: In [dblookup('Somalia', 'First Fiber Optic Connection Year') -> November 2013] November 2013, Somalia received its first fiber optic connection. The country previously had to rely on expensive satellite links due to the civil conflict, which limited internet usage. However, residents now have access to broadband internet cable for the first time after [dblookup('Hormuud Telecom', 'Agreement With') -> Liquid Telecom] an agreement reached between Hormuud Telecom and Liquid Telecom. The deal will see [dblookup('Liquid Telecom', 'Network Length') -> 17,000 km (10,500 mile)] Liquid Telecom link Hormuud to its 17,000 km (10,500 mile) network of terrestrial cables, which will deliver faster internet capacity. The fiber optic connection will also make online access more affordable to the average user. This in turn is expected to further increase the number of internet users. [dblookup('Dalkom Somalia', 'Agreement With') -> West Indian Ocean Cable Company (WIOCC) Ltd] Dalkom Somalia reached a similar agreement with the West Indian Ocean Cable Company (WIOCC) Ltd, which it holds shares in. Effective the [dblookup('Dalkom Somalia and WIOCC', 'Agreement Effective Date') -> first quarter of 2014] first quarter of 2014, the deal will establish fiber optic connectivity to and from Somalia via the [dblookup('EASSy cable', 'Connectivity Involved Parties') -> Dalkom Somalia, WIOCC Ltd] EASSy cable. The new services are expected to reduce the cost of international bandwidth and to better optimize performance, thereby further broadening internet access. [dblookup('Dalkom Somalia', 'Data Center Location') -> Mogadishu] Dalkom Somalia is concurrently constructing a 1,000 square mile state-of-the-art data center in Mogadishu. The site will facilitate direct connection into the international fiber optic network by hosting equipment for all of the capital's ISPs and telecommunication companies.
examples.text: Communications_in_Somalia: In November 2013, Somalia received its first fiber optic connection. The country previously had to rely on expensive satellite links due to the civil conflict, which limited internet usage. However, residents now have access to broadband internet cable for the first time after an agreement reached between Hormuud Telecom and Liquid Telecom. The deal will see Liquid Telecom link Hormuud to its 17,000 km (10,500 mile) network of terrestrial cables, which will deliver faster internet capacity. The fiber optic connection will also make online access more affordable to the average user. This in turn is expected to further increase the number of internet users. Dalkom Somalia reached a similar agreement with the West Indian Ocean Cable Company (WIOCC) Ltd, which it holds shares in. Effective the first quarter of 2014, the deal will establish fiber optic connectivity to and from Somalia via the EASSy cable. The new services are expected to reduce the cost of international bandwidth and to better optimize performance, thereby further broadening internet access. Dalkom Somalia is concurrently constructing a 1,000 square mile state-of-the-art data center in Mogadishu. The site will facilitate direct connection into the international fiber optic network by hosting equipment for all of the capital's ISPs and telecommunication companies.

examples.annotated_text: Race (human categorization): The concept of racial origin relies on the notion that human beings can be separated into biologically distinct "races", an [dblookup('Concept of Race', 'Scientific Community Acceptance') -> generally rejected by the scientific community] idea generally rejected by the scientific community. Since all human beings belong to the same species, the [dblookup('European Commission against Racism and Intolerance', 'Position on Race Theories') -> rejects theories based on the existence of different "races"] ECRI (European Commission against Racism and Intolerance) rejects theories based on the existence of different "races". However, in its [dblookup('European Commission against Racism and Intolerance', 'Document Using Term "Race"') -> Recommendation] Recommendation ECRI uses this term in order to ensure that those persons who are generally and erroneously perceived as belonging to "another race" are not excluded from the protection provided for by the legislation. The [dblookup('Law', 'Position on Existence of "Race"') -> claims to reject] law claims to reject the existence of "race", yet penalize situations where someone is treated less favourably on this ground.
examples.text: Race_(human_categorization): The concept of racial origin relies on the notion that human beings can be separated into biologically distinct "races", an idea generally rejected by the scientific community. examples.annotated_text: Military_history_of_the_United_States: The [dblookup('Korean War', 'Parties Involved') -> United States, United Nations Allies, Communist Powers] Korean War was a conflict between the United States and its United Nations allies and the communist powers under the influence of the Soviet Union (also a UN member nation) and the People's Republic of China (which later also gained UN membership). Principal allies of South Korea included the [dblookup('South Korea', 'Allies During Korean War') -> United States, Canada, Australia, United Kingdom] United States, Canada, Australia, the United Kingdom, although many other nations sent troops under the aegis of the United Nations. Allies of North Korea included the [dblookup('North Korea', 'Allies During Korean War') -> People's Republic of China, Soviet Union] People's Republic of China, which supplied military forces, and the Soviet Union, which supplied combat advisors and aircraft pilots, as well as arms, for the Chinese and North Korean troops.
examples.text: Military_history_of_the_United_States: The Korean War was a conflict between the United States and its United Nations allies and the communist powers under influence of the Soviet Union (also a UN member nation) and the People's Republic of China (which later also gained UN membership). The principal combatants were North and South Korea. Principal allies of South Korea included the United States, Canada, Australia, the United Kingdom, although many other nations sent troops under the aegis of the United Nations. Allies of North Korea included the People's Republic of China, which supplied military forces, and the Soviet Union, which supplied combat advisors and aircraft pilots, as well as arms, for the Chinese and North Korean troops.

examples.annotated_text: Department_store: France's major upscale department stores are [dblookup('Galeries Lafayette', 'Flagship Location') -> Boulevard Haussmann, Paris] Galeries Lafayette and [dblookup('Le Printemps', 'Flagship Location') -> Boulevard Haussmann, Paris] Le Printemps, which both have flagship stores on Boulevard Haussmann in Paris and branches around the country. examples.annotated_text: Literature: In the Age of Reason philosophical tracts and speculations on history and human nature integrated literature with [dblookup('Age of Reason', 'Integration With') -> social and political developments] social and political developments. The inevitable reaction was the explosion of [dblookup('Romanticism', 'Reaction To') -> Age of Reason] Romanticism in the later 18th century which reclaimed the imaginative and fantastical bias of old romances and folk-literature and asserted the primacy of individual experience and emotion. But as the [dblookup('19th Century', 'Literature Evolution') -> realism and naturalism] 19th-century went on, European fiction evolved towards realism and naturalism, the meticulous documentation of real life and social trends. Much of the output of naturalism was implicitly polemical, and influenced social and political change, but [dblookup('20th Century', 'Fiction and Drama Shift') -> subjective emphasis] 20th century fiction and drama moved back towards the subjective, emphasising unconscious motivations and social and environmental pressures on the individual. Writers such as [dblookup('20th Century Writers', 'Exponents Of Internal Realities') -> Proust, Eliot, Joyce, Kafka, Pirandello] Proust, Eliot, Joyce, Kafka and Pirandello exemplify the trend of documenting internal rather than external realities.
examples.text: Literature: In the Age of Reason philosophical tracts and speculations on history and human nature integrated literature with social and political developments. The inevitable reaction was the explosion of Romanticism in the later 18th century which reclaimed the imaginative and fantastical bias of old romances and folk-literature and asserted the primacy of individual experience and emotion. But as the 19th-century went on, European fiction evolved towards realism and naturalism, the meticulous documentation of real life and social trends. Much of the output of naturalism was implicitly polemical, and influenced social and political change, but 20th century fiction and drama moved back towards the subjective, emphasising unconscious motivations and social and environmental pressures on the individual. Writers such as Proust, Eliot, Joyce, Kafka and Pirandello exemplify the trend of documenting internal rather than external realities.

examples.text: ASCII: Unfortunately, requiring two characters to mark the end of a line introduces unnecessary complexity and questions as to how to interpret each character when encountered alone. examples.text: Philadelphia: Like many American cities, Philadelphia saw a gradual yet pronounced rise in crime in the years following World War II. examples.annotated_text: Switzerland: Aside from the official forms of their respective languages, the [dblookup('Switzerland', 'Number of Linguistic Regions') -> four] four linguistic regions of Switzerland also have their local [dblookup('Switzerland', 'Dialectal Forms Presence') -> present] dialectal forms. examples.text: Switzerland: Aside from the official forms of their respective languages, the four linguistic regions of Switzerland also have their local dialectal forms. The role played by dialects in each linguistic region varies dramatically: in the German-speaking regions, Swiss German dialects have become ever more prevalent since the second half of the 20th century, especially in the media, such as radio and television, and are used as an everyday language, while the Swiss variety of Standard German is almost always used instead of dialect for written communication (c.f. diglossic usage of a language). examples.annotated_text: Chinese_characters: Chinese characters are logograms used in the writing of Chinese and some other Asian languages. In Standard Chinese they are called [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Standard Chinese Name') -> Hanzi (simplified Chinese: 汉字; traditional Chinese: 漢字)] Hanzi (simplified Chinese: 汉字; traditional Chinese: 漢字). They have been adapted to write a number of other languages including: [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Adaptation Language') -> Japanese] Japanese, where they are known as [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Name in Japanese') -> Kanji] kanji, [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Adaptation Language') -> Korean] Korean, where they are known as [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Name in Korean') -> Hanja] hanja, and [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Adaptation Language') -> Vietnamese] Vietnamese in a system known as [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Name in Vietnamese') -> Chữ Nôm] chữ Nôm. Collectively, they are known as [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Collective Name in East Asia') -> CJKV characters] CJKV characters. In English, they are sometimes called [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Alternative English Name') -> Han characters] Han characters. Chinese characters constitute the oldest continuously used system of writing in the world. By virtue of their widespread current use in East Asia, and historic use throughout the Sinosphere, Chinese characters are among the [dblookup('Chinese characters', 'Global Significance') -> Most Widely Adopted Writing Systems] most widely adopted writing systems in the world.

examples.annotated_text: Annelid: No single feature distinguishes [dblookup('Annelid', 'Taxonomic Classification') -> invertebrate phyla] Annelids from other invertebrate phyla, but they have a distinctive combination of features. Their bodies are long, with segments that are divided externally by shallow ring-like [dblookup('Annelid', 'Body Structure Feature') -> annuli] constrictions called annuli and internally by [dblookup('Annelid', 'Internal Structure Feature') -> septa] septa ("partitions") at the same points, although in some species the septa are incomplete and in a few cases missing. Most of the segments contain the same sets of organs, although sharing a common [dblookup('Annelid', 'Shared Organ Systems') -> gut, circulatory system, nervous system] gut, circulatory system and nervous system makes them inter-dependent. Their bodies are covered by a [dblookup('Annelid', 'Outer Covering Material') -> cuticle made of collagen] cuticle (outer covering) that does not contain cells but is secreted by cells in the skin underneath, is made of tough but flexible collagen and does not molt – on the other hand arthropods' cuticles are made of the more rigid α-chitin, and molt until the arthropods reach their full size. Most annelids have [dblookup('Annelid', 'Circulatory System Type') -> closed circulatory systems] closed circulatory systems, where the blood makes its entire circuit via blood vessels.
examples.text: Annelid: No single feature distinguishes Annelids from other invertebrate phyla, but they have a distinctive combination of features. Their bodies are long, with segments that are divided externally by shallow ring-like constrictions called annuli and internally by septa ("partitions") at the same points, although in some species the septa are incomplete and in a few cases missing. Most of the segments contain the same sets of organs, although sharing a common gut, circulatory system and nervous system makes them inter-dependent. Their bodies are covered by a cuticle (outer covering) that does not contain cells but is secreted by cells in the skin underneath, is made of tough but flexible collagen and does not molt – on the other hand arthropods' cuticles are made of the more rigid α-chitin, and molt until the arthropods reach their full size. Most annelids have closed circulatory systems, where the blood makes its entire circuit via blood vessels.

examples.annotated_text: Gymnastics: A gymnast's score comes from deductions taken from their start value. The start value of a routine is based on [dblookup('Gymnastics', 'Score Component') -> Difficulty of Elements] the difficulty of the elements the gymnast attempts and whether or not the gymnast meets [dblookup('Gymnastics', 'Score Component') -> Composition Requirements] composition requirements. The composition requirements are different for each apparatus; this score is called the [dblookup('Gymnastics', 'Score Name') -> D score] D score. Deductions in execution and artistry are taken from [dblookup('Gymnastics', 'Execution Score Start Value') -> 10.0] 10.0. This score is called the [dblookup('Gymnastics', 'Score Name') -> E score] E score. The final score is calculated by taking deductions from the E score, and adding the result to the D score. Since [dblookup('Gymnastics Scoring System', 'Change Year') -> 2007] 2007, the scoring system has changed by adding bonus plus the execution and then adding those two together to get the final score.
examples.text: Gymnastics: A gymnast's score comes from deductions taken from their start value. The start value of a routine is based on the difficulty of the elements the gymnast attempts and whether or not the gymnast meets composition requirements. examples.annotated_text: Yale_University: Much of Yale University's staff, including most maintenance staff, dining hall employees, and administrative staff, are [dblookup('Yale University', 'Staff Unionization') -> unionized] unionized. Also included in FHUE are the dietary workers at [dblookup('Dietary Workers at Yale-New Haven Hospital', 'Union') -> 1199 SEIU] Yale-New Haven Hospital, who are members of 1199 SEIU. In addition to these unions, officers of the [dblookup('Yale University Police Department', 'Officers Union') -> Yale Police Benevolent Association] Yale University Police Department are members of the Yale Police Benevolent Association, which [dblookup('Yale Police Benevolent Association', 'Affiliation Year') -> 2005] affiliated in 2005 with the [dblookup('Yale Police Benevolent Association', 'Affiliation Organization') -> Connecticut Organization for Public Safety Employees] Connecticut Organization for Public Safety Employees. examples.text: Yale_University: Much of Yale University's staff, including most maintenance staff, dining hall employees, and administrative staff, are unionized. examples.annotated_text: Nonprofit_organization: Resource mismanagement is a particular problem with NPOs because the employees are not accountable to anybody with a direct stake in the organization. For example, an employee may start a new program without disclosing its complete liabilities. The employee may be rewarded for improving the [dblookup('Nonprofit Organization', 'Benefit from Reputation Improvement') -> reputation] NPO's reputation, making other employees happy, and attracting new donors. Liabilities promised on the full faith and credit of the organization but not recorded anywhere constitute [dblookup('Nonprofit Organization', 'Potential Issue') -> accounting fraud] accounting fraud. But even indirect liabilities negatively affect the financial sustainability of the NPO, and the NPO will have financial problems unless strict controls are instated. Some commentators have also argued that receiving [dblookup('Nonprofit Organization', 'Funding Source Concern') -> large for-profit corporations] significant funding from large for-profit corporations can ultimately alter the NPO's functions.

examples.annotated_text: History_of_science: In Babylonian astronomy, records of the motions of the stars, planets, and the moon are left on thousands of [dblookup('Babylonian Astronomy', 'Records Medium') -> clay tablets] clay tablets created by scribes. Even today, [dblookup('Mesopotamian Proto-scientists', 'Contribution To Calendars') -> Identification of astronomical periods] astronomical periods identified by Mesopotamian proto-scientists are still widely used in Western calendars such as the solar year and the lunar month. Using these data, they developed [dblookup('Babylonian Astronomy', 'Mathematical Methods Developed') -> arithmetical methods to compute daylight and predict appearances and eclipses] arithmetical methods to compute the changing length of daylight in the course of the year and to predict the appearances and disappearances of the Moon and planets and eclipses of the Sun and Moon. Only a few astronomers' names are known, such as that of [dblookup('Kidinnu', 'Occupation') -> Chaldean astronomer and mathematician] Kidinnu, a Chaldean astronomer and mathematician. [dblookup('Kidinnu', 'Contribution To Calendars') -> Calculation of solar year] Kiddinu's value for the solar year is in use for today's calendars. Babylonian astronomy was [dblookup('Babylonian Astronomy', 'Historical Significance') -> First refined mathematical description of astronomical phenomena] "the first and highly successful attempt at giving a refined mathematical description of astronomical phenomena." According to the historian A. Aaboe, "all subsequent varieties of scientific astronomy, in the Hellenistic world, in India, in Islam, and in the West—if not indeed all subsequent endeavour in the exact sciences—[dblookup('Babylonian Astronomy', 'Influence On Science') -> Influenced scientific astronomy in various cultures] depend upon Babylonian astronomy in decisive and fundamental ways."
examples.text: History_of_science: In Babylonian astronomy, records of the motions of the stars, planets, and the moon are left on thousands of clay tablets created by scribes. examples.annotated_text: Cork_(city): The climate of [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Climate') -> mild and changeable] Cork, like the rest of Ireland, is mild and changeable with [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Rainfall Characteristic') -> abundant] abundant rainfall and a [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Temperature Characteristic') -> lack of extremes] lack of temperature extremes. Cork lies in [dblookup('Cork (city)', 'Plant Hardiness Zone') -> 9b] plant Hardiness zone 9b. [dblookup('Met Éireann', 'Weather Station Location') -> Cork Airport] Met Éireann maintains a climatological weather station at Cork Airport, a few kilometres south of the city. It should be noted that the airport is at an altitude of [dblookup('Cork Airport', 'Altitude') -> 151 metres (495 ft)] 151 metres (495 ft) and temperatures can often differ by a few degrees between the airport and the city itself. There are also smaller synoptic weather stations at UCC and [dblookup('Weather Station', 'Location') -> Clover Hill] Clover Hill.
examples.text: Cork_(city): The climate of Cork, like the rest of Ireland, is mild and changeable with abundant rainfall and a lack of temperature extremes. Cork lies in plant Hardiness zone 9b. Met Éireann maintains a climatological weather station at Cork Airport, a few kilometres south of the city. It should be noted that the airport is at an altitude of 151 metres (495 ft) and temperatures can often differ by a few degrees between the airport and the city itself. There are also smaller synoptic weather stations at UCC and Clover Hill.

examples.annotated_text: Humanism: Renaissance humanism was an activity of cultural and educational reform engaged in by civic and ecclesiastical chancellors, book collectors, educators, and writers, who by the [dblookup('Renaissance Humanism', 'Terminology Use Before') -> Late Fifteenth Century] late fifteenth century began to be referred to as umanisti – "humanists". It [dblookup('Renaissance Humanism', 'Developed During') -> Fourteenth and Early Fifteenth Centuries] developed during the fourteenth and the beginning of the fifteenth centuries, and was a [dblookup('Renaissance Humanism', 'Response To') -> Scholastic University Education] response to the challenge of scholastic university education, which was then dominated by [dblookup('Scholastic Education', 'Dominated By Philosophy') -> Aristotelian Philosophy and Logic] Aristotelian philosophy and logic. Scholasticism focused on preparing men to be doctors, lawyers, or professional theologians, and was taught from approved textbooks in logic, natural philosophy, medicine, law, and theology. There were important [dblookup('Renaissance Humanism', 'Centres') -> Florence, Naples, Rome, Venice, Mantua, Ferrara, Urbino] centres of humanism at Florence, Naples, Rome, Venice, Mantua, Ferrara, and Urbino.
examples.text: Humanism: Renaissance humanism was an activity of cultural and educational reform engaged in by civic and ecclesiastical chancellors, book collectors, educators, and writers, who by the late fifteenth century began to be referred to as umanisti – "humanists". It developed during the fourteenth and the beginning of the fifteenth centuries, and was a response to the challenge of scholastic university education, which was then dominated by Aristotelian philosophy and logic. Scholasticism focused on preparing men to be doctors, lawyers or professional theologians, and was taught from approved textbooks in logic, natural philosophy, medicine, law and theology. There were important centres of humanism at Florence, Naples, Rome, Venice, Mantua, Ferrara, and Urbino.

examples.annotated_text: University_of_Notre_Dame: Father Joseph Carrier, C.S.C. was Director of the Science Museum and the Library and Professor of Chemistry and Physics until [dblookup('Joseph Carrier', 'End of Tenure') -> 1874] 1874. Carrier taught that scientific research and its promise for progress were not antagonistic to the ideals of intellectual and moral culture endorsed by the Church. One of Carrier's students was Father John Augustine Zahm (1851–1921) who was made [dblookup('John Augustine Zahm', 'Positions Held') -> Professor, Co-Director of the Science Department] Professor and Co-Director of the Science Department at age [dblookup('John Augustine Zahm', 'Age as Co-Director') -> 23] 23 and by [dblookup('John Augustine Zahm', 'National Prominence Year') -> 1900] 1900 was a nationally prominent scientist and naturalist. Zahm was active in the [dblookup('John Augustine Zahm', 'Movement Participation') -> Catholic Summer School movement] Catholic Summer School movement, which introduced Catholic laity to contemporary intellectual issues. His [dblookup('John Augustine Zahm', 'Book') -> Evolution and Dogma] book Evolution and Dogma (1896) defended certain aspects of evolutionary theory as true, and argued, moreover, that even the great Church teachers [dblookup('Evolution and Dogma', 'Referenced Church Teachers') -> Thomas Aquinas, Augustine] Thomas Aquinas and Augustine taught something like it. The intervention of Irish American Catholics in Rome prevented Zahm's censure by the Vatican. In 1913, Zahm and former [dblookup('Theodore Roosevelt', 'Occupation Post-Presidency') -> Explorer] President Theodore Roosevelt embarked on a major expedition through the Amazon.
examples.text: University_of_Notre_Dame: Father Joseph Carrier, C.S.C. was Director of the Science Museum and the Library and Professor of Chemistry and Physics until 1874. Carrier taught that scientific research and its promise for progress were not antagonistic to the ideals of intellectual and moral culture endorsed by the Church. One of Carrier's students was Father John Augustine Zahm (1851–1921) who was made Professor and Co-Director of the Science Department at age 23 and by 1900 was a nationally prominent scientist and naturalist. Zahm was active in the Catholic Summer School movement, which introduced Catholic laity to contemporary intellectual issues. His book Evolution and Dogma (1896) defended certain aspects of evolutionary theory as true, and argued, moreover, that even the great Church teachers Thomas Aquinas and Augustine taught something like it. The intervention of Irish American Catholics in Rome prevented Zahm's censure by the Vatican. In 1913, Zahm and former President Theodore Roosevelt embarked on a major expedition through the Amazon.

examples.annotated_text: Gamal Abdel Nasser: Simultaneous with Israel's February raid, the Baghdad Pact was formed between some regional allies of the UK. Nasser considered the Baghdad Pact a threat to his efforts to eliminate British military influence in the Middle East, and a mechanism to undermine the [dblookup('Baghdad Pact', 'Perceived Threat To') -> Arab League] Arab League and "perpetuate [Arab] subservience to Zionism and [Western] imperialism". Nasser felt that if he was to maintain [dblookup('Egypt', 'Required Action') -> acquiring modern weaponry] Egypt's regional leadership position he needed to acquire modern weaponry to arm his military. When it became apparent to him that Western countries would not supply Egypt under acceptable financial and military terms, Nasser turned to the Eastern Bloc and [dblookup('Gamal Abdel Nasser', 'Arms Agreement') -> US$320,000,000 armaments agreement with Czechoslovakia] concluded a US$320,000,000 armaments agreement with Czechoslovakia on [dblookup('Czechoslovakian Arms Deal', 'Date') -> 27 September 1955] 27 September. Through the Czechoslovakian arms deal, the [dblookup('Czechoslovakian Arms Deal', 'Effect On Balance Of Power') -> equalized power between Egypt and Israel] balance of power between Egypt and Israel was more or less equalized and Nasser's role as the Arab leader defying the West was enhanced.
examples.text: Gamal_Abdel_Nasser: Simultaneous with Israel's February raid, the Baghdad Pact was formed between some regional allies of the UK. Nasser considered the Baghdad Pact a threat to his efforts to eliminate British military influence in the Middle East, and a mechanism to undermine the Arab League and "perpetuate [Arab] subservience to Zionism and [Western] imperialism". Nasser felt that if he was to maintain Egypt's regional leadership position he needed to acquire modern weaponry to arm his military. When it became apparent to him that Western countries would not supply Egypt under acceptable financial and military terms, Nasser turned to the Eastern Bloc and concluded a US$320,000,000 armaments agreement with Czechoslovakia on 27 September. Through the Czechoslovakian arms deal, the balance of power between Egypt and Israel was more or less equalized and Nasser's role as the Arab leader defying the West was enhanced.
